Effectivity 1 Jun 01/21 Introduction 1 thru 3 Jun 01/21 Jun 01/21 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL INTRODUCTION Page 1 Jun 01/21 INTRODUCTION 00000 INTRODUCTION 1. GENERAL This manual has been prepared in accordance with Air Transport Association Specification No. 100 (ATA-100) format and is a guide to investigate and repair structural damage that may occur. The Structural Repair Manual provides specific information not contained in the Maintenance Manuals (TO 1T-6ABD-2-XX) (where XX refers to ATA system designation) or the Illustrated Parts Catalog (TO 1T-6ABD-4). Structural repair information is divided into two areas. General and typical repairs are located in Chapter 51. Specific repairs and parts breakdowns are contained within Chapters 32 through 78. It may be necessary to reference both specific as well as general repair information within this manual to complete a repair. If repair information cannot be found in this manual, contact the cognizant authority. 2. ASSIGNMENT OF SUBJECT MATERIAL The contents of this publication are organized in four levels as follows: A. GROUP Groups are primary divisions of the manual that enable broad separation of content. Typical of this division is the separation between the introduction and structures. Groups are identified by blue divider tabs. B. SYSTEM Each group is broken down into systems, such as doors, fuselage, stabilizers, etc. Each system is assigned a number, which is the first element of a standardized numbering system. The element 53 of the number 53-10-01 refers to the fuselage portion of the aircraft. The system number is also referred to as a chapter number. Systems are identified by yellow divider tabs. C. SUBSYSTEM Each aircraft system is divided into subsystems. Each subsystem is identified by the second element of the standardized numbering system. The element 10 of the number 53-10-01 applies to the frames that make up the fuselage structure. D. SUBJECT A subject within a subsystem is identified by the third element of the standardized numbering system. The element 01 of the number 51-10-01 applies to frame 1 of the fuselage structure. This element is arbitrarily assigned and applies to the specific parts of the fuselage structure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL INTRODUCTION Page 2 Jun 01/21 3. ATA 100 PAGE BLOCK GUIDE The following is a guide to the assignment of the blocks of pages within each system number and subsystem number in the Structural Repair Manual. The text providing structural identification information within a section appears on pages numbered consecutively 1 through 99. The information pertaining to allowable damage within the same subject appears on pages numbered consecutively 101 through 199. Repair information appears on pages numbered 201 through 999. 4. ORGANIZATION A. List of Effective Revisions The list of effective revisions following the title page in the front of this manual, it lists revisions currently effective for this manual. B. List of Page Effectivity The list of page effectivity following each system/chapter divider tab lists the issue date of each page that is effective for that chapter. The list starts with page one and is numbered consecutively thereafter, as necessary. C. Table Of Contents The table of contents is found in front of each chapter following the list of effective pages. The table of contents contains a consecutive breakdown of each section and subsection within that chapter. D. Chapter Index Guide The following is an ATA 100 Chapter Index Guide that references the system number to the chapter name to facilitate locating information in the Structural Repair Manual. Only systems applicable to this manual are listed. TYPE COVERAGE PAGE BLOCKS Structural Identification 1 to 99 Allowable Damage 101 to 199 Repairs 201 to 999 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL INTRODUCTION Page 3 Jun 01/21 E. Changed Text As text is changed by additional or changed information, solid change bars are added along the outside edge of the changed page. Changed pages will also display the change date in the lower outside corner of the page, allowing the reader to differentiate between the previous issue and the later changed page. F. Illustrated Parts Breakdown (1) Illustrations Each illustration, located on the page preceding a parts list page, contains a pictorial representation of the system, subsystem, subject, and item numbers being described on the adjacent page. NOTE Illustrations in this manual are to be used only as aids in identifying parts and should not be used for maintenance procedures. Illustrations are only representations of parts and may not be an exact likeness of the parts represented. (2) Parts List The parts list consists of assemblies broken down into their detail parts. The parts that are different will be indexed and illustrated, with the differences noted in the description. When a part is the same for both the left and right, only the left will be indexed and illustrated. The Units Per Assy column lists the quantity of parts required for each assembly that immediately precedes either the attaching or detail parts. NP indicates non-procurable and AR indicates as required. When a number is shown in the Usable On Code column, refer to the effectivity codes at the end of the parts list for each subject to determine the aircraft serial effectivity. (a) Superseded Part Numbers Superseded part numbers will appear in the description field of the parts list, for example “... Stringer /Supersedes 133-440030-1/”. 133-440030-1 would be the superseded number. LANDING GEAR TABLE OF CONTENTS SUBJECT PAGE Page 1 32-CONTENTS 32-00-00 Structural Identification . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 1 General . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 1 Inspection . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 1 32-20-00 Allowable Damage . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 101 Repair Limitations . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 101 Repairs . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 201 Repair or Replacement . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 201 Nose Landing Gear (NLG) Fork Lug Repair (Large and Small Axle Bore Holes) (Refer to VSP) . . . . . . 201 Large Bore Repair (No More Than 1.7665 Inch Diameter) . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 201 Large Bore Repair (More Than 1.7665 inch but Less Than or Equal to 1.8609 Inch Diameter) . . . . 202 Small Bore Repair (No More Than 1.2165 Inch Diameter) . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 203 Small Bore Repair (More Than 1.2165 Inch but Less Than or Equal to 1.3095 Inch Diameter) . . . . 204 Jun 01/21 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-00-00 Page 1 Jun 01/21 LANDING GEAR NOSE GEAR 32-00-0052-30-00 STRUT 100100100100100 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. GENERAL Refer to Illustrated Parts Catalog (TO 1T-6ABD-4), 32-20-05. 2. INSPECTION The nose landing gear strut is inspected for condition, security, and foreign objects on a regularly scheduled basis. Refer to the Preflight, Thruflight, Postflight Inspection Workcards. Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of damage. Refer to 51-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 101 Jun 01/21 LANDING GEAR NOSE GEAR 32-20-0052-30-00 STRUT 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS If damage affects the nose landing gear strut, piston fork lugs, it should be classified as either repairable or replacement. Refer to 51-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 LANDING GEAR NOSE GEAR 32-20-0052-30-00 STRUT 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT Typical repairs are permanent and should be carried out to restore the nose gear strut, piston fork lugs, to serviceable condition. 2. NOSE LANDING GEAR (NLG) FORK LUG REPAIR (LARGE AND SMALL AXLE BORE HOLES) (REFER TO VSP) A. Large Bore Repair (No More Than 1.7665 Inch Diameter) (1) Carefully machine damaged bore hole as follows: NOTE This repair is used when gouges can be removed by oversizing large bore to no more than 1.7665 inch diameter with minimum lug wall thickness of 0.460 inch. Refer to Figure 203. (a) Machine damaged bore out to 1.7665 inch maximum diameter to remove damage. Make sure bore is clean and within 0.003 inch of roundness. Chamfer entrance of bore to 0.010-0.020 x 45° ± 5°. Machine finish on inner diameter to be 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. Maintain minimum lug wall thickness of 0.460 inch. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. (3) Check bore hole using any of the following NDI techniques. Make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. (5) Apply alodine (type I) (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repaired area outside of piston fork lug. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Primer not allowed in lug bore hole. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (7) Refinish surface, as required, to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00, Table 2. (8) Assemble NLG fork. B. Large Bore Repair (More Than 1.7665 inch but Less Than or Equal to 1.8609 Inch Diameter) (1) Carefully machine damaged bore hole as follows: NOTE This repair applies to gouge depths in the large axle lug requiring bore clean up diameters less than or equal to 1.8609 inch with minimum lug wall thickness of 0.460 inch. Refer to Figure 203. (a) Machine damaged bore out to 1.8600-1.8609 inch diameter. Make sure bore is clean and within 0.003 inch of roundness. Chamfer entrance of bore to 0.010-0.020 x 45° ± 5°. Machine finish on inner diameter to be 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. Maintain in-line condition within 0.0010 inch of the small bore diameter. Maintain minimum lug wall thickness of 0.460 inch. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. (3) Check lug bore hole using any of the following NDI techniques. Make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. (5) Apply alodine (type I) (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repaired area outside of piston fork lug. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Primer not allowed in lug bore hole. (7) Manufacture repair bushing. Refer to Figure 201. Make from aluminum nickel bronze rod per AMS4640. Machine finish 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. (8) Inspect repair bushing to make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (9) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. (10) Cadmium plate repair bushing per SAE AMS-QQ-P-416, Type II, Class 2. (11) Install repair bushing into oversize lug bore hole by freeze fitting into piston fork lug. Completely submerge repair bushing into liquid nitrogen, or 90% pure alcohol bath mixed with dry ice, for 10 minutes minimum prior to installation. Shave bushing flush after installation, as required. (12) After repair bushing installation, drill and ream repair bushing 0.322-0.325 inch diameter, two places, to match existing bolt holes. (13) Line drill and ream repair bushing 1.7565-1.7595 inch diameter. (a) Add a 0.015-0.020 radius or 0.015-0.020 x 45° ± 5° chamfer to inner diameter of bushing after reaming. (14) Deburr all sharp edges. (15) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to any remaining bare metal. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Surface treatment not allowed in lug bore holes. (16) Refinish surface, as required, to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00, Table 2. (17) Assemble NLG fork. C. Small Bore Repair (No More Than 1.2165 Inch Diameter) (1) Carefully machine damaged bore hole as follows: NOTE This repair is used when gouges can be removed by oversizing large bore to no more than 1.2165 inch diameter with minimum lug wall thickness of 0.430 inch. Refer to Figure 203. (a) Machine bore out to 1.2165 inch maximum diameter to remove damage. Make sure bore is clean and within 0.003 inch of roundness. Chamfer entrance of bore to 0.010-0.020 x 45  5. Machine finish on inner diameter to be 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. Maintain minimum lug wall thickness of 0.430 inch. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. (3) Check lug bore hole using any of the following NDI techniques. Make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. (5) Apply alodine (type I) (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repaired area outside of piston fork lug. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Primer not allowed in lug bore hole. (7) Refinish surface, as required, to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00, Table 2. (8) Assemble NLG fork. D. Small Bore Repair (More Than 1.2165 Inch but Less Than or Equal to 1.3095 Inch Diameter) (1) Carefully machine damaged bore hole as follows: NOTE This repair applies to gouge depths in the small axle lug requiring bore clean up diameters less than or equal to 1.3095 inch with minimum lug wall thickness of 0.430 inch. Refer to Figure 203. (a) Machine damaged bore out to 1.3087-1.3095 inch diameter. Make sure bore is clean and within 0.003 inch of roundness. Chamfer entrance of bore to 0.010-0.020 x 45  5. Machine finish on inner diameter to be 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. Maintain in-line condition within 0.0010 inch of the large bore diameter. Maintain minimum lug wall thickness of 0.430 inch. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. (3) Check lug bore hole using any of the following NDI techniques. Make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 32-20-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 (5) Apply alodine (type I) (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repaired area outside of piston fork lug. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Primer not allowed in lug bore hole. (7) Manufacture repair bushing. Refer to Figure 202. Make from aluminum nickel bronze rod per AMS4640. Machine finish 63 micro-inches Ra, or better. (8) Inspect repair bushing to make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (9) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment before continuing with this repair. (10) Cadmium plate repair bushing per SAE AMS-QQ-P-416, Type II, Class 2. (11) Install repair bushing into oversize lug bore hole by freeze fitting into piston fork lug. Completely submerge repair bushing into liquid nitrogen, or 90% pure alcohol bath mixed with dry ice, for 10 minutes minimum prior to installation. Shave bushing flush after installation, as required. (12) After repair bushing installation, drill and ream repair bushing 0.322-0.325 inch diameter, two places to match existing bolt holes. (13) Line drill and ream repair bushing 1.2065-1.2095 inch diameter. (a) Add a 0.015-0.020 radius or 0.015-0.020 x 45  5 chamfer to inner diameter of bushing after reaming. (14) Deburr all sharp edges. (15) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to any remaining bare metal. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Surface treatment not allowed in lug bore holes. (16) Refinish surface, as required, to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00, Table 2. (17) Assemble NLG fork. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-00-00 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES 51-00-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. GENERAL Structural repairs included in this manual are intended as permanent repairs for the structural maintenance of this aircraft. Repairs are designed to fully restore structural integrity of the affected component. Careful evaluation of the extent and severity of the damage is required to prepare a proper repair plan. A. Aircraft Dimensions Major aircraft dimensions are illustrated in Figure 1. B. Aircraft Structure Locations Major structural members are identified in this section. Structural member locations are identified by station numbers. C. Fuselage Frame Locations Fuselage frame (FR) locations and corresponding fuselage stations (FS) are illustrated in Figure 2. Fuselage frames are numbered forward to aft starting at FR1, which is located at the engine firewall. FS numbers represent a length measurement along and perpendicular to the centerline of the aircraft. FS numbers indicate dimensions in inches measured aft from the reference datum located 16.46 inches forward of the foremost edge of the propeller spinner. D. Fuselage Stringer Locations Fuselage stringer (STR) locations are illustrated in Figure 3. Fuselage stringers do not extend the full length of the fuselage. Forward stringers extend from the engine firewall to the aft pressure bulkhead (Frame 4), and are numbered left hand (LH) and right hand (RH) from top to bottom. Aft stringers extend aft from just behind the aft pressure bulkhead (Frame 4) and terminate at various locations. Aft stringers are numbered left hand and right hand from the fuselage underside through the fuselage top center. E. Wing Rib and Stringer Locations Wing ribs, corresponding wing stations, and stringer (STR) locations, are illustrated in Figure 4. Wing ribs are numbered from the center line of the aircraft outboard to the wing tip. Inboard ribs are designated with a letter in front of the rib number. Wing stations indicate dimensions in inches measured from the center line of the aircraft outboard to the wing tip. Inboard wing station (IWS) numbering starts at aircraft center line, WS 0.000, extending outboard left and outboard right to the start of the outboard wing. Outboard wing station (OWS) numbering begins where WS numbering ends, extending outboard to the tip. Upper and lower wing stringers are numbered from the leading to the trailing edge. Most stringers do not extend the full length of the wing. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-00-00 Page 2 Jun 06/16 F. Vertical and Horizontal Stabilizer Rib Locations Vertical stabilizer and rudder ribs are numbered from bottom to top, as are vertical stabilizer and rudder stations (VSS). Refer to Figure 5. Horizontal stabilizer ribs and stations are numbered from the center line of the aircraft outboard left and outboard right to the stabilizer tips. Horizontal stabilizer stations (HSS) indicate dimensions in inches measured from the centerline of the aircraft. Stations to the left of centerline carry a negative (-) station number. Refer to Figure 6. G. Aircraft Waterlines Aircraft waterlines (WL) are illustrated in Figure 7. Waterlines are vertical measurements from a horizontal plane located beneath the underside of the fuselage. The fuselage reference plane for the aircraft is the top of the main lower longeron, located at WL 78.74. Waterlines can help determine where damage begins and ends, where inspection points start and stop, and where a particular cross point may be located. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 1 Jun 04/18 STRUCTURES INVESTIGATING AIRFRAME DAMAGE 51-10-0051-10-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. DAMAGE CLASSIFICATION Damage detailed in this manual ranges from superficial damage to major structural deformation. This manual refers to damage in three categories: allowable damage, repairable damage, and replacement damage. These terms can be used to determine the type of repair required for specific damage. A. Allowable Damage Allowable damage is superficial and will not affect the airworthiness of the aircraft. Examples are minor dents or scratches. This is only applicable to damage sustained by non-structural parts. Examples include cowlings or fairings. Typically results in minor rework. B. Repairable Damage Repairable damage affects structural integrity or deforms airfoils, jeopardizing aircraft airworthiness. A damage inspection must be performed to determine extent and type of damage. Typically results in detailed rework. C. Replacement Damage Replacement damage is to an extent that exceeds repairable limits. Typically results in replacement of aircraft members. 2. DAMAGE TERMS AND DEFINITIONS An alphabetical list of damage terms and definitions is provided for use as a guide in classifying and understanding airframe damage. Table 1 - Terms and Definitions Term Definition Abrasion An area of roughened scratches or marks, usually caused by foreign matter between moving parts of surfaces. Arcing Discharging electricity across a gap or surface. Bent Sharp deviation from original line or plane, usually caused by lateral force. Blister An enclosed raised spot or bulge, usually with a void underneath. Bowed Curved or gradual deviation from original line or plane, usually caused by lateral force. Broken Separated by force into two or more pieces. Buckling Causing to bend, give away or crumple. Chafed Frictional wear damage, usually caused by two parts rubbing with a limited motion, such as vibration. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 2 Jun 04/18 Collapsed Inward deformation of the original contour of a part, usually due to high pressure differential. Corrosion Pitting or surface breakdown of material due to chemical or electro-chemical attack by atmosphere, moisture, or other agents. Crack Detectable split or fracture in a part Crease Permanent deformation or wrinkle of skins, usually caused by hard landing or turbulence. Crushed Destruction of a part or structure by a squeezing force resulting in change of original shape. Deflection The turning away from original shape or direction by an undesired force. Delamination Separation into layers, usually of bonded or composite materials, or metal in the case of intergranular corrosion. Dent A surface impression usually with a rounded bottom. Caused by impact of a foreign object. Material is displaced and stretched. Discoloration A color that is not normal, usually caused by heat. Distortion Deformation of original shape of a part, usually due to structural stresses, excessive localized heating, or any combination of these. Elongation A stretching or lengthening of original dimensions, usually applies to fastener holes. Erosion Gradual removal of material by wear or flow of grit over a surface. Fissure A small scratch or crack. Flash channel Major area of lightning strike. FOD Foreign Object Damage. Damage which occurs from the introduction, injection, or collision with debris. Foreign object A piece of material not usually found in or around a part or location. Fretting Surface erosion caused by slight movement between two parts that are fastened together with considerable pressure. Fused Joining of two materials, usually caused by heat, friction, or excessive current flow. Galled A transfer of material from one surface to another by sliding contact created by heat friction, causes material from one surface to be welded or deposited on the other surface. Gouge Groove in part that displaces material Ionized Converted positive or negative electrical charges. Kink A sharp twist or bend in skin or structure, usually caused by doubling or torsional forces. Nick A sharp surface indentation caused by impact of a foreign object. Material is displaced but seldom separated. Oil canning A condition of sheet metal skin which is slightly bulged or stretched between rows of rivets, usually caused by torsional forces. The bulge, when popped back and forth, will make an audible popping sound. Table 1 - Terms and Definitions (Continued) Term Definition MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 3 Jun 04/18 3. DAMAGE CAUSES The following terms and definitions reflect the most common types of aircraft damage: A. Corrosion Corrosion is a natural phenomenon which attacks metal by chemical or electrochemical action converting the metal into a metallic compound, such as an oxide, hydroxide, or sulfate. There are many different types of corrosive attack which will vary with the metal concerned, corrosive media location, and time exposure. Four conditions must exist before corrosion can occur: (1) Presence of a metal that will corrode (anode) (2) Presence of a dissimilar conductive material (cathode) which has less tendency to corrode (3) Presence of a conductive liquid (electrolyte) (4) Electrical contact between the anode and the cathode, usually metal to metal contact Elimination of any one of these conditions will stop corrosion. The tendency of most metals to corrode creates one of the major damage problems in the maintenance of an aircraft, particularly in areas where adverse environmental or weather conditions exist. Refer to the Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-30-00. Pitted Small irregular shaped hollows in a surface, usually caused by corrosion, erosion, or heavy electrical discharge. Puncture A hole through material, usually caused by penetration of a foreign object. Scored A deep scratch or groove in a material surface, usually caused by movement of foreign matter under pressure across the surface. Scoring may show a discoloration effect from high friction. Scratched Shallow superficial grooves in a material surface, usually caused by movement of a sharp object or grit across the surface. Stress The intensity of force applied over an area, possibly resulting from external loadings or internal reactions to said loadings. Stretched Elongation of a part as a result of exposure to abnormal operating conditions (tension type stress). Swept stroke Striking one area on a surface and moving across surface to other areas. Torn Separation by pulling apart. Twisted A change in original shape of a part or structure by a turning motion, sometimes called distortion. Void An empty space or cavity in a weld or between laminates of metal or composite materials. Wrinkled Small furrow, ridge, or crease on a normally smooth surface, usually caused by hard landing or heavy turbulence. Table 1 - Terms and Definitions (Continued) Term Definition MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 4 Jun 01/21 B. Fatigue Fatigue is the weakening of a material caused by the continued flexing and vibration which occurs during flight. Fatigue damage usually appears in aircraft parts as cracks protruding from, or running adjacent to, fastener holes in areas subject to vibration or flexing. A thorough continuous inspection program can effectively identify the results of fatigue damage. C. Impact Impact damage occurs when an aircraft strikes, or is struck by, a foreign object. This type of damage may occur in flight or on the ground. In flight, the leading edges of wings and stabilizers are most likely to sustain impact damage. On the ground, the entire surface of the aircraft is vulnerable. When impact damage occurs, an in-depth inspection must be performed to determine the extent structure is affected, and damage classification. D. Stress Stress damage occurs when an aircraft is subject to abnormal stress such as turbulent flight, hard landings, high winds while moored, or flight maneuvers beyond the designed characteristics of the aircraft. E. Fire or Exposure to Elevated Temperatures Fire damage often results in structural element deformation and structural corrosion caused by combustion of non-metallic material. Fire can cause loss of structural integrity from heat damage (even if not visible) and a change in the material strength results. Determining the effects of fire on airframe structure and repair is difficult because of the many factors requiring consideration. Different types of alloys react in a variety of ways when exposed to elevated temperatures. For example, 7075-T6 aluminum alloy is an artificially age hardened material. When exposed to temperatures of 300 F (149 C) for a short time, 7075-T6 aluminum alloy experiences a reduction in strength. When exposed to the same temperatures, 2024-T4 aluminum alloy artificially ages to a higher strength material with reduced flexibility. With 2024-T4, this artificial age hardening occurs until a temperature of approximately 400 F (204 C) is reached, then strength properties are significantly reduced. Also, when 2024-T4 aluminum alloy is exposed to temperatures of 300 F (149 C) for a short period of time under uncontrolled conditions such as an aircraft fire, the heat affects corrosion-resistant properties of the metal. F. Lightning Strike Damage resulting from lightning strikes requires extensive investigation to determine the extent of damage and recommended repair procedures. Damage from lightning strikes typically occurs at entry points as burn marks or holes in the skin. A swept stroke usually has several entry points along the flash channel (in many cases attaching to rivets). These appear as burn marks, darkened or bubbled paint on skin surfaces, and arcing holes up to 3/8-inch diameter. G. Wind Damage resulting from high wind greater than 60 KIAS, requires investigation to determine the extent of damage and recommended repair procedures. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 5 Jun 29/20 4. DAMAGE INSPECTION After an aircraft has been subjected to impact damage or abnormal stress, a thorough inspection should be performed to identify damage that has occurred. Types of damage can be differentiated through inspection. Impact damage usually results in scratches, dents, gouges and punctures. Severe impact damage may result in internal structural damage to stringers, bulkheads, frames, etc. Abnormal stress damage usually results in wrinkled and oil canning skins, loose rivets, cracks, etc. and is not always easy to detect. A. Damage Inspection Procedure After any report, suspicion, or discovery of an impact or abnormal stress occurrence, the following damage inspection should be performed: (1) Inspect entire surface of aircraft skin for wrinkled, wavy areas. Inspect any distorted areas found for oil canning condition. Examine suspect areas for loose or missing rivets, or cracks or tears extending from fastener holes. (2) Inspect all exterior skins for visible damage, to include leading edges, trailing edges, skin panels, and landing gear doors. If damage is found, inspect adjacent interior structure for loose or missing rivets, cracks, and distortion. (3) Inspect all stabilizer, flight control, and engine truss attach points for loose attachment hardware, and cracks protruding from fastener holes. (4) Inspect exposed portion of wing spar caps and attaching skins for cracks and distortion. If damage is found, inspect adjacent interior structure for loose or missing rivets, cracks, and distortion. (5) If hard landing has been reported or suspected, inspect landing gear and side brace attachment bolts for signs of yield, deformation, or failure. If damage is suspected, jack aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-07), 07-10-00, and replace noted bolts and nuts. (6) Inspect integral fuel areas for leaks. If leaks are found, internal fuel bay structure should be inspected for cracks, loose rivets, and distortion. Inspect fuel bay sealant for integrity. (7) If damage is detected or suspected in moving assembly (landing gear, flight control, etc.), perform operational checks in accordance with appropriate section of Maintenance Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-2). (8) Any damage found during this inspection should be classified and compared to allowable aerodynamic smoothness and repair tolerances to determine type of repair required. Any distortion of the airframe requires aircraft alignment and symmetry check. Refer to 51-50-01. If damage is judged extensive, and beyond the scope of this Structural Repair Manual, contact cognizant authority. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 6 Jun 01/21 B. Fire or Heat Damage Inspection Inspect the aircraft thoroughly after a fire. Many fire extinguishing agents promote corrosion. In turn, corrosion hides structural damage caused by the fire. Clean the aircraft as soon as possible to minimize the effects of fire extinguishing agents. Visually inspect the aircraft as follows: NOTE Make sure suspected fire or heat damaged areas are free of dirt, oil, smoke, and other contaminants prior to performing the inspection. (1) Inspect for buckling or oil canning. This type of inspection usually reveals a weakened condition of primary internal structures. Carefully inspect around fuselage. (2) Inspect all areas painted with primer and compare coloring. Chromate primers darken when exposed to heat. Clean primed sample piece of metal and compare sample to areas suspected of heat damage. (3) If evidence reveals discoloration of primer, structural integrity of airframe is questionable and nondestructive inspection must be performed. Refer to appropriate sections in Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36). (4) Classify damage and repair using typical repairs. Refer to 51-70-00. If damage is judged to be extensive and beyond the scope of this Structural Repair Manual, contact cognizant authority. C. Lightning Strike Inspection When lightning strike damage is suspected, inspect the aircraft for possible damage to control surfaces and structure as follows: (1) Inspect trailing edges of control surfaces for arcing, holes, buckled, rippled, pinched or darkened skin, and broken or discolored rivets. (2) Inspect rivets which join structural members to adjacent skins on the fuselage, stabilizers, and wings for burned heads. (3) Inspect flight controls for broken bonding straps. (4) Inspect operation of flight control surfaces for smooth movement. Make sure elevator bearings, rudder bearings, aileron bearings, and flap bearings are not binding. (5) Inspect steel parts for damage. (6) Inspect wing tips for burn marks, arcing holes, and rippled skin. (7) Inspect for evidence of swept stroke strike point damage. (8) Inspect skin for blast effect, typically causing caving in of skin. Inspect underlying structure for internal damage. (9) Inspect aircraft for burn marks, arcing holes, rippled skin, and overall condition. Inspect painted surfaces for burned or darkened spots. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-00 Page 7 Jun 01/21 (10) Inspect antennas and antenna mounts for security and condition. (11) Inspect static dischargers on control surfaces and replace damaged static dischargers. (12) Classify damage and repair using typical repairs. Refer to 51-70-00. If damage is judged to be extensive and beyond the scope of this Structural Repair Manual, contact cognizant authority. (13) Inspect propeller for lightning strike damage. If lightning strike occurred, refer to Maintenance Manual, Propellers (TO 1T-6ABD-2-61), Propeller Lightning Strike inspection, 61-00-00 and Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-00-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-01 Page 1 Jun 05/17 STRUCTURES INVESTIGATING AIRFRAME DAMAGE 51-10-01 AERODYNAMIC CONTOUR TOLERANCES 00000 SURFACE CONTOUR 1. MAINTAINING SURFACE CONTOUR This section defines aerodynamic contour (smoothness) tolerances, which include contour variations caused by dents, surface waviness, skin or repair patch edges, and fastener characteristics. The limits defined are the maximum acceptable tolerances to be used in the repair of this aircraft. Maintaining aircraft surface smoothness within these prescribed limits will assure continued aerodynamic performance qualities. A. Definition of Zones The relative importance of surface smoothness varies with the location on the aircraft. For the purpose of defining the tolerances, the aircraft is divided into zones. Refer to Figure 1. (1) Zone 1 Zone 1 includes the wing leading edge and 4.5 to 7.4 inches aft. The 4.5 inches covers the area from the tip of the wing to the dihedral break. The 7.4 inches covers the area from the dihedral break to the fuselage mate point. Refer to Figure 1. (2) Zone 2 On the wing, Zone 2 includes the area aft of Zone 1 to the aft spar (or auxiliary spar), except on the lower surface inboard of the dihedral break, extending to the aft edge of the main spar. The aileron is included in Zone 2. On the fixed portion of the empennage, Zone 2 includes the entire area, other than the strakes, ventral, and dorsal fin. Zone 2 includes the area forward of the hinge lines on the control surfaces. On the fuselage, Zone 2 extends from the propeller spinner to the aft end of the pressurized section. (3) Zone 3 Zone 3 includes all external surfaces not designated as Zone 1 or Zone 2. B. Mismatch and Gap of Skin Patch Edges The maximum allowable mismatch (height of the skin edge above the original contour) of a skin scab patch edge in each zone is defined in Table 1. Away from the edge, the maximum height of the patch above the original contour should be equal to or less than the maximum mismatch allowance, when parallel to the airstream. Any mismatch of skin patch edges should be filled and faired smooth using prescribed fillet sealing methods. Refer to 51-20-20. The maximum gap width in each zone shall not exceed the values defined in Table 1. The gap width values of Table 1 apply to skin repairs. Any gap in Zone 1 must be filled using prescribed fillet sealing methods. Refer to 51-20-20. Gaps filled in Zone 1 should be faired smooth to approximate a straight line between edges of the parts being bridged. After curing, there should be no lips or edges detectable to a finger running across the gap. If a lip or edge is noticeable, it should be trimmed smooth. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-01 Page 2 Jun 04/18 C. Surface Wrinkle and Dent Tolerances Deviations from external contour in any 6-inch length of each zone shall not exceed the values defined in Table 2. The values in Table 2 apply to surface dents, depressions, and wrinkles. Depressions and wrinkles can be measured using a flat spline or a steel ruler laid over the adjacent contour. The distance measured from the spline to the bottom of the depression is the out of contour condition. Surface waviness is measured from peak to peak. D. Fastener Replacement All fasteners shall be replaced with the same type as previously installed. Table 1 - Mismatch and Gap Tolerances Zone 1 Allowance Zone 2 Allowance Zone 3 Allowance Mismatch - Perpendicular to Airstream ± 0.02 ±0.04 ±0.06 Mismatch - Parallel to Airstream ± 0.04 ±0.06 ±0.09 Gap Width 0.08* 0.08 0.09 NOTE * Any gap located in Zone 1 must be filled and faired smooth. All allowances are in inches. Table 2 - Surface Wrinkle and Dent Tolerances Zone 1 Zone 2 Zone 3 Parallel to Airstream ±0.03 ±0.045 ±0.06 NOTE All tolerances are in inches. REPAIR LIMITATIONS The limitations defined in this section are applicable to dents, gouges, scratches, pitting, or minor set marks in sheet metal skins that are subsequently painted and are classified as allowable damage. Refer to 51-10-00. All repairs should be smoothed and faired to the existing contour of surrounding aircraft skins, in accordance with Aerodynamic Contour Tolerances. Refer to 51-10-01. A. Dents Minor dents or depressions in sheet metal skins classified as allowable damage (refer to 51-10-00) may be repaired by filling with aerodynamic smoother (2, Table 4, 51-30-01) if:  No internal structural damage is present  No tears, breaks, or cracks are present within the dent area  Depth of the depression does not exceed 0.125 inch  Diameter of the depression does not exceed 2 inches  Length of the depression does not exceed 5 inches  Damage sustained on non-structural part such as cowling or fairing NOTE Damage exceeding these limitations is considered repairable or replacement damage and should be repaired by fabricated patch or part replacement. B. Scratches, Gouges, and Pitting Minor scratches, gouges, or pitting in sheet metal skins classified as allowable damage (refer to 51-10-00) may be repaired by filling with aerodynamic smoother (2, Table 4, 51-30-01) if, after the damage is blended out, the following criteria are met:  The damage does not penetrate more than 15% of the skin thickness or exceed a maximum depth of 0.008 inch in depth  The scratch does not exceed 5 inches in length  Damage sustained on non-structural part such as cowling or fairing NOTE Damage exceeding these limitations is considered repairable or replacement damage and should be repaired using typical repairs. Refer to 51-70-00. Pitting caused by corrosion should be further evaluated and classified. Refer to 51-10-03. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-03 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES INVESTIGATING AIRFRAME DAMAGE 51-10-03 CORROSION 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. CLASSIFICATION OF DAMAGE Evaluation of corrosion damage is required, after general cleaning and inspection, to determine the extent of damage and repair or rework required. Local blending of corroded areas may be required to determine the total extent of the damage. Sound maintenance judgement is required to determine if corrosion has impaired the structural integrity of the material. For specifics on corrosion control methods and techniques, refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-30-00. A. Light Corrosion Light corrosion is characterized by discoloration or pitting to a depth of approximately 0.001-inch maximum. This type of damage is normally removed by hand sanding or a minimum chemical treatment. B. Moderate Corrosion Moderate corrosion is similar to light corrosion except blisters or scaling and flaking are present. Pitting depth may be as deep as 0.010 inch. This type of damage is normally removed by extensive hand sanding. C. Severe Corrosion Severe corrosion is similar to moderate corrosion in appearance, with severe blistering exfoliation and scaling or flaking. Pitting depth will be deeper than 0.010 inch. This type of damage normally impairs the structural integrity of the part. Repair by removing the affected area, replacing the part, or by spot facing a fastener location. 2. DETERMINING DEGREE OF DAMAGE Degree of corrosion damage (light, moderate, or severe) can be measured with a depth gauge or a straight edge and a wire feeler gauge set. Depth of the damage cannot be measured until all corrosion is removed from the area to be measured. Before measurements are made, determine if the affected area has previously been reworked. Measure damage to include material which has previously been removed. A. Measurement Take measurements with a standard depth gauge as follows: (1) Remove loose corrosion if present. (2) Position the depth gauge so that the base is flat against undamaged surface on both sides. When taking measurements on a concave or convex surface, place the base of the depth gauge perpendicular to the curved surface. (3) Take several readings, selecting the deepest as the depth of the corrosion damage. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-10-03 Page 2 Jun 06/16 3. DETERMINING MATERIAL THICKNESS AFTER REWORK After all corrosion damage is removed and the affected material is blended and smoothed, make an accurate measurement of the amount of material removed or the remaining material thickness to make sure that allowable damage limitations are not exceeded. Refer to 51-10-02. Measurement of panel thickness can be made using ultrasonic testing. Ultrasonic testing requires qualified NDI personnel and suitable test standards for calibration. Measurement of the depth of blended pits can be made using a depth gauge, or a straight edge and a wire feeler gauge. In areas where accessibility is limited, the use of modeling clay or other impression substances can be used to determine depth. In the event that material limits have been exceeded, the area or part should be repaired or replaced using Typical Repairs. Refer to 51-70-01. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-00 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES SPECIAL PROCESSES 51-20-00 00000 REPAIR PROCESSES 1. REPAIR PROCESSES This section defines special processes used in structural maintenance and repair of this aircraft. A. Corrosion Prevention Prevention of corrosive attack on aircraft structure and skins is accomplished through frequent cleaning, careful inspection, and the use of proper structural repair procedures. For in-depth corrosion control methods, techniques, and practices, refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. This section describes basic corrosion prevention methods necessary in the assembly and rework of aluminum aircraft skins and structure. Refer to 51-20-10. B. Airframe Sealing Three basic types of seals are used in manufacturing and repair of this aircraft. • Rubber seals are installed at all points where frequent parting of the sealing surface is necessary, such as canopy and avionics bay access doors. • Special seals are used for control cables, torque tubes, and wires passing through pressure vessel boundaries. • Applied sealing compounds are used at points where the seal is seldom broken except for structural maintenance or part replacement, as with riveted skins and structure. This section defines general applied sealing requirements, procedures, and materials required in repair of airframe structure and skins. Refer to 51-20-20. C. Thermal Resistant Coating Thermal resistant coatings provide added protection to the cockpit in the event there is an engine fire. This section defines general requirements, procedures, and materials required in application of thermal resistant coating. Refer to 51-20-30. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-10 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES SPECIAL PROCESSES 51-20-10 CORROSION PREVENTION 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. PREVENTION METHODS This section describes basic corrosion prevention methods necessary for the assembly and rework of aluminum aircraft skins and structure. For in-depth corrosion control methods, techniques, and practices, refer to the Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. Corrosion prevention is of primary importance to all aircraft maintenance personnel. Corrosion of airframe components and structure affects operation and structural integrity. Corrosion can weaken structural members to the point that the affected members require costly repair or replacement. Prevention, removal, and treatment of corrosion, before it accelerates, is of vital importance. The value of maintaining a clean aircraft cannot be overemphasized. Frequent cleaning removes corrosive agents (electrolytes) which are continuously deposited on the aircraft during normal operation. Not only can regular cleaning reduce the possibility of corrosion, proper cleaning also prepares the surface for inspection, and provides a suitable surface for protective treatment and paint preparation. Aircraft parts are protected against corrosion by several methods. Aircraft aluminum alloy sheet is protected by a thin cladding layer of pure aluminum. Other aircraft aluminum alloy parts are protected with an anodic coating system or a chromate treatment. For the purpose of field repairs, chemical conversion treatment and the application of paint primer is an effective way of restoring permanent surface coatings to aluminum alloy surfaces. A. Chemical Conversion Treatment Prior to assembly of locally fabricated sheet metal parts or rework of existing metals, all surfaces should be given a protective treatment and painted. Chemical conversion treatment of aluminum alloys forms a protective coating which resists corrosion and provides a good surface for adhesion of paint primer. This process applies to all aluminum alloys which require a chemical conversion coating in accordance with Military Specification MIL-C-81706. MIL-C-81706 chemical conversion coatings are suitable for field conversion treatment of aluminum alloy surfaces. Chemical conversion coating can be applied by brush or immersion. Brush application must be done on rework areas where original protective coating has been removed. The immersion process is suitable for treating small, locally manufactured or reworked parts prior to installation. Coating results may vary with product types and application methods. Most chemical conversion coatings produce a finish that ranges from a light, golden brassy iridescence, to a heavy, dark, dull brown appearance. The brassy iridescent films are superior to the darker results in both corrosion resistance and paint adhesion qualities. A continuous film is required, but identical color matches between surfaces are not required. These variations in color are not an indication of poor quality in a chemical coating. A gray appearance, or a powdery, non-adherent coating indicates unsatisfactory quality, requiring stripping and recoating. If a golden color is not achieved with the first application, repeat the application. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-10 Page 2 Jun 06/16 WARNING Consumable materials specified in this section are classified as hazardous. The use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) is required when working with these materials. Hazardous materials shall be handled, stored, and disposed of in accordance with applicable local and federal environmental standards, and the manufacturer’s Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS). WARNING Wash all brushes, sponges, rags, etc. immediately after use to prevent inadvertent contact with acid solution, and to eliminate the potential fire hazard created by open air drying of chemical conversion products. (1) Brush Application (a) Mask surfaces outside treatment area which are likely to be affected by solutions with tape, plastic sheet, plastic plugs, or other protection. (b) Remove contaminates from surfaces to be treated by wiping down with solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Without allowing surfaces to dry, rinse with cold water and clean with clean cheesecloth to remove all loose deposits. Check for a water break-free surface. Repeat procedure until a water break-free surface is achieved. (c) After cleaning, immediately treat surface with chemical conversion solution (1, Table 2, 51-30-01). Apply solution with cheese cloth pad, cellulose sponge, or nylon brush using light pressure and continuous even motion. Keep surface wet with solution for the length of time recommended by the manufacturer’s instructions. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions listed on the container for mixing and specific application instructions. (d) After treatment, thoroughly rinse off solution with cold running water, avoiding excessive flow on non-sealed, non-drainable assemblies. Freshly formed films should not be disturbed until completely dry. Rubbing contact can remove freshly formed film. (2) Immersion Application (a) Remove contaminants from surfaces to be treated by wiping down with solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Without allowing the surface to dry, rinse with cold water and clean with clean cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) to remove all loose deposits. Check for a water break-free surface. Repeat procedure until a water break-free surface is achieved. (b) After treatment, thoroughly rinse off solution with cold running water, avoiding excessive flow on non-sealed, non-drainable assemblies. Freshly formed films should not be disturbed until completely dry. Rubbing may remove freshly formed film. (c) After cleaning, fully immerse parts to be treated in a plastic container filled with chemical conversion solution (1, Table 2, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions listed on the container for mixing and specific application instructions. Multiple parts must be arranged so there will be no flat surface contact with each other. Small, individual parts can be treated in a small container. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-10 Page 3 Jun 06/16 B. Paint Primer After chemical conversion coating is completed, apply at least one coat of paint primer (1 or 2, Table 3, 51-30-01) to all aluminum parts, skin edges, drilled holes, etc. prior to assembly. Parts should receive the initial application of paint primer as soon as possible after chemical conversion coating. Particular care should be taken to avoid excessive thickness of primer coatings. Refer to TO 1-1-691. C. Isolation of Dissimilar Metals Galvanic corrosion occurs when two dissimilar metals make contact in the presence of electrolyte. The rate at which galvanic action occurs depends on the type of metals involved, and the size of contact areas. To prevent galvanic action between dissimilar metals, the parts must be isolated by applying at least two coats of primer to the surfaces of each part in the contact area. Prior to applying paint primer, aluminum surfaces should be treated with a chemical conversion coating. Skin edges should be sealed to prevent wicking of moisture (electrolyte) between the metals, consequently initiating galvanic action. Groupings of commonly used aircraft metals are listed in Table 1. Metals listed in the same group are considered similar. Metals listed in each group of Table 1 are considered similar to metals of the same group, but are dissimilar to metals of another group. Table 1 - Dissimilar Metals 1. Group I. All aluminum alloys, cadmium, zinc, and alloys thereof. a) Subgroup A. 1100, 3003, 5052, 6061, 220, 355, 356. All clad alloys. b) Subgroup B. 2014, 2017, 2024, 7075, 195. Under severe corrosive conditions, the subgroups are considered dissimilar metals insofar as corrosion protection is concerned. This is particularly true when a large area of an alloy of Subgroup B is in contact with a small area of Subgroup A. Severe corrosion of the alloy from Subgroup A is expected. 2. Group II. Iron, lead, tin and alloys thereof (except stainless steels). 3. Group III. Stainless steels, titanium, chromium, nickel, silver, gold, platinum, cobalt, rhodium, copper, and alloys thereof, graphite (including dry film lubricants containing graphite). NOTE The materials in the preceding list are classified by external finishes; thus, a cadmium-plated steel part is considered a cadmium part instead of a steel part. Materials are also listed in the order of decreasing activity (susceptibility to corrosion). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES SPECIAL PROCESS 51-20-20 SEALING 200200200200200 AIRFRAME 1. GENERAL Airframe sealing consists of preparation and application of a variety of applied sealants. Sealing produces aerodynamic smoothness, pressure-tight and fuel-tight compartments, and protects against corrosion and the environment. This section defines general applied sealing requirements, procedures, and materials used in the repair of airframe structure and skins. The following are general sealing rules: • Sealant should be applied to surfaces which have been chemical conversion coated, primed, completely dried and thoroughly cleaned. As a general rule, sealant should not be applied to bare metal surfaces. • All assemblies requiring sealing should be drilled, deburred, reamed, prefitted, and cleaned before sealant is applied. If rework is necessary before sealant has cured, the wet sealant must be protected. • All surfaces must be thoroughly cleaned and dried before application of sealant. Before applying sealant, verify that cleaning has been accomplished. • Sealant should not be applied when ambient temperature is below 60 °F. • The type of sealant will be determined by the intended use. Refer to Table 7, 51-30-01. • Structures having overhead fillet seals, gap seals, or hole seals should not be vibrated excessively, such as by riveting, until sealant has reached a tack-free stage. • All seals should be continuous, either within themselves or by overlapping adjoining seals. Pressure vessel or fuel bay sealing must be performed on the inside boundary (pressurized side) of the surface being sealed. A. Sealing Requirements This aircraft has specific sealing requirements that must be adhered to in order to preserve a corrosion free environment, as well as maintaining the integrity of the pressure vessel and integral fuel tanks. The requirements outlined below are the same as those used in the manufacturing process of the aircraft. • All parts (skin laps, seams, bulkheads, doublers, stringers, nutplates, screws, bolts, etc.) and all holes, gaps, slots, etc. that lead out, attach to, or cross parts that lead out of pressure boundaries, must be sealed in accordance with this section. All rivets that project to the outside of the airframe will be driven wet with sealant. • Interior parts that form joints which do not provide pressurization or weatherization leak paths do not require faying surface sealing. Interior parts which have a faying surface seal between the surfaces do not require rivets to be driven wet. Nutplates in non-pressurized areas do not require a faying surface or coating seal unless installed on a dissimilar metal. Refer to 51-20-10. • All electrical wire bundles and cables which pass through pressure boundaries will be sealed using an injection seal. Sealant will cover each individual wire and both ends of spare wires or cable to provide a satisfactory seal. • All plumbing fittings which pass through pressure boundaries will be sealed using a combination of faying surface seal and/or fillet seal. Fittings provided with gaskets or preformed packings do not require sealing. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 202 Jun 06/16 • The engine firewall will be sealed with sealant (10, Table 7, 51-30-01). Metal adhesion primer (1, Table 9, 51-30-01) will be used to enhance sealant adhesion to stainless steel and titanium firewall parts except on faying surface seals. Sealant should not be applied thicker than 0.125 inch. • The wheel wells will be sealed with faying surface seals followed by fillet seals to protect against water penetration. • Integral fuel tank sealing will be accomplished to all leak paths except removable doors and fittings that are provided with gaskets or preformed packing. All fasteners and nutplates inside the fuel tank will be sealed. Interior parts that form joints that do not provide leak paths do not require sealing. Do not apply any sealer in stringer and spar holes in the ribs of the fuel cell. Reference Paragraph F, Step (6) and Figure 207. (1) The assembly and sealing operation will be accomplished on subassembly and major assemblies in the following sequence: (a) Prefit, drill, ream, and deburr all parts. Refer to 51-40-00. (b) Clean all areas to be sealed. (c) Determine type of sealer to be used. (d) Prepare sealant, if required. (e) Apply sealant (faying surface seals, pre-assembly fillet seals). (f) Assemble faying surface and pre-assembly fillet seals. (g) Reclean all areas receiving additional sealing. (h) Apply injection seals. (i) Apply fillet and coating seals. (j) Allow sealant to cure. (k) Accomplish pressure or leak test. (l) Repair leaks as necessary. B. Preparation The importance of good cleaning practices cannot be overemphasized. Thorough cleaning is critical for proper adhesion of sealant during the repair process. Cleaning procedures apply not only to major surfaces, but also to all fasteners installed wet with sealant during the assembly process. Any contamination will prevent the sealer from adhering to a surface. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 203 Jun 06/16 WARNING Consumable materials used in this section are classified as hazardous. The use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) is required when working with these materials. Hazardous materials must be handled, stored, and disposed of in accordance with applicable local and federal environmental standards and manufacturer’s Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS). (1) Preliminary Cleaning Remove previously applied sealant with a plexiglass, phenolic, or hardwood scraper (to prevent scratches), and a rag dampened with solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Remove all chips and loose debris using a vacuum device, a dry rag, or a bristle brush. Avoid blowing debris with compressed air. (2) Final Cleaning Final cleaning should be accomplished immediately prior to sealant application using the two-cloth wipe method outlined below. NOTE Do not try to clean a large area all at once. Trying to clean a large area at once may allow solvent to evaporate, leaving the surface contaminated. Do not use red shop rags or laundered rags for cleaning. (a) To reduce the possibility of leaving lint, use cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) and fold so that edges are not exposed. (b) Dampen one cheesecloth with solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drips from the cheesecloth. CAUTION Cleaning solvents should never be poured or sprayed on structure because of the possibility that solvent could run back between layers of structure, then creep back out bringing contamination to surfaces being sealed. (c) Wipe area to be sealed with dampened cheesecloth. Before solvent evaporates, immediately wipe again with second clean, dry cheesecloth. (d) Repeat cleaning until there is no discoloration on the dry cheesecloth. Use new clean, dry cheesecloth each time. (e) Use extreme care in cleaning all hard-to-reach areas (corners, gaps, drilled holes, etc.). Paint brushes, cotton tipped swabs, or pipe cleaners (3, 7, or 8, Table 10, 51-30-01) may be required to clean hard-to-reach areas. After surfaces, fasteners, etc. are thoroughly cleaned, white cotton gloves (2, Table 10, 51-30-01) should be worn when handling cleaned items to prevent contamination. (3) Special Cleaning MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 204 Jun 06/16 Wire and cable bundles must be cleaned before applying sealant. This may be accomplished using an acid brush dampened with solvent (6, Table 1, 51-30-01) or by flushing the bundle with the solvent. Immediately wipe dry with a clean dry cloth or blow dry with clean, oil free compressed air. Plastic/acrylic surfaces should be cleaned in accordance with Final Cleaning procedures, using solvent (6, Table 1, 51-30-01) on plastic and acrylic materials. (4) After Assembly Clean-Up After each assembly operation has been completed on detailed assemblies, sub-assemblies, and major assemblies, excess sealant should be removed. Excess sealant is the sealant on the inside and outside of all surfaces after assembly is complete. Excess sealant should be removed as follows: (a) Excessive sealant that has not reached the tack-free condition should be removed by wiping the area with a clean cheesecloth dampened with solvent (4 or 6, Table 1, 51-30-01). Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drip form the cheesecloth. Large amounts of sealant may be removed with a plexiglas, phenolic, or hardwood scraper. Caution must be taken not to scratch through the primed surface. NOTE Do not use red shop rags or laundered rags for cleaning. (b) Excessive sealant that has passed the tack-free condition should be removed by scraping with a plexiglas, phenolic, or hardwood scraper. Caution must be taken not to scratch through the primed surface. C. Types of Sealants Various types of applied sealants are used in the assembly of the aircraft. The majority of sealants used are polysulfides which are non-silicone; however, some silicone sealants are used. Silicone seals work well as mechanical seals because they age slowly. Weathering does not affect silicone seals to the extent that it would other types of seals. Polysulfide sealants have good fuel and hydraulic fluid resistance qualities. The Sealant Material List defines the recommended use of various sealants and application and cure times. Refer to Table 7, 51-30-01. Make sure the following precautions are followed when using sealants of more than one type: • Keep silicone and non-silicone sealants separate to prevent cross-contamination. • Do not use tools, mixing containers, or equipment that has been used with non-silicones for working with silicones, and vice versa. • When applying silicone sealants do not contaminate adjacent areas. Silicone acts as a release film and will prevent adhesion of any subsequent applied finishes. • To avoid deterioration, avoid contact with hydraulic fluid, fuel, organic solvents, paint strippers and acids when applying sealant. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 205 Jun 06/16 D. Sealant Mixing Two part sealants must be completely mixed. When sealant is completely mixed, color will be uniform throughout. A streaked appearance is evidence of insufficient mixing. Incomplete mixing may also affect cure and performance properties of sealant. It is also important to keep air entrapment to a minimum during the mixing process. Two part sealants must be mixed in the correct proportions (or ratios) of accelerator to base. Prepare sealants in accordance with manufacturer’s instructions. Each container has the correct mixing ratios printed on the label. Labels should be checked before each use, as the manufacturers may change the mixing ratio for a particular batch of material. E. Application of Sealants The application time of two part sealants must be observed. Sealant must not be used after the application time has expired. The type of sealant should be chosen, when possible, to provide ample time to complete the sealing task, taking temperature and relative humidity into consideration. Application and cure times specified by the manufacturer’s specifications are maximum allowable based on 77±2 °F with 50±5% relative humidity. As a general rule, reduce application and cure times by one-half for every 10 °F rise in temperature. For every 10 °F below 77 °F, double the application and cure times stated. Application time for frozen sealants shall be reduced by 45 minutes from the standard two part material application times. Application and cure time is defined below: • Application time: The maximum amount of time in which sealant can be satisfactorily applied after the sealant is mixed. After this point, the material does not wet properly. Sealant which does not wet properly or is difficult to extrude from sealant gun should be discarded. • Tack-free time: The condition between application and the elapse of cure time when sealant is still plyable yet is not sticky to the touch. During the tack-free time, sealant is not hard enough to be handled without damaging or deforming the sealant job. • Cure time: The minimum amount of time that must elapse before sealant reaches final hardening stage. After cure time has elapsed, sealant is hard enough to be handled without damage or deformation. If an assembly cannot be completed within the application time of the sealant being used in Table 4, 51-30-01, draw type temporary fasteners must be used in every hole, until assembly is completed. At the time the assembly is completed, every temporary fastener must be replaced with a permanent fastener, installed wet with sealant, to seal the permanent fastener in the assembly. If an assembly or repair is done that compromises the cockpit pressurized area, a cockpit pressure check must be done. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Air Conditioning (TO 1T-6ABD-2-21), 21-30-00. The space surrounded by the firewall, canopy, pressure floor of the cockpit and CFR 4 is considered the cockpit pressurized area. F. Types of Seals A variety of adhesion sealing methods are used in the assembly and repair of aircraft structure and skins. (1) Faying Surface Seals Sealant is applied between mating surfaces of two or more parts or skins before assembly. Refer to Figure 201. (a) Apply sealant to one mating surface. Spread to desired consistency with a putty knife or small roller. A roller should be used whenever possible. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 206 Jun 06/16 (b) Tight fitting parts which cannot be pried apart or dissembled, after being assembled for drilling, should be cleaned before assembly. After drilling, these parts should be deburred and cleaned again, where possible. A faying surface seal can then be applied by injecting sealant into each rivet hole while closing off the hole on the opposite side, pressure flowing sealant between all parts. Parts or skins may have to be held apart using wedges to obtain desired sealant flow. (c) Sealant shall cover entire mating surfaces and be continuous without voids. Sufficient sealant should be applied to fill all mis-matches of parts, joggles, gaps or voids, and provide a slight squeeze-out when parts are assembled. Squeeze-out sealant should be continuous, and be faired back into the joint to make a fillet seal. Apply extra sealant where necessary to obtain a consistent fillet seal. (d) Install all permanent fasteners within application time of sealant. A maximum separation of 0.004 inch is allowed in faying surface at shank of fastener. (e) Nut plates and other dissimilar metal fixtures fastened to aluminum parts should be sealed with a faying surface seal prior to installation. (2) Fillet Seal A fillet seal fills the mismatch of surfaces of mated parts. Sealant is applied into and over a joint, or seam, of two or more parts. Refer to Figure 202. (a) Apply sealant with sealant or caulking gun, and appropriate size nozzle. Force sealant into seams or mismatch areas of parts by keeping nozzle tip pointed into the seam and almost perpendicular to line of travel. (b) Fair sealant into joint or seam using a putty knife or equivalent. Press tool against sealant and move parallel to joint or seam, ensuring that air is not trapped within sealant. Work out, remove, and repair any air bubbles. (c) Fillet seals should be continuous without voids, and should adhere to and overlap adjoining structure. All fillet seals should have approximate dimensions as shown. (3) Faying Surface Fillet Seal For areas not accessible for normal fillet sealing, the application of an extra bead of sealant applied in conjunction with faying surface seal will provide a fillet seal when parts are assembled. This method is referred to as a faying surface fillet seal. Refer to Figure 203. (a) Apply 0.0625 to 0.125-inch bead of sealant on top of a faying surface seal at the edge of the part of assembly. (b) Assemble parts and fair sealant squeeze-out as a normal fillet seal. (4) Coating Seal Sealant is applied to completely cover parts such as rivets, nut plates, bolts, or permanent fasteners for purposes of pressure vessel or fuel bay sealing and corrosion prevention. Pressure vessel coating seals are to be installed on the pressure side of the vessel. Refer to Figure 204. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 207 Jun 06/16 NOTE When installing nut plates in a pressure vessel, nut plates will be sealed using a faying surface seal and a coating seal. Refer to Figure 201 and Figure 204. Prevent sealant from entering the threads of the nutplate. (a) Apply sealant with a putty knife, sealant gun, or brush. Brush method is preferred. (b) Apply a liberal amount (0.015 to 0.035 inch) of sealant to completely cover areas concerned, making sure to work sealant into crevices and gaps. When using a brush, stroke sealant in multiple directions. Work out any air bubbles while ensuring complete coverage. (c) Coating seals should be continuous without pinholes, cracks, air bubbles, or separation from adjoining parts. Coating seals should overlap adjoining parts by approximately 0.250 inch, with the exception of parts, structure, or fasteners that, for purposes of inspection visibility, will not be covered. When applying a coating seal to spar caps fasteners, leave at least 1/8 inch visible along the edge of the spar cap, and at least 0.250 inch on the web side of a fastener. (d) Apply sealant to countersink holes, universal rivet holes, or rivet shanks prior to installing the rivet. Installation must be completed while sealant is wet and within prescribed application time. Refer to Table 7, 51-30-01. Apply sealant with a brush or sealant gun. (5) Injection Seal Sealant is applied to fill gaps, holes, or voids caused when one part overlaps another. Refer to Figure 205. Injection seals are also used to seal voids or gaps not sealed during assembly. Injection sealing procedures are also used to seal wire bundles and cables which pass through the pressure vessel. Sealant is injected between wires in the bundle or around cables on both side the pressure seal fitting and finished with a fillet seal installed on the pressure side. Refer to Figure 206. (a) Inject sealant into one side of the hole or cavity until the sealant extrudes from the other end of the cavity using sealant or caulking gun and appropriate size nozzle. (b) Injection sealing of assembled parts not accessible for other types of seals requires at least 0.0313-inch hole or gap at the injection point, and relief area to allow sealant and air bubbles to extrude. Extruding sealant verifies a proper seal. (6) Gap and Hole Seal Sealant is applied to fill holes, gaps, or voids that are part of the integral fuel tank and pass through or attach to the fuel bay pressure boundary, and are caused by parts not butting together. Refer to Figure 207. CAUTION Fuel system venting and draining require that stringer and spar holes in ribs 11 through 20 (left and right, upper and lower), within the fuel cell remain free of sealer. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-20 Page 208 Jun 06/16 (a) Apply a liberal amount of sealant to completely cover area using a putty knife or sealant gun. Sealant must overlap edges of the hole or gap by at least 0.250 inch and should be approximately 0.250- to 0.500-inch thick. (b) Holes or slots which create an opening with a dimension greater than 0.250 inch should have sealant reinforced with a section of preformed aluminum. Gaps, blind holes, or pockets that cannot be readily sealed may be sealed with premolded plugs. Plugs should be made from sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) and installed wet. An appropriately shaped plastic, phenolic, or hardwood block can be used to pack sealant plug into the gap or pocket.
