GENERAL For the purposes of this manual, there are two systems that complete the thermal resistant coating for the fire barrier. One system is composed of the AF412 primer and the ACM C60 foam. The second system is composed of the AF491 parting agent and the AF405 intumescent. Refer to Table 11, 51-30-01. A. Coating Requirements When applying a thermal resistant coat, use the following requirements: • Thermal coatings may be applied to clean bare metal and primed surfaces that are completely dry. • All surfaces must be thoroughly clean and dry before application of any thermal coating. • Thermal coatings must not be applied in temperatures below 60 °F. WARNING Consumable materials used in this section are classified as hazardous. The use of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) is required when working with ACM C60. Apply thermal coating in a well ventilated area. The use of a fan will be necessary if thermal coating is applied in a closed area (i.e., wheel well). Hazardous materials must be handled, stored, and disposed of in accordance with applicable local and federal environmental standards and manufacturer’s Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS). B. Preparation Plug open holes and apply plastic caps over open plumbing fittings. Use the following procedure for cleaning: (1) Preliminary Cleaning If grease, or oil-like films are present, clean the area with a rag dampened with solvent (2, 3, or 4 Table 1, 51-30-01). Remove all chips and loose debris using a vacuum device, a dry rag, or a clean bristle brush. (2) Final Cleaning Final cleaning should be accomplished immediately prior to thermal coating application using method outlined below. (a) To reduce the possibility of leaving lint, use cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) and fold so that edges are not exposed. (b) Dampen one cheesecloth with solvent (2, 3, or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drips from the cheesecloth. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-30 Page 202 Jun 06/16 CAUTION Cleaning solvents should never be poured or sprayed on structure because of the possibility that solvent could run back between layers of structure, then creep back out bringing contamination to surfaces being sealed. (c) Thoroughly clean area to be thermal coated with dampened cheesecloth. Before solvent evaporates, immediately wipe again with second clean, dry cheesecloth. (d) Repeat cleaning until there is no discoloration on the dry cheesecloth. Use a new clean, dry cheesecloth each time. (e) Use extreme care in cleaning all hard-to-reach areas (corners, gaps, drilled holes, etc.). Paint brushes, cotton tipped swabs, or pipe cleaners (3, 7, or 8, Table 10, 51-30-01) may be required to clean hard-to-reach areas. After surfaces, fasteners, etc. are thoroughly cleaned, white cotton gloves (2, Table 10, 51-30-01) should be worn when handling cleaned items to prevent contamination. (f) Cover or protect cleaned area from contamination if any delay in the application of thermal coating is expected. If delay is 30 minutes or longer, area must be recleaned. (3) After Assembly Clean-Up After each assembly operation has been completed on detailed assemblies, sub-assemblies, and major assemblies, excess sealant should be removed. Excess sealant is the sealant on the inside and outside of all surfaces after assembly is complete. Excess sealant should be removed as follows: (a) Excessive sealant that has not reached the tack-free condition should be removed by wiping the area with a clean cheesecloth dampened with solvent (6, Table 1, 51-30-01). Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drip from the cheesecloth. Large amounts of sealant may be removed with a plexiglas, phenolic, or hardwood scraper. NOTE Do not use red shop rags or laundered rags for cleaning. (b) Excessive sealant that has passed the tack-free condition should be removed by scraping with a plexiglas, phenolic, or hardwood scraper. Caution must be taken not to scratch through the primed surface. C. Material Mixing (1) AF412 Tie Coat Shake Part B container before opening to disperse color well. Add contents from Part B container into Part A container. Mix until color is consistent and even. If needed use solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) as a thinner to ease the application process. (2) ACM C60 Akrotherm Prepare a stick free surface. Shake Part B container before opening to disperse color well. Place Part A on stick free surface. Add Parts B and C evenly while folding Part A. Continue folding and kneading until color is consistent and even. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-30 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (3) AF405 Therm Coat Add contents from Part B container into Part A container. Fold the two parts into each other. Be sure to scrape sidewalls of container while mixing in order to obtain a thorough mix. Mix for 5 minutes. Application time begins at start of mixing. To extend application time and cure time, add 2.1% MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) by volume to combined volume of Part A and Part B. Adding 2.1% MPK to combined volume of Part A and B adds 15 minutes to application time and 15 minutes to cure time. Example: 145cc of Part A plus 140cc of Part B = 285cc of AF405 Therm Coat. .021 X 285cc = 6cc of MPK to be added. It is acceptable to add the calculated volume of MPK (6cc) to Part A (145cc) prior to mixing Part A and Part B. D. Tie Coat and Akrotherm Application NOTE Follow all application and cure times. Refer to Table 11, 51-30-01. (1) Mix Tie Coat. (2) Apply Tie Coat to desired surface 0.002- to 0.010-inch thick using a paint brush (3, Table 10, 51-30-01). (3) Allow Tie Coat to cure. (4) Mix Akrotherm. (5) Flatten Akrotherm to required thickness. Refer to Figure 201. (6) Cut square pieces of Akrotherm and gently apply by hand to required surface. Do not press Akrotherm onto flat surfaces with thumb or sharp objects. A trowel or spatula may be used to press materials into corners. The material thickness must remain the same as in Step (5). (7) Repeat Step (6) until entire surface is covered. (8) Allow Akrotherm to cure. NOTE Akrotherm may be finished using 120-grit sandpaper then 320-grit, as long as the required thickness remains the same. However, finishing is not required and serves as an esthetic quality only. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-30 Page 204 Jun 06/16 NOTE Apply tie coat and akrotherm to sealers and/or bonding agents only after sealers/bonding agents have properly cured. E. AF491 Parting Agent Application One coat of AF491 Parting Agent is to be brushed onto electrical connectors to aid in the removal of AF405 Therm Coat for subsequent maintenance. Do not apply AF491 Parting Agent thickly enough to cause dripping or running. Minor overlap of AF491 Parting Agent onto firewall is permissible up to 0.10 inch. F. Therm Coat Application NOTE Apply parting agent and Therm Coat to sealers and/or bonding agents only after sealers/ bonding agents have properly cured. NOTE Apply Therm Coat only in locations shown in Figure 203. NOTE Follow all application and cure times. Refer to Table 11, 51-30-01. (1) Mix Therm Coat. (2) Apply Therm Coat to desired surface 0.15- to 0.25-inch thick using a tongue depressor, plastic spatula, or Semco Sealing gun. (3) Allow Therm Coat to cure. G. Repair of Akrotherm for Fire Protection Requirements If Akrotherm is damaged and meets any of the following criteria, perform Repair of Akrotherm for Fire Protection Requirements. If damage does not meet the following criteria, perform Repair of Akrotherm for Esthetic Requirements. • Thickness of damage is greater than 1/4 the original Akrotherm thickness and covers 10% of the area covered by Akrotherm. • Thickness of damage is greater than 1/4 the original Akrotherm thickness and the area covers the equivalent of 3 square inches or more. • Substructure is exposed over an area 1/2 square inch or greater. CAUTION Do not remove metal or paint when removing existing Akrotherm. (1) Remove loose Akrotherm using a plastic spatula or by sanding. It is not necessary to remove Akrotherm down to aircraft structure. (2) Clean in accordance with Preparation above. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-20-30 Page 205 Jun 06/16 (3) Apply Tie Coat and Akrotherm to reworked surfaces (including existing Akrotherm) in accordance with application procedures above. (4) Apply topcoat in accordance with Corrosion Control Manual. Priming is not required. Transition marks between old and new topcoat are acceptable. H. Repair of Akrotherm for Esthetic Requirements Perform Repair of Akrotherm for Esthetic Requirements only if damage does not meet the criteria described in Repair of Akrotherm for Fire Protection procedure above. CAUTION Do not remove metal or paint when removing existing Akrotherm. (1) Sand down to lowest point of damaged area while transitioning to surrounding surface. Perform finish sanding with 320-grit sandpaper to remove fiber protrusions. (2) Clean in accordance with Preparation above. (3) Apply Tie Coat and Akrotherm to reworked surfaces (including existing Akrotherm) in accordance with application procedures above. (4) Apply topcoat in accordance with Corrosion Control Manual. Priming is not required. Transition marks between old and new topcoat are acceptable. REPAIR MATERIALS This section provides aluminum material specifications needed for repair of structural members and repairs requiring fabrication of skin patches or reinforcements. This section also includes consumable material specifications to include preparation and finish products, sealants, adhesives, fillers, etc. 2. IDENTIFYING ALUMINUM STOCK The majority of structural components used in this aircraft are manufactured from aluminum alloys. Aluminum, when used in aircraft construction, is combined with various percentages of other metals (generally copper and magnesium) to form alloys. Aluminum alloys possess a higher strength to weight ratio than pure aluminum, with a sacrifice in corrosion resistance. Most aircraft grade aluminum alloy sheet is protected against corrosion by a thin cladding layer of pure aluminum known as Alclad. USE OF MATERIAL Choosing the correct sheet material for structural and skin repairs is extremely important. Major factors for consideration are corrosion resistance, alloy composition, gage, temper, and workability. Aircraft aluminum alloy sheets are protected against corrosion by a thin cladding layer of pure aluminum, bearing the trade name of Alclad. Care should be taken to maintain the thin coating of pure aluminum when working with this material. When repairs require replacement or addition of material such as doublers or skin patches, factors such as alloy composition and sheet gauge must be considered. The material chosen must provide cross-sectional strength in tension, compression, shear, and weight bearing at least equal to that of the original material. Never substitute a material thinner than the original. Substitution of material can present a corrosion hazard if the material is not identical in alloy composition to the original material. Isolation of dissimilar metals is extremely important. Refer to Chapter 51-20-10. To provide a method for identifying the various grades of aluminum and aluminum alloy stock, materials are marked with symbols identifying the alloy number and the temper of the material. The alloy is identified by a standard marking system consisting of numbers which identify the particular composition of the metal, such as 2024 or 2017, and a letter suffix designating the temper or condition of the material. The suffix designations applicable to aluminum alloy sheet and extruded stock, heat treated in accordance with Military Specification MIL-H-6088, are listed in Table 1. With aluminum alloys, the factor of workability or ease of forming varies with temper condition. The majority of aircraft aluminum sheet metal used in manufacturing and repair is conditioned to a fully heat treated and aged state, designated by a T alloy designation suffix. Additional digits are added to the suffix letter defining different characteristics added to the basic heat treatment. A. Annealed Condition Use of annealed material (designated by a O alloy designation suffix) is limited in use to small items requiring compound bends. Most parts can be formed without annealing the metal, but if extensive forming operations are planned, such as small radius bends or complex curves, the metal requires a dead-soft or annealed condition. Items are then heat treated after forming. Items manufactured from this material should be replaced if damaged. This material should not be used for repair work without prior heat treating. Table 1 - Temper Designation Suffix Heat Treated Condition O Soft or fully annealed H Fully cold-worked or hard-wrought W Condition following solution treatment, and prior to aging T Fully heat treated and aged RT Temper resulting from cold-working, after heat treatment and aging MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-30-02 Page 2 Jun 06/16 B. T3 Temper Condition The vast majority of all skins and formed structural items are solution heat treated and cold worked to a T3 temper condition (designated by a T3 alloy designation suffix). Sheet material in this condition is easily worked and does not require heat treatment after forming, providing that bending allowances are observed. For this reason, 2024-T3 material is recommended for fabrication of skin patches or reinforcements. C. T4 Temper Condition T4 temper condition (designated by a T4 alloy designation suffix) is produced by solution heat treatment and normal aging to a stable condition. 2024-T4 is similar in strength and formability qualities to that of 2024-T3, and can be used in material substitution. D. T6 Temper Condition For purposes of structural repair, sheet material in a T6 temper condition (designated by a T6 alloy designation suffix) should not be used. Parts in this temper condition are formed prior to heat treating or are manufactured by welding. Parts manufactured from these materials should be replaced if damaged. 2. SHEET METAL FORMING When it is necessary to fabricate a replacement part to reinforce skins or structure, precautions must be observed to make sure that the integrity of the repair is equal to that of the original structure. All bending should be accomplished in accordance with standard and minimum bend radius tables. Refer to Table 1 and Table 2. If metal is stretched beyond limitations, the result will be fatigue cracks and/or intergranular corrosion. Material must be carefully inspected for cracks in the bend radius after forming. Where repairs require compound bending or acute bends in excess of 90°, it may be advantageous to replace the part completely. NOTE Bend radius is designated to the inside of the bend. All dimensions listed in Table 2 and Table 3 are in inches and are recommended bend radii for 90° bends. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-40-06 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES FASTENERS 51-40-06 REPAIRS 200200200200200 DIMPLING 1. GENERAL Dimpling is a common practice used on relatively thin skins and sheet-metal parts when preparing holes for countersink rivet installation. A dimple is formed in sheet-metal by using a male and a female die. When the two dies are forced together under pressure, a dimple is formed. When thin skin is attached to a heavier structural member, the heavy member is countersunk, and the thin skin is dimpled into the countersink depression. Refer to Figure 201. Dimpling should be accomplished on an undersized hole to prevent metal stretch and subsequent hole enlarging. After dimpling, the hole should be reamed or drilled to the correct size for the specific rivet being installed. Radius dimpling is used as an alternative method when a punch and die set is not available. Dimpling bars or sets can be made in the shop by cutting steel stock to the size needed for the job, drilling a hole the same size as the rivet to be used, and then setting a microstop countersink to cut approximately 0.015-inch deeper than the rivet head. Refer to 51-40-07. Accomplish radius dimpling as outlined in the dimpling procedure below. A. Dimpling Procedure (1) Prepare appropriate sized hole. Refer to 51-40-00. (2) Place dimpling bar under rivet hole and insert countersink rivet in hole. Refer to Figure 202. (3) Using a pneumatic rivet gun with a mushroom head set, drive rivet head into countersink depression of dimpling bar. (4) Remove rivet from hole. Drill or ream dimpled hole to proper size. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-40-06 Page 202 Jun 06/16 Figure 201 - Dimpling Sheet Metal Figure 202 - Coin Dimpling PT51E 971885AA.AI SHARP EDGES AS DIMPLED SMOOTH HOLE HOLE REAMED PT51E 973995AA.AI MUSHROOM RIVET SET DIMPLING BAR THIN SHEETS DRAW BAR MUSHROOM RIVET SET THIN SHEET COUNTERSINK RIVET HEAVY SHEET MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-40-07 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES FASTENERS 51-40-07 REPAIRS 200200200200200 COUNTERSINKING 1. GENERAL When using countersink rivets in relatively thick sheet-metal or parts, it is necessary to countersink the surface of the material. Countersinking is accomplished using a 100° microstop cutting tool that cuts only deep enough that the head of the rivet will be flush with the surface. Refer to Figure 201. Whenever metal is cut away to form a countersink, the area around the rivet head is weakened. To compensate for the loss of strength, a greater number of rivets are often used in order to increase bearing and shearing strengths. To minimize loss of strength, minimum sheet thickness required for countersinking standard 100° rivets is subject to limitations. Refer to Table 201. Countersinks which are cut too deep and extend through the entire depth of the hole will result in an enlarged hole and an excessive loss of strength. A. Countersinking Procedure (1) Prepare appropriate sized hole. Refer to 51-40-00. (2) Adjust microstop to desired depth of cut. Use a test piece to verify proper cut and countersink depth. Cut only deep enough so that head of rivet is flush with surface of metal. (3) Using adjusted microstop in a variable speed drill, cut countersink depression. Hold drill and microstop steady, 90° to the work surface at all times. (4) Insert appropriate sized rivet to verify proper cut and countersink depth. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-50-00 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES SUPPORT OF AIRCRAFT FOR REPAIR 51-50-00 51-50-00 00000 HANDLING AND SHORING 1. HANDLING Special care must be observed when handling structurally damaged aircraft to prevent further damage. Unplanned towing or hoisting can induce further damage to landing gear, skins, doors, canopy, engine, propeller, and primary or secondary structure. The aircraft must be stabilized prior to towing or hoisting by securing or removing any loose objects. Defueling may be required to decrease aircraft weight or alleviate further strain on a damaged wing before towing or hoisting. For jacking and hoisting equipment and procedures, refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-7), 07-10-00. The preferred method of transporting a damaged aircraft to a repair facility is towing of the aircraft. Towing is recommended only if the landing gear can be locked in place and a suitable surface is available to tow the aircraft. For towing equipment and procedures, refer to Maintenance Manual, Towing and Taxiing (TO 1T-6ABD-2-9), 09-10-00. When towing is not possible due to collapsed or fully retracted landing gear, it may be feasible to jack or hoist the aircraft in order to extend the landing gear. Prior to jacking, inspect the structure adjacent to the aircraft jacking points for damage which may be compounded if a jacking operation is undertaken. If landing gear can successfully be extended and locked in place, towing is the preferred method of transporting a damaged aircraft. If the aircraft is damaged to the extent that towing is not practical or if aircraft damage occurs in an area where towing is not possible and field repair is not feasible, it may be necessary to hoist the entire aircraft for ground transporting purposes. Support equipment is available for shoring the entire aircraft or the wing. 2. SHORING Shoring stands are available to support the entire aircraft or the wing, for purposes of transportation, storage, and maintenance. A. Wing/Fuselage Stand The wing/fuselage stand (Part Number 133-384004-1) allows transportation and shoring of the entire aircraft or only the wing, when removed from the fuselage. The stand is designed to support the entire aircraft utilizing the two forward lower wing jacking points and the tail jacking point. Refer to Figure 1. The stand is equipped with four hand operated floor jacks that provide a level, non-movable shoring fixture. Straps attached to the stand mounted wing jacks are threaded into upper wing fixtures, located directly above the lower jacking points, securing the wing to the stand. The stand mounted tail jack is secured to the aircraft tail jacking point by means of a ball-lock pin inserted through the tiedown point. The wing/fuselage stand is equipped with one additional caster for handling the wing stand separately. With the entire aircraft secured in stand, transport using a tow vehicle and the stand mounted tow bar. Transporting is limited to smooth, flat, paved surfaces. The wing jacking section of the wing/fuselage stand can be separated from the tail jacking section for wing-only shoring. The following steps provide instructions for shoring the aircraft on the wing/fuselage stand: CAUTION When towing stand, speeds of more than 5 MPH may result in damage to the aircraft and equipment. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-50-00 Page 2 Jun 06/16 (1) Rotate all four adjustable height jacks to fully retracted position. (2) Position wing/fuselage stand beneath aircraft on a flat, hard surface, capable of withstanding the combined weight of aircraft and stand without sinking into the surface. (3) Rotate floor jacks until pads press firmly on the ground. Do not raise stand with floor jacks. (4) If fuselage is to be separated from wing, proceed to wing stand instructions. CAUTION When the wing/fuselage stand is combined, do not use the center adjustable height jack on the wing stand to support any weight of the fuselage. (5) Rotate both wing adjustable height jacks until firmly mated with wing jacking points. Carefully thread both wing height jacks and strap T-handled pins into upper wing threaded fixtures located directly above the lower jacking points. (6) Rotate aft fuselage adjustable height jack until firmly mated with tail jacking point. Secure aft fuselage jacking point to tail jack by installing ball-lock pin through aft fuselage tie-down ring. (7) Rotate handles of wing and tail jacks to raise the aircraft to appropriate height for transporting. Raise aircraft evenly and avoid weight imbalance. (8) Connect stand mounted tow bar to tow vehicle. (9) Retract floor jacks for towing. B. Wing Stand (Separated from Wing/Fuselage Stand) The wing stand is used to separate the fuselage from the wing and shore the wing after the wing is removed. The wing stand utilizes the two forward wing jacks and an adjustable height wing jack, designed specifically for wing jacking only. Refer to Figure 2. Straps attached to the stand mounted wing jacks thread into upper wing fixtures located directly above the lower jacking points, securing the wing to the stand. The following steps provide instructions for shoring the wing on the wing stand: CAUTION The wing stand is designed for transporting by hand only. Do not tow with tow vehicle. (1) Separate wing/fuselage stand by removing ball-lock pin from detachable frame connection and remove tail portion of stand. Refer to Figure 1. (2) Position wing stand beneath the wing. CAUTION Do not detach the fuselage from the wing until the stand is properly positioned and the jacks are firmly secured to the wing. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-50-00 Page 3 Jun 29/20 (3) Remove the left and right lift fitting plugs. (4) Rotate both forward wing adjustable height jacks until firmly mated with wing jacking points. Carefully thread both forward wing height jacks and strap T-handled pins into upper wing threaded fixtures, located directly above the lower jacking points. (5) Rotate the aft wing adjustable height jacks until seated in aft pin hole on the wing. Do not allow any weight from the aircraft to be placed on the aft wing adjustable height jack. (6) Rotate floor jacks until pads press firmly on the ground. Do not raise stand with floor jacks. (7) Detach fuselage from wing. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57), 57-00-00. (8) Hoist fuselage from wing. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-07), 07-10-00. NOTE If transportation of wing is required, perform Wing Hoisting. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-07), 07-10-00. Contact cognizant authority. Make sure wing is positioned on the three wing stand adjustable height jacks, and tie down straps are installed. (9) Retract floor jacks for transporting. It may be necessary to secure the wing to the wing stand using tie-down straps when transporting on uneven surfaces. GENERAL Symmetry and alignment checks are required for aircraft that have been subjected to severe turbulence, hard landing, or collision which results in wrinkles, creases, buckles, misalignment, etc., to aircraft skins or structure. Alignment is determined by measuring the distance from reference points on the aircraft and comparing them to other coordinates. Symmetry is determined by comparing like or opposite reference points on the aircraft. Reference points 1A and 1B, left and right, as well as reference points 2 thru 8, left and right are identified by symmetry rivets at predetermined locations. Refer to Table 201. Symmetry and alignment checks require the Leveling Check procedure completed, the use of calibrated optical leveling equipment, and a minimum of two qualified personnel. Information required to perform and calculate aircraft symmetry and alignment, as well as leveling reference points, have been established. Refer to Figure 202. To achieve accurate readings, the aircraft must remain perfectly still and level during the procedure, and leveling must be rechecked anytime the aircraft is touched or subjected to air movement. Checks should be carried out under the following conditions: • The aircraft must have been parked in a hangar for a minimum of 1 hour prior to check. • All hangar doors must be closed. • The hangar must be free of any moving air. • The aircraft must not be exposed to direct sunlight. • The hangar floor must be level and made of concrete or similar material. • The landing gear must be retracted. • The fuel tanks must be empty. • Flaps must be in the UP position. • All flight controls must be in the neutral position and gust lock engaged. • All doors, cowlings, and access panels must be closed. • Position aircraft 25 feet away from anything else. • The canopy must be closed. A. Leveling Check (1) Defuel aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Servicing (TO 1T-6ABD-2-12), 12-10-00. (2) Jack aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-7), 07-10-00. (3) Retract landing gear. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-02. (4) Level aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Leveling and Weighing (TO 1T-6ABD-2-8), 08-20-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-50-01 Page 202 Jun 06/16 (5) Position optical leveling equipment approximately 3 feet left of buttock line (BL) and 10 feet aft of aircraft. Level optical leveling equipment. Refer to Figure 203. B. Symmetry and Alignment Check (1) Prepare an In-Service Check Form. Refer to Figure 207. NOTE Wing symmetry reference points are identified by rivets with a washer installed under the rivet head. (2) Apply masking tape to underside of aircraft and identify all reference points (31 points). (3) Position optical leveling equipment, to include optical level and stand, so readings can be taken from scale suspended from reference point (RP) 1B and from RPs 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7. Refer to Figure 204. Level horizontal stabilizer RPs 17, 18, 19, and 20. Refer to Figure 202. Adjust optical leveling equipment tripod to allow readings to be taken at a level approximately 4-8 inches below lowest point of fuselage. (4) With aircraft leveled using inclinometer, make sure main landing gear are at least 1 inch from floor. Adjust left and right RP 2 points to read the same, ±0.03 inch. Using RP 17 on lower left side of horizontal stabilizer, adjust tail to 30.86±0.03 inches from RP 2 reading. Refer to Figure 202. (5) If adjustments are required at RP 17 points, make sure measurements for RP 2 points read the same, ±0.03 inch. (6) Take measurement from scale suspended from RP 1B above right wing. Subtract this reading from 36 inches (RP 1B is 36-inches above reference level). Result indicates height of optical leveling equipment above reference level and provides correction factor. Correction factor must be added to all other optical readings to determine actual dimensions of associated RPs above fixed reference level. Refer to Figure 204. (7) Enter reading taken from RP 1B in space labelled “Optical Level Reading” on In-Service Check Form and enter correction factor in eight allocated “Correction Factor” spaces. (8) Suspend scale from RP 2 under right wing. Taking care not to disturb setting of optical leveling equipment, swivel head as required and take reading from scale. Enter reading in column 2 on In-Service Check Form, add correction factor to reading, and then enter results in “Actual Dimension” space. (9) Repeat Step (8) for RP 3 thru RP 7 right, and then RP 2 thru RP 7 left, filling in form as work progresses. (10) Measure and record RPs 17, 18, 19, and 20, left and right, from lower horizontal stabilizer. Refer to Figure 202. (11) Measure and record dimension A, left and right, from RP 8 to RP 11. Refer to Figure 205. (12) Measure and record dimension B, left and right, from RP 8 to RP 9. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-50-01 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (13) Measure and record dimension C, left and right, from RP 8 to RP 1B. (14) Visually level propeller blades laterally. (15) Measure and record dimension D, left and right, from RP 1A to RP 13 and to RP 14. Refer to Figure 206. (16) Using equations, make sure all tolerances are met. Refer to Figure 201. NOTE If tolerances are not met, contact the cognizant authority. In-Service Check Form (Symmetry and Alignment) PT51E 120758AB.AI MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-00 Page 1 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES CONTROL SURFACE BALANCING 51-60-00 00000 BALANCING 1. GENERAL When installing or replacing the exterior markings (tail flashing) on the rudder, balancing of the rudder is required. Control surfaces on the aircraft which require balancing are the elevator, elevator trim tab, rudder, rudder trim tab and ailerons. Refer to Figure 1. Whenever a control surface is painted, reworked and/or modified in any way, balancing must be accomplished. The surface shall be finish-painted, including all touch up, prior to balancing. The control surface will be removed from the aircraft for balancing. Balancing of control surfaces must be completed in a draft free area. The balance requirement in inch-pounds of moment about the hinge line is given for each control surface in the applicable section. A. Balancing Procedures A balance fixture (P/N 133-384007-1) is required for balancing flight control surfaces. The flight control balance fixture consists of a rigid frame with two balance blades each mounted on top of a weldment. Refer to Figure 2. One weldment is adjustable for movement to adjust to different flight control surfaces. The 0.125-inch thick steel balance blades adjust to accommodate the different hinge points on the five types of control surfaces. The balance fixture must be leveled prior to flight control balancing. The fixture has a storage compartment for stowing equipment. The following tools and equipment are required for all control surface balancing: • Package of line or twine (50 to 200 feet in length) capable of withstanding 25 pounds minimum static load • Pin (trim tab pivot) approximately 42 inches long • Bubble level or equivalent • Minimum 5-lb bag of no. 9 chilled lead shot • Cup • Scale with current certification to National Institute of Standards and Technology Standards The fixture and equipment used will provide accuracy, and should be checked every 6 months to make sure of continued accuracy. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-00 Page 2 Jun 06/16 Figure 1 - Control Surfaces PT51E 981345AA.AI RUDDER RUDDER TRIM TAB ELEVATOR AILERON AILERON ELEVATOR TRIM TAB MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-00 Page 3 Jun 06/16 Figure 2 - Balancing Fixture PT51E 981344AA.AI BALANCE BLADE LEVELING PAD (4 PLCS) STORAGE STATIONARY WELDMENT ADJUSTABLE WELDMENT BALANCE BLADE MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-01 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES CONTROL SURFACES 51-60-01 ELEVATOR AND TRIM TAB 200200200200200 BALANCING 1. GENERAL This section covers elevator and elevator trim tab balancing checks and adjustment. A. Elevator Trim Tab Balance Procedure The static nose heavy (over balance) of the elevator trim tab assembly must balance from -0.2 inch-pounds to -0.7 inch-pounds measured mass moment forward of the hinge line. If the elevator trim tab balance is within acceptable limits, no adjustment is required. Use the following procedure to balance the elevator trim tab. Refer to Figure 201. (1) Remove elevator from aircraft. Refer toMaintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. (2) Remove trim tab from elevator. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-31-01. (3) If any repairs are to be made, complete all repairs and refinish elevator trim tab to finished configuration. Install all hardware including hinge pin as if trim tab was installed on the elevator. Do not use any temporary hardware. (4) Create level line on inboard tip of elevator trim tab. Make sure line is centered as shown in Figure 201. (5) Make sure balance fixture is level by using bubble level provided with balance fixture. Align balance blades to mate with elevator trim tab hinge pin inboard and outboard of trim tab. After alignment is made, make sure balance blades are level with each other using bubble level. (6) Mate elevator trim tab hinge pin to balance blades on balance fixture. Make sure balance blades do not contact elevator trim tab skin. (7) Connect one end of twine to top of cup. Use 2-inch piece of masking tape to fasten other end of twine to upper surface of elevator trim tab 2 inches in front of trailing edge near inboard edge. Make sure twine drapes freely over trailing edge at inboard corner of trim tab. Trailing edge at inboard corner of trim tab is +3.694 inches aft of hinge line. (8) Slowly fill cup with lead shot counterbalance weight until elevator trim tab is level. (9) Make sure elevator trim tab is level by placing bubble level close to level line created in Step (4). Make sure bubble level does not touch trim tab. (10) Remove counterbalance tape, twine, and cup of lead shot from elevator trim tab and weigh together on scale. (11) Determine if adjustment weight must be added or removed by finding counterbalance weight from Step (10) in Table 201. Add or remove adjustment weight at -3.36 and -4.29 inches forward of hinge as required. Refer to Figure 201. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-01 Page 202 Jun 06/16 NOTE Washers (P/N NAS1149F0316P) weigh 0.0005 pound each. Substitute longer grip screws (P/N MS24693), if required, to maintain a minimum of 2 full threads past the nuts. NOTE As an alternative to removing washers, drill the counterbalance (P/N 133-610028). (12) Repeat Steps (7) thru (11) until proper balancing is achieved without adding or removing adjustment weights. (13) Remove elevator trim tab from balance fixture. (14) Install trim tab on elevator. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-31-01. (15) Perform Elevator Balance Procedure. B. Elevator Balance Procedure The static nose heavy (over balance) of the elevator assembly must balance from -1.0 inch-pounds to -1.5 inch-pounds measured mass moment forward of the hinge line with the elevator trim tab in the neutral position. If the elevator balance is within acceptable limits, no adjustment is required. Use the following procedure to balance the elevator. Refer to Figure 202. (1) Remove elevator from aircraft if required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. (2) Make sure elevator trim tab has been balanced and installed. Secure in neutral position by wrapping 2-inch piece of masking tape around trailing edge if required so it spans gap between elevator and elevator trim tab. (3) If any repairs are to be made, complete all repairs and refinish elevator to finished configuration. Install all hardware including hinge bolts, static wicks, and bond straps as if elevator was installed on the aircraft. Use of temporary hardware is prohibited. (4) Install finish-painted spare elevator lower surface access panel (362FB). (5) Position elevator position sensor cable along right side directly under hinge centerline and tape in place. NOTE Locate the double row of rivets below and aft of the hinge line. The hinge line is 1.09-inches forward of the double row of rivets at the lateral centerline, and 0.97-inch forward at the middle hinge. (6) Create level line on left or right tip cap on elevator. Make sure line is centered as shown in Figure 202. (7) Make sure balance fixture is level by using bubble level provided with balance fixture. Align balance blades to mate with elevator hinge bolts. After alignment is made, make sure balance blades are level with each other using bubble level. (8) Mate elevator hinge bolts to balance blades on balance fixture. Make sure that balance blades do not contact elevator skin. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-01 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (9) Connect one end of twine to top of cup. Use 2-inch piece of masking tape to fasten other end of twine to upper surface of elevator 2 inches in front of trailing edge. Make sure twine drapes freely over elevator trailing edge at lateral centerline. Elevator trailing edge at lateral centerline is +15.507 inches aft of elevator hinge line. (10) Slowly fill cup with lead shot counterbalance weight until elevator is level. (11) Make sure elevator is level by placing bubble level close to level line created in Step (6). Make sure bubble level does not touch elevator. (12) Remove counterbalance tape, twine, and cup of lead shot from elevator and weigh together on scale. (13) Determine if adjustment weight must be added or removed by finding counterbalance weight from Step (12) in Table 202. Add or remove adjustment weights as follows: (a) Remove elevator fairing tip cap. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Stabilizers (TO 1T-6ABD-2-55), 55-20-02. (b) Add or remove adjustment weight at -4.82 inches forward of hinge as required. Refer to Figure 202. NOTE Adjustment weights (P/N 133-610025-17) weigh 0.009 pound each and weights (P/N 133-610025-19) weigh 0.069 pound each. A maximum of 13 adjustment weights (P/N 133-610025-19) may be added to each side. A maximum of one adjustment weight (P/N 133-610025-17) is advised on each side. A maximum total of 13 adjustment weights (133-610025-17 plus 133-610025-19) may be added to each side. The number of adjustment weights on the right side must be within one of the number of adjustment weights on the left side. (c) Install elevator fairing tip cap. Refer to 1T-6ABD-2-55, 55-20-02. (14) Repeat Steps (9) thru (13) until proper balancing is achieved without adding or removing adjustment weights. (15) Remove elevator from balance fixture. (16) Remove spare elevator lower surface access panel (362FB). (17) Remove tape from elevator position sensor cable and from elevator trim tab trailing edge. (18) Install elevator on aircraft. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-30-01. 51-60-02 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES CONTROL SURFACES 51-60-02 RUDDER AND TRIM TAB 200200200200200 BALANCING 1. GENERAL This section covers rudder and trim tab balancing checks and adjustment. When installing or replacing the exterior markings (tail flashing) on the rudder, balancing of the rudder is required. A. Rudder Trim Tab Balancing Procedure The static nose heavy (over balance) of the rudder trim tab assembly must balance from -1.3 inch-pounds to -1.5 inch-pounds measured mass moment forward of the hinge line. If the rudder trim tab balance is within acceptable limits, no adjustment is required. Use the following procedure to balance the rudder trim tab. Refer to Figure 201. (1) Remove rudder from aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-08. (2) Remove rudder trim tab from rudder in accordance with the following: (a) Remove screw and catch assembly which retain rudder trim tab hinge pin. (b) Support tab and remove hinge pin. (c) Remove rudder trim tab. (3) If any repairs are to be made, complete all repairs and refinish rudder trim tab to finished configuration. Install all hardware including hinge pin with screw and catch assembly as if trim tab was installed on the rudder. Do not use any temporary hardware. (4) Create level line on lower tip of rudder trim tab. Make sure line is centered as shown in Figure 201. (5) Make sure balance fixture is level by using bubble level provided with balance fixture. Align balance blades to mate with rudder trim tab hinge pin above and below upper and lower tips. After alignment is made, make sure balance blades are level with each other using bubble level. (6) Mate rudder trim tab hinge pin to balance blades on balance fixture. Make sure that balance blades do not contact rudder trim tab skin. (7) Connect one end of twine to top of cup. Use 2-inch piece of masking tape to fasten other end of twine to upper surface of rudder trim tab 2 inches in front of trailing edge. Make sure twine drapes freely over trailing edge at corner of lower tip of trim tab. Trailing edge at corner of lower tip is +4.485 inches aft of hinge line. (8) Slowly fill cup with lead shot counterbalance weight until rudder trim tab is level. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-02 Page 202 Jun 06/16 (9) Make sure rudder trim tab is level by placing bubble level close to level line created in Step (4). Make sure bubble level does not touch trim tab. (10) Remove counterbalance tape, twine, and cup of lead shot from rudder trim tab and weigh together on scale. (11) Determine if adjustment weight must be added or removed by finding counterbalance weight from Step (10) in Table 201. Add or remove adjustment weights as required. Refer to Figure 201. NOTE Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630003-31) are -4.653 inches to hinge and weigh 0.033 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630003-43) are -4.662 inches to hinge and weigh 0.066 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630003-45) are -4.201 inches to hinge and weigh 0.110 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630003-77) are -4.724 inches to hinge and weigh 0.424 pound. NOTE It is permissible to use no adjustment weights up to a maximum of eight 133-630003-31, -43, or -45 adjustment weights. However, if one 133-630003-77 adjustment weight is used, a maximum of four additional -31, -43, or -45 adjustment weights may be used. Substitute longer grip screws (P/N MS24694) if required to maintain a minimum of 2 full threads past the nuts. (12) Repeat Steps (7) thru (11) until proper balancing is achieved without adding or removing adjustment weights. (13) Remove rudder trim tab from balance fixture. (14) Install rudder trim tab on rudder in accordance with the following: (a) Align tab hinge half with rudder hinge half. (b) Install hinge pin. (c) Secure hinge pin with catch assembly and screw. (15) Perform Rudder Balance Procedure. B. Rudder Balance Procedure The static tail heavy (under balance) of the rudder assembly must balance from +3.7 inch-pounds to +4.6 inch-pounds measured mass moment aft of the hinge line with the rudder trim tab assembly in the neutral position. If the rudder balance is within acceptable limits, no adjustment is required. Use the following procedure to balance the rudder. Refer to Figure 202. (1) Remove rudder from aircraft if required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-08. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-02 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (2) Make sure rudder trim tab has been balanced and installed onto rudder. Secure rudder trim tab in neutral position by wrapping 8-inch piece of masking tape centered around rudder trim tab lower tip adjustment weight so it spans gap attaching it to both sides of rudder. (3) If any repairs are to be made, complete all repairs and refinish rudder to finished configuration. Install all hardware including rudder trim push rod and hinge bolts plus all static wicks and bond straps as if rudder was installed on aircraft. Do not use temporary hardware. Make sure rudder trim push rod is adjusted to 16.42 inches long from attach point center-to-center. (4) Create level line on bottom tip of rudder. Make sure line is centered as shown in Figure 202. (5) Make sure balance fixture is level by using bubble level provided with balance fixture. Align adjustable balance blades to mate with upper and lower rudder hinge bolts. After alignment is made, make sure balance blades are level with bubble level. (6) Mate rudder hinge bolts to balance blades on balance fixture. Make sure that balance blades do not contact rudder skin. (7) Connect one end of twine to top of cup. Use 2-inch piece of masking tape to fasten other end of twine to top side of rudder 2 inches behind leading edge. Make sure twine drapes freely over rudder balance horn leading edge at corner of lower end of rudder balance horn. Leading edge at corner of lower end of rudder balance horn is -11.822 inches in front of hinge line. (8) Slowly fill cup with lead shot counterbalance weight until rudder is level. (9) Make sure rudder is level by placing bubble level close to level line created in Step (4). Make sure bubble level does not touch rudder. (10) Remove counterbalance tape, twine, and cup of lead shot from rudder and weigh together on scale. (11) Determine if adjustment weight must be added or removed by finding counterbalance weight from Step (10) in Table 202. Add or remove adjustment weights as follows: (a) Remove mass balance horn cover. Refer to Figure 202. (b) Add or remove adjustment weights as required. NOTE Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630025-23) are -9.013 inches to hinge and weigh 1.389 pounds. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630025-25) are -8.260 inches to hinge and weigh 0.089 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630025-27) are -8.260 inches to hinge and weigh 0.021 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630025-29) are -8.528 inches to hinge and weigh 0.500 pound. Adjustment weights (P/N 133-630025-31) are -8.341 inches to hinge and weigh 0.251 pound. NOTE The maximum total weight of adjustment weights plus attaching hardware shall not exceed 10.71 pounds. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-02 Page 204 Jun 06/16 (c) Install mass balance horn cover. (12) Repeat Steps (7) thru (11) until proper balancing is achieved without adding or removing adjustment weights. (13) Remove rudder from balance fixture. (14) Remove tape from rudder trim tab. (15) Install the rudder on aircraft. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-20-08. GENERAL This section covers aileron balancing checks and adjustment. A. Balance Procedure The static nose heavy (over balance) of the aileron assembly must balance from -3.0 in-lbs to -3.5 in-lbs measured mass moment forward of the aileron hinge line with the aileron trim tab in the neutral position. If the aileron balance is within acceptable limits, no adjustment is required. Use the following procedure to balance the aileron. Refer to Figure 201. (1) Remove aileron from aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-00. NOTE For surfaces where aileron trim tab has been adjusted per TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-10-00, do not adjust aileron trim tab prior to aileron balancing. If aileron trim tab adjustment is required per 27-10-00, set trim tab at neutral position prior to aileron balancing. (2) If any repairs are to be made, complete all repairs and refinish aileron to finished configuration. Install all hardware including hinge bolts, static wicks, and bond straps as if aileron was installed on the aircraft. Do not use any temporary hardware. (3) Create level line on outboard tip of aileron passing through centerline of leading edge tool hole touching upper edge of trailing edge tool hole. Refer to Figure 201. (4) Make sure balance fixture is level by using bubble level provided with balance fixture. Align balance blades to mate with aileron inboard and outboard hinge bolts. After alignment is made, make sure balance blades are level with each other using bubble level. (5) Mate aileron hinge bolts to balance blades on balance fixture. Make sure that balance blades do not contact aileron skin. Make sure hinge bolt on inboard end rests on balance blade within 0.25 inch from aileron structure. (6) Connect one end of twine to top of cup. Use 2-inch piece of masking tape to fasten other end of twine to upper surface of aileron 2 inches in front of trailing edge. Make sure twine drapes freely over aileron trailing edge at outboard corner of aileron trim tab cove. Aileron trailing edge at outboard corner of aileron trim tab cove is 11.182 inches aft of hinge line. (7) Slowly fill cup with lead shot counterbalance weight until aileron is level. (8) Make sure aileron is level by placing bubble level close to level line created in Step (3). Make sure bubble level does not touch aileron. (9) Remove counterbalance tape, twine, and cup of lead shot from aileron and weigh together on scale. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-03 Page 202 Jun 06/16 (10) Determine if adjustment weight must be added or removed by finding counterbalance weight from Step (9) in Table 201. Add or remove adjustment weights starting at inboard positions #1 -4.280 inches, #2 -4.175 inches, #3 -4.105 inches, and #4 -4.000 inches forward of hinge, and proceeding outboard toward position #5 -3.931 inches forward of hinge as required. Install adjustment weights beginning at inboard location and proceeding outboard and use only one aluminum cover per stacking location. Refer to Figure 201. NOTE Adjustment weights (P/N 133-130009-13) weigh 0.128 pound each, and adjustment weights (P/N 133-130009-17) weigh 0.031 pound each. Substitute longer grip screws, if required, to maintain a minimum of 2 full threads past the nut plates. NOTE A total of 13 adjustment weights may be used. A maximum of 13 adjustment weights (P/ N 133-130009-13) may be used in a maximum of five stacking locations when adjustment weight (P/N 133-130009-17) is not used. When adjustment weight (P/N 133-130009-17) is used, a maximum of one weight (P/N 133-130009-17) must be placed in the most outboard location, and up to 12 additional adjustment weights (P/N 133-130009-13) may be used in a maximum of five stacking locations. Refer to Figure 201 for stacking locations and the maximum stacking order. (11) Repeat Steps (6) thru (10) until proper balancing is achieved without adding or removing adjustment weights. (12) Remove aileron from balance fixture. (13) Install aileron on aircraft. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-27, 27-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-03 Page 204 Jun 06/16 Figure 201 - Aileron Balance Procedure (Sheet 1 of 2) A PT51E 981343AC.AI DETAIL A AILERON MATED WITH FIXTURE LEVEL LINE CUP WITH LEADSHOT TOP OF AFT TOOL HOLE CENTER OF FWD TOOL HOLE MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-60-03 Page 205 Jun 06/16 Figure 201 - Aileron Balance Procedure (Sheet 2 of 2) PT51E 981342AC.AI A DETAIL A COUNTER WEIGHTS ALUMINUM COVERS FIVE STACKING LOCATIONS 2 3 4 5 1 AILERON MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-00 Page 1 Jun 01/21 STRUCTURES TYPICAL REPAIRS 51-70-00 00000 REQUIREMENTS 1. TYPICAL REPAIRS Many components of the airframe structure are similar in design and fabrication. Examples are sheet metal webs, formed structural shapes, extrusions, and bonded assemblies. Typical repairs have been compiled in this section to eliminate duplication of repair procedures under each applicable component. Repairs covered in this section are general in nature and are applicable to the type of member shown, regardless of location on the aircraft. Typical repairs should only be accomplished if specific repair instructions are not provided in the applicable chapter, section, or subject. 2. REPAIR REQUIREMENTS WARNING Prior to starting repairs in the integral fuel tank area, make sure area has been dried out and ventilated, as vapor forms an explosive mixture. CAUTION Make sure all rivet stems and waste material are removed from repair area. Damage classified as allowable or repairable damage may be repaired using typical repairs. Refer to 51-10-00. Seal all repairs made in pressurized areas and fuel cells. Refer to 51-20-20. If the repair compromises the cockpit pressurized area, a cockpit pressure check must be done. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 21-30-00. Universal head rivets should be used on internal structures. On external structures the replacement rivet must match the type of rivet removed, unless otherwise noted. When rivets are used in thin gage skin, the skin must be dimpled and not countersunk. Refer to 51-40-00 for fastener type, spacing, and edge distance. When repairs are applied to a control surface, balancing procedures must be completed. Refer to 51-60-00. NOTE Refer to NAS 523 or engineering drawing for proper identification of fasteners. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-01 Page 201 Jun 06/16 STRUCTURES TYPICAL REPAIRS 51-70-01 SKIN/STRINGER/RIB DAMAGE 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. GENERAL Minor skin panel dents, gouges, scratches, pitting and tooling marks are applicable to allowable damage limitations. Minor skin panel damage may be repaired using aerodynamic smoother if allowable damage limitations are not exceeded. Refer to 51-10-02. Skin panel repairs should be smoothed and faired to the existing contour of surrounding aircraft skins. Refer to 51-10-00. A. Blending, Smoothing, and Filling Repairs Prepare aerodynamic smoothers in accordance with manufacturer’s procedures. Make sure that all butt joints that require filling and smoothing have a minimum gap of 0.020 inch and a maximum gap of 0.150 inch. (1) Blend out gouges, scratches, pitting, and displaced material with 400-grit emery cloth (5, Table 10, 51-30-01). Do not remove material below bottom of damage being blended. (2) After scratch, gouge, or pitting damage is blended out and smoothed, accurate measurement should be made of amount of material removed or remaining material thickness to make sure that allowable damage limitations are not exceeded. Refer to 51-10-02. (3) Using 400-grit emery cloth, lightly scuff sand area to be filled. It is not necessary to remove paint if adhesion is adequate. (4) Remove contaminants from surfaces to be filled by wiping down with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01). (5) Apply chemical conversion treatment. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Allow chemical conversion coated area minimum of 10 minutes air drying time before applying filler. (7) Mask off area 0.50-inch outside area receiving filler material. (8) Firmly press aerodynamic smoother (2, Table 4, 51-30-01) into depression to eliminate air pockets. Use enough aerodynamic smoother to fair in smoothly with adjacent surfaces within masked off surfaces. (9) After aerodynamic smoother has dried thoroughly, finish by wet sanding with 400-grit aluminum-oxide abrasive paper. Smooth and fair filled repair flush to existing contour of surrounding aircraft skins. (10) Apply exterior finish coatings. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-01 Page 202 Jun 06/16 B. Minor Skin Panel Repairs Minor skin panel damage that exceeds allowable damage limitations is considered repairable or replacement damage. Refer to 51-10-00. Skin panel damage such as a puncture, crack, deep scratch, or an oil canned area not exceeding 2.50 inches in length or diameter may be repaired by fabricated patch. The fabricated patch repair must not interfere with adjacent parts or structure. (1) Cut hole of sufficient size to completely remove damaged area. (2) Deburr hole and check for any cracks or other damage in and around initial damage area. (3) Fabricate plug to fit hole. Use same alloy composition and sheet gage as original skin. Plug to hole edge clearance should range from 0.015 to 0.035 inch. (4) Fabricate doubler of same alloy composition and next sheet gage heavier than original skin. Refer to Table 201 for diameter and sheet gage limitations. (5) Place plug in hole and place doubler on inside surface of hole. Make sure plug fits flush with outer surface. Determine and drill fastener pattern to secure doubler and patch to repair hole. Space fastener holes evenly. Refer to Figure 201. (6) Secure plug and doubler to damaged area with proper type and size fasteners. C. Skin Panel with Stringer Damage Skin panel with stringer damage repairs will be accomplished using the following methods: (1) Remove damaged skin and stringer. (2) Radius all skin corners to 0.5 inch. (3) Remove five fasteners from each side of damaged area. (4) Cut and remove damaged stringer. Observe for proper edge distance on each side of section removed. Refer to Table 202 and Figure 202. CAUTION Be extremely careful not to cause more damage to skin when cutting damaged stringer. (5) Remove five additional fasteners from ends of original stringer. (6) Fabricate skin insertion of same type of material and thickness as skin. Skin-to-insertion clearance is 0.015 to 0.035 inch. (7) Fabricate stringer insertion of same material type and thickness as damaged stringer. (8) Fabricate two doublers made of same type of material as skin. The doubler must be 1.5 inches larger on all sides than damage removal hole. One doubler must overlap damage removal hole by 1.4 inches on one side for flange to be bent later. Refer to Figure 202. (9) Remove center of doubler if repair is in non-pressurized area. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-01 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (10) Joggle short doubler for stringer insertion flange. (11) Bend flange to 90° angle on long doubler. Make sure flange is long enough to maintain proper edge distance requirements when mated with stringer insertion. (12) Drill required size fastener hole in back-to-back rows through skin, doubler, and insertion. Refer to 51-40-00 for edge distance, spacing, and size requirements of fasteners. (13) Fabricate stringer insertion of same dimensions, type material, and thickness as damaged section. Length must pick up 10 fastener holes with required edge distance on each side of damage removal hole. (14) If repair is in pressurized area, spread thin layer of sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) on last five holes on each end of bottom of stringer insertions. (15) Fasten in place with temporary fasteners. (16) Prepare two stringer reinforcements that will pick-up 10 fastener holes on ends of stringer insertion. (17) Install fasteners through skin, stringer insertion, original stringer, and reinforcements. (18) Install fasteners (equally spaced to fasteners installed above) through reinforcements and stringer. (19) Install fasteners through skin and doubler of same type as installed in surrounding area. If repair is in pressurized area, spread thin layer of sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) on skin and on insertion contact side of doubler. Refer to 51-20-20. D. Cracked Rib (Nonpressurized Area) A cracked rib in a nonpressurized area will be repaired using the following procedures: (1) Stop drill all crack ends. Refer to Table 202. (2) Fabricate doubler of same material as rib, but one size greater in thickness. The doubler diameter must allow for installation of one fastener at each end of crack and two staggered rows of fasteners above and below crack. Refer to Figure 203. NOTE The doubler may be of any shape; however, square or rectangular shaped doubler corners must have a 0.5-inch radius. (3) Determine fastener size, pitch (P) and edge distance (E) requirements. Refer to Table 202. (4) Drill fastener holes through doubler and rib. (5) Install fasteners through doubler. E. Cracked Rib (Pressurized Area) A cracked rib in a pressurized area will be repaired using the following procedures: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-01 Page 204 Jun 06/16 (1) Remove damaged section. (2) Fabricate doubler of same type of material as rib, but one size greater thickness than skin. NOTE The doubler may be of any shape; however, square or rectangular shaped doubler corners must have a 0.5-inch radius. (3) Doubler must be larger than removed rib section to allow for drilling of two staggered fastener rows with proper pitch (P) and edge distance (E). Refer to Table 202 and Figure 204. (4) Drill fastener holes through doubler and rib. (5) Spread thin layer of sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) on doubler and secure in place with temporary fasteners. (6) Install fasteners through doubler and skin, and wet with sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01). GENERAL Formed section repairs cover typical repair procedures for damaged L angle, bulkhead and Z sections. A. L Angle Repairs The following angle repairs are for straight and curved L angles. NOTE This repair is not allowed on machined parts, extrusions or spars. (1) Cut and remove the damaged L angle. (2) Remove end fasteners from the original L angle (four for straight or five for curved angles). (3) Fabricate an insertion of the same material thickness and type as the original L angle. (4) Match drill the insertion to pick up the existing holes of the damaged angle. (5) Refer to Table 2 and Table 3, 51-30-02, for reinforcement thickness and bend radius. If the bend radius allows, use 2024-T3 alclad to form the reinforcement. (6) The length of the reinforcement must pick up the fasteners removed from the original L angle and the insertion. Maintain edge distance. Refer to Figure 201. (7) Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for fastener size requirements and overlap dimensions. Drill holes (eight for a straight L angle or ten for a curved L angle) through the reinforcement. Secure the reinforcement with temporary fasteners. (8) Drill eight or ten holes (same fastener size used in Step (7)), through the reinforcement, L angle, and support. (9) Remove reinforcement and debur. (10) Install fasteners (same type and size removed in Step (2)) through the support, L angle, insertion, and reinforcement. If the support is in a pressurized area, apply sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to the fasteners before installation. (11) Install fasteners in the L angle, insertion, and reinforcement. B. Bulkhead with Cracked Rib The following procedures are for repairs to bulkheads with T sections: (1) Stop drill all crack ends. Refer to Table 202, 51-70-01 and Figure 202. (2) Remove fasteners on each side of the crack in the bulkhead rib and T section. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-02 Page 202 Jun 06/16 (3) Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for reinforcement thickness and fabricate a reinforcement from the same type of material as the bulkhead. The length should allow for the proper edge distance of the ten removed fasteners. (4) Position the reinforcement against the existing bulkhead rib and match drill the reinforcement to the holes in the bulkhead rib and T section. Secure the reinforcement in place with temporary fasteners. (5) Drill an equally spaced row of fastener holes through the reinforcement and skin. Match these holes to the existing hole pattern in the bulkhead rib. Secure with temporary fasteners. (6) Drill two equally spaced rows of holes to connect the reinforcement to the bulkhead rib. (7) Install the existing type fasteners through the reinforcement, bulkhead rib, T section flange, and skin. C. Z Section (1) Primary Repairs The following steps provide a primary repair procedure for all Z sections. (a) Drill out fasteners, cut and remove damaged Z section. Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for amount of fasteners to be removed on each side of damage. (b) Prepare an insertion to replace the damaged Z section. Use the same type of material, thickness, dimensions, and hole patterns as the damaged Z section. (c) Install the insertion by fastening only the bottom holes. Use same type fasteners as original fasteners. (d) Prepare a doubler of the same type of material as the Z section. Refer to Table 2 and Table 3, 51-30-02 for material thickness and bend radius. The dimensions of the doubler should match the top portion of the Z section, leaving a 0.05-inch space at the bottom. The length must pick up the fastener holes in the insertion and original Z section. Refer to Figure 203. (e) Match the holes for the doubler with the top holes through the insertion, Z section and skin or support. Secure the doubler in position with temporary fasteners in the fastener holes. (f) Drill fastener holes in the top and bottom of the vertical portion of the Z section through the doubler, original Z section, and insertion. Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for fastener size. These holes must be spaced equally with the existing rows of fastener holes in the flanges of the Z section. Drill a staggered row of fastener holes between the upper and lower fastener holes in the vertical portion of the Z section. Refer to Figure 203. (g) Install fasteners through holes drilled in the above step. (h) Remove temporary fasteners and install permanent fasteners through the doubler, Z section and skin or support. (i) Remove temporary fasteners and install permanent fasteners through the doubler, insertion and skin or support. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-02 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (2) Alternate Z Section Repair NOTE Alternate Z section repairs may be used when the primary method can not be used due to limited space or when damage can be repaired without having to remove the Z section. (a) Cut away damaged area of Z section. (b) Remove existing fasteners (ten top and ten bottom) from the Z section. Refer to Figure 204. (c) Prepare two reinforcement angles using the same type of material as the Z section. Refer to Figure 204. Refer to Table 2 and Table 3, 51-30-02 for material thickness and bend radius. The length must pick up the existing fastener holes in the Z section. (d) Match the holes for each reinforcement with the fastener holes through Z section. Secure each reinforcement in position with temporary fasteners. (e) Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01, for fastener size and drill the required fastener holes in two staggered rows through both reinforcements and the Z section. Maintain fastener spacing and edge distance. Refer to 51-40-00. (f) Install fasteners in both reinforcements and Z section. (g) Remove temporary fasteners and install permanent fasteners through the top and bottom holes of both reinforcements, Z section and skin. GENERAL Formed section repairs include typical repair procedures for damage to flanges and channels. A. Flange Crack Repairs The following procedure will be used for repairs to cracked flanges: (1) Stop drill all crack ends. Refer to Table 202, 51-70-01. (2) For a crack that extends 1/2 of the flange width, remove four fasteners on each side of crack. For a crack that extends to the radius of the flange, remove five fasteners on each side of crack. Refer to Figure 201. (3) If the crack is less than 1/2 the width of the flange, prepare a strap of the same type of material and thickness as the flange. (4) Install fasteners (same type as existing fasteners) through the skin, flange, and strap. (5) If the crack is to flange radius, fabricate a reinforcement of the same type of material and thickness as the flange, and use the reinforcement overlap dimension stated in Table 203, 51-70-01. (6) Drill the existing fastener holes through the reinforcement, flange, and skin. (7) Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for edge distance, pitch, and fastener size requirements. Drill fastener holes. (8) Install fasteners in the reinforcement, rib flange, and skin. (9) Install fasteners in the reinforcement and rib. B. Channel Section Repairs The following procedure will be used for channel section repairs: (1) Drill out fasteners and cut away damaged area of channel. (2) Fabricate an insertion of the same thickness, type of material, dimensions, and length as the damaged portion of channel. (3) Match drill the existing size fastener holes through the insertion. (4) Install the insertion using the same type and size of existing fasteners, leaving the last four holes next to the channel open. (5) Fabricate a reinforcement from 2024-T3 alcad of size greater thickness than the damaged channel, if the bend radius will allow. Refer to Table 2 and Table 3, 51-30-02. (6) Remove four fasteners from the original channel next to the insertion. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-03 Page 202 Jun 06/16 (7) The reinforcement length must pick up the four existing fasteners through the insertion and the original channel. Refer to Figure 202. Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for edge distance, pitch and fastener requirements. (8) Drill the fastener holes through the channel, reinforcement, and insertion with four holes in the insertion flange and four in the original channel flange. Refer to Figure 202. (9) Install fasteners through the reinforcement, insertion, original channel, and skin or support. (10) Install fasteners in the original channel insertion and reinforcement flanges. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-03 Page 203 Jun 06/16 Figure 201 - Flange Crack Repairs PT51E 981105AA.AI E E E P E P C STRAP SKIN ANGLE REPAIR OF CRACK TO CENTER OF FLANGE WIDTH REPAIR OF CRACK TO EDGE OF FLANGE RADIUS LEGEND P= PITCH E= EDGE DISTANCE C= OVERLAP DIMENSION MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-03 Page 204 Jun 06/16 Figure 202 - Channel Section Repairs PT51E 981094AA.AI P E C C SKIN OR SUPPORT SKIN OR SUPPORT REINFORCEMENT REINFORCEMENT INSERTION ORIGINAL CHANNEL LEGEND P= PITCH E= EDGE DISTANCE C= OVERLAP DIMENSION MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-04 Page 201 Jun 01/21 STRUCTURES TYPICAL REPAIRS 51-70-04 WEB SECTION 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. GENERAL Web section repairs cover typical repair procedures for damage to fuselage frames and wing ribs. A. Fuselage Frame The following procedure will be used for repairs to fuselage frame: (1) Remove damaged area. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Deburr and smooth rough edges. (3) Clean area with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01). Allow to dry thoroughly. (4) Fabricate a patch of the same thickness and material as the frame. (5) Drill a fastener pattern using number 30 holes (0.128-inch diameter). Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for edge distance and pitch requirements. (6) Match drill the fastener holes to the frame. (7) Fasten the patch to the frame. (8) Clean area again and prime as needed. B. Wing Rib The following procedure will be used for wing rib repairs: NOTE Refer to 51-70-00, prior to performing any wing rib repairs in the fuel cell areas. (1) Remove damaged area. Refer to Figure 202. (2) Deburr and smooth damaged area. (3) Clean damaged area with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01). (4) Fabricate a reinforcement plate of same thickness and material as rib. (5) Drill even pattern of holes, spaced 0.75-inch apart on the reinforcement plate. Refer to Table 203, 51-70-01 for edge distance and fastener size requirements. (6) Match drill the holes to the rib, picking up the existing holes along the flange of rib. (7) Fasten the reinforcement in place. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-04 Page 202 Jun 01/21 Figure 201 - Damaged Fuselage Frame Repair PT51E 981253AA.AI FINISHED REPAIR FASTENER PATTERN FUSELAGE FRAME PATCH MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-04 Page 203 Jun 06/16 Figure 202 - Wing Rib Repair PT51E 981254AA.AI REINFORCEMENT PLATE CLEAN DAMAGED AREA ORIGINAL DAMAGED WEB AREA MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-05 Page 201 Jun 01/21 STRUCTURES TYPICAL REPAIRS 51-70-05 BONDED PANEL 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. GENERAL A honeycomb or laminated structural part (bonded panel) is a sandwich type construction which, in the most simple form, is two relatively thin sheets of structural material bonded to a thick, lightweight core. The function of the center layer, or core, is to hold the other layers apart and provide stiffness to prevent the layers from becoming elastically unstable under high stress loads. Honeycomb areas should be inspected routinely for poor bonds and voids. Two methods are used to reveal core damage. In one method, a coin is tapped lightly on the surface. A well bonded area produces a sharp, metallic ring, while a poorly bonded area produces a dull thud. Another method uses ultrasonic testing to detect damage. If any defect is suspected and found, the following repair methods will be used. A. Honeycomb Scratch and Dent Repair When repairing scratches and dents in honeycomb areas, limit the number of dents to no more than five dents in any 3 square-inch area. Limit dents and scratches to no more than 5 percent of surface area. Limit dent and scratch sizes to 0.5 inch in diameter and depth to no more than 0.065 inch. No voids are allowed under depressed skin. Refer to Figure 201. (1) Lightly roughen area with 400-grit emery cloth (5, Table 10, 51-30-01). (2) Clean area with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01) and air dry thoroughly. Follow with second solvent and clean rag. Wipe with separate clean rag. (3) Apply adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01) smoothly until adhesive is flush with surface. Allow adhesive to cure to manufacturer’s specifications. (4) Smooth repair to match surrounding area using 400-grit emery cloth (5, Table 10, 51-30-01). B. Honeycomb Core and One Skin Repair When repairing the core of honeycomb, limit voids between skin and core to less than 5 percent of the surface area, with no void to exceed 1.5 square inches. Location of voids are limited to a minimum of 3 inches from any major structural area. (1) Clean surface with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01). Allow to dry. (2) Drill two No. 50 (0.0070) diameter holes through face of sheet and into void. Maintain 0.60-inch minimum spacing. (3) Inject adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01) into void. Do not use more than 1.5 cc of adhesive per square inch of void. Inject adhesive smoothly until adhesive is flush with outer surface. (4) Clamp surface in flat position and allow adhesive to cure to manufacturer’s specification. (5) Clean and smooth repaired area to match surrounding area. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-05 Page 202 Jun 01/21 C. Honeycomb Aerodynamic Surface Repair When repairing damage to surfaces that require aerodynamic contour tolerances to be maintained, use the following procedure. Refer to 51-10-01 for aerodynamic contour tolerances. (1) Counter bore area to diameter which is sufficient to remove all skin and core damage. Go through only first layer of skin and core. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Fill hole with adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01) until adhesive is flush with surface. Allow adhesive to cure. More adhesive may be required later before applying doubler to prevent void between fix and doubler. (3) Fabricate patch from material of same type and thickness as original skin. Overlap damage by 1 inch. Bevel edges of non-faying side. (4) Roughen faying surfaces of bonded parts with 400-grit emery cloth (5, Table 10, 51-30-01). (5) Clean surfaces with solvent (3, Table 1, 51-30-01) to remove any sanding residue and primer. Follow up with second solvent and clean rag cleaning. (6) Bond patch in place with adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01) and apply 10 psi bond pressure to make sure patch stays in place. Use one or two layers of scrim cloth (9, Table 10, 51-30-01) on bond line. If skin is not smooth, nest patch so that patch is compactly fitted into skin. (7) Allow adhesive to cure to manufacturer’s specifications. (8) Prime and paint to match surrounding area. 2. COIN AND SONIC TAP TESTS Coin and sonic tap test methods consist of lightly tapping part of a surface with a tap hammer. Acoustic response is compared with a known good area. These test are limited to finding relative shallow defects on skins with a thickness of less than 0.032 inches. In honeycomb structure, far side bond line cannot be evaluated from near side surface. Thus, access to both sides is required for a complete inspection of honeycomb structures. It should be noted that knowledge of internal geometry and composition of a part is critical to interpretation of acoustic response, as response of a good part can change dramatically with changes in geometry and composition. Coin and sonic tap tests may be used as a quick evaluation of any accessible aircraft surface to detect presence of delamination or unbond and should be utilized during assessment of indications found during visual inspections to determine if further investigation by machine is required. Sonic Tap Test is the most applicable method to be utilized for the inspection of bevels and/or closeout surfaces and may be the sole method for accessing and determining extent of damage and/or acceptance of such areas. A. Coin Tap Test (1) Using a coin, such as a quarter, tap lightly on the required surfaces to detect any areas where bond is not complete. A well bonded area produces a sharp, metallic ring, while an unbonded area produces a dull thud. B. Sonic Tap Test (1) Preparation: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-05 Page 203 Jun 01/21 NOTE Sonic tap test can be performed over painted surfaces if the paint is uniform and adhered to the part’s surface. Take into consideration the affect paint, surfaces, and fillers may have on acoustics response. (a) All surfaces to be inspected must be dry and free of contaminates (such as oil, grease, loose paint, or dirt). Contaminates will inhibit a suitable condition for sonic tap test inspection to be performed. (b) Visual inspection shall be performed for gouges, low areas, raised areas and any irregularities on the surface indicating possible damage. Such items shall be noted for use during interpretation of the sonic test tap. (c) Sonic tap test shall be performed in an area sufficiently free from noises. Noisy areas will interfere with interpretation of acoustic response. Sound level shall be measured and must not exceed 80dB. (2) Equipment: Sonic Tap Hammer (P/N TS1469) or equivalent. Maximum weight of 1.5 ounces. Refer to Figure 202. (3) Test Procedure: (a) Lightly tap surface of part with a constant tap rate, so a consistent sound is produced in order that a difference in sound tone can be detected. The entire area to be inspected must be tapped 100% using a 0.25 inch by 0.25 inch tapping grid. (4) Indication Evaluation: (a) Compare the acoustic response to that of a known good area. (b) A “flat” or “dead” response is indicative of a delamination or unbond which may require further evaluation by other NDI ultrasonic inspection methods. Inspect area if it cannot be proven to be caused by geometry or inherent manufacture characteristics, such as areas containing potting or an area that has a structure/component bonded on the opposite face of sheet which would absorb acoustic response. (5) Procedure: (a) Mark any delamination or unbond and record findings. (b) Contact cognizant authority to report location and size of damage.
