GENERAL The instrument panel repair section covers typical repair procedures for instrument panel and component cutouts. A. EFIS Cutouts (T-6A Only) The following procedure will be used to rework the EFIS control panel cutouts in the instrument panel. Refer to Figure 201. CAUTION Protect adjacent areas and equipment around EFIS cutouts to prevent FOD. Operate vacuum in area being worked while removing material. (1) Use small flat fine file to remove material evenly from all four sides of cutout until indicator slides freely through cutout. Do not exceed overall inside dimension of 5.05 inches. Do not file corner areas. (2) Treat bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). B. EID Cutouts (T-6A Only) The following procedure will be used to rework the EID display panel cutouts in the instrument panel. Refer to Figure 202. CAUTION Protect adjacent areas and equipment around EID cutouts to prevent FOD. Operate vacuum in area being worked while removing material. (1) Use small flat fine file to remove material evenly from all four sides of cutout until indicator slides freely through cutout. Do not exceed overall inside dimension of 3.22 inches. Do not file corner areas. (2) Treat bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-06 Page 202 Jun 01/21 C. RMU Cutouts (T-6A Only) The following procedure will be used to rework the RMU cutouts in the instrument panel. Refer to Figure 203. CAUTION Protect adjacent areas and equipment around RMU cutouts to prevent FOD. Operate vacuum in area being worked while removing material. (1) Use small flat fine file to remove material evenly from all four sides of cutout until RMU slides freely through cutout. Do not exceed overall inside dimension of 2.42 inches by 5.96 inches. Only if necessary, remove material from chamfered corners so edge distance from center of mounting hole to chamfered edge is 0.170 inch. (2) Treat bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). D. Press Nut Repair NOTE The Press Nut Repair procedure only applies to loose or missing press nuts (P/N MRPN4-40SCL or MRPN6-32SCL). Do not oversize press nut (P/N MRPN4-40SCL) to a larger size press nut (P/N MRPN6-32SCL). NOTE For press nut (P/N MRPN4-40SCL), hole diameter is not to exceed 0.156-0.161 inch. If hole diameter is greater than 0.161 inch, the Nut Plate Repair procedure must be performed. NOTE For press nut (P/N MRPN6-32SCL), hole diameter is not to exceed 0.187-0.191 inch. If hole diameter is greater than 0.191 inch, the Nut Plate Repair procedure must be performed. (1) Measure and make sure press nut (P/N MRPN4-40SCL) mounting hole diameter is within 0.156-0.161 inch, or press nut (P/N MRPN6-32SCL) mounting hole diameter is within 0.187-0.191 inch. (2) Using solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), clean backside of instrument panel around hole to be bonded. Allow to air dry. If solvent alone cannot clean surface area due to debris, it is permissible to sand or polish surface using 320 grit sandpaper or finer (31, Table 10, 51-30-01). If area is sanded, clean area with solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01) and allow to air dry. Refer to Figure 204, Sheet 1 of 3. (3) Using solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), clean new press nut mating surface and allow to air dry. (4) Apply cold bond adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01) , to mating surface of new press nut where it engages instrument panel. Position press nut in place by maneuvering grooves/gouges on press nut to match grooves/gouges on backside of instrument panel. Hold press nut in position. Refer to Figure 204, Sheet 2 of 3). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-06 Page 203 Jun 06/16 (5) Apply petrolatum (32, Table 10, 51-30-01) to press nut threads and draw Cleco shaft. (6) Place washer on draw Cleco. Carefully insert draw Cleco and washer through hole in instrument panel and through press nut. Washer must be positioned between draw Cleco and instrument panel. Refer to Figure 204, Sheet 3 of 3. (7) Draw Cleco down until all parts are secure. (8) Allow adhesive to cure. After adhesive is cured, remove draw Cleco and washer. E. Nut Plate Repair (1) Measure and make sure forward or aft instrument panel mounting hole diameter is greater than 0.161-0.191 inch. Refer to Figure 205. (2) Clean mounting holes in instrument panel. NOTE Prior to securing nutplate to backside of instrument panel, make sure clearance exists between nutplate and instrument. (3) Temporarily install instrument onto instrument panel with screw (33, Table 10, 51-30-01) through enlarged hole location. Install nut plate (34, Table 10, 51-30-01), or equivalent nut plate, on back side of panel. (4) Make sure clearance exists between nut plate and instrument. NOTE It is permissible to slightly sand or blend head of nut plate until sufficient clearance between nut plate and instrument is obtained. (5) If nut plate interferes with instrument, place nut plate in best position possible for installation and mark location. Mark location of sanding required on nut plate. Sand or blend head of nut plate until clearance is sufficient. Do not sand or blend more than 0.015-0.020 inch from head of nut plate. Apply brush cad plate to 0.005 inch thick maximum, per MIL-STD-865, or apply wash primer (5, Table 3, 51-30-01), to protect all bare metal on nut plate. (6) With clearance present between instrument and nutplate, position nut plate in best position possible. Drill rivet holes to 0.096-0.101 inch diameter, and countersink holes 100°X0.036 inch deep. Maintain minimum edge distance of 2 times rivet diameter plus 0.05 inch for nut plate rivets. (7) Prior to nut plate installation, clean area surface with solvent (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Allow to air dry. (8) Install nut plate (34, Table 10, 51-30-01) using two rivets (35, Table 10, 51-30-01). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 51-70-06 Page 204 Jun 06/16 F. Flap Switch Connector Bracket Cutout The following procedure will be used to rework the flap switch connector bracket cutout located on the wing aft spar. Refer to Figure 206. CAUTION Protect adjacent areas and equipment around flap switch connector bracket cutout to prevent FOD. Operate vacuum in area being worked while removing material. (1) Use small flat fine file to remove material evenly around cutout until connector slides freely into the cutout. Maintain edge distance on mounting holes to connector hole. Maximum allowable connector hole diameter is 1.187 inch. (2) Treat bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. GENERAL This chapter contains information and structural part breakdowns applicable to baggage doors, service access doors, and landing gear doors. Refer to Figure 00-01. The chapter consists of three sections: • Baggage door: Refer to Section 52-30-00. • Service access doors: Doors which provide access to avionics, single point refueling, maintenance servicing, air conditioning, and hydraulics. Refer to Section 52-40-00. • Landing gear retractable doors: Nose landing gear, inner main landing gear, and outer main landing gear doors. Refer to Section 52-80-00. Specific structural inspections, damage limitations, and repair criteria applicable to doors are contained in this chapter. 2. INSPECTION Doors are inspected for dents, cracks, misalignment, corrosion, and delamination, on a regularly scheduled basis, in accordance with the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-6). Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of damage. Refer to 51-10-00. STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to the baggage door. Each part called out in the baggage door figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed in the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-30-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 DOORS BAGGAGE 52-30-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in sheet metal skins of the baggage door, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. If damage has affected baggage door aerodynamic fit, closure, leak proof sealing, or edge gap clearance, the damage should be classified as repairable or replacement damage. Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified but should be such as to avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-30-00 Page 201 Jun 29/20 DOORS BAGGAGE 52-30-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural and skin repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-02. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure, Typical repairs are permanent and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the door. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. Whether repair or replacement is required, the baggage door should be fitted and trimmed to ensure unrestricted closing, leak proof sealing, and appropriate edge gap clearance. The door should be flush to maintain aerodynamic surface smoothness and to minimize air and moisture leakage. Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified but should be such as to avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. A. Baggage Door (P/N 133-440029-113) Latch Replacement (After TCTO 1T-6A-856) NOTE This installation procedure applies to baggage door (P/N 133-440029-113) with upgraded latches (P/N S4534-3). NOTE Permissible to replace latches with baggage door remaining on aircraft. (1) Open and secure baggage door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Doors (TO 1T-6ABD-2-52), 52-30-02. (2) Remove rivets securing latch to door. Refer to Structural Repair Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-3), 51-40-00. If performing this step on aircraft, take necessary precautions to protect installed equipment from drilling operation. Refer to Figure 201. (3) Remove latch from door. NOTE Permissible to reuse doublers (P/N 133-440127-0001) on outside of baggage door if they are serviceable and not damaged. (4) Inspect doubler for condition. (5) As required, remove and replace damaged doubler on outside of baggage door. If doubler condition is serviceable, proceed to Step (6). (a) Carefully remove doubler from door. (b) Remove residual adhesive from exterior surface areas. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-30-00 Page 202 Jun 29/20 (c) Use clean lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01), moistened with alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), to clean exterior surface areas. (d) Clamp new doubler to door. Door latch and doubler edge distance to be 0.190 inch. Refer to Figure 201, (Sheet 2). Using appropriate size drill bit, drill 0.128 - 0.133 inch holes through doubler using existing holes in door. (e) Remove clamp and doubler from door. (f) Position and temporarily secure doubler and latch to door. (g) Operate latch and make sure latch operates freely and color yellow is visible in open position. NOTE Permissible to trim doublers to match existing door if latch does not operate freely. Maintain 0.190 inch minimum latch and doubler edge distance. Refer to Figure 201, (Sheet 2). (h) Using appropriate size drill bit, drill 0.128 - 0.133 inch holes through latchusing existing holes in door. (i) Apply masking tape to create top and side borders adjacent to doubler. (j) Remove latch and doubler from door. (k) Use appropriate tool to remove paint from inside border region. (l) Dress affected areas with sandpaper (30, Table 10, 51-30-01). (m) Use clean lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01), moistened with alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), to clean affected surface areas. (n) Apply alodine (1, Table 2, 51-30-01) and primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to affected surface areas. (o) Faying surface seal doubler to door with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (6) Faying surface seal new latch (P/N S4534-3) on baggage door with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (7) Install fasteners (P/N 132369AD4-4) wet with sealant Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (8) Check latches to make sure they engage and function correctly. (9) Apply two coats polyamide epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to fasteners and any exposed metal. (10) Apply two coats of paint to fasteners and any exposed metal to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (11) Close baggage door. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-30-00 Page 203 Jun 29/20 B. Baggage Door (P/N 133-440029-181) Latch Replacement NOTE This maintenance procedure applies to baggage door (P/N 133-440029-181) with upgraded latches (P/N S4534-3) installed. NOTE Permissible to replace latches with baggage door remaining on aircraft. (1) Open and secure baggage door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Doors (TO 1T-6ABD-2-52), 52-30-02. (2) Remove rivets securing latch to baggage door. Refer to 51-40-00. If performing this step on aircraft, take necessary precautions to protect installed equipment from drilling operation. Refer to Figure 202. (3) Remove latch from baggage door. (4) Remove residual sealant from baggage door surface areas. (5) Position and temporarily secure latch on door. Make sure latch operates freely. (6) Using appropriate size drill bit, drill 0.128 - 0.133 inch holes through latch using existing holes in door. (7) Remove latch from door. (8) Faying surface seal new latch (P/N S4534-3) on baggage door with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (9) Install fasteners (P/N 132369AD4-4) wet with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01).Refer to 51-20-20. (10) Check latches to make sure they engage and function correctly. (11) Apply two coats polyamide epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to fasteners and any exposed metal. (12) Apply two coats of paint to fasteners and any exposed metal to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (13) Close baggage door and engage latches. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to service access doors. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in sheet metal skins of service access doors, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. If damage has affected service access door aerodynamic fit, closure, leak proof sealing, or edge gap clearance, the damage should be classified as repairable or replacement damage. Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified but should be such as to avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. A. Speed Brake Outer Mold Line (OML) Skin Panel Limitations This repair can be used on all speed brake assemblies (P/N 133-100401). Refer to Figure 101.  No cracks are allowed in any details except for damage areas as defined in Figure 206 and Figure 207.  Only one repair area at a time shall be worked to completion before another area is started. (1) For OML skin panel (P/N 133-100405-3):  Damage is allowed in the shaded area as shown in Figure 206.  Damage shall not extend past the shaded area, if damage extends past the shaded area contact cognizant authority before continuing with this standard repair for evaluation or replace the damaged detail with a new or serviceable detail/assembly.  If the remaining material thickness is 0.035 inch or greater proceed with Paragraph 1.E. speed brake outer mold line (OML) skin panel, minor damage repair.  If the remaining material thickness is greater than 0.025 inch, but less than 0.035 inch, then proceed to Paragraph 1.F. Speed brake skin panel OML, major damage repair (doubler only).  If the remaining thickness is less than 0.025 inch proceed with Paragraph 1.G. speed brake skin panel OML, major damage, trim out and repair or contact cognizant authority.  OML skin panel repair doublers shall not be closer than 0.50 inch from each other, if less than 0.50 inch both repair doublers in affected areas must be removed and replaced with one adjoining repair doubler. (2) For the Rib (P/N 133-100403-7):  Cracks in the outboard/inboard edge of rib at the flange tangent radius, repair with Paragraph 1.H. speed brake lower flange rib repair. Refer to Figure 207 (Sheet 1 of 3). NOTE Cracks shall not exceed 0.90 inches and repair shall not remove more than one fastener on inboard end and one fastener on outboard end.  Cracks at the inboard and outboard ends simultaneously, repair with Paragraph 1.H. speed brake lower flange rib repair. Refer to Figure 207 (Sheet 1 of 3). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-40-00 Page 102 Jun 01/21 NOTE If cracks develop on each end simultaneously, cracks shall not exceed 0.90 inch and repair shall not remove more than one fastener on inboard end and one fastener on outboard end.  Cracks shall not be longer than a maximum 1.75 inches from the end of the rib to remove two fasteners, simultaneously. Repair with Paragraph 1.H. speed brake lower flange rib repair. Refer to Figure 207 (Sheet 2 of 3). NOTE If two fasteners are removed on one end simultaneously, no cracks shall be allowed on the opposite end.  If cracks develop past 1.75 inches cut out maximum allowance, the rib must be repaired with a complete flange repair. Refer to Paragraph 1.H. speed brake lower flange rib repair and Figure 207 (Sheet 3 of 3). (3) If damage is found beyond the limits of any repair, contact cognizant authority before continuing with this standard repair for evaluation or replace the damaged detail with a new or serviceable assembly. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural and skin repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-02. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity of the door. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. Whether repair or replacement is required, the service access doors should be fitted and trimmed to ensure unrestricted closing, leak proof sealing, and appropriate edge gap clearance. The door should be flush to maintain aerodynamic surface smoothness and to minimize air and moisture leakage. Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified but should be required to avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. A. Forward Access Door Repair (1) Drill 0.312-0.316 inch diameter drain hole in reinforcement. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Treat bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). (3) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) over alodine-treated area. B. Hydraulic Service Door Latch and Fuselage Catch Installation NOTE Install all rivets wet using sealant (7, Table 7, 51-30-01). (1) Verify which latch is installed in top center position. If door latch is (Item 6 with catch P/N 133-440029-145), proceed to Step (3). If door latch is (Item 6 without catch P/N 133-440029-89), continue with Step (2). Refer to Figure 202 and 52-40-02. NOTE Do not remove either of two side latches. (2) Remove latch (Item 6, P/N 133-440029-89) from top center position of hydraulic service door, continue with Step (4). (3) Install latch (Item 6, P/N 133-440029-145) in top center position of hydraulic service door and secure with four rivets (P/N NAS1097AD4). (4) Extend speed brake and install collar. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-60-01. (5) Drill out three top center rivets (adjacent to upper latch) in hydraulic service door opening structure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-40-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (6) Touch countersink back side of top center hole. Install one rivet (P/N MS20470AD4) in middle of drilled out rivets. Make sure butt is flush on inside of structure. (7) Close and latch hydraulic service door and make sure door is pushed up tight to door opening. (8) Temporarily mark where upper edge of latch finger is located to help position fuselage catch (Item 7, P/N 133-440029-147). Refer to Figure 202 and 52-40-02. (9) Unlatch and open hydraulic service door. (10) Position fuselage catch and clamp in place so that edge of fuselage catch is no more than 0.09-inch below temporary mark made in Step (8). Refer to Figure 203. (11) Drill and deburr two rivet holes to a diameter of 0.128/0.133 inch in fuselage catch. (12) Install fuselage catch with two rivets (MS20470AD4), wet with sealant (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). (13) Touch up paint with primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (14) Remove locking collar, as required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 27-60-03. If speed brake has been disconnected, reconnect speed brake to actuator. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 27-60-01. (15) Retract speed brake. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 27-60-01. C. Hydraulic Service Door Mating Surface Modification NOTE Do not cut notches or drill rivet holes at this time. (1) Use 0.063 inch thick sheet metal (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) per AMS 4025 or AMS-QQ-A-250/11 to locally manufacture doublers. Refer Figure 204. (2) Form doublers to fit fuselage inner mold line contour. (3) Locate and mark forward and aft latch locations. Make sure upper latch keeper fully engages fuselage catch installation. Refer to Section B. Mark locations for notches and rivet holes. (4) Cut notch and break sharp edges on doublers. (5) Apply alodine (1, Table 2, 51-30-01) to surfaces and all perimeter edges of forward and aft doublers. (6) Apply one coat of paint primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to surfaces and all perimeter edges of forward and aft doublers. NOTE Allow paint to completely dry prior to proceeding. (7) Align doublers with hydraulic service door. Match drill rivet holes from existing aircraft hole pattern. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-40-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 CAUTION Damage to the wiring harness and electrical system may result if chaffing occurs due to insufficient clearance between aft doubler and wire harness. If clearance cannot be obtained, it is permissible to not install aft doubler. (8) Make sure clearance between aft doubler and wire harness exists. (9) Apply faying surface sealant (2, Table 7, 51-30-01) to unpainted surface of forward and aft doublers. (10) Position doublers onto hydraulic service door land area inside fuselage. Install fasteners (P/N MS20470AD4), wet with sealant (2, Table 7, 51-30-01), utilizing existing rivet locations. Maintain minimum 1.5-inch edge distance on doubler. (11) Paint outer surface of doublers to match hydraulic service door color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, 20-20-00, and 20-50-00, Table 2. D. Avionics Door Latch Replacement (After TCTO 1T-6A-856) NOTE This installation procedure applies to left avionics door, with Kit (P/N 133-4045-0003) incorporated, and right avionics door, with Kit (P/N 133-4045-0004) incorporated, and upgraded latches (P/N S4534-3) installed. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-40-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 (d) Clamp new doubler to door. Using appropriate size drill bit, drill 0.128 - 0.133 inch holes through doubler using existing holes in door. (e) Remove clamp and doubler from door. NOTE Permissible to trim doublers to match existing door if latch does not operate freely. Door latch and doubler edge distance to be 0.190 inch. Refer to Figure 205, Sheet 2. Protect bare metal in accordance with Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (m) Use clean lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01), moistened with alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), to clean affected surface areas. (n) Apply alodine (1, Table 2, 51-30-01) and primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to affected surface areas. (o) Faying surface seal doubler to door with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (6) Faying surface seal new latch (P/N S4534-3) on avionics door with sealant, Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (7) Install fasteners (P/N 132369AD4-4) wet with sealant Type 2, Class B (2, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-20. (8) Check latches to make sure they engage and function correctly. (9) Apply two coats polyamide epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to fasteners and any exposed metal. (10) Apply two coats of paint to fasteners and any exposed metal to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (11) As required, close left and right avionics doors. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-40-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 E. Speed Brake Outer Mold Line (OML) Skin Panel, Minor Damage Repair Damage to speed brake OML skin panel can be repaired if limitations are not exceeded. Refer to Allowable Damage, Speed Brake Outer Mold Line (OML) Skin Panel Limitations. Repair damage as follows: NOTE Review this procedure in its entirety and verify access to perform repair and install fasteners as stated. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment before continuing with this repair. (1) Locally blend and polish smooth, removing minimum amount of material necessary to clear all damage and achieve a smooth profile: (a) Maintain 5:1 minimum blend slope lengthwise/longitudinally, and 63 RMS or better surface finish. Do not exceed 0.015 inch blend depths, remaining material thickness must be 0.035 inch minimum. 1 If less than 0.035 inch remaining material thickness, proceed to speed brake OML skin panel (doubler only), major damage repair procedure. 2 If greater than 0.035 inch is remaining material thickness, proceed to Step (2). (2) Inspect speed brake OML skin panel for cracks and to make sure no damage remains using one of the following methods: (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method "D"), sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (3) Apply Alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (4) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (5) Apply one coat of topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (6) Install anti-chafe tape (35, Table 1, 51-30-01) after topcoat, as required to any removed area. Refer to Figure 206. (7) Assemble, as required. (8) Install speed brake. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-60-01. (9) Perform speed brake Extending and Retracting procedure. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 27-60-01. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to landing gear doors. Each part called out in a landing gear doors figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 101 Jun 01/21 DOORS LANDING GEAR 52-80-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Minor defects in sheet metal skins of landing gear doors, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. Landing gear doors are manufactured as a bonded panel assembly. Any damage beyond minor skin defects may affect the structural integrity of the bond assembly. If damage has affected landing gear door bonded structure, aerodynamic fit, closure, or edge gap clearance, the damage should be classified as repairable or replacement damage. Refer to 51-70-00. All doors should be flush to maintain aerodynamic surface smoothness and to minimize air and moisture leakage. A. Landing Gear Door Limitations NOTE In the technical data provided below, a (+) sign is used in reference to a forward facing mismatch, and a (-) sign is used in reference to an aft facing mismatch. NOTE Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified; however, clearances should avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. The maximum allowable mismatch (height of the door edge above the original contour) and edge gap clearance for nose landing gear doors are as follows. Refer to Figure 101.  Forward end of nose landing gear doors maximum mismatch tolerance is +0.120 inch. Elsewhere maximum mismatch tolerance is +0.025 inch and -0.055 inch. An additional allowance of 0.020 inch is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  The maximum allowable mismatch (height of the door edge above the original contour) and edge gap clearance for main landing gear (MLG) doors are as follows. Refer to Figure 102.  Door-to-door maximum mismatch tolerance is +0.055 inch.  Maximum gap for nose landing gear forward end of doors is 0.200 inch.  Maximum gap for outboard sides of doors adjacent to cowling is 0.180 inch. An additional allowance of +0.020 inch for gap is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  Maximum gap between doors is 0.120-inch maximum. An additional allowance of +0.030 inch is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  Maximum gap for aft end of doors is 0.200 inch.  Maximum mismatch for forward edge of inboard door and spar along corner doubler (aircraft PT-4 thru PT-49) and spar along doubler on forward edge of door (aircraft PT-50 and after) tolerance is +0.250 inch.  Maximum mismatch for aft and inboard edges of inboard door tolerance is +0.125 inch.  Maximum mismatch for forward and outboard edges of outboard door and spar tolerance is +0.125 inch. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 102 Jun 01/21  Maximum mismatch for aft edge of outboard door tolerance is +0.125 inch.  Maximum mismatch for door-to-door tolerance is +0.055 inch. An additional allowance of +0.020 inch is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  Allowable gap for inboard MLG doors, inboard edge of door (hinge end), is 0.250-inch minimum and 0.370-inch maximum.  Maximum gap for inboard MLG doors, other than inboard edge, is 0.150 inch. An additional allowance of +0.050 inch is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  Allowable gap for outboard MLG doors, outboard edge of door (hinge end), is 0.125-inch minimum and 0.320-inch maximum. Allowable gap for forward outboard corners is 0.06-inch minimum.  Maximum gap for outboard MLG doors, other than outboard edge, is 0.150 inch. An additional allowance of +0.050 inch is permitted for up to 20% of door length.  Minimum edge gap clearances are not specified but should be such as to avoid impaired closure and fretting edges. B. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Crack Limitations  Inspect inboard door for cracks. Figure 103 and Figure 104 illustrate locations of the cracks and crack limitations.  If cracks do not exceed limits in Figure 103 and Figure 104, the door may be repaired.  If cracks exceed limitations in Figure 103, the door must be replaced.  A crack in the location illustrated in Figure 104 may be any length up to the limits of the crack area.  If cracks progress forward or inboard of the formed radius, or past the noted rivet locations illustrated in Figure 104, contact cognizant authority for further analysis/assessment or replace door. C. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Inner Skin Crack Limitations  Inspect left and right inboard main landing gear doors inner skin for cracks.  Cracks and limitations are broken down into zones. Refer to Figure 201.  Only repair one zone at a time. Work shall be completed before another zone is started.  Inner skin shall not be removed and replaced in the field. Skin removal and replacement without tooling and jigs will result in a loss of contour causing main landing gear door to become unusable.  No cracks are allowed beyond cutout areas. Refer to Figure 201.  Doublers shall not be closer than 0.50 inch from each other; if less than 0.50-inch between doublers in affected area, remove and replace with an adjoining repair doubler.  If repair doublers develop cracks as defined by Figure 201, repair doubler cracks can be repaired in accordance with 52-80-00, Figure 201. If cracks in repair doublers exceed limitations in Figure 201, replace doublers. D. Main Landing Gear Outboard Doors Push Rod Pin Limitations This repair is used for the pushrod pin (P/N 133-100711-1/-3) that connects the pushrod to the MLG outboard door. The pin may become loose from the retaining adhesive, and/or loose in the door.  This repair may be used on left door, right door, or on both doors, simultaneously. Refer to Figure 105. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 103 Jun 01/21  No cracks, dis-bond, delamination allowed in underlying structure or block.  Hole shall not exceed 0.416 inch maximum diameter.  If hole exceeds 0.416 inch contact cognizant authority for evaluation before proceeding with repair. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural and skin repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-02. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the door. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. Whether repair or replacement is required, landing gear doors should be fitted and trimmed to ensure unrestricted closing and appropriate edge gap clearance. All doors should be flush to maintain aerodynamic surface smoothness and to minimize air and moisture leakage. A. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Crack Repair Cracks in main landing gear inboard door can be repaired if crack limitations in Figure 103 are not exceeded. Repair cracks in accordance with the following: (1) Stop drill crack end. Crack may be stop drilled multiple times if crack length does not exceed limitation. (2) If any crack exceeds limitations, main landing gear inboard door must be replaced. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (3) If any crack progresses forward or inboard of formed radius, or past noted rivet locations illustrated in Figure 104, contact cognizant authority for further analysis/assessment or replace main landing gear inboard door. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-32, 32-10-06. B. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Pre-Warp (1) The inboard door is preloaded on the aft edge opposite of the actuator so that it does not gap under air loads. When inboard door is manually pushed to the closed position, an approximate gap of 0.7 to 1.3 inches or more at the forward edge is normal when resistance is felt. C. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Inner Skin Crack Repair (1) As required, Remove Main Landing Gear Inboard Door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (2) Cracks in main landing gear inboard door inner skin can be repaired if crack limitations in Figure 104 are not exceeded. Repair cracks in accordance with the following: (a) Carefully dis-assemble, de-rivet, or remove structure, as required. Take care not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and underlying structures. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (b) If repair is in Zone 1, refer to Figure 201, Sheet 1, remove door spring housing. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-08. Retain for re-installation after repairing is complete. (3) Locate and mark end of cracks using one of the following methods: (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection, refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method "C" Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Carefully cut out cracks on the inner skin as shown in appropriate Zone locations, removing minimum material necessary and taking care not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. Refer to Figure 201, Sheets 1 thru 6. Trim minimum 0.10 inch beyond end of cracks. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on existing fasteners and maintain radius as shown. (5) Deburr all sharp edges. (6) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of the following methods to make sure no cracks have formed in repair area. Report any adverse results to cognizant authority prior to continuing with repair: (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection, refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method "C" Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. NOTE If cracks develop in inner skin outside the shown cutout area, refer to Figure 201, (Zone 1) Sheet 1, (Zone 2) Sheet 2, or (Zone 6) Sheet 6, the inner skin is beyond repair and must be replaced with a new or serviceable skin. NOTE If cracks develop in inner skin outside the shown cutout area, refer to Figure 201, (Zone 3) Sheet 3, (Zone 4) Sheet 4, or (Zone 5) Sheet 5, it is permissible to move the cutout area as required, maintain the minimum 0.50 inch at edge as shown. (7) As required for each zone or zones: (a) As required, make new repair doublers (P/N SR-TS-ATA52-22131-1/-2/-3/-4/-5/-6), as shown in Figure 201, Sheets 1 thru 6. Make from one of the following methods: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 1 Use 0.032-inch Sheet metal (44, Table 10, 51-30-01) per SAE AMS-QQ-A-250/5. Form to nest into existing skin. Minimum bend radius 0.12 inch. Heat treat to T42 per SAE AMS2770 after forming. 2 Make from a newly procured (P/N 133-100705-5/-6/-7/-8) Inner Skin. (8) Drill for all new and existing fastener locations as shown in Figure 201 and Table 201 (Fasteners Refer to 51-40-00 through 51-40-08, as required. Maintain 4D to 6D spacing on all new fasteners (measured from center to center) and 2D minimum edge distance on all fasteners (measured from center of hole to edge of part). (9) Deburr all sharp edges. (10) Clean repair surfaces. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (11) Apply alodine type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (12) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (13) Install repair parts in place using cold bond adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01) mixed and applied. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (14) Install fasteners as shown in appriate Figure 201 (Sheets 1 thru 6) and Table 201 (Fasteners). Refer to 51-40. Install blind fasteners wet with adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (15) Apply one coats of topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (16) Remove existing bolts from spring housing assembly (P/N NAS6204-5) and install retained spring housing assembly with 6 bolts (P/N NAS6204-6) and one each washers (P/N NAS1149C0416R) and (P/N NAS1149C0432R). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-08. (a) At time of installation ensure spring housing assembly is positioned fwd as far as possible to allow clearance on the unlock pushrod assembly clevis pin head at the spring housing assembly. Ensure no rubbing or chafe occurs. Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for further assessment. (17) Install left or right main gear inboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (18) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. D. Main Landing Gear Inboard Door Hinge Bushing Oversized Bores Repair NOTE This repair procedure applies to main landing gear inboard door hinge (P/N 133-100707-1, -2, -9, or -10). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 NOTE Never use a hammer or any other type of impact method, while performing this procedure. (1) Remove bushing from hinge. Refer to machine shop practices. (2) Inspect hinge bore to make sure that no cracks have formed using one of the following methods: (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for use on aluminum parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection, refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00, General Procedure Solvent Removable, Method “C” Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. NOTE If cracks are found, hinge is beyond repair and must be replaced with a new or serviceable hinge. NOTE If required, permissible to ream minimal amount to make round not exceeding maximum allowed. NOTE Do not exceed maximum diameter of 0.3851 inch. If diameter is larger than 0.3851 inch, contact cognizant authority before continuing with this repair. NOTE Minimum lug thickness allowed is 0.105 inch. If lug thickness is less than 0.105 inch, contact cognizant authority before continuing with this repair. (3) Make sure hinge bores are round and true. Refer to Figure 202. NOTE No primer allowed in the bore. (4) Apply alodine type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (5) Take measurement of bore diameter. For bore diameter of 0.3746-0.3751 inch, proceed to Step (6). For bore diameter 0.3752-0.3791 inch, proceed to Step (7). For bore diameter 0.3792-0.3851 inch, proceed to Step (8). (6) For bore diameter 0.3746-0.3751 inch: (a) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-1/-2): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N NAS76A4-008P) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 3 Install bushing flush with face of lug. 4 Proceed to Step (6)(c). (b) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-9/-10): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N 133-100704-9) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. 3 Proceed to Step (6)(c). (c) Prime and paint to match surrounding area, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (d) Install left or right main gear inboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (e) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. (7) For bore diameter 0.3752-0.3791 inch: (a) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-1/-2): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N NAS76A4-008P) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. 3 At time of bushing installation, install bushings wet with primer (64, Table 10, 51-30-01) and locking compound (62, Table 10, 51-30-01) or equivalent. 4 Install bushing flush with face of lug. 5 Proceed to Step (7)(c). (b) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-9/-10): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N 133-100704-9) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. 3 At time of bushing installation, install bushings wet with primer (64, Table 10, 51-30-01) and locking compound (62, Table 10, 51-30-01) or equivalent. 4 Proceed to Step (7)(c). (c) Lightly abrade bush surface, receiving locking compound with scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01). (d) Clean surface and bore, use cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) with solvent (2, 3, or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01), before solvent evaporates. Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drips from cheesecloth. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 206 Jun 01/21 NOTE Solvent drying time will be affected by temperature and humidity. (e) After cleaning surfaces, apply primer (64 or 65, Table 10, 51-30-01) to surface of new bushing and inner bore of support. Allow to dry for 5 to 15 minutes or until completely dry. NOTE Assemble bushing within 3 minutes after applying locking compound. (f) Apply locking compound (6, Table 10, 51-30-01) to both surfaces and spread evenly with an acid brush (6, Table 10, 51-30-01). (g) Apply a small bead of locking compound to edge of inner surface that receives bushing. (h) Once bushing is in place, take care not to disturb for a minimum of 5 minutes (i.e. handling). Clean off excess locking compound. (i) Allow locking compound to cure for a minimum of 24 hours. (j) Prime and paint to match surrounding area, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (k) Install left or right main gear inboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (l) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. (8) For bore diameter 0.3792-0.3851 inch: (a) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-1/-2): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N NAS76A4-008P) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. 3 Install bushing flush with face of lug. 4 At time of bushing installation, install bushings wet with primer (64 or 65, Table 10, 51-30-01) and locking compound (62, Table 10, 51-30-01) or equivalent. 5 Proceed to Step (8)(c). (b) Hinge support fittings (P/N 133-100707-9/-10): 1 Install (2) bushings (P/N 133-100704-9) in hinge bore. 2 Press bushings or freeze fit bushings into bore. 3 At time of bushing installation, install bushings wet with primer (65, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (64, Table 10, 51-30-01) and locking compound (63, Table 10, 51-30-01). 4 Proceed to Step (8)(c). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 207 Jun 01/21 (c) Lightly abrade bush surface, receiving locking compound with scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01). (d) Clean surface and bore, use cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) with solvent (2, 3, or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01), before solvent evaporates. Do not dampen to the point that excess solvent drips from cheesecloth. NOTE Solvent drying time will be affected by temperature and humidity. (e) After cleaning surfaces, apply primer (64, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (65, Table 10, 51-30-01) to surface of new bushing and inner bore of support. Allow to dry for 5 to 15 minutes or until completely dry. NOTE Assemble bushing within 3 minutes after applying locking compound. (f) Apply locking compound (63, Table 10, 51-30-01) to both surfaces and spread evenly with an acid brush (6, Table 10, 51-30-01). (g) Apply a small bead of locking compound to edge of inner surface that receives bushing. (h) Once bushing is in place, take care not to disturb for a minimum of 5 minutes (i.e. handling). Clean off excess locking compound. (i) Allow locking compound to cure for a minimum of 24 hours. (j) Prime and paint to match surrounding area, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (k) Install left or right main gear inboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-06. (l) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. E. Main Landing Gear Outboard Door Oversize Push Pin Hole Repair MLG outboard door push pin hole can be repaired if limitations in Allowable Damage, Main Landing Gear Outboard Doors Push Rod Pin Limitations are not exceeded. Repair as follows: WARNING Removal of composite material by drilling/reaming, sanding, routing, etc., produces small airborne composite particles harmful to personal health and equipment. A vacuum system shall be used in conjunction to this procedure to prevent airborne particles. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 208 Jun 01/21 WARNING Removal of material by drilling/reaming, sanding, routing, etc., produces small airborne particles harmful to personal health. Dust masks shall be worn by all personnel in the area. NOTE Review this procedure in its entirety read through repair in its entirety and verify access to perform repair and install fasteners as stated. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment before continuing with this repair. (1) As required, Remove left or right main landing gear outboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. (a) Retain hinge hardware: pins (P/N MS20392-3C61), washers (P/N NAS1149F0463P), washers (P/N NAS1149F0432P), for later re-installation. Discard cotter pins (P/N MS24665-172). (b) Retain bonding jumper hardware: screws (P/N MS24694-S52), washers (P/N NAS1149F0332P), for later re-installation. Discard nut (P/N 130909N29). (c) Retain main landing gear door: cotter pin (P/N MS24665-132), nut (P/N MS14145-4) and washer (P/N 100951S05OZY) securing push rod to gear door. Discard cotter pin (P/N MS24665-132) and nut (P/N MS14145-4). NOTE For removal of pin (P/N 133-100711-1 or -3), it is permissible to apply heat up to 200°F maximum to facilitate removal of pin without damaging laminate. Apply heat for 30-60 (maximum) seconds. If more heat is required, then shield surrounding area from heat. (2) Remove and discard existing pin (P/N 133-100711-1 or -3). NOTE Do not exceed 0.416 inch maximum diameter, if over 0.416 inch diameter contact cognizant authority for evaluation before proceeding further with this standard repair. (3) Drill/ream hole to 0.411-0.416 inch diameter as shown in Figure 203, Detail A-A, make sure hole is round. (4) Permissible to drill a 0.098 inch diameter weep hole at bottom of push rod pin hole. Drill from inboard side of door. Refer to Figure 203, Detail A-A. (5) Make sure to remove any dust/debris from hole and clean area with solvent (2, 3, or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). NOTE If delamination or bearing failure is found, contact cognizant authority for evaluation before proceeding further with this standard repair. (6) Inspect edge of graphite door at pin hole for signs of bearing failure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 209 Jun 01/21 (7) Perform Tap Test inspection on doors in region of pins attachment for delamination. Refer to 51-70-05, Paragraph 2, Coin and Sonic Tap Tests. NOTE Do not allow solvent to evaporate, surfaces may become contaminated. (8) Wipe area to be sealed with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Wipe surfaces clean with lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01) before solvent evaporates. Make sure surfaces are clean and oil-free. (9) Bond a new pin (P/N 133-100711-3) into push rod pin hole: (a) Use adhesive (7, Table 5, 51-30-01) mixed with 2% by weight with finely chopped fiberglass matting (material code - WF), to bond pin into door. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (b) Prior to pin installation, wipe adhesive mixture into inner diameter of hole and around diameter of pin. (c) Install pin. Turn pin 1/8 to 1/4 turn, while inserting to make sure adhesive mixture fills knurls. Verify squeeze out of adhesive mixture and remove excess. (d) Make sure 0.098 inch diameter weep hole is filled with adhesive mixture as pin is installed. (e) Secure pin with masking tape, to prevent adhesive from pushing pin out. (f) Allow adhesive to cure for 24 hours at room temperature or heat to 200°F maximum for 1 hour, before applying stress on pin. (g) If required, allow cool down time prior to installing door on aircraft. NOTE Install hinge with new cotter pin (P/N MS24665-172), retained pins (P/N MS20392-3C61), retained washers (P/N NAS1149F0463P), and retained washers (P/N NAS1149F0432P). (10) Install removed components, structure, or fasteners removed in Step (2). Use same type and size fasteners/hardware as removed. (11) As required, clean repair surfaces. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (12) Apply alodine type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (13) Apply two coats of primer (7, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (14) Apply two coats of topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. NOTE Install push rod to doors with new cotter pins (P/N MS24665-172), new cotter pins (P/N MS24665-132), and new nuts (P/N MS14145-4). (15) Install left or right main gear outboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 52-80-00 Page 210 Jun 01/21 (16) Clean, prepare surface, and electrical bond area for installation of bonding jumper and mounting surface. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 20-03-00. (17) Install bonding jumper with a new nut (P/N 130909N29), retained screws (P/N MS24694-S52), and retained washers (P/N NAS1149F0332P). (18) Make sure Main Landing Gear Doors have unrestricted closing and required edge gap clearance. Refer to 52-80-00, Repair Limitations. (19) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear, (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. IDENTIFICATION 00000 1. GENERAL This chapter contains information and structural parts breakdowns applicable to fuselage primary and auxiliary structure and outside skins. Major components of the fuselage structure are illustrated in Figure 00-01. The chapter consists of four sections:  Frames: Fuselage frames 1 thru 11. The crew compartment section of the fuselage is a pressurized vessel which is situated between the forward pressure bulkhead (1) and the aft pressure bulkhead (4). Refer to 53-10-00.  Secondary structure: Stringers, brackets, and other supporting parts. Refer to 53-20-00.  Skins: Fuselage sheet metal skins from FS 118.110 thru FS 373.260. Refer to 53-30-00.  Fairings: Dorsal fin, ventral fin, and strakes. Refer to 53-40-00. Specific structural inspections, damage limitations, repair criteria, and structural identification specific to the fuselage are contained in this chapter. 2. INSPECTION The fuselage is inspected on a regularly scheduled basis in accordance with the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-6), Section II, for dents, cracks, loose or missing rivets, corrosion, and distortion. Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of the damage. Refer to 51-10-00. 3. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to fuselage frames. Each part called out in a fuselage frame figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 FUSELAGE FRAMES 53-10-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS If damage affects the frame structure, it should be classified as either repairable or replacement, refer to 51- 10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 FUSELAGE FRAMES 53-10-0053-10-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-03. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the frame. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Contact cognizant authority prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts. 2. REPAIR OF FUSELAGE FRAME 9 A. Procedure (1) Using either fluorescent penetrant or eddy current nondestructive inspection (NDI) techniques, inspect crack to accurately locate ends of crack. CAUTION When stop-drilling crack, make sure no damage occurs to the underlying structure. (2) Using 0.125-inch drill bit, stop-drill ends of crack. Refer to Figure 201 for crack limits. (3) Inspect crack using NDI procedure after drilling to make sure crack does not extend beyond drilled holes. (4) Locate reinforcement (P/N 133-440080-1) on frame. If necessary, install shim (12, Table 10, 51-30-01), trimmed to frame profile, between frame and skin using sealant (2, Table 7, 51-30-01) on faying surfaces. Refer to 51-20-10 for shim protection requirements. (5) On reinforcement, drill all holes to match existing holes and pilot holes, as shown on Figure 201, to 0.128-0.133-inch diameter. If larger fasteners are installed other than those called out, contact cognizant authority prior to performing rework. NOTE Maintain two fastener diameters minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (6) If required, drill holes through frame, skin, and shim to 0.129-0.132 inch. If oversize fastener required, drill holes to 0.143-0.146 inch. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (7) Deburr and smooth all sharp edges. (8) Treat bare metal with alodine (6, Table 1, 53-00-00). (9) Apply primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00) over alodine-treated area. (10) Bond reinforcement to frame using adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01) and scrim cloth (13, Table 1, 53-00-00). Allow adhesive to cure using manufacturer’s instructions. (11) Install fasteners (18, Table 1, 53-00-00) through reinforcement and frame. Refer to 51-40-01. (12) Install fasteners (24, Table 1, 53-00-00 or; 25, Table 1, 53-00-00, if oversize) through frame skin and shim, if installed. Refer to 51-40-02. 3. FRAMES 8, 9, AND 9A STRINGER 1 (LEFT AND RIGHT) CLIP FASTENER REPLACEMENT A. Procedure (1) If necessary, remove loose fasteners. If larger fasteners are installed other than those called out, contact cognizant authority prior to performing rework. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Ream hole to 0.1605-0.1625-inch diameter and install new fastener (23, Table 1, 53-00-00), maintaining 0.25-inch edge distance. 4. REPAIR OF AUXILIARY FUSELAGE FRAME LOWER FLANGE A. Procedure CAUTION Protect surrounding area and underlying structure from damage during this procedure. (1) Cut and remove forward portion of auxiliary frame lower flange along aft joggle. Maintain minimum two-diameter edge distance on all fasteners. Refer to Figure 202. (2) Check remaining auxiliary frame lower flange and underlying structure using eddy current inspection general procedure for use on aluminum parts. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01. Make sure no cracks exist or have formed. Report any adverse results to cognizant authority prior to continuing with procedure. (3) Make repair shim from 0.090-inch sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) with profile as shown in Figure 202. Joggle to match existing lower flange on auxiliary frame. Acceptable to machine repair shim up to 0.020 inch minimum thickness as required in lieu of joggle. Maintain 0.030 to 0.060 inch radius. (4) Make repair flange from 0.040-inch sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) with profile as shown in Figure 202. Joggle to match existing structure on auxiliary frame. (5) Make rub strip from 0.062-inch phenolic sheet (32, Table 1, 53-00-00) with profile as shown in Figure 202. Maintain 0.25-inch minimum radius on corners. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (6) Drill holes for all existing fastener positions as indicated in Figure 202. Maintain minimum of two-diameter edge distance for all fastener positions. All existing fasteners shall be same type and size as original. (7) Counterbore rub strip holes 0.141-0.145-inch diameter and 0.025-0.030-inch deep. Install suitable length new fasteners same type and size fasteners as indicated in Figure 202. (8) Deburr all sharp edges. (9) Bond repair filler, repair flange, and rub strip using adhesive (7, Table 5, 51-30-01). (10) Apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. (11) Apply primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00) to alodine treated area. 5. REPAIR OF LONGERON MATERIAL WEAR AT CANOPY SILL POSITION INDICATOR SWITCH STRIKER PLATE A. Procedure (1) Manufacture repair plate using sheet metal (29, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to MIL-S-5059 and Figure 203. (2) Blend out sharp edges in areas of left side beam (P/N 133-430058-15) to be reinforced. (3) Prepare left side beam area to be bonded by scuff sanding with sandpaper (17, Table 10, 51-30-01). Clean sanded area using alcohol (9, Table 1, 53-00-00). (4) Fill any gouges or holes with adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01) or equivalent. (5) Apply adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01) to prepared side beam area and apply repair plate. Allow adhesive to cure. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (6) Check rigging of canopy sill position indicating switch. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Special Purpose Equipment (TO 1T-6ABD-2-95), 95-10-14. 6. REPAIR OF FRAME 2, LOWER FLANGE, AFT NOSE GEAR DOOR WEAR AREA A. Procedure, Flange Thickness Less Than 0.080-inch After Blending NOTE Flange thickness (after blending) must be greater than or equal to 0.070-inch to perform this repair. If remaining material thickness is less than 0.070-inch, contact cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. NOTE Perform Section B, Procedure, Flange Thickness Greater Than 0.080-inch After Blending, when minimum remaining flange thickness is 0.080 inch or greater after blending. (1) Remove nose landing gear doors. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-20-06. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 (2) Remove five bolts and washers from aft most portions of left and right outboard thermal blankets. Partially remove blankets to access frame flange. Do not remove thermal blankets entirely. Refer to Figure 204. (3) Carefully remove (ACM C60) Akrotherm in required repair areas. Refer to Figure 204. Remove (ACM C60) Akrotherm 0.25-inch up from angle doubler as shown in Figure 204. Refer to (TO 1T-6ABD-3)51-20-30 for removal instructions. (4) Carefully drill out 3 lower nut plates and 11 rivets on lower portion of Frame 2, making sure not to enlarge fastener holes. Refer to Figure 205. (5) Blend chafed area as shown in Figures 206, 207, and 210. Surface finish to be 125 RMS (or better). Blend transition on aft side of worn area and unworn area to create a smooth transition. Refer to Figures 206 and 210. (6) Perform one of the following methods to make sure no cracks have formed in Frame 2. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (7) Make one angle doubler from 0.063-inch, aluminum sheet (57, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 208. Form to match existing contour and heat treat to 7075-T73 SAE AMS 2770. Perform NDI inspection per Step (6). If cracks are found, remake part. (8) Manufacture one web filler from 0.020-inch, aluminum sheet (40, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (43, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 209. (9) Temporarily install angle doubler and web filler. Check for proper fit and secure in place. Refer to Figures 205 and 207. Locate 11 rivet holes and drill per 51-40-01. (10) Locate and drill/countersink three holes through angle doubler for nut plate bolts. Refer to Figure 207. (11) Remove angle doubler. Locate and drill all rivet holes for installation of nut plates on angle doubler. (12) With all holes drilled in all parts, remove angle doubler and web filler. Deburr all drilled holes. (13) Protect bare metal. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (14) Install three nut plates (34, Table 10, 51-30-01) to angle doubler. Refer to Figure 207. (15) Install double flush rivets (35, Table 10, 51-30-01) in Frame 2 to fill existing nut plate rivet holes as shown in Figure 207. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 (16) Install web filler as shown in Figure 207 using adhesive (7, Table 5, 51-30-01). Mix and apply per manufacturer’s instructions. (17) Install doubler angle as shown per Figure 205 and 207. Bond doubler angle to web filler using adhesive (7, Table 5, 51-30-01). Mix and apply per manufacturer’s instructions. Remove any excess adhesive. Secure in place using 11 rivets (41, Table 10, 51-30-01). (18) Apply Type 2, Class B sealer (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to lower side of frame in blended area. Refer to 51-30-01 and Figure 210. After sealer is applied to lower frame, apply release agent to the aft edge of gear doors to mold sealant to shape of doors. After sealant has cured, open gear doors and trim excess sealant to match edge of frame. (19) Install 0.60x0.50-inch anti-chafe tape (35, Table 1, 53-00-00) onto doubler angle. Refer to Figure 210 for chafe tape placement. (20) Touch-up paint as required. (21) After adhesive and touch-up paint have cured, install new (ACM C60) Akrotherm (2, Table 11, 51-30-01) to areas where removed in Step 3. Refer to 51-20-30. (22) Secure Left and Right outboard thermal blankets with bolts and washers. Refer to Figure 204. (23) Install nose landing gear doors. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-20-06. (24) Perform Nose Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 32-00-01. B. Procedure, Flange Thickness Greater Than 0.080-inch After Blending (1) Blend chafed area as shown in Figures 206, 207, and 210. Surface finish shall be 125 RMS (or better). Blend transition on aft side of worn area and unworn area to create a smooth transition and 5:1 blend slope. Refer to Figures 206 and 210. If there is less than 0.080-inch remaining thickness after blending, perform Section A., Procedure, Flange Thickness Less Than 0.080-inch After Blending. (2) Perform one of the following methods to make sure no cracks have formed in Frame 2. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (3) Protect bare metal. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (4) Perform Nose Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-00-01. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 206 Jun 01/21 (5) Apply Type 2, Class B sealer (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to lower side of frame in blended area. Refer to Figure 210 and 51-30-01. After sealer is applied to lower frame, apply release agent to aft edge of gear doors to mold sealant to shape of doors. After sealant has cured, open gear doors and trim excess sealant to match edge of frame. (6) Install removed components and parts, as required. (7) Touch-up paint as required. 7. FRAME 4B WEB CRACK REPAIR A. Procedure (1) Carefully de-rivet existing fasteners as required to complete the steps indicated below, taking care not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structures. (2) Carefully remove and discard speed brake bracket, P/N 133-580000-29 or -57, taking care not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structures. (3) Locate and mark end of cracks using one of the following Non Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (4) Carefully cut out cracks from frame web as shown in Figure 215, removing minimum material necessary and taking care not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. Trim 0.10-inch beyond end of crack. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on existing fasteners (measured from center of hole to edge of part) and maintain minimum 0.25-inch radius. (5) Visually inspect area to make sure that no cracks remains, and no new cracks have formed using one of the following NDI methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (6) Make repair doubler (P/N SR-TS-ATA53-23016-1) from 0.040-inch sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) with profile as shown in Figure 215. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 207 Jun 01/21 (7) Drill all holes as shown in Figure 215. Refer to 51-40-00. Maintain 4D to 6D spacing on all new fasteners (measured from center to center) and 2D minimum edge distance on all other fasteners (measured from center of hole to edge of part). (8) Deburr all sharp edges. (9) Apply alodine type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (10) Apply one coat of epoxy primer (7, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (11) Install repair parts in place using adhesive (7, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (12) Install fasteners as shown in Figure 215. Refer to 51-40. Install fasteners wet with sealant (3,4,or 5, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (13) Install speed brake bracket (P/N 133-580000-7029), (no pilot holes), using the same type and size fasteners as existing, as shown in Figure 215. Refer to 51-40-00. Length to suit. (14) Apply top coat to match existing color, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (15) Rig speed brake. Refer to maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-60-01. (16) Perform rigging flap and speed brake position switches. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 27-50-00. 8. INSULATION BLANKET REPAIR A. Procedure NOTE Lettering must remain on outside of insulation blankets. (1) Repair insulation blankets or bags that are torn or punctured with tape (36, Table 1, 53-00-00). Refer to Illustrated Parts Catalog (TO 1T-6ABD-4), 25-80-05. (2) Heat seal or tape to seal all insulation blanket edges as required. (3) Repaired insulation blankets to maintain original dimensions. 9. REPAIR OF LEFT AND RIGHT AVIONICS BAY DOOR LAND A. Procedure NOTE This repair can be performed in its entirety or as required for damage. NOTE Skin damage/deformation less than twice skin thickness does not require cutting out damage, repair doubler applied only. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 208 Jun 01/21 NOTE If an external skin repair doubler is installed, an internal repair doubler must also be installed at that location. NOTE Cracks in reinforcement are not to exceed 1.150 inches in length. (1) Remove and discard rubber seal (P/N 131776). (2) Remove fasteners and parts as required to perform the following steps. Use caution not to oversize existing holes or damage underlying/surrounding structure. (a) If skin damage or deformation is present at lower hinge area, remove existing doubler (P/N 133-440065). Retain for use as pattern to make lower skin repair doubler (P/N SR-TS-00051-21/-22). (b) If no skin damage/deformation present at lower hinge area, do not remove the existing doubler (P/N 133-440065). (3) Visually inspect existing hinges and attach brackets for damage. If damage is found, inspect for cracks using one of inspection methods listed in Step (9). If cracks are found remove and discard existing part and install new. (4) Perform Nondestructive Inspection of skin and reinforcement using one of the following methods to locate and mark end of cracks. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. CAUTION Protect surrounding area and underlying structure from damage when performing Step (5). (5) Carefully cut out damage in reinforcement (P/N 133-440036-1/-3/-5/-7) only at upper and lower hinge locations as shown in Figure 211, Sheet 1 and Figure 212, Sheet 1. Hand form any remaining damage to skin and reinforcement back to within 0.010-inch of original contour. Maintain 0.25-inch radius minimum. (6) If required for skin damage/deformation at upper/lower hinge attachment only: (a) If skin damage/deformation is twice skin thickness or less: 1 Hand form any remaining damage to skin back to original profile within 0.010-inch of original contour. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 209 Jun 01/21 (b) If skin damage/deformation is greater than twice skin thickness: CAUTION Protect surrounding area and underlying structure from damage when performing Step 1. 1 Carefully cut out damage in skin (P/N 133-440004-1/-3 only) at upper and lower hinge locations as shown in Figure 211, Sheets 2 and 3. Hand form any remaining damage to skin back to within 0.010-inch of original contour. Maintain 0.25-inch radius minimum. (7) If required for door damage/deformation at upper/lower hinge attachment only: CAUTION Protect surrounding area and underlying structure from damage when performing Step (a). (a) Carefully cut out damage in inner skin (P/N 133-440029-29/-30 only) at upper and lower hinge locations as shown in Figure 213. Hand form any remaining damage to skin back to within 0.010-inch of original contour. Maintain 0.25-inch radius minimum. (8) Deburr all sharp edges along cut lines. (9) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of the following methods to make sure no cracks remain and no new cracks have formed. Make sure no fluorescent penetrant in door honeycomb core. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. Procedure (1) Blend and polish smooth stringer flange, removing minimum amount of material necessary to clear all damage and achieve a smooth profile. Maintain 10:1 minimum blend slope and 63 RMS (or better) surface finish. (2) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of the following methods to make sure damage has been completely removed. Report any adverse results to cognizant authority prior to continuing with repair. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-10-00 Page 212 Jun 01/21 (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (3) Measure blend dimensions as follows: (a) Blend depth may be measured by taking the difference of nominal part thickness and remaining thickness at blend location. Refer to Figure 216. Blend depth should be noted in stringer bulb and stringer flange as affected by blending. (b) Blend width, radially in fuselage and distance outward along stringer leg, should be measured. Refer to Figure 216. (4) Determine if blend location is repairable. (a) Compare blend depths to Table 201. If directed to perform stringer splice repair. Refer to 51-70-01 and Step (4)(b). (b) Compare blend width to Table 202. If directed to clean and re-protect, proceed to Step (10) and skip Steps (13) and (14). (c) Compare blend width to Table 202. If directed to install repair extrusion, proceed to Step (5) after completing. (d) Compare blend width to Table 202. If directed to perform stringer splice repair. Refer to 51-70-01 and Step (15).
