ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to the fuselage secondary structure. Each part called out in a fuselage frame figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/ material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special instructions, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 101 Jun 01/21 FUSELAGE STRUCTURE 53-20-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS If damage affects the fuselage structure, the damage should be classified as either repairable or replaceable damage. Refer to 51-10-00 and 51-70-00. A. Lower Fuselage AFT of Frame 6 Flange Limitations This repair is used for cracks, cracking and/or deformation in the aft fuselage skin (P/N 133-440027-11) between FS 261.764 and FS 281.449, and damage, creases, and deformation on frame 6 lower flange and chafing damage on the lower fuselage stringers at doubler (P/N 133-440004-29). Refer to Figure 101. (1) For chafed/damaged stringers (P/N 133-440030-1/-2) may be repaired one of two ways depending on the extent of the damage: (a) If the remaining thickness is 0.050 inch or greater, proceed to Frame 6 stringer minor chafe/ damage repair. (b) If the remaining thickness is less than 0.050 inch, proceed to Frame 6 stringer major chafe/ damage repair or contact cognizant authority. (2) Cracks are limited to the lower skin only. Refer to Figure 101. NOTE It is permissible to decrease the size of the cut out limited to the damage of each event, as required. (3) Skin crack cut out shall not be greater than shown in Figure 219 shaded area, including 0.10 inch beyond end of crack. (4) If cracks are outside the shaded area, report adverse finds to cognizant authority for further assessment before continuing with this repair. NOTE It is permissible to use of the following repairs in conjunction with each other or individually; Frame 6 Stringer Minor Chafe/Damage Repair, Frame 6 Stringer Major Chafe/ Damage Repair, Lower Fuselage Skin Repair Aft Of Frame 6 Flange, Frame 6 Lower Flange Repair or in conjunction with each repair. (5) Frame 6 damage is limited to the lower flange and web, only in the cut area. Cut out shall not be greater than shown in Figure 220. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 102 Jun 01/21 Figure 101 - Lower Fuselage AFT of Frame 6 Flange Limitations AFT RIGHT SKIN CRACKS LIMITED TO THIS AREA ONLY STRINGER CHAFE LIMITED TO THESE AREAS ONLY CREASE FRAME 6 DAMAGE LIMITED TO THIS AREA ONLY DAMAGE AREA STRINGERS, SKIN, FRAME 6 PT53E 210586AA.AI MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 FUSELAGE STRUCTURE 53-20-00 53-20-0053-20-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list (Figure 1) that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-03. Refer to Typical Repairs, 51-70-00 for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the fuselage structure. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. 2. REPLACEMENT OF LONGERON BUSHING A. Inspection (1) Inspect inside diameter of bushing. Maximum allowable inner diameter with wear limit is 0.4320 inch. NOTE Measure bushing across the short or narrow section of the slot. B. Removal (1) Remove bushing from longeron. Be careful not to damage longeron. (2) Remove any foreign material from counterbore in longeron. C. Installation (1) Make sure counterbore in longeron is free from any remaining adhesive. (2) Clean surface of bushing and counterbore of longeron with solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (3) Apply primer (14, Table 10, 51-30-01) to counterbore in longeron and exterior surface of bushing. (4) Apply locking compound (1, Table 1, 53-00-00) to exterior surface of bushing. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 202 Jun 29/20 NOTE Install bushings with slot oriented fore/aft for positions 1, 2, 4, and 5. Install bushing with slot oriented inboard/outboard for position 3, center bushing. (5) Install bushing in longeron with oblong, inside diameter running fore/aft along longeron. Press down on bushing to make sure it is properly seated. Refer to Figure 205. 3. REPLACEMENT OF FRETTED RUDDER CABLE PULLEY BRACKET ATTACH FASTENERS If rudder cable pulley bracket (P/N 133-524051) attach fasteners are fretted, it is permissible to replace the four existing solid rivets. Refer to Table 201. Install rivets wet using sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01), or equivalent. 4. REWORK AND INSTALLATION OF FORWARD RUDDER PULLEY BRACKET NOTE Pulley bracket does not come drilled with hole for installation of pulley or cable guide pins. This task is to locate and drill the holes to properly install the pulley and cable guide pins. NOTE The preferred spare for P/N 133-524051-7 is P/N 133-524051-11 and the preferred spare for P/N 133-524051-8 is P/N 133-524051-12. A. Procedure (1) After removal of existing rudder pulley bracket, create template from surface of removed bracket to locate holes for pulley and cable guide pins. Template will have five holes when complete. When making template, use side of removed rudder pulley bracket with two tooling holes (0.190-inch), one pulley hole (0.313-inch), and two holes for cable guide pins (0.190-inch). Use appropriate sized transfer punch to mark template and drill #30 pilot holes for pulley and cable guide pins. (2) Create spacer from 0.63-inch thick block of aluminum or wood that will fit between upper and lower surfaces of the rudder pulley bracket. Refer to Figure 209 (3) Insert 0.63-inch spacer between upper and lower surfaces of rudder pulley bracket. Clamp in place using C clamps to prevent movement when drilling through parts. Table 201 - Recommended Hole Size Rivet Part Number Recommended Hole Size NAS1921C04 0.129/0.132 NAS1921M04 0.129/0.132 NAS1739B04 0.143/0.146 NAS1919M05-***(WD-5) 0.160/0.164 NAS1919M05W-*** (ALX-5) 0.160/0.164 *** equals grip length as required MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (4) Using two tooling hole (0.190-inch) locations, locate template created in Step (1) on new rudder pulley bracket and secure with #10 Clecos. Drill three #30 holes through the top surface only, one hole for the pulley and two holes for the cable guide pins. (5) Using drill guide to make sure holes are drilled straight, drill through upper surface and 0.63-inch spacer to create three #30 holes in the lower surface, one hole for pulley and two holes for cable guide pins. (6) After three #30 holes are drilled in lower surface, step drill/ream all pulley and guide pin holes to finished sizes. Finished size of pulley hole is 0.313-0.317-inch (5/16 drill). Finished size of holes for cable guide pins is 0.190-0.195-inch (#11 drill). Ream both upper and lower surfaces of pulley bracket and 0.63-inch spacer to finished size. Reaming can be completed with 0.63-inch spacer between bracket surfaces or removed from bracket. (7) Deburr all holes and break all sharp edges. (8) Temporarily install 0.63-inch spacer between upper and lower surface of pulley bracket. It is permissible to use existing hardware for 0.313-inch pulley hole. Use #10 draw Cleco or any nut-and-bolt combination in guide pin holes to secure 0.63-inch spacer in new bracket. This process helps to maintain proper dimension of pulley bracket while locating bracket in the aircraft. (9) Locate rudder pulley bracket (left P/N 133-524051-7 or -11 and right P/N 133-524051-8 or -12) in aircraft and temporarily install with Clecos. (10) Remove rudder pulley bracket from the aircraft and remove fasteners securing the 0.63-inch spacer to bracket. After hardware is removed, remove spacer from the bracket. (11) Touch up all bare stainless steel with two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). (12) Install rudder pulley bracket wet using Type 2, Class B sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) and install with new fasteners identified in Table 201. 5. REWORK OF CANOPY GAP NOTE The gap allowed between the canopy sill and the forward corner areas of the canopy frame is between 0.10 inch and 0.13 inch for right side of canopy and between 0.03 inch and 0.13 inch for left side of canopy. If gap is less than 0.10 inch on right side, or less than 0.03 inch on left side, rework gap refer to the following procedure. A. Rework (1) Identify areas in which gap is less than 0.10 inch on right side of canopy and less than 0.03 inch on left side of canopy. Refer to Figure 201. (2) In areas identified, inspect flush condition between skin and sill. If skin is not flush with sill within +0.00/-0.03 inch, remove material from skin as follows: (a) Trim skin using pencil drill tool with 0.125-inch OD solid carbide burr. (b) After trim operation, apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 (c) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area and touch up to match existing sill color using paint (4, Table 3, 51-30-01). (d) Apply sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to produce good transition surface. Refer to Figure 202. (e) Touch up sealant to match existing skin color using paint (22, Table 1, 53-00-00). (3) If gap is still not within allowable tolerances, remove material from canopy frame as follows: (a) Trim frame using pencil drill tool with 0.125-inch OD solid carbide burr. (b) After trim operation, apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. (c) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area and touch up to match existing color using paint (4, Table 3, 51-30-01). 6. REPLACEMENT OF HAND HOLD DOOR SPRING Hand form 0.50-inch leg of door spring to form a 30-50 bend located 0.40 inch from leg end. Refer to Figure 203. Make sure door closes properly after door spring installation. 7. INSTALLATION OF SHIM BETWEEN BRACE AND BEAM OF PRESSURE FLOOR ASSEMBLY It is permissible to shim the gap between the pressure floor brace and pressure floor beam. Refer to Figure 204. Use liquid shim for gaps less than 0.025 inch and use a manufactured shim for gaps between 0.025- 0.050 inch as described below. It is permissible to have a short edge distance when using the manufactured shim only. Refer to 53-20-05 for part information. A. Procedure (1) Fill gaps less than 0.025 inch between pressure floor brace and pressure floor beam with adhesive (10 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01). (2) Use shim for gaps between 0.025-0.050 inch. Taper shim, as required, and fill remaining gaps not greater than 0.025 inch with adhesive (10 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01). If shim is trimmed or tapered, apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to bare metal on shim and then apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). 8. LONGERON REPAIR A. Procedure NOTE Size of gouge to be no longer than 1.125 inch and no wider than 0.500 inch. Maximum depth of all gouges to be 0.030 inch. (1) Smooth and blend to remove gouged area to slope having width-to-depth ratio of 5:1. Remove minimum amount of material to eliminate discrepancy. Do not blend beyond 0.030 inch depth for any gouge. Maintain maximum surface texture average of 0.063 inch minimum by using 400 grit sandpaper (29, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 206. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 205 Jun 05/17 (2) Use best method to determine depth of discrepancy after rework. If greater than 0.030 inch, contact cognizant authority for disposition. (3) NDI the area using Part 6 Eddy Current Inspection General Procedure for use on aluminum parts. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, 20-10-01. If no cracks are detected, continue with Step (4). If cracks are detected, contact cognizant authority for further instructions. (4) Mask areas not intended to be coated. (5) Protect all bare metal with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). (6) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to treated area. (7) Touch up paint. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, 20-20-00. (8) Remove latch guide pin (P/N 133-510081-3) at repair location and replace with new latch guide pin (P/N 133-510081-5). Refer to Canopy Maintenance and Build-Up Manual, 95-10-10. (9) If latch guide pin (P/N 133-510081-5) is unavailable, it is permissible to rework pin (P/N 133-510081-3) to pin (P/N 133-510081-5) configuration. Re-identify reworked part to SR-TS-00038-1 pin. Ink identify, location on pin optional. Refer to Figure 207. (10) If pin (P/N 133-510081-3) must be reworked and re-identified to SR-TS-00038-1, blend edges to 0.060 radius. Perform Magnetic Particle inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Methods (33B-1-1). 9. FORWARD FRAME 1 (FR1) REPAIR This procedure was developed to alleviate further damage to Frame 1 and battery nylon straps during battery removal or installation. A. Procedure (1) Unsnap fire blanket next to FR1, left side angle flange, and position out of way of work area. (2) Perform visual inspection using 10X magnification on deformed area of FR1, left side angle flange. Locate and mark ends of any cracks found on angle flange. CAUTION Do not exceed the maximum dimensions for material removal. (3) Carefully cut and remove damaged area of angle flange. Refer to Figure 208 for repair profile. Maintain 0.25-inch minimum radius on all corners of cut line. Maintain minimum 2 times fastener diameter edge distance with any existing nearby fastener locations. Make sure deformation is removed. Make sure cut line extends 0.10 inch beyond any crack found. (4) Deburr all sharp edges. (5) Perform visual inspection using 10X magnification on FR1, left side angle flange. Make sure no cracks are present. (6) Position fire blanket onto pressure bulkhead and snap to secure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 206 Jun 01/21 10. FUSELAGE SKIN REPAIR AFT OF CANOPY A. Procedure (1) Carefully blend any chafing damage in canopy rail as shown in Figure 217, Sheet 1. Make sure requirements are met per Figure 217, Sheet 1. Maintain 5:1 minimum blend ratio and 63 RMS or better surface finish. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (2) Carefully blend any chafing damage in the strap as shown in Figure 217, Sheet 1. Make sure requirements are met per Figure 217, Sheet 1. Maintain 5:1 minimum blend ratio and 63 RMS or better surface finish. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (3) At chafing location in skin: (a) If minimum remaining thickness in damage area is 0.016 or greater, careful blend any chafing damage in doubler as shown in Figure 217, Sheet 1. Make sure requirements are met per Figure 217, Sheet 1. Maintain 5:1minimum blend ratio and 63 RMS or better surface finish. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. UPPER ECS INLET SCREENS REMOVAL AND INSTALLATION (REFER TO VSP) A. Removal (Original Screens) NOTE Review this procedure in its entirety prior to making any modifications to the aircraft. Observe all warnings and cautions. Whenever any part of the aircraft is dismantled, adjusted, repaired, or renewed, detailed inspection must be made on completion to make sure tools, rags, and any other loose articles or foreign matter are not present. Make sure systems and installations in the work area are clean and no distortion is present that could impede safe operation of the aircraft. (1) Remove air conditioning cooling condenser blower. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Air Conditioning (TO 1T-6ABD-2-21), 21-50-02. (2) Remove access panel (861). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Dimensions and Areas (TO 1T-6ABD-2-6), 06-50-00. (3) Remove clamps and flex ducts from outflow and safety valve outlets. (4) Remove electrical connector (P2152P3) from resistor assembly. Refer to Figure 214. (5) Remove 17 screws and associated hardware from condenser inlet duct assembly. Separate upper and lower condenser inlet duct halves. (6) Remove hoses and drain tubes from lower duct. (7) Remove condenser inlet duct halves from aircraft. (8) Remove four screws securing left Kydex inlet duct (P/N 133-1334-1). Refer to Figure 215. (9) Remove four screws securing right Kydex inlet ducts (P/N 133-1333-1). (10) Apply heat, up to 180 °F, to sealant area to break bond line. (11) Use non-metallic scraper to separate Kydex inlet ducts from sealant and remove from fuselage. (12) Apply heat, up to 180 °F, to sealant area to break bond line securing inlet screens (P/N 133-1338-1) to fuselage. (13) Using non-metallic scraper, separate inlet screens from sealant and remove from fuselage. CAUTION Do not scrape or gouge the fuselage skin when removing the sealant. (14) Apply heat, up to 180 °F, and use non-metallic scraper, MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), and scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01) to remove all sealant from interior surface of fuselage skin. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 216 Jun 01/21 B. Repair and Protection of Interior Skin (1) Inspect interior skin for corrosion. Document if corrosion was found. (2) Acceptable to blend minor corrosion, not to exceed 0.003 inch in depth. After blend, measure remaining thickness of skin in accordance with 51-10-03. Verify remaining thickness is 0.029 inch or greater. Maintain 63 RMS or better surface finish and blend slope no steeper than 10:1. (3) Perform fluorescent penetrant in accordance with ASTM E 1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A, and 10x magnification, (4) Make sure no corrosion remains and no cracks have formed. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment. (5) If no corrosion is found, or if post blend repair is within acceptable post blend criteria, apply alodine type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (6) Apply 2 coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to interior fuselage skin area. C. Installation (ECS Shims P/N 133-4044-0003) (1) After primer has cured, dry fit and locate new inlet shims (P/N 133-1358-1) left and (P/N 133-1358-1) right (note same part numbers). Secure to interior fuselage skin with clamps. (2) Carefully drill four screw holes 0.139-0.148 inch diameter through inlet shims. (3) Remove inlet shims. Scuff both surfaces of inlet shims with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) and scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01). (4) Thoroughly clean inlet shims mating surfaces with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) and scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01). (5) Apply a thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to inlet shim (mating surface to fuselage skin). (6) Install inlet shim against interior skin and hold in place with 4 Cleco’s in holes. Also install several clamp Cleco’s in opening area to secure inlet shim tightly against interior fuselage skin while sealant cures. (7) After sealant cures, remove Cleco’s and clean off excess sealant with a non abrasive scraper. (8) Dry fit check new inlet screens (P/N 133-555055-0003). Trim screen areas where new screws will penetrate through skin. Do not allow screen to touch any aluminum when installed. (9) Apply a thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to inlet shim. Embed inlet screens (P/N 133-555055-0003) in sealant. Make sure screens are installed so as not to touch any aluminum when installed. Refer to Figure 215. (10) Apply a thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to right Kydex inlet ducts (P/N 133-1333-1). Use new duct if original duct could not be removed without damaging. (11) Apply a thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to left Kydex inlet ducts (P/N 133-1334-1). Use new duct if original duct could not be removed without damaging. (12) Install four new screws (P/N MS35206-230) to secure right Kydex inlet duct (P/N 133-1333-1) in place. Clean excess sealant from area with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 217 Jun 01/21 (13) Install four new screws (P/N MS35206-230) securing the left Kydex inlet duct (P/N 133-1334-1) in place. Clean excess sealant from area with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (14) After interior sealant is cured, install condenser inlet duct assembly halves previously removed from aircraft. Refer to Figure 214. (15) Install hoses on drain tubes on lower duct half. (16) Install 17 screws associated hardware to secure upper and lower halves of condenser inlet duct assembly. (17) Install electrical connector on resistor assembly (P2152P3). (18) Install clamps and flex ducts on outflow and safety valve outlets. (19) Install air conditioning cooling condenser blower, refer to Maintenance Manual, Air Conditioning (TO 1T-6ABD-2-21), 21-50-02. (20) Install access panel (861). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Dimensions and Areas (TO 1T-6ABD-2-6), 06-50-00. (21) Perform Condenser Blower Operational Check. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 21-50-02. (22) Touch up any bare exterior aluminum with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-10. (23) Apply two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to exterior repair areas. (24) Apply two coats of topcoat paint to primed areas, screw heads, and fillet sealed areas. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (25) Make appropriate log book entries noting the kit number and serial number installed. 18. LOWER ECS OUTLET SCREENS REMOVAL AND INSTALLATION (REFER TO VSP) NOTE All company kits, unless otherwise designated, are approved for installation on airplanes in original or modified configurations only. Company kits may not be compatible with aircraft modified by supplemental type certificate (STC) installation or modifications other than company approved kits. NOTE Review this procedure in its entirety prior to making any modifications to the aircraft. Observe all warnings and cautions. Whenever any part of the aircraft is dismantled, adjusted, repaired, or renewed, a detailed inspection must be made on completion to make sure that tools, rags, and any other loose articles or foreign matter are not present. Make sure systems and installations in the work area are clean and that no distortion is present that could impede safe operation of the aircraft. A. Removal (Original Screens) (1) Open baggage door (814). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Dimensions and Areas (TO 1T-6ABD-2-6), 06-05.00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 218 Jun 01/21 (2) On aft baggage wall, remove four screws securing condenser exhaust duct support brackets. Refer to Figure 214. (3) Remove access panel (862). Refer 06-50-00. (4) Remove condenser exhaust lower duct assembly from opening in right tail access area. (5) Apply heat, up to 180 F, to sealant area to break bond line on lower left and right duct flanges. (6) Use non-metallic scraper to separate Kydex outlet duct flanges from sealant. Remove flanges (P/N 133-1300-1 right and 133-1301-1 left) from fuselage. (7) Apply heat, up to 180 F, to sealant to break bond line securing the (P/N 133-1324-1) outlet screens from fuselage. Refer to Figure 216. (8) Use non-metallic scraper to separate outlet screens from sealant. Remove screens from fuselage. (9) Apply heat, up to 180 F, to remaining sealant on the interior fuselage skin. CAUTION Do not scrape or gouge the fuselage skin when removing the sealant. Damage to aircraft may occur. (10) Use non-metallic scraper, MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), and scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01), and remove all sealant from interior surface of fuselage skin. B. Repair and Protection of Interior Skin (1) Inspect interior skin for corrosion. Document if corrosion was found. (2) Acceptable to blend minor corrosion, not to exceed 0.003 inch in depth. After blend, measure remaining thickness of skin. Refer to 51-10-03. Verify remaining thickness is 0.029 inch or greater. Maintain 63 RMS or better surface finish and blend slope no steeper than 10:1. (3) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. and 10x magnification. (4) Make sure no corrosion remains and no cracks have formed. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment. (5) If no corrosion is found, or if post blend repair is within acceptable post blend criteria, apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to bare aluminum. (6) Apply 2 coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to interior fuselage skin area. C. Installation (ECS Shims P/N 133-4044-0001) (1) After primer has cured, dry fit and locate new outlet shims (P/N 133-1357-1) left and (P/N 133-1356-1) right (note same part numbers). Secure to interior fuselage skin with clamps. Refer to Figure 216. (2) Thoroughly clean outlet shim mating surfaces with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) and scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-20-00 Page 219 Jun 01/21 (3) Apply thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to outlet shim, mating surface to fuselage skin. (4) Install outlet shim against interior skin and hold in place with several clamp Cleco’s in opening area to secure outlet shim tightly against interior fuselage skin while sealant cures. (5) After sealant cures, remove Cleco’s. Clean off excess sealant with non abrasive scraper. (6) Dry fit check new outlet screens (P/N 133-555055-0001). Do not allow screen to touch any aluminum when installed. (7) Apply thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to outlet shim. Embed new outlet screens (P/N 133-555055-0001) in sealant. Make sure screens are installed so as not to touch any aluminum when installed. (8) Apply thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to left Kydex outlet duct (P/N 133-1301-1). Use new duct if original duct could not be removed without damaging. Refer to Figure 216. (9) Apply thin layer of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to right Kydex outlet duct (P/N133-1300-1). Use new duct if original duct could not be removed without damaging. (10) Install left Kydex outlet duct (P/N133-1301-1) in place. Clean excess sealant from area with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (11) Install right Kydex outlet duct (P/N133-1300-1) in place. Clean excess sealant from area with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (12) After interior sealant is cured, clean excess sealant. (13) Install condenser blower exhaust lower duct assembly on mating flanges. Refer to Figure 214. (14) On aft baggage wall, install four screws to secure condenser blower exhaust duct brackets. (15) Close baggage door (841). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Dimensions and Areas (TO 1T-6ABD-2-6), 06-50-00. (16) Install access panel (862). Refer to 06-50-00. (17) Apply fillet seal with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) around edge of ECS opening on exterior skin. (18) Touch up any bare exterior aluminum with alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). (19) Apply two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to the exterior repair areas. (20) Apply two coats of topcoat paint to the primed areas, and fillet seal areas. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (21) Make appropriate log book entries noting the kit number and serial number installed. Procedure NOTE It is permissible to decrease the size of cutout as required limited to the damage of each event. Skin crack cut out must not exceed shaded area. NOTE The maximum gap allowed between the rub strip pieces on the aft edge to the rub strips running on the right and left sides is 0.24 inch. FAIRINGS 53-40-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to fuselage fairings. Each part called out in a fuselage fairings figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications: (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 FUSELAGE FAIRINGS 53-40-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in the fairings and ventral fin, such as dents, gouges, scratches and pitting are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 201 Jun 29/20 FUSELAGE FAIRINGS 53-40-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-02. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. A. Repair of Ventral Fin Inspect ventral fin for serviceability before performing repair procedure. Refer to Repair Limitations. (1) Remove paint in affected area plus surrounding 2-1/2 inches. (2) Remove damaged skin using skin knife and high speed router. NOTE If core is not damaged, continue with Step (8). (3) Remove damaged core using high speed router and fixture as required. NOTE Do not allow router bit to remove original bond line; if bit cuts through to metal opposite side, then prepare bare metal for bonding using etcher (2, Table 1, 53-00-00). Refer to MIL-HDBK-337. (4) Cut replacement piece of core from phenolic core having same cell size. (5) Install replacement core with same core direction as original and bond using adhesive (3, Table 1, 53-00-00) in place, 1/4 inch higher than skin. (6) Secure core in place with vacuum bag or C-clamps. (7) After cured, cut phenolic core flush with skin using high speed router. (8) If no core damage is present, manufacture filler from 0.020 sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). (9) Manufacture doubler from 0.025 sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Doubler must overlap cutout by 2 inches. Chamfer edges facing ventral fin. (10) Prepare filler and internal doubler skin with etcher (2, Table 1, 53-00-00). Refer to MIL-HDBK-337. (11) Bond filler and doubler in place using adhesive (3, Table 1, 53-00-00). Use vacuum bag for pressure and pull 20 in. Hg minimum pressure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (12) Drill drain hole same size and location as original. (13) Treat bare aluminum with alodine (6, Table 1, 53-00-00), primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00), and paint topcoat (8, Table 1, 53-00-00). B. Removal of Ventral Fin (1) Remove fasteners on each side of ventral through steel angles and ventral fin. CAUTION Do not exceed 200 F when heating adhesive for removal. CAUTION When removing ventral fin, make sure no damage occurs to underlying skin. (2) Heat joint between ventral fin and steel angles to 180-200 F to release adhesive. Using thin knife, cut through adhesive to release parts. Remove old adhesive from steel attaching angles while adhesive is still hot. (3) Scuff sand inside of angles where ventral fin attaches. (4) Clean surfaces with alcohol (9, Table 1, 53-00-00) and allow to air dry. C. Installation of Ventral Fin (1) Insert ventral fin in mating surface of fuselage. NOTE During installation, make sure ventral fin maintains like vertical position as the ventral fin that was removed. (2) Drill 0.129-0.132-inch holes through steel angles into ventral fin skins and install new rivets. If holes are oversized, drill to 0.160-0.164 inch for next size rivet (14 or 15, Table 1, 53-00-00). Treat bare metal. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (3) Clean ventral fin and steel angle areas to be bonded with alcohol (9, Table 1, 53-00-00) and allow to air dry. (4) Mix glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-3% by weight with adhesive (10 or 12, Table 10, 51-30-01) prior to application. (5) Apply adhesive (10 or 12, Table 10, 51-30-01) to inside of steel angles. (6) Insert ventral fin between steel attaching angles and install rivets (14 or 15, Table 1, 53-00-00). (7) Remove excess adhesive. (8) Treat bare aluminum with alodine (6, Table 1, 53-00-00), primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00), and paint topcoat (8, Table 1, 53-00-00). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 D. Re-bonding Dorsal Ribs (1) Remove dorsal door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-20-03. (2) Prepare bonding surfaces as follows: (a) Scuff sand dorsal and rib surfaces with 180-grit sandpaper (17, Table 10, 51-30-01). Remove all prior adhesive. (b) Clean dorsal and rib surfaces with alcohol (9, Table 1, 53-00-00). Surfaces shall be clean, free of dirt, oils, and other contaminating materials. (c) Allow to air dry before applying adhesive. (3) Use scrim cloth (13, Table 1, 53-00-00) to control bondline thickness. (4) Apply adhesive (28, Table 1, 53-00-00) and assemble rib to dorsal. (5) Hold rib in position until adhesive cures to handling strength. (6) Install dorsal door. Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-53, 53-20-03. E. Dorsal Skin Repair NOTE Dorsal skin repair limitations: Do not exceed maximum trim dimensions of 2.50 inches by 0.70 inch. (1) Carefully de-rivet existing fasteners as required to complete steps indicated below. Make sure to not oversize existing holes and to not damage any surrounding and underlying structures. CAUTION Do not exceed 150 °F when apply heat to dorsal rib. Damage to inside mold line (IML) may occur. (a) As required, heat and remove dorsal rib. (2) Ream or slot out crack damage through laminate assembly as shown in Figure 201 (Sheet 1). Remove crack damage. Use caution to not damage any adjacent structure. (3) Visually inspect laminate assembly around discrepancy. Make sure crack is removed and no additional damage exists. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (4) Fabricate fiberglass (3, Table 6, 51-30-01) repair plies (P1 and P2) per requirements in Table 201 and Figure 201 (Sheet 1). Make sure minimum overlap requirements are met for each. Refer to Table 201. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 204 Jun 29/20 (5) Use sandpaper (17, Table 10, 51-30-01), and scuff-sand surfaces of laminate assembly for bonding. Remove glaze from surfaces of laminate assembly, but do not allow any fibers to be broken. (6) Use cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01), and solvent wipe surface with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), isopropyl alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01), solvent solution of 50% distilled or deionized water (10, Table 10, 51-30-01) and 50% isopropyl alcohol (by volume), or naphtha (6, Table 1, 51-30-01). Repeat as necessary until surface is free of dust, oil, fingerprints, powder from sanding, and other contamination. Before solvent is allowed to dry, dry wipe with clean cheesecloth. (7) Prepare adhesive (9, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions for mixing and specific application instructions. (8) Apply adhesive to laminate assembly's inner surface layup area. (9) Install repair ply (P1) on laminate assembly's inner surface. Refer to Tables 201 and Figure 201 (Sheet 1). Make sure ply orientation is correct. (10) Using squeegee, apply pressure and remove all air, excess resin, and wrinkles. (11) Mix a small amount of adhesive with finely chopped fiberglass matting (material code - WF) to make a paste that will not flow. Fill discrepant slotted hole with paste. (12) Apply adhesive to laminate assembly on outer surface layup area. (13) Install repair ply (P2) on laminate assembly of outer surface. Refer to Tables 201 and Figure 201 (Sheet 1). Make sure ply orientation is correct. (14) Using squeegee, apply pressure and remove all air, excess resin, and wrinkles. (15) Allow repair to cure. Refer to adhesive instructions from manufacturer. (16) Clean surface of repair area by lightly sanding, as required. (17) Inspect layups for discrepancies per requirements of Step (3). (18) Reassemble with same type and size fasteners removed in Step (1) as required. (a) Reinstall dorsal rib from Step (1) (a) using adhesive (9, Table 5, 51-30-01), mixed with 0.007 / 0.015 inch diameter glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) with a weight of 2-5%. (19) Refinish to match, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. Table 201 - Repair Layup Configuration Ply Number Orientation Ply Overlap Material Code 1. P1 0 ±20 2.0 Inch Minimum Woven Fiber (WF) 2. P2 0 ±20 2.0 Inch Minimum WF MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 F. Dorsal Rib (133-640003-7/-9/-29) Repair NOTE Cracks are limited to the rib flange and radius. Refer to Figure 201 (Sheet 2), Section B-B for typical cracking. NOTE Doubler must overlap rib by minimum 1.00 inch. Trimming material away from rib web is not permitted. (1) Use 20X magnification to locate and mark ends of cracks. (2) Carefully, trim out crack damage in dorsal rib as shown in Figure 201 (Sheet 2). Remove crack damage. Use caution, and do not damage any adjacent structure. (3) Deburr all sharp edges. (4) Use 20X magnification to make sure all cracks have been removed and no cracks remain. (5) For (P/N 133-640003-7/-29) ribs, procure (from Textron Aviation) repair doublers (P/N SR-TS-00072-1) left and/or (P/N SR-TS-00072-2) right. Refer to Figure 202 (Sheet 2). (6) For (P/N 133-640003-9) ribs, procure (from Textron Aviation) repair doublers (P/N SR-TS-00072-3) left and/or (P/N SR-TS-00072-4) right. Refer to Figure 202 (Sheet 2). NOTE Do not trim aft edges of repair doubles. Only permissible to trim upper and inboard edges. (7) Trim repair doublers (P/N SR-TS-00072-1) left, (P/N SR-TS-00072-2) right, (P/N SR-TS-00072-3) left and/or (SR-TS-00072-4) right to fit. (8) Install repair parts in place using adhesive (7 or 13, Table 10, 51-30-01) mixed and applied. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (a) Fill any gaps between inside mold line (IML) of skin assembly and rib with additional adhesive. (b) If repair doublers have been trimmed, make sure edges of doubler are re-sealed using excess adhesive. G. Removal of Dorsal Fin (1) Position jack (6, Table 1, 07-00-00) under tail jack pad. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Lifting and Shoring (TO 1T-6ABD-2-7), 07-10-00. (2) Remove access panels (862, 320, and 311AS), as required. (3) Remove dorsal door (320). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-20-03. (4) Remove screws and open baggage compartment upper panel (841AT). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 206 Jun 29/20 (5) Remove screws from exhaust duct brackets and remove upper and lower condenser exhaust ducts. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Air Conditioning (TO 1T-6ABD-2-21), 21-50-02, Figure 201. (6) Remove four screws, two each side, securing dorsal fin to vertical stabilizer. CAUTION Use extreme caution when removing dorsal fin sealer. Do not gouge or damage the aluminum fuselage skin. (7) Carefully trim and remove sealer from around dorsal fin on aft fuselage skin. Take care not to gouge or damage aluminum fuselage skin. (8) Use 2-inch diameter, 180 grit, sanding disc and sand top of each (P/N 132269A4) rivet head to remove surface finish down to lock ring in rivet head. Make sure to keep top of rivet head flat. (9) Use #30 drill bit and drill center stem of each rivet deep enough to remove lock ring. CAUTION Use extreme caution when driving the stems out of the rivets. Do not elongate rivet holes or damage the aluminum fuselage skin. (10) Use 1/16-inch drift punch and 8-ounce ball peen hammer to carefully drive rivet stems out of rivets. CAUTION Prevent foreign object entry into fuselage interior. Use tape, rags, and all means possible to collect all pieces of each rivet during rivet removal. (11) Use #30 drill bit and drill head of (P/N 132269A4) rivets. Take care not to drill into the material beneath rivet heads. CAUTION Use a bucking bar to back up the frame flanges at all points where the dorsal fin attaching rivets intersect with stringer and frame flanges. Failure to do so, while driving out the rivets, can result in bent or damaged frame flanges. (12) Use 1/8-inch drift punch and 8-ounce ball peen hammer to carefully drive rivet butts out of structure. Rivet butts should drive out easily. CAUTION Relax elevator cable tensions as necessary. Do not lie on tensioned elevator cables. Damage may result to the elevator control system or the surrounding aircraft structure. (13) Collect all rivet butts and rivet stems from aft fuselage. (14) Make dorsal fin separation tool as follows: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 207 Jun 29/20 (a) Wrap one end of safety wire (36, Table 10, 51-30-01) around a wooden dowel to serve as a handle. (b) Wrap opposite end of safety wire around a second wooden dowel to serve as a handle. NOTE Apply heat to sealed surfaces to aid the release of cured sealant. (15) Use heat gun and heat flange area to approximately 120 °F. Stay ahead of work area by 12-inches. (16) While heating dorsal fin flange, grasp both handles and pull safety wire between dorsal fin and aluminum structure. Always keep safety wire parallel to work surface. Work through dorsal door (320) opening. Start at vertical stabilizer and dorsal fin interface and work safety wire between dorsal fin flange and vertical stabilizer leading edge. (17) As safety wire pulls through cured sealant, separating dorsal fin from aircraft structure, insert wooden tongue depressors between dorsal fin flange and aircraft structure behind safety wire. (18) After entire left side of dorsal has been separated, apply heat to right flange and work aft. Remove wooden tongue depressors on left side as safety wire approaches, and install them on right side just behind safety wire. (19) When dorsal fin separates from aircraft structure, lift up and aft simultaneously to clear Emergency Locator Transmitter (ELT) antenna. CAUTION Use extreme caution when removing dorsal fin sealer. Do not scratch or damage the aluminum fuselage skin. (20) Use plastic scraper and solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) to remove all traces of cured sealant from aircraft structure. Take care not to scratch or damage aluminum fuselage skin. (21) Use indigo blue pencil to mark rear two holes on right and left sides with two long extension lines that intersect centerline of holes. Make sure extension lines will be visible and extend beyond flanges of new dorsal fin when set in place. This will aid in ensuring proper placement of new dorsal fin and maintaining required edge distance. (22) Use indigo blue pencil to mark a minimum edge distance line along dorsal fin lower flange on bottom side. This line will later be used to back drill holes through fuselage. H. Installation of Dorsal Fin (1) Position dorsal fin onto aircraft. Make sure ELT antenna is properly positioned through lightning hole in dorsal fin rib. Lower dorsal fin down and forward simultaneously into position. (2) Position leading edge of dorsal fin over existing holes in fuselage. Install #40 Cleco's from under side of fuselage. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 208 Jun 29/20 NOTE Installing the Cleco's from the under side of fuselage allows the dorsal fin to be secured with the 17 #40 pre-drilled holes in the dorsal fin, through the #30 diameter existing holes in the aircraft skin. The dorsal fin holes will be drilled to full size in a later step. (3) Measure marks previously made on aft two holes on left and right sides. Determine if dorsal fin will have required edge distance and if fit is correct at vertical stabilizer leading edge and lower flanges. Excessive gaps between new dorsal fin and aircraft structure are not permitted. Dorsal fin should fit square on aircraft structure. Refer to Figure 202. (4) Locate and drill aft four holes in dorsal fin (2 each side). Step drill to #30 and install #30 Cleco’s. CAUTION Relax elevator cable tensions as necessary. Do not lie on tensioned elevator cables. Damage may result to the elevator control system or the surrounding aircraft structure. (5) Before drilling holes, make sure edge distance line, that was previously drawn on bottom side of lower dorsal fin flange, is either in line with existing hole or is outboard of it on both sides. (6) Back drill holes through all point locations (stringer and frame flange intersections) from fuselage interior. Make sure to keep drill perpendicular to hole when drilling. Drill all point locations to #30 and install #30 Cleco's. (7) Back drill remainder of holes in left and right side flanges. Secure with Cleco's every fourth hole. CAUTION The two full size holes in Frame 6 are inaccessible from the fuselage interior to back drill. Do not use a hole finder for these last two holes. The hole finder can cause a misalignment in the holes after the hole finder is removed and the parts are re-mated. (8) Remove #40 Cleco's one at a time. Enlarge holes to #30. (9) Remove Cleco's and dorsal fin. Place 2-inch square piece of masking tape on the lower surface of dorsal fin bottom flange. (10) Insert two MB4 rivets into two holes at frame 6. (11) Install dorsal fin and secure with Cleco's. (12) Remove dorsal door (320). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-20-03. (13) For the two full size holes at Frame 6, use a wooden dowel and hammer. Place wooden dowel over missing holes at Frame 6 and gently strike dowel with hammer. (14) Use an awl to mark last four holes in dorsal fin through vertical stabilizer leading edge holes accessible through dorsal door (320) opening. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 53-40-00 Page 209 Jun 29/20 (15) Use 1 and 2-inch masking tape to mask off around edge of dorsal fin, setting back approximately 3/16-inch constant. CAUTION Take care not to the let drill bit or holes drift. Damage to aircraft structure or dorsal fin could result from misaligned holes. (16) Remove dorsal fin. Locate two marks on masking tape. Carefully drill holes first with a #40 drill then drill to full size #30 drill. (17) Locate four locations marked inside the dorsal fin at the vertical stabilizer leading edge. Step drill starting with #40, then to final size 0.200/0.250 inch. (18) Remove two MB4 rivets inserted in Step (10). (19) Debur fuselage and dorsal fin. (20) Thoroughly clean mating surfaces. (21) Apply a thin, even coat of sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to fuselage and vertical stabilizer leading edge mating surface. (22) Apply a thin, even coat of sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01) to mating surface of dorsal fin. (23) Position dorsal fin onto aircraft. Make sure ELT antenna is properly positioned through lightning hole in dorsal fin rib. Lower dorsal fin down and forward simultaneously into position. Secure using #30 Cleco's. (24) Install all fasteners wet with sealant (3, Table 7, 51-30-01). (25) Fair sealant squeeze-out using tongue depressor or equivalent. (26) Clean up all excess sealant and remove masking tape. (27) Inspect and clean aft fuselage. (28) Install dorsal door (320). Refer to TO 1T-6ABD-2-53, 53-20-03. (29) Install upper and lower condenser exhaust ducts. Install screws to secure exhaust duct brackets. (30) Set elevator cable tensions and check elevator travel if elevator cable tension previously lowered. Perform elevator Rigging, as required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-00. (31) Install access panels (862, 320, and 311AS), as required. (32) Apply anti-static coating to dorsal fin. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00. 54-00-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. GENERAL This chapter contains information and structural parts breakdowns applicable to the engine cowling structure and skins. Refer to Figure 00-01. The chapter consists of one section: • Engine cowlings: Removable sections. Refer to 54-20-00. Specific structural inspection, damage limitations, and repair criteria applicable to cowlings are contained in this chapter. 2. INSPECTION The cowlings are inspected for dents, cracks, loose or missing rivets, and corrosion on a regularly scheduled basis in accordance with the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-6). Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of the damage and required repairs. Refer to 51-10-00. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to engine cowlings. Each part called out in the engine cowling figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 101 Jun 05/17 NACELLE 54-20-0054-20-00 ENGINE COWLINGS 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in engine cowling sheet metal skins, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. 2. WEAR LIMITATIONS Bolt head may be imprinted on face of receptacle on lower aft cowling to a maximum depth of 0.016 inch. Refer to 54-20-05, Item 61. Diameter of pin guide must be maximum of 0.454 inch. Refer to 54-20-02, Item 46. Forward upper cowling safety latch may exhibit signs of wear along surface of latch arm adjacent to hook. If wear exceeds 0.050 inch depth, replace safety latch. If present, check pushbutton for security and tightness and look for wear on mounting rivet in center of button. If button is loose and there is visible wear to rivet, replace safety latch. Refer to 54-20-01, Item 23. NOTE Pushbutton wear limitations apply to safety latch (P/N HA330-3) only. A. Cowling Gap Limitations NOTE Use the following procedure to determine if cowling gaps are within serviceable limitations. (1) Record each cowling gap width measurement e, perpendicular to air flow, that exceeds 0.060 inch and add the total lengths b. Refer to Figures 101 through 103. NOTE Cowling parallel gaps are not used for this procedure. (2) If total length of cowling gaps b is less than 116 inches, no further action is required and cowling is serviceable. (3) If total length of cowling gaps b is more than 116 inches, measure depth h and length b of each exceeding cowling gap. Multiply h x b and sum the results. NOTE If depth (h) cannot be measured, use cowling skin thickness for (h) value. (4) If the total of all h x b areas is less than 5 square inches, no further action is required and cowling is serviceable. (5) If the total of all gap areas is more than 5 square inches, contact cognizant authority. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. 2. REPAIR OF NOSE LANDING GEAR LONGERON A. Procedure (1) Remove aft and forward brackets from nose landing gear longeron. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Remove rivets from nut plates and remove nut plates from nose landing gear longeron. (3) Remove bolts and washers from nose landing gear longeron. (4) Perform eddy current inspection general procedure on nose landing gear longeron to determine end of cracks prior to stop-drilling. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01. If cracks radiate more than 0.75 inch from bracket upper fastener or extend within 0.25-inch radius of other fasteners, report findings to cognizant authority for further disposition. (5) Using 0.125-inch drill bit, stop-drill ends of cracks. (6) Make repair doubler from 0.063-inch sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) with width of doubler to be from tangency to tangency. Trim channel doubler to clear upper, aft existing rivet as shown in Figure 201 and 203. (7) Cut two pieces of 132440 or 131966 extrusion to length of the width of repair doubler. Refer to 51-30-03, Figure 1. Cut both 131966 extrusions to 3/4 X 3/4 to length of width of repair doubler. NOTE Trimming of 131966 extrusion to 3/4 X 3/4 may not be required provided no interference exists and adequate rivet edge distance is maintained. (8) Prepare surfaces to be bonded by scuff sanding with sandpaper (11, Table 10, 51-30-01). (9) Clean all surfaces to be bonded using alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Surfaces must be free of dust, dirt, oil, and other contaminants. Allow alcohol to air dry prior to applying locking compound. (10) Bond repair doubler and extrusion using sealant (7, Table 7, 51-30-01). (11) Apply alodine (1, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material on new doubler, extrusion, and brackets. (12) Apply primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to alodine-treated areas. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (13) As required, trim skin to provide clearance for three rivets above gear door brackets. Only remove enough material to allow installation of rivets. Refer to Figure 201. (14) Install forward and aft brackets using pin (20, Table 10, 51-30-01) with length of 0.125-0.178 inch (#5), 0.188-0.249 inch (#6), or 0.250-0.314 inch (#7) and collar (21, Table 10, 51-30-01). Install all other fasteners with length to be determined at installation. (15) If nut plate installed as shown in Figure 202, trim aft extrusion to 0.30 inch from pin centerline to clear nut plate. (16) Using rivets (26, Table 10, 51-30-01), install nut plate (25, Table 10, 51-30-01). (17) Install washer (24, Table 10, 51-30-01) and nut (22, Table 10, 51-30-01) onto bolt (23, Table 10, 51-30-01), and install bolt into nut plate. NOTE Fastener installation must be spaced evenly and in line as much as possible. Minimum edge distance of 0.190 inch allowed for upper and lower edge fasteners. (18) Deburr all sharp edges and break all sharp corners. 3. REPAIR OF LEFT AND RIGHT FORWARD LOWER MID COWLING FRAME WEB A. Procedure NOTE Minimum cracking from formed radius in frame allowed is 0.1 inch. NOTE This repair applies to cracking in the forward lower cowling mid frame web only (left and right side, P/N 133-910086-3/-19). Refer to Figure 205 and Figure 208. (1) Carefully drill out fastener locations. Remove and discard existing damaged doublers (P/N 133-910086-7/-11). Use caution to make sure fastener holes are not damaged. (2) Using either fluorescent penetrant or eddy current nondestructive inspection (NDI) techniques, locate and mark ends of cracks: (a) Eddy current inspection refer to: Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (3) Cut out existing cracks as indicated in Figure 205 and Figure 208. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on existing fasteners. Maintain 0.25 inch minimum radius. Trim 0.10 inch beyond end of crack. Do not cut into formed radius in frame. (4) Deburr all sharp edges. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (5) Using either fluorescent penetrant or eddy current nondestructive inspection (NDI) techniques, make sure no cracks remain and no cracks have formed: (a) Eddy current inspection refer to: Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (6) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with repair. (7) Make (P/N SR-TS-00007-1/-2) left and right repair angles as shown in Figures 205 and 208. Make from 1.00 inch thick plate metal, (37, Table 10, 51-30-01) or 1.00 inch thick plate metal, (39, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 207 and Figure 210. Skim machine 0.025 inch off all faces before machining to final dimensions from one side to prevent distortion of final part. (8) Use 0.040 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) and make (P/N SR-TS-00007-3/-4) repair filler. Match cutout. Refer to Figure 205 and Figure 208. (9) Crack check, using Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) or Eddy current. Refer to Step (5). Make sure no cracks have formed in machined repair parts. If cracks are found, discard and make new. (10) Obtain new undrilled frame doublers (P/N 133-910086-7 /-11) to replace existing if damaged. (11) Layout and pre-assemble new (P/N SR-TS-00007-1/-2) repair angles to frame assemblies as shown in Figures 205 and 208. (12) Permissible to trim upper end of new repair angles to allow clearance between (P/N 133-910086-13/-15) supports and repair angles. Maintain minimum 0.030 inch gap. (a) If trimmed, re-check for cracks, using Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) or Eddy current. Refer to Step (5). Make sure no cracks have formed in machined repair parts. If cracks are found, discard and make new. (13) Drill new fastener positions and to match existing. Refer to Figure 205, Figure 208, and 51-40-00. Maintain a minimum 2D edge distance on all fasteners and 4D to 6D spacing on all new fasteners. (14) Deburr all sharp edges. (15) Cold bond repair angles and new frame doublers using cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01), or equivalent. Mix with glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-5% by weight to control bond line. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 (16) Alodine and prime all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (17) Install fasteners as indicated in Figures 205 and 208. Refer to 51-40. Install blind fasteners wet using cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. NOTE If fasteners have been removed from skin to gain access to the frame, they must be replaced using NAS1097AD4 or CR3214-4 rivets. 4. REPAIR OF LEFT AND RIGHT FORWARD LOWER MID COWLING FRAME WEB AND FLANGE A. Procedure NOTE This repair applies to cracking in the forward lower cowling mid frame web and flange (left and right side, P/N 133-910086-3/-19). Refer to Figure 206 and Figure 209. (1) Carefully drill out fastener locations. Remove and discard existing damaged doublers (P/N 133-910086-7/-11). Use caution to make sure fastener holes are not damaged. (2) Using either fluorescent penetrant or eddy current nondestructive inspection (NDI) techniques, locate and mark ends of cracks: (a) Eddy current inspection refer to: Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (3) Cut out existing cracks as indicated in Figures 206 and 209. Section of frame outer flange is completely removed, removing 3 fastener holes from outer flange. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on existing fasteners. Maintain 0.25 inch minimum radius. Trim 0.10 inch beyond end of crack. (4) Deburr all sharp edges. (5) Using either fluorescent penetrant or eddy current nondestructive inspection (NDI) techniques, make sure no cracks remain and no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection refer to: Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 (c) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) refer to: ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (6) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with repair. (7) Make (P/N SR-TS-00007-1/-2) left and right repair angles as shown in Figures 206 and 209. Make from 1.00 inch thick plate (37, Table 10, 51-30-01) or 1.00 inch thick plate (39, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 207 and Figure 210. Skim machine 0.025 inch off all faces before machining to final dimensions from one side to prevent distortion of final part. (8) Make (SR-TS-00007-3/-4) left and right repair filler. Make from 0.040 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01), minimum bend radius 0.16 inch. Alternatively, make from 0.040 thick sheet metal, (44, Table 10, 51-30-01), heat treat to T42 per SAE AMS2770. Profile to match cutout as shown in Figures 206 and 209. (9) Make (SR-TS-00007-5/-6) shims from 0.040 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) or 0.040 inch thick sheet metal, (58, Table 10, 51-30-01). Maintain 0.03 to 0.05 gap between shim outer edges and adjacent parts. Alternatively, make from 0.040 thick sheet metal, (44, Table 10, 51-30-01), heat treat to T42 per SAE AMS2770. Profile to match cutout. Refer to Figures 206 and 209. (10) Make (SR-TS-00007-7/-8) left and right repair angles as shown in Figures 206 and 209. Using 0.040 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) minimum bend radius 0.16 inch. Alternatively, make from 0.040 thick sheet metal, (44, Table 10, 51-30-01), minimum bend radius 0.06 inch, heat treat to T42 per SAE AMS2770, after forming. Alternatively, manufacture section using a new, undrilled frame. Refer to (PN 133-910086-3/-19) (11) Crack check, using Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) or eddy current. Refer to Step (5). Make sure no cracks have formed in machined repair parts. If cracks are found, discard and make new. (12) Obtain new undrilled frame doublers (P/N 133-910086-7 /-11) to replace existing if damaged. (13) Layout and pre-assemble new (P/N SR-TS-00007-1/-2) repair angles to frame assemblies as shown in Figures 206 and 209. (14) Permissible to trim upper end of new repair angles to allow clearance between (P/N 133-910086-13/-15) supports and repair angles. Maintain minimum 0.030 inch gap. (a) If trimmed, re-check for cracks, using Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI) or Eddy current. Refer to Step (5). Make sure no cracks have formed in machined repair parts. If cracks are found, discard and make new. (15) Drill new fastener positions and to match existing. Refer to Figures 206 and 209 and 51-40-00. Maintain a minimum 2D edge distance on all fasteners and 4D to 6D spacing on all new fasteners. (16) Deburr all sharp edges. (17) Cold bond repair angles and new frame doublers using cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01), or equivalent. Mix with glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-5% by weight to control bond line. Refer to Manufacturer’s instructions. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 206 Jun 01/21 (18) Alodine and prime all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (19) Install fasteners as indicated in Figures 206 and 209. Refer to 51-40. Install blind fasteners wet using cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. NOTE If fasteners have been removed from skin to gain access to the frame, they must be replaced using NAS1097AD4 or CR3214-4 rivets. 5. REPAIR OF AFT UPPER COWLING A. Procedure NOTE Repair the aft upper cowling when paint and filler chip away exposing the ECS inlet duct. Repair only if the exposed area is not soft. (1) Clean ECS duct inlet exposed area and surrounding areas using lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01) moistened with alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 204. Surfaces must be free of dust, dirt, oil, and other contaminants. Allow alcohol to air dry prior to applying filler. (2) Apply filler (1, Table 6, 51-30-01, or 10, Table 10, 51-30-01, or 12, Table 10, 51-30-01) as required. Make sure surface exposed to airflow is smooth. (3) Apply one coat of anti-static coating (4, Table 6, 51-30-01) to repaired section. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. NOTE Allow anti-static coating to dry at least 24 hours. (4) Check resistance for 100-100,000 ohms. 6. LOWER FORWARD COWLING, AFT FRAME, UPPER LEFT CORNER OF OIL COOLER INLET REPAIR A. Procedure NOTE If cracks are 0.50 inch or less in length. Refer to Figure 211 for repair information. NOTE If cracks are greater than 0.50 inch in length. Refer to Figure 212 for repair information. (1) Carefully dis-assemble, de-rivet, or remove structure as required. Take care not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and underlying structures. (2) Carefully remove and retain oil cooler inlet (P/N 133-910090-1). Take care not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and underlying structures. (3) Use one of the following methods to locate and mark end of cracks: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 207 Jun 01/21 (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. (4) As required, carefully cut out damage. Refer to Figure 211 or Figure 212, Section A-A. Make sure cut lines are 0.10 inch minimum from end of cracks. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance to adjacent fasteners. Maintain minimum 0.25 inch radius. Use caution to make sure underlying structure is not damaged. (5) Deburr all sharp edges. (6) Use one of the following methods to inspect area. Make sure no cracks have formed or remain: (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (7) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with repair.
