SHEDDER SCREEN REPLACEMENT/REPAIR NOTE This replacement/repair procedure applies to the engine inlet shedder screen, lower aft cowling area, with part number 133-910116-5. A. Removal (1) Remove lower aft cowling. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-05. (2) As required, drill out fasteners to remove shedder screen. CAUTION Do not exceed 180  F when applying heat to shedder screen and lower aft cowling. Damage to aircraft may occur. (3) As required, apply heat to remove shedder screen from cowling. Refer to Figure 213. (4) Clean any remaining sealant from mating surfaces using nonmetallic scraper. (5) As required, remove corrosion from flanges. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (6) As required, remove corrosion from forward frame (P/N 133-910116-3). NOTE After all corrosion is removed and affected material is blended and smoothed, measure remaining material thickness. Make sure to determine if flange is serviceable as follows: (a) If flange thickness is greater than or equal to 0-045 inch, clean surface, apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01), then apply two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (b) If flange is less than 0.045 inch thick, replace frame with (P/N 133-910116-3). B. Installation (1) Drill pilot holes out to 0.128-0.133 inch. (2) Scuff surface with scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01) and clean surface using solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), using two-cloth wipe method outlined below: NOTE Do not try to clean a large area all at once. Cleaning a large area can allow solvent to evaporate, leaving the surface contaminated. Do not use red shop rags or laundered rags for cleaning. (a) To reduce the possibility of leaving lint, use cheesecloths (1, Table 10, 51-30-01), folded so edges are not exposed. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 217 Jun 01/21 (b) Dampen one cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) with solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Make sure cheesecloth is not dampened with excess solvent causing drips. CAUTION Cleaning solvents should never be poured or sprayed on structure because of the possibility that solvent can enter between layers of structure, and then flow into unwanted areas, causing contamination to surfaces being sealed. (c) Wipe area to be sealed with dampened cheesecloth. Before solvent evaporates, immediately wipe area again with second clean, dry cheesecloth. (d) Repeat cleaning until there is no discoloration on the dry cheesecloth. Use new clean, dry cheesecloth each time. (e) Use extreme care in cleaning all hard-to-reach areas (corners, gaps, drilled holes, etc.) Paint brushes, cotton tipped swabs, or pipe cleaners (3, 7, or 8 Table 10, 51-30-01) may be required to clean hard-to-reach areas. After surfaces, fasteners, etc. are thoroughly cleaned, white cotton gloves (2, Table 10, 51-30-01) should be worn when handling cleaned items to prevent contamination. (3) Clean edge of screen with scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01) and clean surface using solvent (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), using damp cloth, dry cloth method wipe method outlined above. NOTE If another sealant manufacturer is selected, use their recommended adhesion promoter. (4) Apply adhesion promoter (P/N PR-148) used with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) on surface of screen that will mate with the angle bracket and allow to cure. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. NOTE Screen must be stretched tight and lay flat during fitment and installation. (5) Lay down a piece of poly film and stretch new screen tightly to full size. (6) Apply sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) to area being treated with adhesion promoter. Make sure wires are coated thoroughly. Allow sealant to cure. NOTE Allow sealant to fully cure between applications to act as a barrier. (7) Use sealant roller to apply a thin bead of sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01) on entire mating surface of cowling angles. NOTE Screen must be stretched tight and lay flat during fitment and installation. (8) Position screen assembly in cowling, wet with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01), secure with temporary fasteners (Clecos). Allow screen to cure in place. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 218 Jun 01/21 (9) Remove Clecos and install fasteners (P/N NASM20470AD-4) wet with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01). Permissible to use alternate fasteners wet with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01). Refer to Paragraph 7.C., Alternate Fastener and Collar Installation. (10) Install lower aft cowling. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-05. (11) Allow sealant to cure, per manufacturer's recommendations, prior to returning aircraft to service. C. Alternate Fastener and Collar Installation NOTE In order to adequately protect the pin and collar. This procedure applies to installing the HL12-5 Hi-Loks (Titanium) and HL198-5 collars. NOTE The recommended fasteners for long-term repair are HL12-5 Hi-Loks (Titanium) and HL198-5 collars. (1) Clean new pins and collars with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), or isopropyl alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Allow to thoroughly dry. (2) Apply primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00) to fastener pin heads and shanks only. Do not apply primer to threads. (3) Apply primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00) to collars. Do not apply primer to threads. (4) After fastener primer is completely dry, install HL20-5 pins in 0.164-0.168 inch holes wet with sealant (5, Table 7, 51-30-01). Do not apply sealer on threads. (5) After pins and collars are installed, prime pin heads and collars with epoxy primer (7, Table 1, 53-00-00). 13. REPAIR OF LOWER FORWARD COWLING, LEFT AND RIGHT UPPER CORNER CRACK A. Procedure NOTE Perform this procedure to repair sheet metal cracks on the lower forward cowling skin, upper forward corner. Refer to Figure 214. (1) Use one of the following methods to locate and mark end of cracks: (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 219 Jun 01/21 (2) Carefully cut out cracking from skin as shown in Figure 214. Remove minimum material necessary and take care not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. Trim 0.10 inch beyond ends of cracking. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on existing fasteners and maintain minimum 0.25 inch radius. (a) For right side repair, heat can be applied to the adhesive to help separation of cracked aluminum skin section from composite fairing. Heat application must be local and limited in duration. A hot knife is the preferred tool for this. Apply hot knife at 30 second intervals, do not exceed temperature of 250 F. (3) Deburr all sharp edges. (4) Use one of the following methods to inspect area. Make sure no cracks have formed or remain: (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures for Use on Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (5) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with repair. (6) For left side repair use the following procedures: (a) Make repair filler (P/N SR-TS-ATA71-16278-1) as shown in Figure 214 (Sheet 1), Detail B. Make from 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (74, Table 10, 51-30-01). Form to match contour. Alternate material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). NOTE If sheet metal (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) is used, crack check per Step (4)(b). If cracks are found, discard and make new. (b) Make repair angle (SR-TS-ATA71-16278-2) as shown in Figure 214 (Sheet 1), Detail B. Make from 0.050 inch thick sheet metal (58, Table 10, 51-30-01). Form to match contour. Heat treat to T62 condition per SAE AMS2770 after forming. Alternate Material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Maintain minimum 0.20 inch bend radius. Alternate Material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (74, Table 10, 51-30-01). Alternate material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal (44, Table 10, 51-30-01. Heat treat to T42 condition per SAE AMS2770 after forming. Alternate Material: Permissible to make from new cowling skin (P/ N 133-910083-5). (7) For right side repair use the following procedures: (a) As required, make repair filler (SR-TS-ATA71-16278-3). Make from 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (74, Table 10, 51-30-01). Alternate Material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 214 (Sheet 2), Detail C. Form to match contour. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 220 Jun 01/21 NOTE If sheet metal (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) material is used, perform Step (4). If cracks are found, discard and make new. (b) As required, make repair angle (SR-TS-ATA71-16278-4) in Figure 214 (Sheet 2), Detail C. Make from 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (58, Table 10, 51-30-01). Heat treat to T62 condition per SAE AMS2770 after forming. Alternate Material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Maintain minimum 0.20 inch bend radius. Alternate Material: from 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (27, Table 10, 51-30-01) or (74, Table 10, 51-30-01). Alternate material: 0.050 inch thick sheet metal, (44, Table 10, 51-30-01). Heat treat to T42 condition per SAE AMS2770 after forming. Permissible to make from new cowling skin, (P/N 133-910083-5). (8) Drill/ream and countersink all holes as shown in Figure 214. Refer to 51-40-00. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance (measured from center of hole to edge of part) and 4D to 6D spacing on all new fasteners unless noted otherwise (measured from center to center). (9) Deburr all sharp edges. (10) Fill all redundant countersinks with conical washers, bonded in place using adhesive (10 or 12, Table 10, 51-30-01) mixed. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. It is permissible to make conical washers from drilled-off fastener heads of suitable type and size, shave conical washers flush with skin, as required. (11) Protect all bare aluminum with alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-10. (12) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to the repair area. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00. (13) Right side only, make sure composite fairing structure is bonded to the aluminum skin and repair parts. Use adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01) mixed with 0.007-0.015 inch diameter glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) mixed 2 - 5% by weight. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (14) Install repair parts in place using adhesive (7 or 13, Table 10, 51-30-01) mixed and applied. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. Fillet fair in and remove excess adhesive. (15) Install fasteners, length to suit, as shown in Figure 214. Refer to 51-40-00. (16) As required, assemble using same type and size fasteners, length to suit. Refer to 51-40-00. (17) Top coat to match existing, as required. 14. LOWER AFT, ENGINE COWLING, PLENUM WALL, LEFT AND/OR RIGHT OUTBOARD END, BELOW COWL, CRACK REPAIR A. PLENUM PANELS AND COWLING DOORS ANTI-CHAFE REPAIR A. Procedure NOTE This procedure provides instructions to build up areas, as required, where the abrasive- resistant coating/anti-chafing strip applied to interior perimeter of plenum chamber panels and accessory bay engine cowling doors has worn through, or is damaged. These typical repairs apply to plenum panel (821), right plenum panel (822), left cowling door (823), and right cowling door (824) assemblies. NOTE Surfaces to be bonded, cemented or sealed shall be free of dust, dirt, oils, fingerprints, and other surface contaminating materials. (1) Clean all metal surfaces with solvents (4, 6, or 7, Table 1, 51-30-01) or an approved alkaline cleaning solution. The surface may be scuff-sanded as necessary. (2) Apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (3) If required, use epoxy primer surfacer to fill pits at core bevel edge. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (7, Table 3, 20-50-00). Hand sand using sandpaper (69, Table 10, 51-30-01) to remove excess. (4) Apply one coat of polyamide epoxy primer coating (7, Table 3, 51-30-01) to work area and allow to dry. NOTE If adhesive (9, Table 5, 51-30-01) is not readily available, it is acceptable to use adhesive (28, Table 1, 53-00-00). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions for mix ratio, work and cure times. (5) Mix adhesive (9, Table 5, 51-30-01), using a ratio of 100 parts of Uralane 5776-A with 40 parts of Uralane 5776-B by weight. Adhesive (9, Table 5, 51-30-01) has an application time of 35 minutes. (6) Apply a smooth, even coat not to exceed 0.030 inch thick to inner surface periphery of engine cowl panels and doors. Adhesive will cure to handling strength in 24 hours. Full cure takes five to seven days at room temperature. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 224 Jun 01/21 17. AIR CONDITIONING COMPRESSOR FAIRING (P/N 133-910105 -17/-19) MINOR REPAIRS A. Procedure NOTE For cosmetic repairs that do not compromise the carbon fibers and/or Phosphorous Bronze Lightning Strike (PBLS) screen, the following repair can be used. For other types of damage, report findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with repair. NOTE To repair open edge damage, use either adhesive (11, Table 5, 51-30-01) or cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01), mixed with 3-5% by weight of chopped graphite fiber. Refer to TO 1-1-690. (1) Perform a tap test to make sure underlying structure is not soft. Refer to 51-70-05, Paragraph 2, Coin and Sonic Tap Tests. (2) Thoroughly clean pitted area using MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) with cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01) several times until cloth is clean after wiping area. (3) Apply aerodynamic smoother (2, Table 4, 51-30-01) or cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01) to voids. Allow area to cure to manufacturer’s specification. (4) Sand filler smooth and make sure no voids are visible in repair areas. If voids are present, repeat Steps (2) and (3). (5) Thoroughly clean area using MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) with cheesecloth (1, Table 10, 51-30-01). (6) Apply one coat of P900 or equivalent surfacer. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (7) Apply topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). 18. AIR CONDITIONING COMPRESSOR FAIRING (P/N 133-910105 -17/-19) REMOVAL AND INSTALLATION A. Removal (1) Mark original location of fairing on lower forward cowling. (2) Remove paint to expose all fastener heads. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheets 1 and 2). (3) Remove upper forward cowling. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-01. (4) Carefully drill out all fasteners securing fairing (P/N 133-910105 -17 or -19) to lower forward cowling assembly. Do not oversize fastener holes. Retain any washers that were installed with rivets and document locations where washers were installed. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheet 1). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 225 Jun 01/21 CAUTION Do not heat composite or surrounding areas in excess of 180 F. Damage to fairing may occur. (5) Remove fairing from lower forward cowling assembly. Permissible to heat bond line to allow fairing to be removed from lower forward cowling assembly. (6) Clean all remaining adhesive with a non-abrasive scraper from mating surfaces on lower forward cowling assembly. (7) After all adhesive is removed, clean mating surfaces with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). B. Installation (1) With upper forward cowling removed from aircraft, use it as a guide for locating longeron and latch on lower forward cowling. Latch upper forward cowling (4 latches) to secure assembly to lower forward cowling. Fit check new replacement fairing (P/N 133-910105-17/-19) and longeron using pilot holes in part, locate longeron and latch assembly on lower forward cowling per best shop practices. (2) Secure fairing in place and back drill all holes. (3) Mark area to accommodate latch location. (4) Remove fairing from lower forward cowling. (5) Trim area for latch location. Maintain 3D minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (6) Countersink all holes in replacement fairing (P/N 133-910105-17/-19). (7) Temporarily install replacement fairing (P/N 133-910105-17/-19) to make sure all holes line up and latch cut out is proper. Make sure upper cowling assembly can be installed and latched at all 4 locations. Trimming may be required. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheet 1). (8) Apply masking tape to areas of cowling to prevent adhesive contact. (9) Remove upper forward cowling and replacement fairing (P/N 133-910105-17/-19). (10) After all adhesive is removed, clean mating surfaces with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). NOTE It is acceptable to use, adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01) with glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-3% by weight, as an alternative. Mix prior to application. (11) Mix adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01) with glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-5% by weight to control bond line. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (12) Apply a thin bead of cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01) to mating surfaces. (13) Install rivets (71, Table 10, 51-30-01) wet with adhesive cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01), length to suit, make sure locations identified with washers (72, Table 10, 51-30-01) are installed in same locations. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheets 1 and 2). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 54-20-00 Page 226 Jun 01/21 (14) Fillet seal edge of fairing to lower cowling assembly. Refer to 51-20-20, Figure 202. (15) Remove masking tape. (16) Clean excess adhesive from surfaces with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (17) After adhesive is fully cured, trim fairing to fit upper forward cowling. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheet 1). Maintain 3D minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (18) Seal trimmed edges with cold bond adhesive (38, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to Figure 222 (Sheet 3). (19) After cowling is installed, inspect overall area for interference and proper trimming of fairing. (20) Inspect compressor clutch to make sure minimum 0.25 inch clearance is maintained. Refer to Figure 222 (Sheet 4). As required, remove cowling and trim fairing to obtain clearance. Maintain 3D minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (21) Paint air conditioning compressor fairing (P/N 133-910105-17/-19) to match aircraft. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual. (22) Paint surfaces exposed to direct airflow with 528-310 or 10P2-3 anti-static paint. Check resistance for 100 to 100,000 Ohms per MIL-C-83231 after allowing paint to dry at least 24 hours. 19. GENERAL This chapter contains information and structural parts breakdowns applicable to the elevator, rudder, vertical and horizontal stabilizer skins, and internal structure. Refer to Figure 00-01. This chapter consists of four sections: • Horizontal stabilizer: Structure and skins. Refer to 55-10-00. • Elevator: Refer to 55-20-00. • Vertical stabilizer: Structure and skins. Refer to 55-30-00. • Rudder: Refer to 55-40-00. Specific structural inspection, damage limitations, and repair criteria applicable to the stabilizers are contained in this chapter. 2. INSPECTION Stabilizers are inspected for dents, cracks, loose or missing rivets, corrosion, and distortion on a regular scheduled basis, in accordance with the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-6), Section II. Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of the damage. Refer to 51-10-00. 3. CONSUMABLE MATERIALS The consumable materials listed in Table 1 are required to perform maintenance on this system. Table 1 - Consumable Materials Material Specification Product 1. Alodine MIL-DTL-81706A Chemical Conversion Coating 2. Primer MIL-PRF-23377 3. Paint MIL-PRF-85285 4. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to the Horizontal Stabilizer. Each part called out in the horizontal stabilizer figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-10-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 STABILIZERS HORIZONTAL 55-10-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in horizontal stabilizer sheet metal skins, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-10-00 Page 201 Jun 29/20 STABILIZERS HORIZONTAL 55-10-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find designated material. Choosing correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. A. Horizontal Stabilizer Hinge, Temporary Blend Repair (Refer to VSP) NOTE Blend or trim is only allowed on left and right lower flange edge. NOTE Nicks, scratches and/or chafing on the elevator center hinge, left or right flanges, and elevator skin, where depth of damage is less than 0.032 inch diameter deep into parent material may remain in place. This can be measured using 0.032 inch diameter safety wire. NOTE Nicks, scratches and/or chafing on the elevator center hinge, left or right flanges and elevator skin, where depth of damage is more than 0.032 inch diameter deep into parent material shall have permanent trim repair accomplished. Refer to Sections 1.B and 1.C. NOTE Blending is only a temporary repair. Permanent trim repair shall be accomplished at next available downtime, Phase, or Postflight Inspection. NOTE Nick, scratches, signs of chafing, or loss of primer and/or topcoat where depth of damage is less than 0.032 inch diameter deep into parent material, and final dimensions are not less than those in Figure 201, may be blended and refinished. (1) With elevator installed, blend smooth and break any sharp edges at nick, scratch, or chaffed area. Remove minimum amount of material necessary to clear damage or interference. (2) Apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-10-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (3) Apply epoxy primer (2, Table 1, 55-00-00) to repair surface. (4) Finish repair surface to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00. B. Horizontal Stabilizer Hinge, Outer and Mid-Hinges Repair (1) Remove elevator. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. NOTE Scratch depth is limited to 0.01-inch deep. Perform outer- and mid-hinge scratch repair as follows. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Stabilizers (TO 1T-6ABD-2-55), 55-10-00, Figure 1. (2) Use sandpaper (4, Table 1, 55-00-00) to blend scratches 0.01-inch deep or less and within 0.25 inch on each side of scratch. (3) Apply alodine (1, Table 1, 55-00-00) to exposed material. (4) Apply primer (2, Table 1, 55-00-00) to area and touch up to match existing color using paint (3, Table 1, 55-00-00). Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00. (5) Install elevator. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. C. Horizontal Stabilizer Hinge, Center-Hinge Repair, and Elevator Trim Permanent Repair (1) Remove elevator. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. NOTE Blend or trim is only allowed on left and right lower flange edge. (2) Use sandpaper (4, Table 1, 55-00-00) to carefully blend out damage on lower flange, outer edge, of hinge. Do not exceed dimensions in Figure 201. Make sure sharp edges are deburred. Make sure 2D minimum edge distance is maintained. (3) Check area, using any one of the following nondestructive testing (NDT) techniques to make sure no cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection(FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Report any adverse inspection results to cognizant authority prior to continuing this repair. (5) Apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-10-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (6) Apply epoxy primer (2, Table 1, 55-00-00) to repair surface. (7) Finish repair surface to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-50-00. (8) Install elevator. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-30-01. (9) Make sure no further chafing occurs on center hinge. (10) If damage present on elevator leading edge skin, it is permissible to locally trim skin back flush with elevator rib to remove damage. Make sure minimum cutline radius 0.5 inch and 2D minimum edge distance. Deburr all sharp edges. Touch up repair area per Steps (5) through (7). (11) If elevator leading edge skin is trimmed per Step (10), perform Elevator Balance Procedure. Refer to 51-60-01. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-30-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 STABILIZERS VERTICAL STABILIZER 55-30-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the stabilizer. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. 2. REPAIR OF RUDDER TRIM BELLCRANK BRACKET (AFTER TCTO 1T-6A-826 OR -829) A. Procedure NOTE This repair procedure applies to rudder trim bellcrank bracket (PN 133-526013-0003). (1) As required, carefully derivet, unbolt, or remove any components or structure to complete this procedure. Take care not to oversize existing holes. Do not damage any surrounding and underlying structures. NOTE Cracks resulting from interference, in permissible damage area, are defined in Figure 201. If cracks are found in permissible damage area, trimming must extend 0.10 inch past ends of cracks and remain within permissible damage area as defined. (2) If cracks found, use one of the following methods to find and accurately mark ends of cracks to make sure complete removal. Maintain 0.10 inch minimum from ends of cracks. Refer to Figure 201, Sheet 1, for permissible damage area. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method "D"), sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (3) If unable to maintain minimum 0.10 inch from end of cracks and permissible damage area, report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment prior to continuing repair. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-30-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (4) Carefully trim bellcrank rudder trim bracket as shown in Figure 201, Sheet 1. Take care not to damage any surrounding and underlying structures. Maintain minimum radius as shown. (5) Deburr all sharp edges. (6) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of the following methods to make sure no cracks remain and no new cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Section 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method "D"), sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI): Refer to ASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (7) Report any adverse results to cognizant authority for assessment prior to continuing repair. (8) Apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (9) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Refer to Figure 201, Sheet 2, for rudder trim bellcrank bracket installation measurements and rivet information. (10) For fasteners removed in Step (1), verify hole condition. Install same type and size fasteners (18, Table 1, 53-00-00) as existing. Refer to 51-40-00. (11) Post assembly prime by applying one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (12) Apply top coat to match existing color, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (13) Perform Rudder Trim Rigging procedure. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-00. Make sure no further interference present with rudder trim bellcrank and rudder trim bellcrank bracket. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-40-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 STABILIZERS RUDDER 55-40-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. 2. RUDDER PLUG REPLACEMENT NOTE This procedure provides instructions to remove (if needed) and install rudder plug (P/N 133-630002-5). If installing rudder plug due to a missing existing plug, rudder shall be rebalanced. Refer to 51-60-02. A. Rudder Plug Removal (1) As required, remove rudder from aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-08. (2) Remove cotter pin, castellated nut, washers, and bolt to disconnect rudder trim push rod from trim control horn. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), (27-20-08), Figure 201. Discard cotter pin and castellated nut. (3) Remove rudder trim tab from rudder as follows: (a) Remove screw and catch assembly which retain rudder trim tab hinge pin. (b) Support tab and remove hinge pin. (c) Remove rudder trim tab. CAUTION Do not exceed 200 F when heating adhesive for removal. CAUTION When removing plug, make sure no damage occurs to adjacent skin. (4) Heat joint between plug and rudder surface to 180-200 F to release adhesive, then remove plug. Remove old adhesive from rudder surfaces while adhesive is still hot. Refer to Figure 201. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-40-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 B. Rudder Plug Installation (1) Using a scouring pad (59, Table 10, 51-30-01), scuff-sand inside rudder surfaces where plug attaches to remove residual adhesive. (2) Clean surfaces with Naphtha (6, Table 1, 51-30-01) and allow to air dry. (3) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (4) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. NOTE As required, sand, size, and shape rudder plug to make sure left and right skin have flat surfaces. (5) Test fit rudder plug in space provided to make sure proper fit. NOTE Bonding surfaces shall be free of dirt, oil, and other contaminating substances. (6) Clean rudder plug and rudder surface areas to be bonded with alcohol (9, Table 1, 53-00-00) and allow to air dry. (7) Mix glass beads (5, Table 6, 51-30-01) at 2-3% by weight with adhesive (10, Table 5, 51-30-01) prior to application. NOTE During installation, make sure triangular space aft of rudder plug is free of adhesive for drainage purposes. Refer to Figure 201. (8) Apply adhesive to inside of rudder surfaces. (9) Insert and bond rudder plug in place. Smooth adhesive on all surfaces. (10) After adhesive has cured, apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (11) As required, apply topcoat to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (3, Table 2, 20-50-00). (12) Install rudder trim tab on rudder as follows: (a) Align tab hinge half with rudder hinge half. (b) Install hinge pin. (c) Secure hinge pin with catch assembly and screw. (13) Secure rudder trim push rod to trim tab control horn with bolt, washers (one under bolt head and one under nut), and new self-locking castellated nut. Using torque wrench (10, Table 1, 27-00-00), torque nut to 40-50 inch-pounds and install new cotter pin. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-08, Figure 201, Sheet 2. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 55-40-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (14) Perform Rudder Balance Procedure. Refer to 51-60-02. (15) As required, install rudder on aircraft. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-20-08. GENERAL This chapter contains information and structural parts breakdowns applicable to wing skins and internal structure as well as flaps, ailerons, speed brake, and spare wing installation. Refer to Figure 00-01. The chapter is broken down into six sections: • Wing center section: Between right OWS .000 and left OWS .000. Refer to 57-10-00. • Wing outboard section: Between right and left OWS .000 and 148.031. Refer to 57-20-00. • Wing flaps: Inboard and outboard flap surfaces. Refer to 57-50-00. • Ailerons: Aileron and trim tab. Refer to 57-60-00. • Speed brake: Refer to 57-70-00. • Spare wing installation: Refer to 57-80-00. Specific structural inspection, damage limitations, and repair criteria applicable to wings are contained in this chapter. 2. INSPECTION Wings, flaps, ailerons, and the speed brake are inspected for dents, cracks, loose or missing rivets, corrosion, and distortion on a regularly scheduled basis in accordance with the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-6), Section II. Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of the damage. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 WINGS CENTER SECTION 57-10-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find designated material. Choosing correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. If part replacement is required and fabrication of replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find part number. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. 2. WING, MAIN SPAR, LOWER CAP CORROSION REPAIR NOTE The following repair procedure applies to the wing, main spar, lower cap with part numbers: 133-100052-1 or 133-100052-3. NOTE Do not perform blending in wet bays or in locations with obstruction due to other structure, systems, or equipment. Contact cognizant authority for further assessment with adverse findings in these areas. NOTE This repair procedure does not apply to locations where a repair has previously been performed. If previous repairs exist, contact cognizant authority for further assessment. A. Repair Procedure (1) Carefully blend out all corrosion. Remove minimum material necessary to clear all damage. Maintain 63 RMS or better surface finish and a blend slope no steeper than 10:1 after blending along direction of spar. (2) For corrosion less than 0.10 inch from edge of any fastener, carefully remove noted fasteners. Use caution not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. (3) Inspect holes for corrosion using 10x magnification. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (4) Inspect area to make sure that corrosion has been completely removed using one of the following nondestructive inspection (NDI) methods: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (a) Fluorescent penetrant (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201 00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (form D) developer. (b) FPI: Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. 1 If performing FPI, prior to inspection, blend area is required to be etched. 2 Use alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01) to clean area to be etched. 3 Etch area with caustic soda solution for 1-3 minutes. Caustic soda is made from 20 grams of potassium nitrate and 10 grams of sodium hydroxide, added to 100 milliliters of distilled or deionized water. 4 Water rinse etch area with deionized water. 5 Neutralize etch area with 5% nitric acid solution (e.g. 5 milliliters of nitric acid added to 95 milliliters of distilled or deionized water). 6 Water rinse etch area with deionized water. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (5) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (6) Measure blend area. (a) For blends occurring on spar flange, determine minimum remaining material by performing one of the following methods. 1 On blended area, create a 0.25 inch by 0.25 inch grid map for measuring remaining thickness. Refer to Figure 201. NOTE Material thickness just outside blend area should also be measured to determine original part thickness. a Layout grid on area to be measured. b Use ultrasonic nondestructive inspection to measure minimum thickness of each grid location and document. 2 On blended area, create a topographic map measuring regions of remaining thickness. Refer to Figure 202. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 NOTE Material thickness just outside blend area should also be measured to determine original part thickness. a Use ultrasonic nondestructive inspection to locate and map thinnest area/areas to +0.005 inch and identify as location A. b Continue outboard of location A, mapping bands of 0.005 inch changes in thickness. c Once outside blend area, note thickness adjacent to blend. (b) For blends occurring on spar slug, measure blend depths. Due to nonparallel surfaces of spar slug geometry, ultrasonic NDI is not an accurate method to obtain material thickness data. 1 Blend depth measurements shall be taken using a grid or topographic map. Refer to Step (6)(a). (c) Blend area measurements, including thicknesses, depths, lengths, and widths should be photographically documented for damage reporting. Refer to Figure 204. Document findings in Remis or Decklate. Use work unit Code IICAG(FC). (7) Calculate total blend area: (a) Determine applicable zone location. Zones are identified in Figures 204 and 205. Zone boundaries between ribs are defined by thickness changes in one of spar flanges or slug shown in Figure 203. Refer to blueprint flange thicknesses in Figure 205 to confirm zone location. If zone locations cannot be identified, contact cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (b) Typical blends are shown in Figure 203. Blends can be to spar flange, spar slug, or both where blended areas overlap a common wing station. Sample calculations of total blend area for single and combined conditions are shown below. 1 Single flange blend calculations: Remaining thickness, tr = measured by repair entity per Step (6) Blueprint thickness, tbp = reference Figure 205 Blend depth, d = tbp – tr Blend width, w = measured by repair entity Total blend area, A = w * d 2 Single slug blend: Blend depth, d = measured by repair entity Blend width, w = measured by repair entity Total blend area, A = w * d MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 3 Combined flange and slug blend calculations: Flange blend depth, df = calculate as in (7) (b) 1. Flange blend width, wf = measured by repair entity Flange blend area, Af = wf * df Slug blend depth, ds = measured by repair entity Slug blend width, ws = measured by repair entity Slug blend area, As = ws * ds Total blend area, A = Af + As (8) Determine repairability of blend location as follows: (a) Total blend area through a common wing station must be less than value specified in Figure 206. (b) For flange blends, remaining thickness must be greater than the value specified in Figure 206. (c) All blends failing to meet these two conditions should be referred to cognizant authority for further assessment. (9) Break all sharp edges 0.02/0.03 inch radius in local area to be peened. (10) Mask off area to be peened by extending 0.50 inch beyond outer perimeter of blend area. (11) Remove all finishes in masked area in preparation for peening. Make sure to not remove additional material or not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structures. (12) Area within masked boundary shall be shot/flap peened per Method 1 or Method 2 below: NOTE Do not shot peen or flap peen underneath right side rib 3 and/or 5. If blends include these locations, contact cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (a) Method 1 - Auto shot peen area per SAE AMS2430T: 1 Media type to be ASR (cast steel shot, regular) or ASH (cast steel shot, hard). 2 Media size. Refer to Figure 207. 3 Peening intensity, refer to Figure 207. 4 Coverage to be 150%. 5 Peened areas shall be chemically decontaminated to remove residual iron. Proceed to Step (13). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 (b) Method 2 - Rotary flap peen area per SAE AM2590 issued December 2010 or later: 1 Flap assemblies shall conform to SAE AS2592 or MIL-W-81840, Type II, Class 1, 2, or 3. 2 Peening intensity, refer to Figure 208. 3 Coverage shall be 150%. 4 Proceed to Step (14). (13) All aluminum within peened area is likely to be contaminated with iron. These areas must be treated to reduce likelihood of dissimilar metal corrosion as follows: (a) Clean blend area with an approved solvent to remove any oils or soils that may be on spar. (b) Carefully apply a 10% by volume solution of nitric acid to affected area. NOTE The nitric acid solution will discolor any primer and/or paint it touches. Nitric acid solution should not come into contact with steel or be allowed near seams. If the nitric solution is not removed it can cause corrosion. Swabbing the affected areas with a cotton swab to control the application of the nitric acid solution is recommended. (c) Allow nitric acid solution to remain on aluminum surface for 2 - 5 minutes. (d) Remove nitric acid solution and rinse with clean water. (14) Remove masking applied in Step (10). (15) Clean surfaces. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (16) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (17) Apply one coat of epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (18) For fasteners removed in Step (2), verify hole condition and install fasteners of same type and size as those removed. Refer to 51-40-00. (19) Post assembly prime by applying one coat of epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to the repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (20) Finish surface to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, 20-20-00. (21) Apply corrosion preventative compound (60, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer's instructions, to non-painted areas. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-40-00, Application of Corrosion Inhibiting Compound, Cor-Ban 35 (Main Wing Lower, Dry Bay) Application. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 206 Jun 01/21 3. LEFT AND RIGHT WING, RIB MID 7, UPPER FLANGE, FORWARD END REPAIR A. Repair Procedure NOTE Only one fastener may be removed from the upper flange of the rib. NOTE It is only permissible to remove material from the flange and radius of the rib. (1) As required, carefully disassemble, remove rivets, or remove structure to complete this procedure. Take care not to oversize existing holes. Do not damage any surrounding and/or underlying structures. (2) Using any one of the following nondestructive testing (NDT) techniques, locate and mark ends of cracks. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 57-10-07, Wing Rib Mid 7, Upper Flange Inspection. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (c) FPI: Refer to FASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (3) Carefully cut out cracks from upper flanges of ribs. Refer to Figure 209. Remove minimum material necessary and take care not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. Make sure cut line is minimum of 0.10 inch minimum beyond end of cracks. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance to adjacent fasteners and maintain minimum 0.25 inch radius. (4) Deburr all sharp edges. (5) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of the following methods to make sure no cracks remain and no new cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 57-10-07, Wing Rib Mid 7, Upper Flange Inspection. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 207 Jun 01/21 NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant Inspection (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2, WP 201-00, (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (c) FPI: Refer to FASTM E1417, type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. (6) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for assessment prior to continuing repair. (7) As required, fabricate repair angles (P/N SR-TS-00068-1), left and/or (P/N SR-TS-00068-2) right as shown in Figure 209. Make from 0.040 inch thick, sheet metal (57, Table 10, 51-30-01). Form to nest into existing rib. Minimum bend radius 0.12 inch. Heat treat to T73 per SAE AMS2770, after forming. (8) As required, fabricate repair fillers (P/N SR-TS-00068-3 (left) and/or P/N SR-TS-00068-4 (right)) as shown in Figure 209. Make from 0.040 inch thick, sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). (9) Drill/ream all holes as shown in Figure 209. Refer to 51-40-00. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance on all fasteners and 4D to 6D pitch distance on all new fasteners. (10) Deburr all sharp edges. (11) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (12) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-10. (13) Install repair parts in place using cold bond adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01) mixed and applied. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (14) Install fasteners as shown in Figure 209. Install any other removed fasteners with same type and size as existing. Refer to 51-40-00. Length to suit. (15) Apply top coat, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). 4. WING, MAIN SPAR BLEND REPAIR A. Repair Procedure NOTE The following repair procedure applies to the wing, main spar, lower cap with (P/N 133-100052). (1) Smooth and blend to remove gouge area to a slope of width to depth ratio of 10:1. Remove minimum amount of material to remove discrepancy. Maintain roughness average of 125 micro-inch minimum surface texture. Refer to Figure 210. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 208 Jun 01/21 (2) Determine depth of discrepancy after rework. Perform General Procedure For Use On Aluminum Parts per Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), 20-10-01, or best method to determine if cracks exist. (a) If depth of discrepancy is greater than 0.050 inch, when compared to nominal thickness local to blended area or cracks are found, record depth, size, and location of cracks and submit to cognizant authority for further evaluation. (b) If depth of discrepancy is 0.050 inch or less, when compared to the nominal thickness local to the blended area and no cracks are found, continue with rework. (3) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (4) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01). Refer to 51-20-10. (5) Apply paint to match existing color using paint (22, Table 1, 53-00-00). 5. WING, MAIN SPAR, UPPER CAP CORROSION REPAIR NOTE The following repair procedure applies to the wing, main spar, upper cap with part numbers: 133-100051-1 or 133-100051-3. NOTE Do not perform blending in wet bays or in locations with obstruction due to other structure, systems, or equipment. Contact cognizant authority for further assessment with adverse findings in these areas. NOTE This repair procedure does not apply to locations where a repair has previously been performed. If previous repairs exist, contact cognizant authority for further assessment. A. Repair Procedure (1) Carefully blend out all corrosion. Remove minimum material necessary to clear all damage. Maintain 63 RMS or better surface finish and a blend slope no steeper than 10:1 after blending along direction of spar. (a) For corrosion less than 0.10 inch from edge of any fastener, carefully remove noted fasteners. Use caution not to oversize existing holes and not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structure. (b) Inspect holes for corrosion using 10x magnification. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (2) Inspect area to make sure that corrosion has been completely removed using one of the following nondestructive inspection (NDI) methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant (FPI): Refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201 00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (form D) developer. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 209 Jun 01/21 (b) FPI: Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 grade A. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. NOTE If performing FPI, prior to inspection, blend area is required to be etched. 1 Use alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01) to clean area to be etched. 2 Etch area with caustic soda solution for 1-3 minutes. Caustic soda is made from 20 grams of potassium nitrate and 10 grams of sodium hydroxide, added to 100 milliliters of distilled or deionized water. 3 Water rinse etch area with deionized water. 4 Neutralize etch area with 5% nitric acid solution (e.g. 5 milliliters of nitric acid added to 95 milliliters of distilled or deionized water). 5 Water rinse etch area with deionized water. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (3) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (4) Measure blend area. (a) For blends occurring on spar flange, determine minimum remaining material by performing one of the following methods. 1 On blended area, create a 0.25 inch by 0.25 inch grid map for measuring remaining thickness. Refer to Figure 201. NOTE Material thickness just outside blend area should also be measured to determine original part thickness. Refer to Figure 201. a Layout grid on area to be measured. b Use ultrasonic nondestructive inspection to measure minimum thickness of each grid location and document. 2 On blended area, create a topographic map measuring regions of remaining thickness. Refer to Figure 202. NOTE Material thickness just outside blend area should also be measured to determine original part thickness. Refer to Figure 202. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 210 Jun 01/21 a Use ultrasonic nondestructive inspection to locate and map thinnest area/areas to +0.005 inch and identify as location A. b Continue outboard of location A, mapping bands of 0.005 inch changes in thickness. c Once outside blend area, note thickness adjacent to blend. (b) For blends occurring on spar slug, measure blend depths. Due to nonparallel surfaces of spar slug geometry, ultrasonic NDI is not an accurate method to obtain material thickness data. 1 Blend depth measurements shall be taken using a grid or topographic map. Refer to Step (4)(a). (c) Blend area measurements, including thicknesses, depths, lengths, and widths should be photographically documented for damage reporting. Refer to Figure 211. Document findings in Remis or Decklate. Use work unit Code IICAG(FC). (5) Calculate total blend area: (a) Determine applicable zone location. Zones are identified in Figure 211. Zone boundaries between ribs are defined by thickness changes in one of the spar flanges or slug shown in Figure 203. Refer to blueprint flange thicknesses in Figure 212 to confirm zone location. If zone locations cannot be identified, contact the cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (b) Typical blends are shown in Figure 203. Blends can be to spar flange, spar slug, or both where blended areas overlap a common wing station. Sample calculations of total blend area for single and combined conditions are shown below: 1 Single flange blend calculations: Remaining thickness, tr = measured by repair entity per Step (4) Blueprint thickness, tbp = refer to Figure 212 Blend depth, d = tbp – tr Blend width, w = measured by repair entity Total blend area, A = w * d 2 Single slug blend: Blend depth, d = measured by repair entity Blend width, w = measured by repair entity Total blend area, A = w * d 3 Combined flange and slug blend calculations: Flange blend depth, df = calculate as in (5) (b) 1. Flange blend width, wf = measured by repair entity Flange blend area, Af = wf * df MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 211 Jun 01/21 Slug blend depth, ds = measured by repair entity Slug blend width, ws = measured by repair entity Slug blend area, As = ws * ds Total blend area, A = Af + As (6) Determine repairability of blend location as follows: (a) Total blend area through a common wing station must be less than value specified in Figure 213. (b) For flange blends, remaining thickness must be greater than the value specified in Figure 213. (c) All blends failing to meet these two conditions should be referred to cognizant authority for further assessment. (7) Break all sharp edges 0.02/0.03 inch radius in local area to be peened. (8) Mask off area to be peened by extending 0.50 inch beyond outer perimeter of blend area. (9) Remove all finishes in masked area in preparation for peening. Make sure to not remove additional material or not to damage any surrounding and/or underlying structures. (10) Area within masked boundary shall be shot/flap peened per Method 1 or Method 2 below: NOTE Do not shot peen or flap peen underneath right side rib 3 and/or 5. If blends include these locations, contact cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (11) Method 1 - Auto shot peen area per SAE AMS2430T: (a) Media type to be ASR (cast steel shot, regular) or ASH (cast steel shot, hard). (b) Media size, refer to Figure 214. (c) Peening intensity, refer to Figure 214. (d) Coverage to be 150%. (e) Peened areas shall be chemically decontaminated to remove residual iron. Proceed to Step (11). (12) Method 2 - Rotary flap peen area per SAE AM2590 issued December 2010 or later: (a) Flap assemblies shall conform to SAE AS2592 or MIL-W-81840, Type II, Class 1, 2, or 3. (b) Peening intensity, refer to Figure 215. (c) Coverage shall be 150%. (d) Proceed to Step (12). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 212 Jun 01/21 (13) All aluminum within peened area is likely to be contaminated with iron. These areas must be treated to reduce likelihood of dissimilar metal corrosion as follows: (a) Clean blend area with an approved solvent to remove any oils or soils that may be on spar. (b) Carefully apply a 10% by volume solution of nitric acid to affected area. NOTE The nitric acid solution will discolor any primer and/or paint it touches. Nitric acid solution should not come into contact with steel or be allowed near seams. If the nitric solution is not removed it can cause corrosion. Swabbing the affected areas with a cotton swab to control the application of the nitric acid solution is recommended. (c) Allow nitric acid solution to remain on aluminum surface for 2 - 5 minutes. (d) Remove nitric acid solution and rinse with clean water. (14) Remove masking applied in Step (8). (15) Clean surfaces. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (16) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (17) Apply one coat of epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (18) For fasteners removed in Step (1)(a), verify hole condition and install fasteners of same type and size as those removed. Refer to 51-40-00. (19) Post assembly prime by applying one coat of epoxy primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to the repair area. Refer to 51-20-10. (20) Finish surface to match existing color. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. (21) Apply corrosion preventative compound (60, Table 10, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer's instructions, to non-painted areas. 6. WING, AFT SPAR, ATTACH FITTING BOLT BORE REPAIR NOTE This repair procedure applies to all wing attach detail fittings (P/N 133-100181) at aft spar. NOTE No cracks are allowed in any detail part. Refer to Figures 217 and 218. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 213 Jun 01/21 NOTE If damage is equal to or less than 0.3820 inch diameter, go to Paragraph 6.A. for repair procedures. If damage is equal to or greater than 0.3821 inch diameter, and does not exceed 0.424 inch maximum diameter, go to Paragraph 6.B for repair procedures. If damage exceeds 0.424 inch diameter, contact cognizant authority prior to continuing with repair for evaluation, or replace damaged detail with a new or serviceable detail/ assembly. A. Bore Damage Less Than 0.3820 Inch Diameter Repair NOTE If hole is not clean, round, or straight, proceed to Paragraph 6.B. (1) As required, drill/ream wing aft spar attach fitting bolt bore, to maximum 0.3820 inch diameter through attachment fitting. Use drill block to make sure perpendicularity and maintain original hole center line. Make sure hole is clean, round, and straight. Refer to 51-40-00. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. (3) Inspect wing aft spar fitting bolt bores to make sure no damage remains, and no cracks have formed using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (4) If no cracks or damage are found, go to Step (6). (5) If minor cracks are found along periphery of hole, go to Paragraph 6.B. for oversizing bolt bore. If minor cracks cannot be removed by oversizing bolt bore, report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (6) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Primer is not allowed in bolt bore. (7) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (8) Apply topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23). (9) Assemble wing to fuselage. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57), 57-00-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 214 Jun 01/21 B. Oversize Bore Damage Greater Than 0.3821 Inch Diameter Repair NOTE This procedures applies to oversize bore damage greater than 0.3821 inch diameter, and does not exceed maximum 0.4240 inch diameter. NOTE Make sure hole is clean, round, and straight. Refer to 51-40-00. Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (1) Drill/ream wing aft spar attach fitting bolt bore, to 0.421-0.424 inch diameter through attachment fitting. Use drill block to make sure perpendicularity and maintain original hole center line. (2) Deburr all sharp edges. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (3) Inspect wing aft spar fitting bolt bores to make sure no damage remains, and no cracks have formed using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. (4) Cold work wing aft spar attach fitting bolt bore using latest revision of Fatigue Technology Inc. (FTI) Process Specification 8101 (cold expansion of holes using standard split sleeve system and countersink cold expansion), STDN 14-0-N. (a) Make sure surrounding fasteners are installed prior to cold working hi-loks (P/N HL18PB). (b) Inspect attach fitting surrounding fastener holes for any signs of bulging or distortion caused by cold working. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (5) Final ream wing aft spar attach fitting bolt bore to 0.439-0.441 inch diameter. Use drill block to make sure perpendicularity and maintain original hole center line. Make sure hole is clean, round, and straight. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 215 Jun 01/21 NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (6) Deburr all sharp edges. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (7) Inspect wing aft spar attach fitting bolt bore to make sure no cracks have formed using eddy current (bolt probe) inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use on Aluminum Parts. NOTE It is acceptable to fabricate repair bushing from alternate materials listed in Table 201. (8) Fabricate repair bushing (P/N SR-TS-ATA57-27189-1). Refer to Figure 217. (9) Deburr all sharp edges. (10) Crack check bushing using one of methods below. If cracks are found, discard bushing and make new bushing. (a) Magnetic particle inspect bushing. Refer to ASTM E 1444, using acceptance criteria per MIL STD-1907 Grade A. Table 201 - Bolt Bore Bushing Options Material Specifications 4130 round steel tubing SAE AMS6360, Type I, Condition N, 0.500 inch maximum diameter 4130 round steel bar SAE AMS6348, Condition N, 0.500 inch maximum diameter 4130 round steel bar SAE AMS6361 (125 ksi), 0.500 inch maximum diameter SAE AMS6348 (125 ksi), 0.500 inch maximum diameter SAE AMS6362 (125 ksi), 0.500 inch maximum diameter 4340 bar SAE AMS6415, 0.500 inch maximum diameter 17-4PH Stainless Steel SAE AMS5643/H1025 (No heat treat required) NOTES 1. Heat treat all 4130 or 4340 bushings to 155-185 ksi. Refer to SAE AMS2759/1. 2. Machine finish 125 RMS or better. 3. Determine length by measuring thickness of attachment fitting, and refer to Fatigue Technology Inc. (FTI) Process Specification 9601 (installation of bushings using the BushLoc (BlCx ) System). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 216 Jun 01/21 (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (11) If cracks are found, discard and make new bushing. NOTE Do no apply cadmium plating to inner bore. (12) Cadmium plate bushing. Refer to SAE AMS-QQ-P-416, Class 2, Type 1. (13) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to mating surface inside bolt bore. Refer to 51-20-10. (14) Install repair bushing. Refer to Figure 218. Refer to Fatigue Technology Inc. (FTI) Process Specification 9601 (installation of bushings using Bushloc® (BlCx™) System). Make sure to use BushLoc® Standard Number (BSN) -5/2 tooling. (15) Make sure repair bushing faces are flush with surrounding surfaces. Mill bushings flush if needed NOTE Do no apply cadmium plating to inner bore. (16) Protect all bare steel using brush cad plate per MIL-STD-865, latest rev. Maintain minimum 0.0003 inch thickness. NOTE In lieu of brush cadmium plating, it is acceptable to apply Metaflex wash primer (9, Table 3, 51-30-01), refer to manufacturer’s instructions, or wash primer (5, Table 3, 51-30-01) and prime with two of urethane primer (8, Table 3, 51-30-01) or one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (17) Drill/ream bushing to 0.375/0.379 diameter hole. (18) Deburr all sharp edges. (19) Crack check bushing using one of methods below. If cracks are found, discard bushing and make new bushing. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (20) If cracks are found: (a) Carefully remove bushing and discard. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 217 Jun 01/21 (b) Measure bolt bore diameter. If diameter is 0.439- 0.441 inch, install a new bushing. Refer to Steps (14) thru (19). (c) If bolt bore diameter is greater than 0.441 inch, report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (21) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE Do no apply primer to inner bore. (22) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (23) Apply topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (3, Table 2, 20-50-00). (24) Assemble wing to fuselage. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57). 7. WING SPIGOT FITTING, FUSELAGE SPIGOT FITTING, AND LOWER SPIGOT FITTING REPAIR NOTE This procedure provides instructions to inspect wing spigot, fuselage spigot, and lower fuselage spigot fittings and blend discrepancies as required. Aircraft with discrepant spigot fittings require a minimum of two inspections. An initial inspection for an interim disposition to blend damage and a subsequent inspection for post-blend measurements. A. Wing Spigot Fitting Repair (1) Take pictures of discrepant parts to document current condition. Refer to Figure 219. (2) Using sandpaper, (17, Table 9, 51-30-00), blend wing spigot fitting surfaces minimum amount as required to remove damage. (a) Final blend diameter to depth ratio shall be 10:1. (b) Final surface finish shall be RMS 32 or better. (3) Inspect blended surface on wing fitting to make sure no damage remains using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: NOTE Mask off adjacent seams, interfaces, and joints as required to prevent intrusion of fluorescent penetrant. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 218 Jun 01/21 (4) Acceptance/Rejection Criteria: (a) If no damage is noted, proceed to Step (5). (b) If damage (pitting, fretting, wear, or gouging) is noted, report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (5) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE It may be necessary to take measurements of wing spigot fitting at several locations around bore. Minimum/maximum dimensions may be found at locations other than 12-6 o’clock and 3-9 o’clock. (6) Measure wing spigot fitting diameters. Refer to Figure 219 as guidance for determining measurement locations. (7) If wing spigot fitting is within allowable tolerance (1.397–1.399 inches) at all locations along length of fitting, and has passed NDI per Paragraph 7.A.(3), wing spigot fitting is acceptable as is. WARNING If wing spigot fitting dimension is out of tolerance, aircraft is not airworthy until a final disposition is released by cognizant authority. (8) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment. Provide pictures detailing post blend condition, and completed table of measurements from Figure 219 prior to continuing with this repair. (9) Apply lubricant to wing spigot fitting to prevent corrosion. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57), (14, Table 2, 57-00-00). B. Fuselage Spigot Fitting Assembly Repair NOTE Fuselage spigot fitting assembly consists of a fuselage spigot fitting structurally mounted to aircraft, and a removable lower fuselage spigot fitting. Blending of damage can be done with fitting assembly disassembled however, diameter measurements require lower fuselage assembly be attached. Hand tightened is acceptable, torquing is not required. (1) Take pictures of discrepant parts to document current condition. Refer to Figure 220. (2) Using sandpaper, (17, Table 9, 51-30-00), blend fuselage spigot fitting and/or lower fuselage spigot fitting surfaces minimum amount as required to remove damage. (a) Final blend diameter to depth ratio shall be 10:1. (b) Final surface finish shall be RMS 32 or better. (3) Inspect blended surface on fuselage spigot fitting and lower fuselage spigot fitting to make sure no damage remains using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 219 Jun 01/21 NOTE Mask off adjacent seams, interfaces, and joints as required to prevent intrusion of fluorescent penetrant. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Acceptance/Rejection Criteria: (a) If no damage is noted, proceed to Paragraph 7.B.(5). (b) If damage (pitting, fretting, wear, or (gouging) is noted, report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (5) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE It may be necessary to take measurements of fuselage spigot fitting at several locations around bore. Minimum/maximum dimensions may be found at locations other than 12-6 o’clock and 3-9 o’clock. (6) Measure fuselage spigot fitting and lower fuselage spigot fitting diameters as follows: Refer to Figure 220 as guidance for determining measurement locations. (a) Install lower fuselage spigot fitting (hand tight only). (b) Make sure mating surfaces of fuselage spigot fitting and lower fuselage spigot fitting surfaces are touching. (c) Use impression putty (68, Table 10, 51-30-01), or equivalent, to take impression mold of bore to measure diameter of bore around blended areas. Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (d) After impression mold has cured, remove lower fuselage spigot fitting and mold impression from fuselage spigot fitting. NOTE It may be necessary to take measurements of fuselage spigot fitting mold impression at several locations around bore. Minimum/maximum dimensions may be found at locations other than 12-6 o’clock and 3-9 o’clock. (e) Measure fuselage spigot fitting mold impression diameter. Refer to Figure 220 as guidance for determining measurement locations. (7) If fuselage spigot fitting is within allowable tolerance (1.400–1.401 inches) at all locations along length of fitting, and has passed NDI per Paragraph 7.B.(3), fuselage spigot fitting is acceptable as is. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 220 Jun 01/21 WARNING If fuselage spigot fitting dimension is out of tolerance, aircraft is not airworthy until a final disposition is released by cognizant authority. (8) Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment. Provide pictures detailing post blend condition, and completed table of measurements from Figure 220 prior to continuing with this repair. (9) Apply lubricant to fuselage spigot fitting, and to lower fuselage spigot fitting to prevent corrosion. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57), (14, Table 2, 57-00-00). 8. MAIN LANDING GEAR (MLG), DOOR HINGE (P/N 133-100136-1/-2/-3/-4) REMOVAL AND INSTALLATION NOTE The following repair procedure applies to the left side MLG outboard door hinges (P/N 133-100136-1/-3) and right (typical) MLG outboard door hinges (P/N 133-100136-2/-4). A. Removal (1) Remove left MLG outboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. NOTE Existing Hi-Lok (P/N HL18PB-6-19) should remain in place after removal of outboard door hinge fitting. (2) Remove nuts (P/N 130909N29) and washers (P/N NAS620-10) to remove outboard door hinge fitting (P/N 133-100136-1/-3). Refer to Figure 221. (3) Remove sealant on outboard door hinge fitting. NOTE Take note of how many shims are installed prior to removal. Make sure same configuration of shims is used in forward and aft locations of each fitting when installing outboard door hinge fitting. (4) Remove outboard door hinge fitting, and shims from aircraft. NOTE Typically, the forward fitting requires one shim (0.016 inch) and the aft fitting requires two shims (0.032 inch). (5) Check shims (P/N 133-100136-5) thickness (0.016 inch) for forward and aft location. (6) Remove residual sealant and clean outboard door hinge fitting mounting location. Refer to 51-20-20. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-10-00 Page 221 Jun 01/21 B. Installation (1) Transfer hole locations from original fitting to new fitting. (2) Drill final hole 0.190-0.194 inch diameter through new fittings. NOTE Use appropriate amount of shims as noted during removal. (3) Install shims (P/N 133-100136-5). (4) Temporarily install new outboard door hinge fitting with clamps. Make sure holes line up for install. (5) Secure outboard door hinge fittings in place with washers and nuts and remove clamps. (6) Manually cycle left main gear to UP position. (7) Temporarily install outboard MLG door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. (8) Check if MLG door fits, or requires adjustment in door land area, or if shimming needs to be reworked for proper fit to door land area. (9) Remove outboard MLG door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. (10) Manually lower main landing gear to full DOWN position. (11) Remove fittings by removing nuts and washers then slide fitting off Hi-Lok pins and prepare for install. (12) Make sure proper shims were used in Step (3) and satisfactory in Step (8). (13) Install fittings wet, use sealant (7, Table 7, 51-30-01), install nuts (P/N 130909N29), washers (P/N NAS62D-10), shims (P/N 133-100136-5) and new Hi-Lok (P/N HL18PB-6-19). Refer to TO 1-1A-8 for installation of Hi-Lok fasteners. Refer to Figure 221. (14) Install left outboard MLG door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 32-10-15. (15) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 32-00-01.
