ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to the wing outboard section. Each part called out in the wing outboard section figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/ material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-20-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 WINGS OUTBOARD SECTION 57-20-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in outboard section wing sheet metal skins, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-20-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 WINGS OUTBOARD SECTION 57-20-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. A. Rib 12 Thru 16 Inspection (1) Extend flaps to LAND position. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-00. (2) Visually inspect left and right ribs 12 thru 16 for any deformation or dents. Refer to Figure 201. (a) If deformations or dents are noted, document length, width, and depth of deformation/dent. Refer to Figure 201. (3) If any deformation or dent is outside allowable limits specified below, proceed to Paragraph 1.B. If deformation or dent is within specified limits, it is acceptable to remain in service. (a) Deformation or dent isolated to the lower rib cap or web and does not extend into radius or rib web. (b) Deformation or dent height less than 0.125 inch either above or below rib cap. (c) Length of deformation or dent must be greater than four times depth of dent (no sharp transitions). B. Rib 12 Thru 16 Removal and Replacement (1) As required, carefully remove rivets to remove deformed/dented rib. Take care not to oversize existing holes, or damage surrounding or underlying structures. (2) Inspect aft spar, upper wing skin area, and angle to make sure no cracks have formed using one of following nondestructive inspection (NDI) methods: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-20-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, General Procedure, solvent removable, Method C, sensitivity level 3 (high), and nonaqueous (Form D) developer. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (c) Eddy current inspection: Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (3) Drill new rib to match existing fastener locations. Refer to Figure 201. (4) Deburr all sharp edges. (5) Clean surfaces. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (6) Apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. NOTE During installation of rib and angle, perform faying surface sealing with MIL-S-8802, Type II, Class B sealant, (21, Table 1, 53-00-00). (7) Install rib, angle, and fasteners. Install fasteners wet with sealant, (21, Table 1, 53-00-00). Refer to Figure 201. (8) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (9) Apply topcoat to match existing color, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. 06/16 WINGS SKINS 57-30-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to wing skins. Each part called out in a wing skins figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-30-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 WINGS SKINS 57-30-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in wing sheet metal skins, such as dents, gouges, scratches, and pitting, are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-30-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 WINGS SKINS 57-30-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-00. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for repair and fabrication of metal structure. Typical repairs are permanent, and should be carried out to restore structural integrity. If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. A. Repair of Lower Wing Skin Landing/taxi light brackets should clear lower wing skin without chafing when retracting or extending landing gear. If evidence of chafing is present on landing/taxi light brackets or lower wing skin, repair in accordance with the following procedure: (1) Trim lower wing skin (133-100129). Refer to Figure 201 for trim area. Trim area should start at 5.40 inches from inboard edge of channels (133-100131-15/-16). NOTE Do not trim channels (133-100131-15/-16) attached to aft inboard lower wing skin (133-100129). (2) Smooth sharp edges of trimmed area. (3) Apply primer and top coat. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual. B. Repair of Lower Wing Skin - Main Gear Outboard Door Land (Left and Right) (1) Remove left or right main gear outboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Landing Gear (TO 1T-6ABD-2-32), 32-10-15. (2) Chemically remove paint from affected area (NDI area). Refer to Figure 202, Sheet 1. (3) Perform Penetrant Inspection on areas shown in Figure 202, Sheet 1. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 8; TO 33B-1-1, Section 2.4.2.1; and TO 33B-1-2, WP 201. Make sure no cracks are present. (4) On 0.040-inch thick material only, remove minimum length of 0.150 inch of material forward and aft of hinge opening. Refer to Figure 202, Sheet 2. Actual length of material to be removed and discarded must be determined by whether or not crack is present. If crack length greater than 0.150 inch, drill 0.040-inch material, . Removed material must not exceed 1.25 inch maximum crack length. If crack length greater than 1.25 inch, contact cognizant authority. If crack within 0.150-1.25 inch, continue with Step (5). (5) Using sandpaper (17, Table 10, 51-30-01), smooth and blend cut away area to maintain 63 micro-inch, or better, surface roughness. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-30-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 (6) Perform Penetrant Inspection to make sure crack has been removed. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 8; TO 33B-1-1, Section 2.4.2.1; and TO 33B-1-2, WP 201. (7) Apply alodine (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to exposed material. (8) Apply primer and top coat. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual, 20-50-00. (9) Install left or right main gear outboard door. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 32-10-15. (10) Perform Main Landing Gear Door Check and Adjustment. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 32-00-01. C. Center Wing Forward Lower Skin Chafing Repair (1) Remove forward lower skin (150AB). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-40-04. Refer to Figure 203. (2) As required, remove aft lower skin (150BB). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-40-05. (3) Inspect forward lower skin (150AB) and stiffener flange (P/N 133-400005-15) for damage. (4) On forward lower skin (150AB), locally blend and polish smooth gouges. Remove minimum amount of material necessary to clear all damage and achieve smooth profile. Maintain 10:1 minimum blend slope and 63 RMS (or better) surface finish. Do not exceed blend depth of 0.030 inch minimum remaining material thickness. NOTE If remaining material thickness is less than 0.030 inch, report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (5) Carefully hand form 150AB stiffener flange as much as 0.050 from original contour to increase clearance from fastener heads to make sure no further chafing. (6) Inspect area to make sure no cracks have formed using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (c) Eddy current inspection, refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (7) Remove and replace blind fasteners with chafing marks. Install fasteners as indicated in Figure 203. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-30-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (8) Deburr all sharp edges. (9) Clean surfaces, refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (10) Apply alodine, type I (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (11) Apply one coat of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (12) As required, re-install lower panel access doors with same type fasteners as existing. Length to suit. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57). (13) Install one (1) layer of anti-chafe tape, Maintenance Manual, Wings (TO 1T-6ABD-2-57), (19, Table 2, 57-00-00) (width as required). Refer to Figure 203. (14) Install aft lower skin (150BB). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-40-05. (15) Install forward lower skin (150AB). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Fuselage (TO 1T-6ABD-2-53), 53-40-04. (16) Apply topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (3, Table 2, 20-50-00). Jun 06/16 WINGS FLAPS 57-50-00 00000 STRUCTURAL IDENTIFICATION 1. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to flaps. Each part called out in the flaps figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/material list. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as indexed on the illustration • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 WINGS FLAPS 57-50-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in the flaps such as dents, gouges, scratches and pitting are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 WINGS FLAPS 57-50-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. A. Inboard Flap Bushing Replacement Install outboard bushing (133-160006-11) onto journal assembly (133-160006-17/-18) as follows: (1) Clean journal and outboard bushing with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Wipe surface clean with lint-free-cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01) before solvent evaporates. Make sure surfaces are clean and oil-free. (2) Check journal outside diameter is 0.8132-0.8142 inch. (3) Check outboard bushing inner diameter is 0.8128-0.8121 inch. NOTE For installation, outboard bushing may be heated to 250 F maximum or journal may be frozen to -320 F maximum. (4) Install bushing onto journal and position bushing flush with end of journal up to 0.030 inch past end of journal. Refer to 57-50-01, Figure 50-01. B. Inboard Flap Lower Skin and End Plate Crack Repair (1) Remove inboard flap. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-01. (2) As required, remove other components, structure, or fasteners to complete this repair. (3) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of methods below to locate and mark end of crack. Refer to Figures 202 thru 204. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Make sure to not exceed flap skin cutout limitations. Refer to Table 201. (5) Cut out existing cracks as indicated in Figures 201 thru 204. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance to existing fasteners. Use caution to make sure underlying structure is not damaged. Make sure cut lines are 0.10-inch minimum from end of cracks. (6) Perform nondestructive inspection using one of methods below to make sure no cracks remain and no new cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01 General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. Table 201 - Flap Skin Cutout Limitations Damage Area Limitations Flap Inboard End (Bottom side, along edge) 1.6 inches maximum length, 0.75 inch maximum width along side. Refer to Figure 202. Flap Inboard End (Bottom side, forward and aft corners) 2.5 inches maximum length, 1.0 inch maximum width at ends. Refer to Figure 202. Flap Outboard End 4.0 inches maximum length, 1.0 inch maximum width. Refer to Figure 203. Flap Trailing Edge 1.0 inch maximum length, 0.75 inch maximum width. Refer to Figure 204. Crack(s) permitted any place along end plate. Doubler installed must have two rows of fasteners on each side. Repair can be used multiple times on end plate. Maintain 2 inches minimum distance between doublers. If less than 2 inches between doublers, doublers must be made into one doubler. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. A. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (7) As required, make doubler (P/N SR-TS-00060-1) to profile. Refer to Figure 202. Use 0.020 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Minimum bend radius 0.09-inch. (8) As required, make doubler (P/N SR-TS-00060-2) to profile. Refer to Figure 203. Use 0.020 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Minimum bend radius 0.09-inch. (9) As required, make filler (P/N SR-TS-00060-3) to profile Refer to Figure 202 and/or Figure 203. Use 0.020 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). (10) As required, make doubler (P/N SR-TS-00060-4) to profile. Refer to Figure 203. Make from 0.032 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01) form to nest onto existing end plate. Minimum 0.19 inch bend radius. Chamfer forward edge to match thickness of skin 0.012 inch deep x 0.12 inch wide. Alternatively, make from a new end plate (P/N 133-160007). (11) Drill new doublers and filler to match existing and new fastener locations. Refer to Figures 201 thru 204. Maintain four to eight-diameter spacing on all new fasteners and 2D minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (12) Deburr all sharp edges. (13) Clean surfaces, refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (14) Apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (15) Install repair parts in place using adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (16) Apply two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (17) Install fasteners as noted in Figures 201 thru 204. Refer to 51-40-00 thru 51-40-02. Install fasteners wet with adhesive (10 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01). (18) Apply two coats of topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (3, Table 11, 20-50-00). (19) Install inboard flap. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-01. (20) Install components, structure, or fasteners removed in Step (2). Use same type and size fasteners/ hardware as existing. (21) Rig flaps and perform operational check, as required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-00. Gap limitations shall comply with 51-10-01. Gap between edge of speed brake and inboard edge of flap to be 0.10-0.36 inch. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 204 Jun 01/21 C. Skin To Shaft Attach Angle Repair (1) Remove inboard flap. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-01. (2) Remove other components, structure, or fasteners to complete this repair, as required. Make sure to remove all debris, fastener tails and burrs from inside shaft. (3) Perform Nondestructive Inspection using one of methods below to locate and mark end of crack. Refer to Figure 205. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, 20-10-01, General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. (4) Make sure to not exceed attach angle cutout limitations. Refer to Table 202. (5) Cut out damaged section of angle. Refer to Figure 205. Maintain 2D minimum edge distance to existing fasteners. Use caution to make sure underlying structure is not damaged. Make sure cut lines are 0.10-inch minimum from end of cracks. (6) Perform nondestructive inspection using one of methods below to make sure no cracks remain and no new cracks have formed. (a) Eddy current inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 6, 20-10-01 General Procedures For Use On Aluminum Parts. NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to TO 33B-1-2, SWP 201-00, Solvent Removable, Method C, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), and Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer. Table 202 - Attach Angle Cutout Limitations Damage Area Limitations Skin To Shaft Attach Angle 1.0 inch maximum length, 1.0 inch maximum width. Refer to Figure 205. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-50-00 Page 205 Jun 01/21 NOTE Fluorescent penetrant not allowed in fastener bores. (c) Fluorescent penetrant inspection. Refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) Developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907, Grade A. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment before continuing with this repair. (7) As required, make filler (P/N SR-TS-00060-5) to profile. Refer to Figure 205. Use 0.020 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01). Minimum bend radius 0.09-inch. (8) As required, make angle (P/N SR-TS-00060-6) to profile. Refer to Figure 205. Use 0.020-0.032 inch thick sheet metal (12, Table 10, 51-30-01), or make from angle (P/N 133-160004). Form new angle to nest onto existing end plate. Minimum bend radius 0.12-inch. (9) Drill new filler and angle to match existing and new fastener locations. Refer to Figure 205. Maintain existing spacing on all fasteners and 2D minimum edge distance on all fasteners. (10) Deburr all sharp edges. (11) Clean surfaces, refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-10-00. (12) Apply alodine (Type I), (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to all bare aluminum. Refer to 51-20-10. (13) Install repair parts in place using adhesive (7 or 13, Table 5, 51-30-01). Refer to manufacturer’s instructions. (14) Apply two coats of primer (1, Table 3, 51-30-01) to repair area. (15) Install fasteners as noted in Figure 205. Refer to 51-40-00 thru 51-40-02. Install fasteners wet with adhesive (10 or 12, Table 5, 51-30-01). (16) Apply two coats of topcoat to match existing color as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), (3, Table 11, 20-50-00). (17) Install inboard flap. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-01. (18) Install components, structure, or fasteners removed in Step (2). Use same type and size fasteners/ hardware as existing. (19) Rig flaps and perform operational check, as required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-50-00. Gap limitations shall comply with 51-10-01. Gap between edge of speed brake and inboard edge of flap to be 0.10-0.36 inch. ILLUSTRATED PARTS BREAKDOWN This section provides an illustrated parts breakdown applicable to the ailerons and aileron trim tabs. Each part called out in the aileron and trim tab figure is assigned a number, with a corresponding reference on the parts/ material list. The parts/material list is located after each figure. Each part reference listed on the parts/material list includes the following information: • Item number of the part as called out on the parts/material list • Description of the part • Part number • Part material specifications (thickness, alloy composition, temper condition, material used for manufacture, special information, etc.) MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-60-00 Page 101 Jun 06/16 WINGS AILERONS AND AILERON TRIM TABS 57-60-00 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS Defects in the ailerons and aileron trim tabs such as dents, gouges, scratches and pitting are subject to airworthiness limitations. Refer to 51-10-02. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-60-00 Page 201 Jun 01/21 WINGS AILERONS AND AILERON TRIM TABS 57-60-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT If part replacement is required and fabrication of a replacement part is not practical, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the part number. WARNING Certain parts have been identified as fracture critical. Prior to attempting maintenance involving these fracture critical parts, contact cognizant authority. A. Outboard Aileron Hinge Assembly Bushing (1) Remove aileron if required. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. (2) Check aileron bushings for proper outside diameter, 0.997-0.998 inch. If aileron bushing meets this dimension, it can be reused. If not, replace bushing. Refer to Illustrated Parts Catalog, (TO 1T-6ABD-4), 57-60-05. (3) Check aileron hinges on left and right aft outboard wing for proper inside diameter, 1.000-1.001 inches. Refer to 57-20-02 and 57-20-04. If not within proper inside diameter, contact technical support representative. (4) Lightly abrade bushing surface with abrasive mat (15, Table 10, 51-30-01). (5) Clean outside diameter of bushings and inside diameter of aileron hinges with solvent (1 or 4, Table 1, 51-30-01). Wipe surfaces clean with lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01) before solvent evaporates. Make sure surfaces are clean and oil-free. (6) Apply primer (14, Table 10, 51-30-01) to surface. (7) Apply adhesive (13, Table 10, 51-30-01) to surface. Locate bushing within 0.010 inch of edge of part. (8) Allow adhesive to cure for 24 hours. (9) Install aileron if required. Refer to Maintenance Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. B. Outboard Aileron Hinge Bushing Replacement (P/N 133-130005-5) (1) Remove aileron. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. (2) Inspect outboard wing aileron hinge assembly bushing for condition, security, and bushing migration. Refer to Paragraph 1.A. Outboard Aileron Hinge Assembly Bushing. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-60-00 Page 202 Jun 01/21 NOTE Never use a hammer or any other type of impact method while performing this procedure. (3) Remove bushing from bracket as follows: NOTE If shoulder-type extraction pin is unavailable, use a steel pin. NOTE Make sure not to score the bracket housing as the bushing is removed. (a) Extract bushing from hole, using shoulder-type extraction pin that is a minimum of 0.01 inch smaller in diameter than bracket bore. (b) Place pilot end in to bushing. (4) Measure hole diameter thru rib and doubler. Make sure bore diameter is 0.3937-0.3943 inch. (5) Apply primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) inside of hole thru rib, doubler, and mating surface of rib flange where bushing will seat. NOTE Never use a hammer or any other type of impact method while performing this procedure (6) Install bushing by pushing/pulling into place until bushing flange seats into rib surface. Refer to Figure 201. (7) Apply primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) to edges of bushing. (8) Install aileron. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. C. Inboard Aileron Hinge Bearing Replacement (P/N MS27643-5) (1) Remove aileron. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. (2) Remove nuts, washers, screws, and retainer plate (P/N 133-100372-5). Discard nuts. Refer to Figure 202. NOTE When extracting bearing from a hole, apply pressure only on bearing outer race. If bearing is retained by a shoulder in housing so that force must be applied on inner race, use least force required. It is acceptable to use heat up to 150 F to aid in bearing removal. CAUTION Some heat guns can produce excessive heat (greater than 180 F) that can damage nearby components. When using heat gun, take care not to damage nearby components or paint with excessive heat. Be aware of potential fire hazards. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 57-60-00 Page 203 Jun 01/21 (3) Remove bearing. As required, apply heat to aid in bearing removal. (4) Make sure housing bore surface roughness does not exceed 63 micro-inch. The bore shall have a diameter of 1.2508-1.2498 inches and be free of nicks, scratches, burrs, tool marks, and corrosion. (5) Clean bore housing with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) or isopropyl alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01) using a lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01). Allow to thoroughly dry. Make sure bore housing is free from all primer where bearing flanges seat. (6) Prior to inserting a bearing, make sure it rolls freely. (7) Apply primer (14, Table 10, 51-30-01) to both surfaces spread evenly. Allow to thoroughly dry. CAUTION Never use a hammer or any other type of impact method while performing this procedure. NOTE When applying adhesive (13, Table 10, 51-30-01), do not allow it to contact any surfaces other than outer bearing race. NOTE Assemble bearing within three minutes after application of adhesive. (8) Apply adhesive (13, Table 10, 51-30-01) to both surfaces and spread evenly with an acid brush (6, Table 10, 51-30-01). Apply a small bead of adhesive (13, Table 10, 51-30-01) to edge of inner surface that receives bearing. NOTE Once bearing is in place, do not disturb, such as handling, for a minimum of five minutes. (9) Press bearing into a housing bore, apply force on bearing outer race only. (10) Clean off excess adhesive with MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01) or isopropyl alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01). Wipe clean with a lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01) and allow to thoroughly dry. (11) After inserting bearing, make sure that it still rolls freely, comparing it to itself prior to insertion. (12) Install retainer plate, screws, washers, and new nuts. Refer to Illustrated Parts Catalog (TO 1T-6ABD-4), 57-60-05. Refer to Figure 202. (13) Allow to cure for a minimum of 24 hours prior to placing in service (14) After adhesive has cured, install aileron as required. Maintenance Manual, Flight Controls (TO 1T-6ABD-2-27), 27-10-01. REPAIR LIMITATIONS If damage affects the engine truss, it should be classified as either repairable or replacement. Refer to 51-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 201 Jun 04/18 POWER PLANT ENGINE TRUSS 71-20-0052-30-00 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT When part repair is elected, refer to the parts/material list that accompanies each figure to find the designated material. Choosing the correct material for structural and skin repairs is extremely important. Refer to 51-30-02. Refer to Typical Repairs (51-70-00) for recommended repair and fabrication of metal structure, Typical repairs are permanent and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the engine truss. A. Engine Truss Corrosion Repair NOTE The following procedure is performed to treat general or superficial corrosion found on the engine truss by visual inspection. Any post blend measurements beyond the allowable limits in Table 201 - Engine Truss Minimum Allowable Wall Thickness must be reported to the cognizant authority. (1) Determine type of engine truss component to be repaired. Refer to Figure 201. (2) Using nylon brush (46, 47, 48, or 49, Table 10, 51-30-01), wire brush (50, Table 10, 51-30-01) or paint stripper (51, Table 10, 51-30-01) followed by rust remover (52, Table 10, 51-30-01), remove paint, corrosion, and loose debris. NOTE Use of nylon brush minimizes removal of parent material during corrosion removal. Size and shape of nylon brush selected depends on location of corrosion to be removed. The brushes work most effectively when used with a pneumatic drill. Adhere to maximum rpm ratings on brushes. It is permissible to use sandpaper (30, Table 10, 51-30-01) or Scotch Brite to remove corrosion from areas not accessible by nylon brush. NOTE If staining or minor surface corrosion is removed, with no parent material removed, NDI is not required. Proceed to Step (9). (3) If using paint stripper, perform following steps: (a) Wash surfaces to remove oils, dirt, grease, and deposits making sure hidden areas, crevices, corners, and other difficult-to-access areas are clean. (b) Rinse surfaces thoroughly. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 202 Jun 04/18 CAUTION Some heat guns can produce excessive heat (greater than 180 °F) that can damage paint on truss or damage nearby components. When using heat gun, take care not to damage nearby components or paint on engine truss with excessive heat. Be aware of potential fire hazards. (c) Dry surfaces completely. NOTE The use of a low-temperature heat gun is permitted, as needed, to assure crevices are dry. (d) Check surfaces for cleanliness, paint damage (flaking or chipping) and corrosion (primarily filiform, exfoliation, pitting, and rust, including flash rust). (e) Mask areas not intended to be stripped. Make sure engine components are properly covered to prevent contact with paint stripper. (f) Using brush, carefully apply paint stripper to areas that are difficult to access. (g) Allow paint stripper to remain for time designated by manufacturer’s instructions. (h) Remove excess paint stripper with clean cloth. (i) Wash areas with liquid soap (53, Table 10, 51-30-01) and water. Agitate areas with cotton swabs or bristle brushes, as necessary, to make sure hidden areas, crevices, corners, and other difficult-to-access areas are cleaned. (j) Thoroughly rinse area. (k) Apply solvent (7, Table 1, 51-30-01) to areas, as necessary, to facilitate drying. (4) If using rust remover, perform following steps: NOTE Evapo-Rust is a water-based rust remover containing a chelating ingredient. The product works best in immersion, working in 30 minutes to 24 hours depending on rust severity, surface preparation, alloy type, and temperature. Areas requiring rust removal should be free of contaminates (such as wax, oil, grease, and dirt), loose paint, and areas painted over with corrosion underneath. Evapo-Rust works faster as the temperature increases; use of Evapo-Rust at temperatures below 60 °F may be unsatisfactory. Evapo-Rust is typically used at or above prevailing shop temperatures of 65 °F or above with surfaces within the same temperature range. (a) Make sure surfaces to be treated are clean and free from contaminates. (b) Mask areas not intended to be treated. Make sure engine components are properly covered to prevent contact with rust remover. (c) Brush or spray rust remover on surfaces to be treated. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 203 Jun 04/18 (d) Repeat applications, as needed, to keep work areas moist. Use cotton swabs or bristle brushes, as necessary, to make sure hidden areas, crevices, corners, and other difficult-to-access areas are contacted with rust remover. (e) Wash areas with liquid soap (53, Table 10, 51-30-01) and water. Use cotton swabs or bristle brushes, as necessary, to make sure rust remover is removed from hidden areas, crevices, corners, and other difficult-to-access areas. CAUTION Some heat guns can produce excessive heat (greater than 180 °F) that can damage paint on truss or damage nearby components. When using heat gun, take care not to damage nearby components or paint on engine truss with excessive heat. Be aware of potential fire hazards. (f) Dry surfaces completely. NOTE The use of a low-temperature heat gun is permitted, as needed, to make sure crevices are dry. (5) Using sandpaper (31, Table 10, 51-30-01), smooth and blend affected area. (6) Thoroughly rinse area with water and dry completely. (7) Remove masking. (8) After all corrosion is removed and affected material is blended and smoothed, measure remaining material thickness and make sure the following allowable damage limitations are not exceeded: (a) Engine truss mount tubes vary in diameter and wall thickness. Diameter of tubes is either 1.2 or 1.5 inches. Figure 202 identifies nominal wall thickness of each engine truss mount tube. Table 201 identifies nominal tube wall thickness and minimum tube wall thickness. Blended areas must have minimum blend ratio length/width to depth of 10:1. After corrosion or damage is repaired, remaining wall thickness must not be less than minimum tube wall thickness. Measure engine mount tube thickness using ultrasonic testing. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 4, 71-20-01. If tube wall thickness is below minimum allowable wall thickness, contact cognizant authority. Table 201 - Engine Truss Minimum Allowable Wall Thickness Nominal Tube Wall Thickness (inches) Minimum Tube Wall Thickness (inches) 0.049 0.044 0.058 0.053 0.065 0.059 0.083 0.077 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 204 Jun 04/18 (b) Weld types vary on engine truss mount. Determine thickness of two components being welded together and type of joint. Refer to Figure 202 and Figure 203. Use minimum face or bead width from Table 202 for thinner of two components. Maximum depth of repair from a smooth surface on weld is given in column C. Values in column C are determined as 10% of thickness of bead ((Face/2) X 0.1). If material is removed from truss mount assembly, refer to Table 201 for minimum limits. Blended areas must have minimum blend ratio length/width to depth of 10:1. (c) When repairs are made to engine truss attach fittings (bathtub fittings), gussets, or engine mount isolator fittings, perform blend over minimum 1-inch by 1-inch area to maximum allowable depth of 0.025 inch. Blended areas must have minimum blend ratio length/width to depth of 10:1. The bathtub fittings are comprised of two tubes, the inside tube has a nominal wall thickness of 0.058 inch and the outside tube has a nominal wall thickness of 0.063 inch. Acceptable to measure engine mount tube bathtub thickness using ultrasonic testing. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 4, 71-20-01. If tube wall thickness is below minimum allowable wall thickness, contact cognizant authority. (9) Wash area and thoroughly rinse with clean water. CAUTION Some heat guns can produce excessive heat (greater than 180 °F) that can damage paint on truss or damage nearby components. When using heat gun, take care not to damage nearby components or paint on engine truss with excessive heat. Be aware of potential fire hazards. (10) Dry area and crevices completely using hot air blower. CAUTION To avoid flash rust, minimize the time between drying after the application of rust remover and the application of primer pretreatment. (11) Mask areas not intended to be treated. (12) Apply primer wash (5, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. (13) Apply two coats of primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. Allow primer to cure. (14) Apply two coats of aluminum epoxy (54, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow aluminum epoxy to cure. Table 202 - Weld Joint Allowables Column A Thickness of Thinner Component of weld Joint (inches) Column B Part Number Minimum Face Bead Width Dimension (inches) Column C Maximum Depth of Repair (inches) 0.040 to 0.072 0.12 0.006 0.073 to 0.125 0.19 0.010 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 205 Jun 29/20 (15) Apply corrosion preventive compound (55, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow compound to dry. NOTE Per manufacturer, corrosion preventive compound should be applied using the specifically designed ACS-System (airmix application equipment) or the AAS-System (airless application equipment) for best results. Dry time is 1 hour. Brush application of corrosion preventive compound is possible but may result in less uniform appearance and longer drying time. (16) Remove masking. B. Engine Truss Tube Chafe Repair (1) Using flashlight and mirror, visually inspect engine truss tubes. Inspect full length and entire surface of tubes. Refer to Figure 204. (2) Determine type of engine truss component to be repaired. Refer to Figure 201. (3) Identify tube wall thickness. Refer to Figure 202. (4) Measure and record length, width and depth of chafed area. Length: Width: Depth: (5) Take photos of chafed area. (Data may be required if field repair drawing is necessary.) (6) Smooth and blend area to remove chafing damage, keeping minimum blend ratio, length/width to depth, of 5:1. Remove minimal amount of material to remove damage. Maintain roughness average 63 micro-inch surface texture using 400 grit sandpaper (30, Table 10, 51-30-01). (7) Perform nondestructive inspection after blending to make sure no cracks exist. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 8, 71-20-01, for general understanding of fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI) on truss tube. Record result of inspection. Report any findings to cognizant authority. (8) Perform nondestructive inspection to verify wall thickness. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 4, 71-20-01. Record wall thickness of blended area at thinnest measured wall thickness, and record wall thickness of adjacent non-worked area. Document results as a matrix pattern (0.25 x 0.25 inch matrix). Refer to Figure 206. Results (blended area): Results (adjacent non-worked area): (9) Measure and record length, width and depth of area after blending. Length: Width: Depth: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 206 Jun 29/20 (10) Take photos of blended area. (11) If blended area of wall thickness is equal to or greater than referenced Minimum Tube Wall Thickness, proceed with steps below. If wall thickness is less than Minimum Tube Wall Thickness, contact cognizant authority. Refer to Table 203. (12) Mask areas not intended to be treated. (13) Apply primer wash (5, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. (14) Apply two coats of primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. Allow primer to cure. (15) Apply one coat of aluminum epoxy (54, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow aluminum epoxy to cure. (16) Apply corrosion preventive compound (55, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow corrosion preventive compound to dry. (17) Remove masking. (18) To prevent further chafing of parts, it is permissible to install cushioned “P” clamps or tape (56, Table 10, 51-30-01), as required, or replace prop rod clip if location of damage is due to prop rod. Refer to 54-20-04. C. Engine Truss Gouge Repair NOTE Use this procedure to repair gouges to both left and right sides of engine truss caused by interference with cowl door strut assembly spring clip. Refer Figure 204. (1) Measure circumferential width of gouge. (2) If gouge circumferential width exceeds 0.320 inch, contact cognizant authority. (3) If gouge diameter is 0.320 inch or less, carefully blend out all damage using sandpaper (30, Table 10, 51-30-01). Remove minimum amount of material required to remove all damage. Maintain blend ratio of 5:1 minimum and surface finish roughness average of 63 microinch. (4) Perform Penetrant Inspection to make sure there are no cracks after blending. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 8, 71-20-01. Contact cognizant authority to report any adverse findings. Table 203 - Engine Truss Minimum Allowable Wall Thickness Nominal Tube Wall Thickness (inches) Minimum Tube Wall Thickness (inches) 0.049 0.044 0.058 0.053 0.065 0.059 0.083 0.077 MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 207 Jun 01/21 (5) Perform Ultrasonic Inspection to determine remaining wall thickness. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Manual, Part 4, 71-20-01. Contact cognizant authority if wall thickness is less than 0.067 inch for repair. (6) Mask areas not intended to be treated. (7) Apply primer wash (5, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. (8) Apply two coats primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. Allow primer to cure. (9) Apply one coat aluminum epoxy (54, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow aluminum epoxy to cure. (10) Apply corrosion preventive compound (55, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow corrosion preventive compound to dry. (11) Remove fasteners securing cowl door strut spring clip to aft cowling door. Refer to Figure 205 and, 51-40-02. (12) Remove cowl door strut spring clip and deburr holes in aft cowling door. (13) Position replacement cowl door strut spring clip (133-910107-51) on aft cowling door and secure with CR3214-4 fasteners. Refer to 51-40-02. (14) Apply chemical conversion solution (2, Table 2, 51-30-01) to bare metal. (15) Apply one coat primer (6, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. (16) Touch up paint, as required. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-20-00. D. Engine Truss Tube Minor Chafe Damage Repair (1) Locally blend and polish smooth, removing minimum amount of material necessary to clear all damage and achieve a smooth profile: (a) Maintain 20:1 minimum blend slope lengthwise/longitudinally, and 63 RMS or better surface finish. (b) Maintain 5:1 minimum and 10:1 maximum blend slope circumferentially and 63 RMS or better surface finish. (2) Check wall thickness of damaged tubes: (a) If wall thickness for (P/N 133-910026-47) and/or (P/N 133-910026-49), is less than 0.031 inch or width (circumferentially) is greater than 0.60 inch. Refer to 1.E. Engine Truss Tube Major Chafe Damage Repair. (b) If wall thickness for (P/N 133-910026-51) and/or (P/N 133-910026-53), is less than 0.040 inch or width (circumferentially) is greater than 0.50 inch. Refer to 1.E. Engine Truss Tube Major Chafe Damage Repair. (c) If wall thickness is 0.031 inch or greater and width (circumferentially) of blend is less than or equal to 0.60 inch. Proceed to Step (3). (d) If wall thickness is 0.040 inch or greater and width (circumferentially) of blend is less than or equal to 0.50 inch. Proceed to Step (3). MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 208 Jun 01/21 (3) Protect bare metal using wash primer (5, Table 3, 51-30-01). (4) Apply two coats urethane primer (8, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. Refer to manufactures instructions. (5) Apply one coat aluminum epoxy (54, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow aluminum epoxy to cure. (6) Make sure urethane primer completely covers tubes and adjacent tubes in areas of weld. (7) Apply corrosion preventive compound (55, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow corrosion preventive compound to dry. Refer to Corrosion Control Manual (TO 1T-6ABD-23), 20-40-00. (a) Runs, drips, or sags are acceptable. (b) Permissible to remove heavy over spray or puddles with lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01). (8) Make sure a minimum clearance of 0.1 inch between inlet screen and truss tubes to alleviate further damage. (9) To prevent further chafing of parts, it is permissible to install cushioned “P” clamps or tape (56, Table 10, 51-30-01), as required. E. Engine Truss Tube Major Chafe Damage Repair (1) Check wall thickness of damaged tubes: (a) If wall thickness is 0.031 inch or greater and width (circumferentially) of blend is less than or equal to 0.60 inch. Refer to 1.D. Engine Truss Tube Minor Chafe Damage Repair. (b) If wall thickness is 0.040 inch or greater and width (circumferentially) of blend is less than or equal to 0.50 inch. Refer to 1.D. Engine Truss Tube Minor Chafe Damage Repair. (c) If wall thickness for (P/N 133-910026-47) and/or (P/N 133-910026-49), is less than 0.031 inch or width (circumferentially) is greater than 0.60 inch. Proceed to Step (2). (d) If wall thickness for (P/N 133-910026-51) and/or (P/N 133-910026-53), is less than 0.040 inch or width (circumferentially) is greater than 0.50 inch. Proceed to Step (2). (2) Remove engine truss assembly. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-20-01. (3) Remove linseed oil plugs from damaged left hand and/or right hand lower truss tubes, (P/N 133-910026-47/-49/-51/-53) and from adjacent tubes to which new lower truss tubes are to be welded: (a) Make sure adjacent tubes: yoke tube (P/N 133-910026-17), left hand lower horizontal (P/N 133-910026-31), right hand lower horizontal (P/N 133-910026-33), left hand aft lower (P/N 133-910026-35), right hand aft lower (P/N 133-910026-37), center tube (P/N 133-910026-55), and center lower tube (P/N 133-910026-57). Refer to Figure 202. (b) Take care not to oversize holes or damage any surrounding structure. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 209 Jun 01/21 (c) Allow linseed oil to drain out. (d) Blow dry air through tubes for 30 minutes to make sure tubes are free of oil and/or moisture. (4) Mark locations of damaged tubes for reference when installing new tubes and cut to remove tubes from Truss Assembly. (5) Carefully blend to remove remnants of welds where damaged tubes were removed. (a) Take care not to blend into surface of adjacent tubes. (b) Maintain 63 RMS or better surface finish. (6) Make sure trunnion assembly, (P/N 133-910026-59); side tubes, (P/N 133-910026-31/-33/-35/-37/ -41/-45/-55/-57); and wall supports, (P/N 133-910102-19/-21/-69/-71) are all at nominal thickness. Refer to Figure 202. (7) Make sure no cracks have formed with one of following methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant (FPI), refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201 00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method C), sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (form D) developer. (b) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI), refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (high), nonaqueous (Form D), and developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. NOTE Report any adverse findings to cognizant authority for further assessment prior to continuing with this repair. (8) Remove paint and clean truss in area that is to be welded using a chemical stripper (16, Table 10, 51-30-01) or mechanical sanding with sandpaper (31, Table 10, 51-30-01): (a) Care should be taken with use of chemical strippers as some may contribute to corrosion. Stripper should not be allowed to drip into areas other than weld locations. Make sure that all stripper residue is removed after usage. (b) When area is dry, use wire brush (50, Table 10, 51-30-01) or rotary wire brush (steel or stainless steel). (c) Maintain 63 or better surface finish. (d) Using a clean lint-free cloth (19, Table 10, 51-30-01), wipe area clean with alcohol (1, Table 1, 51-30-01) or MPK (4, Table 1, 51-30-01). (9) Strip another area on truss to provide an attachment for welding machine ground clamp. Refer to Step 1.E. (7). (a) Attachment point for clamp should be as reasonably close to weld area as possible. (10) As required, obtain new tubes (P/N 133-910026-47/-49/-51/-53). (11) Preheat areas to be welded to between 400F and 800F using a neutral oxyacetylene flame. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 210 Jun 01/21 NOTE When applying heat to truss assembly, use general shop practice to make sure correct alignment of truss assembly. (12) Locate new tubes precisely using marks from Step (3) and weld new tubes in place using welding wire (61, Table 10, 51-30-01) per AWS A5.25. Refer to general shop practice. NOTE Welder to be qualified to AWS D17.1 or equivalent. (13) Welded areas shall be torch stress relieved with a neutral oxyacetylene flame at a temperature of 1000F. (a) Heat an area of 0.50 inch all around weld location. (b) Use a pyrometer or Tempilstick temperature indicator to determine when proper temperature has been reached. (c) Allow to cool in still air. (14) Make sure welded tubes (P/N 133-910026-47/-49/-51/-53) are straight within 0.02 inch per foot and 0.05 inch through total length: (a) Measurement to be made within 0.50 inch of welds. (15) Perform Magnetic Particle inspection. Refer to Nondestructive Inspection Methods (33B-1-1). (16) Inject linseed oil (45, Table 10, 51-30-01) in tubes per ASTM D260 into lower holes under pressure until it comes out of upper holes. (a) Allow oil to drain out of tubes through lower hole. NOTE It is acceptable to use (P/N A-A-371A) oil as an alternative. (17) Plug oil ports using rivets (P/N NAS1398C4), length as required. (a) Install rivets wet with sealant (3 or 5, Table 7, 51-30-01). (18) Mask areas not intended to be treated. (19) Protect bare metal using wash primer (5, Table 3, 51-30-01). (20) Apply two coats of urethane primer (8, Table 3, 51-30-01) to area. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (a) Apply one coat aluminum epoxy (54, Table 10, 51-30-01) to area. Allow aluminum epoxy to cure. (21) Make sure urethane primer completely covers tubes (P/N 133-910026-47/-49/-51/-53) and adjacent tubes in areas of weld and region which was stripped for ground clamp. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 211 Jun 01/21 (22) After paint has cured, apply one coat of corrosion preventive compound (55, Table 10, 51-30-01) by spray or brush. Refer to manufacturer's instructions. (a) Runs, drips, or sags are acceptable. (b) Permissible to remove heavy over spray or puddles with lint free absorbent rags. (23) Remove masking. (24) Install Engine Truss Assembly. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-20-01. (25) Make sure no more chafing exists. (a) To prevent further chafing of intake duct, it is permissible to install cushioned “P” clamps, as required. (b) As required, reposition clamps or install tape (56, Table 10, 51-30-01) on tubes to prevent further chafing. F. Engine Truss Left Trunnion Assembly Gusset Repair (After TCTO 1T-6A-839/TD T6-AFC-67) NOTE This procedure prevents nutplates installed on brackets (P/N 133-930011-1/-3) from interfering with engine truss tube. Refer to Figure 208. (1) Open left engine cowling door (823). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-09. (2) Remove oil cooler fairing (820). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-06. (3) Remove left lower aft cowling skin (821AB). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Power Plant (TO 1T-6ABD-2-71), 71-10-07. (4) Remove aircraft battery, and discard nut (P/N MS21045-3). Refer to Maintenance Manual, Electrical Power (TO 1T-6ABD-2-24), 24-30-02. (5) Disconnect forward starter/generator flex air duct and tie wraps. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Starting (TO 1T-6ABD-2-80), 80-10-04. (6) Remove bolt (P/N NAS6606-3) and washers (P/N NAS1149F0332P) that secure clamp (P/N MS21919WCJ15) and oil cooler hose assembly to brackets. Do not remove clamp from oil cooler hose assembly. Refer to Figure 208. Discard bolt and washers. (7) Remove bolts (P/N NAS6603-3), washers (P/N NAS1149F03322P), and brackets (133-930011-0001 and 133-930011-0003) from left engine gusset. Discard bolts and washers. (8) Perform one of repair procedures (Repair Option 1 thru 4) as required. (9) Repair Option 1: MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 71-20-00 Page 212 Jun 01/21 (a) Carefully slot misaligned holes in gusset as shown in Figure 209. Maintain minimum 0.150 inch edge ligament (edge of hole to edge of trunnion gusset). (b) Deburr all sharp edges. (c) Inspect discrepant holes to make sure that no cracks have formed using one of following Non-Destructive Inspection (NDI) methods: 1 Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI), refer to TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (fluorescent penetrant, general procedure, solvent removable, method C), Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) developer. Make sure no fluorescent penetrant is in fastener bores. 2 Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI), refer to ASTM E1417, Type I, Sensitivity Level 3 (High), Nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. GENERAL Refer to Illustrated Parts Catalog (TO 1T-6ABD-4), 78-10-05. 2. INSPECTION The engine exhaust pipe is inspected for condition, security, and foreign objects on a regularly scheduled basis, in accordance with the Preflight, Thruflight, Postflight Inspection Workcards. Any damage found should be further investigated to determine the extent and classification of damage. Refer to 51-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 78-20-00 Page 101 Jun 04/18 EXHAUST COLLECTOR/NOZZLE 78-20-0052-30-00 EXHAUST PIPE 100100100100100 ALLOWABLE DAMAGE 1. REPAIR LIMITATIONS If damage affects the engine exhaust pipe, it should be classified as either repairable or replacement. Refer to 51-10-00. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 78-20-00 Page 201 Jun 04/18 EXHAUST COLLECTOR/NOZZLE 78-20-0052-30-00 EXHAUST PIPE 200200200200200 REPAIRS 1. REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT Typical repairs are permanent and should be carried out to restore the structural integrity of the engine exhaust pipe. A. Repair Procedure NOTE This repair procedure applies to exhaust pipes with part numbers 133-950000-1 or 133-950000-7. NOTE Repair exhaust pipe with cracks less than 3 inches in length in accordance with the following repair procedure. NOTE Replace exhaust pipe if cracks are greater than 3 inches in length. (1) Remove affected exhaust pipe from engine. Refer to Maintenance Manual, Exhaust (TO 1T-6ABD-2-78), 78-10-01. (2) Remove all carbon from interior and exterior surfaces using hot soapy water and suitable brush. (a) Allow exhaust pipe to dry thoroughly. (3) Use a suitable NDT technique to accurately locate and mark end of crack(s) using one of the following methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI) in accordance with TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (b) FPI in accordance with ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. (4) Use wire brush (50, Table 10, 51-30-01), on both inside and outside of exhaust pipe weld area. (5) Rinse repair area with methyl propyl ketone (4, Table 1, 51-30-01), and allow to dry. (6) Prior to welding crack, accomplish one of the following procedures: (a) Cap openings in exhaust pipe with wooden blocks and seal remaining crevices with tape. Introduce an argon purge, at 10 cubic feet per hour, 15 minutes before welding and continue until the repair is complete. (b) Place a copper sheet, a minimum of 0.063 inch thick, against the inside surface of the crack. MODEL 3000 STRUCTURAL REPAIR MANUAL 78-20-00 Page 202 Jun 04/18 (c) Alternate methods, in keeping with accepted welding practices, of purging to prevent oxidation on the back side of the weld are acceptable. (7) Repair cracking using gas tungsten arc welding process and a welding rod, type ERNiCrMo - 3 per AWS A5.14. (8) Make sure no cracking has formed or remains using one of the following methods: (a) Fluorescent penetrant inspection (FPI) in accordance with TO 33B-1-2 SWP 201-00 (Fluorescent Penetrant, General Procedure, Solvent Removable, Method C), sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer. (b) FPI in accordance with ASTM E1417, Type I, sensitivity level 3 (High), nonaqueous (Form D) developer with acceptance criteria per MIL-STD-1907 Grade A. (9) If cracks are found, repeat Steps (6) through (8) until no cracks are found. (10) Install exhaust pipe. Refer to Maintenance Manual, 78-10-01.

Published by direction of: Commander, Naval Air Systems Command 12 January 2019 LIST OF EFFECTIVE MAJOR REVISIONS Revision 1: Clarified engine mount truss bolt inspection. Modified wing aft and diagonal spar inspection requirements. Revision 2: Edited zonal inspection requirements. Added zonal inspection for the control stick to Paragraph 2-7.2. Added figures to Appendix A (pages A-221 thru A-244) for documentation of flight control discrepancies found during zonal inspections. Reissue: Complete revision. Eliminated even-odd ACI distinction and required all tasks during each ACI event. Added flight hour thresholds for NDI inspections. Modified bearing inspection requirements and removed requirement to remove bearings every other ACI. Corrected or modified numerous sections. Revision 4: Added the Requirements for inspection of T-6B aircraft in addition to original requirements for T-6A aircraft in the basic release. Added airframe strip and paint requirement as part of the ACI. Added removal of the lower aft engine cowling during disassembly. This provides access to the to the oil cooler that is having corrosion problems, and permits full inspection of the engine truss, which was an existing inspection that could not be fully completed without the lower cowing removed. Added Removal of wing leading edges. The leading edges are primed in the same manner as the rest of the wing that is having corrosion issues. The leading edges are not inspected at the O-level. This inspection ensures the wing leading edges are inspected each ACI cycle. Added details to existing inspections for wing spars and dry bays. The updated instructions break down the original inspection requirements into individual steps to provide better inspection results.
