SECTION I GENERAL INSTRUCTIONS 1-1 SCOPE 1-1.1 GENERAL a. This specification establishes the Aircraft Condition Inspection (ACI) requirements for the T-6A/B aircraft. b. The ACI requirements provide for airframe and system inspection, deficiency identification and correction, preventive maintenance, modification and technical directive compliance. ACI requirements are expected to restore aircraft subjected to this process to a condition which can be maintained at the field level to ensure a high level of operational availability for the duration of the designed service period. These requirements also provide interim support during the total service life and include but are not limited to: (1) A thorough and comprehensive inspection of selected aircraft structure, (flight essential systems and components) by appropriate inspection methods, correcting defects and repairing as required to ensure serviceability until next ACI induction. (2) Incorporation of all authorized depot-level technical directives. (3) Replacement of depot-level time change components which will exceed specified replacement intervals prior to next scheduled ACI. c. Adjustments, checks, tests, repairs, inspections, preventive maintenance, and the rework procedures coincidental thereto shall be accomplished in accordance with applicable directives and publications as directed by this specification. 1-1.2 CONTENTS a. Section I of this specification provides general instructions relative to: (1) The purpose and scope of ACI (2) Specification revision information (3) ACI intervals (4) Definitions of the terminology of Aircraft Condition Inspection (5) Maintenance publications and documents required to perform ACI b. Section II of this specification contains general and specific rework requirements; standards, guidelines, instructions, inspections, tests and rework to be complied with and accomplished by the Rework Activity. Each requirement shall be complied with as an item of scheduled maintenance at the specified rework or time limitation. At completion of all such repair and rework, the aircraft and its accessories/components shall be completely reassembled, applicable systems rigged, aligned and/or tested in accordance with the specified requirements and the aircraft flight checked in accordance with Section III. (1) The scheduled maintenance requirements prescribed in this specification comprise the minimum requirements necessary to ensure the timely discovery and correction of actual and/or anticipated defects based on the aircraft class and intended use. Compliance with these requirements is mandatory. (2) Unscheduled maintenance requirements are those requirements which cannot be directly related to any scheduled requirement. These are only discovered as an incidental result of the following 1-2 functions which are accomplished as a part of and during the scheduled inspections: (1) review of aircraft logbooks and records, (2) the operational/functional testing of system or (3) inspection of the aircraft and its components during ACI. c. Section III describes the Post ACI functional check flight requirements to be complied with prior to the delivery of the reworked aircraft. d. Section IV is a tabulated listing by aircraft systems of components requiring replacement as a function of aircraft flight hours, unit operating time or cycles, or ACI intervals. e. Section V is the Maintenance Requirements Exclusions List that identifies phase maintenance and special maintenance requirements that are completed during the completion of ACI. This list is intended for use to avoid duplication of effort when completion of phase/special inspections are required upon return to the operating activity or desired to be completed concurrently with ACI. f. Section VI is the Aircraft Maintenance History Summary Report Requirements. This section provides general and specific reporting requirements to ensure complete documentation of maintenance performed during ACI. g. Section VII is the Structural Damage Report Requirements. These requirements are supplemented by (1) illustrations giving specific locations and (2) forms to report amount and severity of damage. h. Section VIII contains the functional Reporting Requirements. These requirements are supplemented by forms to report action(s) taken during testing. 1-1.3 AIRCRAFT CONDITION INSPECTION INTERVALS a. Aircraft Condition Inspection (ACI) for the T-6A/B aircraft is prescribed initially as a function of the planned operational service life of the aircraft. Operational service life is measured in terms of operational service months accumulated between periods of standard rework. b. The ACI requirements contained in the T-6 ACI Specification were determined through Reliability Centered Maintenance (RCM) analysis. T-6 ACI requirements will be continuously updated and refined through application of the T-6 RCM program as defined by the T-6 RCM/Age Exploration Program Plan. The T-6 ACI is intended to provide an efficient grouping of those tasks that require depot level skills, equipment, extensive disassembly, special access, or repair facilities that are performed at regularly scheduled intervals determined to be optimum for maintaining the aircraft condition while optimizing the aircraft’s operational availability. c. Based on RCM analysis and task packaging optimization, the initial ACI for each aircraft is be accomplished after 120 months of service, and the interval (operational service months per period) for the T-6A/B Aircraft has been established at 60 months. d. Service periods, total service life and authorized extensions thereto are established by PMA-273, Patuxent River, MD. 1-2 CHANGE RECOMMENDATIONS a. Recommendations for additions, deletions, or changes to the requirements of this specification are invited and should be submitted to the Naval Air Systems Command, PMA-273, 48187 Standley Road, Building 4010, Patuxent River, Maryland, 20670 (Attention: T-6 APMSE). b. Revisions and changes to this specification will be prepared and promulgated by PMA-273, Patuxent River, MD. 1-3 DEFINITIONS a. The purpose of this Glossary is to establish a mutual basis of communication to avoid misinterpretation and 1-3 distortion of the terminology, and therefore, the intent of the requirements contained in the specification. b. The terms are defined in the context of their usage as applied to the requirements of the specification. Generally accepted interpretations and colloquial usage are unacceptable unless in exact agreement. c. Terminology used in the specification and not defined in the Glossary shall receive the interpretation as defined by the Cognizant Government Representative. ABRASION. The wearing away of material by rubbing or scraping (synonymous with chafing). ACCESSIBLE. Areas exposed by the removal of non-permanent fasteners, access doors, panels, fairings, etc. or other disassembly required by a maintenance requirement which does not involve destructive disassembly unless otherwise specified. ACCESSORY. A part, subassembly, or assembly designed for use in conjunction with, or to supplement another assembly, unit, or set that contributes to the effectiveness thereof without extending or varying the basic function of the assembly or set. An accessory may be used for testing, adjusting, or calibrating purposes. Examples are test instrument, recording camera for radar set, headphones, and emergency power supply. AIRCRAFT CONDITION INSPECTION (ACI). Depot level aircraft maintenance accomplished upon an attainment of a specified number of calendar months of service as designated by PMA-273. AIRCRAFT DESIGNATION. A unique number assigned by the OEM to a specific aircraft BUNO or Tail Number. AIRFRAME. The structural components, including the framework and skin, of such parts as the fuselage, empennage, wings, control surfaces, landing gear (minus wheels and tires) and engine mounts. AIRFRAME ACCESSORIES. The items of equipment that are required for operation of the aircraft and that cannot be considered an integral part of the airframe or engine, such as wheels, brakes, hydraulic equipment, fuel system, deicing equipment, anti-icing equipment, and other items not an integral part of the airframe, regardless of whether attached to the engine or airframe. ASSEMBLY. Any combination or number of parts or subassemblies joined together to perform a specific function. ATTACHMENT. A part, subassembly, or assembly designed for use in conjunction with another assembly, unit, or set that contributes to the effectiveness thereof by varying the basic function of the assembly or set. CALIBRATE. To determine and make required corrections in calibration standards or Precision Measuring Equipment (PME) used in precise measurement or to repair adjust and align equipment so that it functions within assigned tolerances; may consist of the comparison of two instruments, one which is a certified calibration standard of known accuracy, to detect and adjust any discrepancy in the accuracy of the other instrument or Plant Equipment (PE) being compared with the certified calibration standard. CHAFING. The wearing away of material by rubbing or scraping (synonymous with abrasion). CHECK. To perform a thorough examination to ascertain the existence of unacceptable deviations from the intended state or condition as established by specifications. CHECK FLIGHT; FUNCTIONAL (FCF). Airborne operational test performed to determine whether the airframe, power plant, accessories, and other items of equipment are functioning per predetermined standards when subjected to the intended operating environment. DRPs shall perform FCFs per the procedures of OPNAVINST 4790.2G, Volume I, Chapter 12. CHECKOUTS. A sequence of functional, operational and calibration tests to determine the condition and status of a system or element thereof. CLEANLINESS. The state of being free from impurities, impediments, and foreign matter not specified to be applied to the surface in question. COGNIZANT GOVERNMENT REPRESENTATIVE. The government office (NAVPRO, AFPRO, CAO, etc.) delegated the local administration of Naval/Air Force (JPATS) contracts. COMPONENT. A number of parts or subassemblies or any combination thereof, joined together to perform a specific function. 1-4 COMPONENT, SCHEDULED REMOVAL. Components whose overhaul or replacement schedule is established as a function of service use (flight hours, unit operating time or calendar time, cycles, events or OSP intervals) (see NAVAIRINST 4790.3B). COMPOSITE MATERIAL. A material composed of two or more different constituents, the combination of which results in a product superior in some mechanical properties to any of its constituents parts. CONCURRENT COMPONENT REWORK. The removal of a defective component from an aircraft, repair of that item concurrent with ACI processing of the aircraft, and reinstallation of that item on the same aircraft. CONFIGURATION IDENTIFICATION. The current approved or conditionally approved technical documentation for a configuration item as set forth in specifications, drawings, and associated lists and reference documents. CONTROL LETTER. A document prepared by the contractor to track a particular maintenance action or item which does not result in a configuration change. Control letters do not require government approval. CORROSION. An action or process which destroys metal by chemical or electrochemical action and converts it into an oxide, hydroxide, or sulfate compound. CRACK. A break, fracture, crevice, or separation in the structure of a part. CRAZING. Fine cracks, which may extend in a network, in plastic material (i.e., windshields, canopy glass, windows, etc.). DAMAGE. Impairment of an aircraft/item/part by a physical force. DEFECT. Any nonconformance of a unit or part with specified requirements (synonymous with discrepancy). DEFECT, CRITICAL. A defect that constitutes a hazardous or unsafe condition, or as determined by experience or judgment could conceivably become so, relative to its deleterious effect on the prime intended function, safety of flight or mission capability of the aircraft or its operating personnel. The condition warrants that corrective action is required prior to release of the aircraft for flight. DEFECT, MAJOR. A defect, other than critical, that could result in failure or materially reduce the usability of the unit or part for its intended purpose. DEFECT, MINOR. A defect that does not materially reduce or if not corrected will not degrade the usability of the unit or part for its intended purpose, or is a departure from standards which has no significant bearing on the effective use or operation of the unit or part. DEFECTIVE. The state of possessing a deviation from specified requirements. DEFORMATION. Any disfiguration or change in form or shape from the intended design configuration. DELAMINATION. A physical break of the bond between the binder material and any two or more plies of laminated panels fabricated of plastic, metal, composite material, or other material. DEPOT LEVEL MAINTENANCE (DLM) SPECIFICATION. A DLM Specification details the engineering and processing requirements to perform scheduled depot level inspection and repair maintenance on aircraft, engines, major components, or support equipment. There are a variety of DLM programs used by NAVAIR to support the scheduled DLM concept. DESIGNATED REPAIR POINT (DRP). The industrial establishment, either government or commercial, designated by NAVAIR or the Department of Defense (DoD) as having DLM responsibility for rework of a particular model aircraft or component. DETAILED VISUAL INSPECTION. An intensive visual examination of a specific area, system, or assembly to detect damage failure or irregularity. Inspection aids (such as a mirror, flashlight, or magnifying glass) should be used as required to ensure all areas are thoroughly examined. DETERIORATION. The breakup, eating away or decomposition of a substance by the action of weather, corrosion, or other environmental conditions. DISCREPANCY. Any deviation, disagreement, difference or inconsistency, physical or otherwise, of an aircraft part or 1-5 assembly from the design specification, usage or operations (synonymous with defect). DISTORTION. Any disfigurement or change in form or shape from the intended design configuration resulting from a twisting or torsional action. DISTURBED SYSTEM. A system whose installed integrity has been interrupted, broken, or interfered with to the extent that system installation and operation cannot be assured without verification by a functional or operational check or test. Examples include removal and maintenance of electrical wiring, connectors and components, or removal of hydraulic lines and components. ECONOMICAL REPAIR. Repair that can be accomplished using the economical repair criteria of NAVAIRINST 4700.20. ELECTRIC/ELECTRONIC WIRING CIRCUITRY VERIFICATION. A test of system wiring and wiring components to verify ability of aircraft or component wiring to perform its intended function when mated to a set of operational black boxes. This may be accomplished by any of the following procedures: a) Functional or operational test of the system using existing aircraft black boxes, if operable, or “slave” units, if available. Tests shall be limited to the depth required to demonstrate adequacy of system wiring. b) Continuity and insulation resistance tests to ensure the adequacy of wiring to perform its intended circuitry function. EQUIPMENT. A collection of items consisting of parts, subassemblies, components, assemblies, units, groups, sets, subsystems, and systems. EVIDENCE. Factual data which establishes the possibility of an existing or impending unsatisfactory condition. EXAMINATION. An element of inspection consisting of investigation, without the use of special laboratory appliances or procedures, of supplies and services to determine conformance to those specified requirements that can be determined by such investigations. Examination is generally nondestructive. EXTERIOR SURFACE. That part of the airframe, or component, exposed to the elements when in a "clean" flight configuration, including wing and stabilizer control surface wells (aileron, flap, rudder, and elevator). Does not include landing gear structure, wheel wells, or areas exposed by deflection of slats, vanes, speed brakes, wing folds, etc., or extension of landing gear. FAILURE. The inability of an item to perform within previously specified or established units. FLEET READINESS CENTER (FRC). One of several government aviation activities located in multiple locations around the United States and Japan authorized to provide/perform integrated off-flight line repair, in-service I-level and D-level scheduled inspections/modifications, check, test, repair/manufacture of aeronautical components and SE for supported aircraft. FLEET READINESS CENTER SOUTHEAST (FRCSE). A government aviation activity located onboard NAS Jacksonville, Florida authorized to provide/perform integrated off-flight line repair, in-service I-level and D-level scheduled inspections/modifications, check, test, repair/manufacture of aeronautical components and SE for supported aircraft. FLEET SUPPORT TEAM (FST). A team delegated the authority and assigned the responsibility to perform specific maintenance engineering and logistical management functions in support of PMA-273. FRAYING. The wearing away by rubbing, usually of woven, braided, or stranded material, which results in a worn or ragged appearance. GROOVE. Any narrow furrow, depression, or slit on the surface of a part. GROUP. A collection of units, assemblies, or subassemblies that is a subdivision of a set or system, but is not capable of performing a complete operational function (see System). INBOARD WING STATION (IWS). A width measurement left or right of and parallel to the centerline of the aircraft. Inboard wing station (IWS) 0.00 is on BL 0.00. INCLUSION. A void or discontinuity in the molecular structure of metal. INSPECT. To perform a critical investigation of an item, unit, component, or airframe through the visual, auditory, 1-6 olfactory and tactile senses independent of or in conjunction with specialized equipment such as NDI. The process uses simple manipulation, gauging, and measurements, as required, for the specific intent of determining conformance to the assigned specifications within the tolerance permitted. INSPECTION. To compare the characteristics of an item with established standards. Inspection includes, but is not limited to, sight, hearing, smell, touch and other investigations; simple physical manipulation, gauging and measurement. The process may require partial disassembly of the item. INSPECTION, CONDITIONAL. An inspection conducted as a result of a specific overlimit condition, or as a result of circumstances or events which create an administrative requirement for an inspection. Examples of overlimit conditions include hard landing, overstress, overtemp, lighting strike, overweight takeoff or landing, and field arrestment. Examples of administrative actions or requirements include precarrier or postcarrier inspections, one-time inspections directed by higher authority (not directed by a TD), and compass calibrations, (when not directed by special inspection MRC's). A logbook entry is required to document a conditional inspection of an aircraft and for any component/equipment having an Aeronautical Equipment Service Record (AESR) logbook or SRC card. INSPECTION, SPECIAL. A scheduled inspection with a standard interval other than daily, calendar/phased, turnaround, major engine, or DLM. The intervals are specified in the applicable Planned Maintenance Systems (PMSs) publication and are based on elapsed calendar time, flight hours, operating hours, or number of cycles/events (e.g., 7, 14, 28 days/50, 100, 150, 200 hours, etc.). Per OPNAVINST 4970.2G, Vol. I, para. 14.1.8. INSPECTION, VISUAL/DYE-PENETRANT. To inspect for cracks first via visual methods and then, if a crack is suspected, confirm or deny presence of crack by use of dye-penetrant technique. LOCAL ENGINEERING SPECIFICATION (LES). A repair instruction developed by the FST (formerly Cognizant Field Activity (CFA)) to be used only when the subject matter cannot be added to an existing technical manual, or for specific depot level repairs. These instructions may also provide repair procedures when replacement parts are not available. In this case, demand for the parts must be documented to supply. An LES can also detail specific DLM process requirements for a particular program to be followed by all DRPs. For contractual reasons, an LES included in a DLM Specification cannot reference a LPS which only applies to FRC’s (formerly NAVAVNDEPOTs). LOCAL PROCESS SPECIFICATION (LPS). A local process instruction used by FRC’s (formerly NAVAVNDEPOTs) to tailor specifications, standards and technical manuals to control local processes. Usually peculiar to a specific process at a specific facility. If included in a DLM Specification, an LPS provides examples of standards and processes that can be used by DRPs performing DLM. MAINTENANCE HISTORY SUMMARY (MHS) REPORT. A report issued after DLM detailing the work performed, man-hours expended, and the aircraft age and flight hours when inducted. MAINTENANCE REQUIREMENT CARD (MRC). Card sets issued by COMNAVAIRSYSCOM containing scheduled maintenance requirements applicable to I-level and O-level activities for the specific aircraft/SE for which they are issued. MAJOR STRUCTURAL DAMAGE. Damage which requires removal or extensive repair, and repair or replacement of airframe structural members. MISSION ESSENTIAL EQUIPMENT. All equipment, parts and accessories necessary to perform a specified mission as defined in OPNAVINST 5442.4M. MODIFY. To alter in appearance, performance, function, position, or effect. NICK. Any notch, slit, cut, or chip on the surface of a part. OVERHAUL, COMPONENT. Rework performed on a component which includes disassembly sufficient to inspect all constituent parts, followed by cleaning, repair, replacement of consumables and defective parts as required, servicing, re-assembly, and checks/tests in accordance with applicable overhaul specifications, instructions and procedures. Typically not a requirement of an airframe DLM Specification unless parts are not available through supply and a special work request is submitted through the ACC. PART. One piece or two or more pieces joined together, not normally subject to disassembly without destruction of designed use. 1-7 PHASED DEPOT MAINTENANCE (PDM). Provides for airframe, systems and component inspection, defect correction, preventative maintenance, modification and TD compliance. Aircraft are inducted for PDM based on a fixed calendar/flight hour schedule. Specific areas of an airframe are inspected at each different depot phase. PITTING. Any small, approximately circular indentation, depression, hollow or scar in the surface of a part; generally the result of corrosion or erosive action. QUALITY ASSURANCE. A planned and systematic pattern of all actions necessary to provide adequate confidence that the item or product conforms to established technical requirements. REFINISH. To restore an existing surface finish without removal of all the existing finish. The process of refinishing includes a) cleaning the affected area to remove all loose and scaling paint or other finishing material, soil, and contaminants b) feather-edging the remaining original finish to a smooth surface and c) applying new finish coatings (including chemical conversion coatings). REFURBISH. To repair and renovate aircraft interior furnishings to acceptable standards of appearance and comfort consistent with the assigned mission of the aircraft. Includes replacement of deteriorated, worn or damaged furnishings. REINSTALL. The reinstallation of a part or component in its former position to accomplish its former function. RELIABILITY. The probability that material will perform its intended function for a specified period under stated conditions. REMOVE. The physical separation of an item from its designed position. Removal is normally required to facilitate a maintenance action on the item or on the area or items exposed by the removal. Implicit in the requirement for removal is the requirement for reinstallation. REPAIR. Whatever is required to restore an item to serviceable status, including preparation, disassembly, inspection, fault correction, replacement of parts, adjustment, reassembly, calibration and tests. REPAIR AS REQUIRED. The repair of discrepant items when the repair is technically feasible or economically justified unscheduled and is based on inspections and tests or authorized directives to restore the item to an operable condition. REPLACE. To install a like serviceable item in place of the removed item. REPLACE AS REQUIRED. The unscheduled replacement of discrepant items when the repair is technically or economically justified and is based on inspections and tests or authorized directives to restore the item to an operable condition. REPLACE-NEW. To install a new, vice repaired and overhauled, serviceable item in place of the replaced item. REWORK ACTIVITY. The industrial establishment, either government or commercial, designated by the Naval Air Systems Command/Air Force Material Command or Department of Defense as having depot maintenance responsibility for rework of a particular model aircraft or aircraft components. SCHEDULED REMOVAL COMPONENT. Component whose overhaul or replacement schedule is established as a function of service use (flight hours, unit operating time or calendar time, cycle, events, or OSP intervals) SERVICE PERIOD. A prescribed number of calendar months that an aircraft is in the physical custody of an operating activity for use prior to ACI. SECURITY INSPECTION. An inspection to verify that an item is positively and safely attached and secured in the approved manner specified by applicable drawings and specifications. SERVICE. The performance of any act (other than corrective maintenance) required to maintain an item of equipment in operating condition, such as lubricating, fueling, oiling, cleaning, etc., but does not include periodic replacement of parts or any corrective maintenance task. SERVICEABLE. The condition of an item in which all requirements of repair, check/test, rework, or modification, as applicable, have been accomplished, making it capable of performing the function or requirements for which originally designed or later modified as directed by approved TDs. (Synonymous with Ready for Issue (RFI)). SERVICE LIFE EXPECTANCY. The projected operational usefulness of an aircraft component in terms of operating 1-8 time, cycles, or calendar age as determined through engineering estimates or actual operational experience. The time or age figure (i.e., 1000 hours, 36 months, etc.) used in relation to service life expectancy represents the point at which continued use of the component would create a high probability of failure within a short period of time. SET. A unit or units and necessary assemblies, subassemblies, and parts connected or associated together to perform an operational function. SPECIFIED. Used to define a definite amount, operation or limitation which has been established and is contained in applicable directives. SUBASSEMBLY. Two or more parts which form a portion of an assembly or a unit, replaceable as a whole, but having a part or parts which are individually replaceable. SYSTEM (ELECTRICAL-ELECTRONICS). A combination of two or more parts, assemblies or sets generally physically separated when in operation and such other assemblies, subassemblies and parts interconnected as necessary to perform an operational function or functions. SYSTEM (GENERAL). A combination of parts, assemblies, and sets joined together to perform a specific operational function or functions. TECHNICAL DIRECTIVE (TD). A document authorized and issued by COMNAVAIRSYSCOM to provide technical information necessary to properly and systematically inspect or alter the configuration of aircraft, engines, systems, or equipment subsequent to establishment of each respective baseline configuration. TDs include all types of changes and bulletins and consist of information that cannot be disseminated satisfactorily by revisions to technical manuals. NATEC controls assignment of TD numbers. TEST. Evaluation of aircraft items (e.g., airframe, power plant, accessories, equipment, equipage, etc.) under specified conditions to verify functional conformance to predetermined requirements in accordance with applicable directives. TEST, BENCH. Test of individual items using shop equipment. TEST, FUNCTIONAL. The quantitative evaluation of a system or component to assure its ability to perform over the full operating range as designed and within specified limits. Test equipment is normally used to provide precise inputs and to make precise measurements. TEST, OPERATIONAL. The exercise of a system or component, within its operating modes, to assure operation without interference and in proper direction and sequence of intended performance. Normal operation is verified through observation of overall performance without resort to measurement. THRESHOLD INSPECTION. An inspection of a designated functionally significant item during scheduled DLM based upon the attainment of some predetermined limit, e.g., flight hours, arrested landings, operating months, fatigue life expended, etc. UNAUTHORIZED INSTALLATIONS. Any modification or addition of material or components to an aircraft not authorized by configuration publications or by a verified NAVAIR TD. UNIT. An assembly or any combination of parts, subassemblies and assemblies mounted together normally capable of independent operation in a variety of situations. UNSCHEDULED MAINTENANCE CHECKS. A maintenance action (functional or operational test, calibration, inspection, etc.) to determine the condition and status of a system/component required as a result of an operational discrepancy or other out-of-limit condition. ZONAL INSPECTION. A general visual inspection of all structure and installations contained within the designated boundaries of a zone. Structure and installations within zones that require more extensive inspections are separately identified by specific requirements. Zonals ensure that the aircraft's true condition is accurately and completely inspected and recorded. ZONE. An area of the aircraft defined by physical boundaries, title, and major installations. A zone encompasses all structure, wiring, connectors, tubing, lines, components and equipment found within the zonal boundaries. Designated zones ensure that every square inch of the aircraft is inspected. 1-9 1-4 ACRONYMS ACC (Aircraft Controlling Custodian) ASR (Assembly Service Record) DLM (Depot Level Maintenance) DRP (Depot Repair Point) EHR (Equipment Historical Record) FCF (Functional Check Flight) FSI (Functionally Significant Item) FST (Fleet Support Team) IWS (Inboard Wing Station) JPATS (Joint Primary Aircraft Training System) LES (Local Engineering Specification) LH (Left Hand) MHS (Maintenance/History Summary) MLG (main Landing Gear) MRC (Maintenance Requirement Card) NBNC (Noted But Not Corrected) NDI (Non-Destructive Inspection) NLG (Nose Landing Gear) OBOGS (Onboard Oxygen Generating System) OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) OSP (Operating Service Period) PMS (Planned Maintenance Systems) P/N (Part Number) RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) RH (Right Hand) SRC (Scheduled Removal Component) SSI (Structurally Significant Item) TD (Technical Directive) T/M/S (Type/Model/Series) TYCOM (Type Commander) WRA (Weapons Repairable Assembly) WUC (Work Unit Code) 1-10 1-5 MAINTENANCE REFERENCES a. Compliance with latest issue date of all military/commercial technical manuals, directives, specifications, publications, and Navy Technical Directives (TD’s)/Air Force Technical Orders (TO’s) listed is mandatory when: (1) They are pertinent to the aircraft or installed equipment and the Rework Activity is authorized to accomplish the work therein. (2) They prescribe rework policies, use of materials and procedures for rework. b. Compliance with the latest revision of all FRCSE instructions listed is mandatory when the ACI is being performed at FRCSE. Other facilities performing this ACI may opt to adhere to these instructions only if the instruction is performed in its entirety. c. The use of locally developed instructions as an equivalent to listed references is not permitted without review and authorization by the Cognizant Engineering Authority.
