0014 T-6 Cockpit Altitude Warning Ground Check JX6100103 T-6 Exterior Paint and Markings Drawing, Navy Orange Scheme 2-1 SECTION II AIRCRAFT CONDITION INSPECTION (ACI) REQUIREMENTS 2-1 GENERAL MAINTENANCE STANDARDS a. This section contains specific rework, inspection, and test requirements to be accomplished by the depot level Rework Activity responsible for the Aircraft Condition Inspection of the T-6A/B series aircraft. Each requirement shall be complied with as an item of scheduled maintenance at each ACI unless otherwise specified. (1) Component nomenclature used herein is in general accordance with that used in the aircraft maintenance manuals. (2) The inspection, replacement or other maintenance action required by this specification on specific equipment not installed on particular T-6A/B aircraft shall be disregarded on those aircraft so affected. (3) Part numbers listed in this specification are for reference only. Equivalent parts with different part numbers or identified only by nomenclature, serving the specified or implied function, are subject to the specified maintenance requirements. 2-1.1 GENERAL REQUIREMENTS a. Aircraft/engine organizational level scheduled maintenance requirements. (1) Phase Inspections: Accomplishment of the next aircraft and engine phase inspection requirements is not a requirement of ACI. Partial compliance occurs through performance of equivalent ACI requirements and is designated by exception on the Maintenance Requirements Exclusion List. (2) Aircraft Special Inspections: Accomplishment of requirements in the Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (A1-T6AAA-6/TO 1T-6ABD-6) that become due during rework is not a requirement of ACI with the exception of requirements for safety of flight and survival systems/equipment. (3) Preflight/Aircraft Launch Inspections: Accomplishment of the Preflight and Aircraft Launch Inspections are requirements of ACI. Preflight and Aircraft Launch Inspections will be performed before all functional check flights following ACI and before final acceptance of the aircraft. (4) Corrosion Control Inspection: Complete compliance of all corrosion inspections occurs through completion of equivalent ACI requirements. (5) Aircraft Unscheduled Maintenance Check: Accomplishment of Unscheduled Maintenance Checks is a requirement of ACI when due. b. Maintenance Practices: All maintenance and structural repairs shall be accomplished in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals, specifications, and standards. All previously installed repairs which do not conform to the Navy/Air Force maintenance practices shall be reworked to the above standards unless otherwise directed by the Cognizant Government Representative. 2-1.2 ENGINEERING SUPPORT REQUIREMENTS a. Engineering capability is required to perform continuous surveillance of the rework process, to solve problems and to develop rework procedures/processes/repairs not otherwise provided for in applicable technical publications. b. Major rework or repair not otherwise provided in applicable technical publications requires a Cognizant 2-2 Engineering Authority approved Repair Plan. 2-1.3 DEFECT CORRECTION CRITERIA a. Critical Defects: All critical defects discovered as a direct result of or incidental to, compliance with ACI requirements shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. NOTE Due to high susceptibility to corrosion, all defects within the wing dry bays shall be corrected during ACI. b. Wing Dry Bay Defects: All defects discovered within the wing dry bays shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. Defects to be corrected include (but are not limited to): (1) Corrosion, including light surface corrosion. (2) Chipped or damaged primer. (3) Thin or worn primer. NOTE Due to high susceptibility to corrosion, all corrosion or coating defects on the engine truss shall be corrected during ACI. c. Engine Truss Defects: All corrosion or coating defects discovered on the engine truss shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. Defects to be corrected include (but are not limited to): (1) Corrosion, including light surface corrosion. (2) Chipped or damaged primer. (3) Thin or worn primer. d. All components which are specifically required to be measured by this specification, and which have dimensions outside of the stated limits shall be repaired in accordance with specifically applicable published repair instructions. If specific repair instructions are not available for that component, the Cognizant Engineering Authority shall be contacted for disposition prior to proceeding with assembly. e. Major Defects: (1) All major defects discovered as a direct result of compliance with ACI requirements shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. (2) Major defects discovered incidental to compliance with ACI requirements that require skills, tools, or other support available only at depot maintenance or are located in an area not normally opened or inspected by organizational maintenance, shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. f. Minor Defects: Minor defects falling under any of the below criteria shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. (1) Located in an area not normally opened or inspected by organizational maintenance during daily operations or during 56/112 day inspections. Defects located within areas accessed only during phase inspections shall be corrected. (2) Require re-sealing of the pressurized cockpit area, whether due to the actual repair or due to gaining access to perform the repair. (3) Located in an area beyond a 30-inch reach from an access panel. (4) Cannot be plainly marked (e.g. circled by grease pencil) and/or described as to the specific location to enable positive location and identification. 2-3 (5) Repair is not covered by published manuals. g. Defects Caused by Rework Activity: All defects caused by the rework activity shall be corrected in accordance with applicable documents. h. Noted But Not Corrected (NBNC) Defects: Only major or minor defects not required to be corrected by the above criteria shall be identified by location, and description on the NBNC Report for appropriate action by the reporting custodian. Section 6-2 contains specific information required for all defects listed on the NBNC report. i. Classification of Defects: Classification of defects shall be subject to the approval of the cognizant engineering authority or government representative, as applicable. 2-1.4 REWORK PROCEDURES a. Applicable Documents: ACI procedures shall comply with publications listed in Section I, maintenance references, applicable Cognizant Government Representative directives, and aircraft/equipment technical manuals applicable to the processing, rework and repair of specific model aircraft/equipment. b. Source Applicable Documents: The Rework Activity shall be responsible for obtaining all publications and references needed for ACI processing as specified herein. The Government will provide an initial allowance of military/DoD documents and specifications only, after which the Rework Activity shall be responsible for maintaining their currency. 2-1.5 AIRCRAFT RECORDS MAINTENANCE a. The rework activity shall maintain the logbooks in accordance with COMNAVAIRFORINST 4790.2, Volume II, Chapter 9 for Navy Aircraft and Air Force TO 00-20-1 for Air Force aircraft while the aircraft is undergoing ACI. b. Upon completion of each ACI rework, a logbook entry shall be made stating compliance with the requirements of this specification. The total flight time accrued to date shall be entered with the above entry in the aircraft logbook. c. All aircraft changes, bulletins, and other directives and modifications accomplished by the rework activity shall be properly recorded in the applicable section of the aircraft logbook. d. Engineering information on all modifications engineered by the Rework Activity directed by the Cognizant Government Representative shall be prepared in general accordance with the format of appropriate directives with engineering drawings prepared, as required. Commercial activities shall prepare the engineering information in accordance with ASME Y14.100; Y14.24; Y14.34M; and Y14.35M. Commercial activities shall forward a copy of all engineering modification/repair schemes and drawings to the Joint Primary Aircraft Training System (JPATS) Aircraft Program Office, Tinker AFB, OK. e. Inspection Work Sheets: (1) The Rework Activity shall utilize appropriate inspection work sheets as approved by the Cognizant Government Representative to record aircraft serial number, items of work, Technical Directives/Orders accomplished, inspections performed, discrepancies discovered, certifications of work accomplished and other necessary data. (a) Describe each discrepancy discovered through compliance with the inspection requirements of this specification. (Identify as critical, major, or minor). (b) List discrepancies reported in aircraft maintenance records. (c) List Technical Directives/Orders authorized for accomplishment. (d) Record all accessories and components removed for rework or replacement (cite identity, 2-4 reason for removal and corrective action/disposition). (2) ACI inspection worksheets attached as appendices A thru N shall be completed while performing the inspection requirements in order to document the nature, severity, and location of all damage found. (3) After the work to be accomplished has been determined and described on the inspection work sheets, the Rework Activity shall correct the discrepancies when required by this specification. 2-1.6 TECHNICAL DIRECTIVE COMPLIANCE OEM Service Bulletins & Instructions, Navy Technical Directives and Air Force Technical Orders shall be complied with and/or incorporated only as directed by the Cognizant Government Representative. 2-1.7 GROUND HANDLING, OPERATION, AND SAFETY PRECAUTIONS a. Operating personnel shall be thoroughly versed in the emergency procedures pertaining to the ground operation of the aircraft contained in the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions. b. Comply with the instructions, procedures, and precautions directed to the aircraft fueling operation of the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions. c. Aircraft servicing, taxiing, towing, parking, jacking, moving, and hoisting shall be in accordance with the instructions and precautions of the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions. d. Ground operation of engines shall be in accordance with the applicable aircraft and engine maintenance instructions. Observe the engine operation and aircraft security precautions specified therein. 2-1.8 BALLISTIC DEVICES Rocket catapults, rocket motors, cartridges, and CADs handling shall be in accordance with the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions and NAVAIR 11-100-1.1-CD. 2-1.9 SCHEDULED COMPONENT REMOVAL/REPLACEMENT CRITERIA Scheduled Removal Components (SRC's) listed in A1-T6AAA-6/TO 1T-6ABD-6, Section III which will reach or exceed the time replacement interval during ACI or the check flight shall be brought to the attention of the Cognizant Government Representative for disposition instructions. 2-1.10 UNSCHEDULED COMPONENT REWORK Items not otherwise scheduled for removal/replacement shall be subject to rework only on a discrepancy basis, i.e.; when determined defective by in place operational and functional checks, tests, and inspection. Items removed on a discrepancy basis will normally be replaced by exchanging for Ready For Issue (RFI) units through the supply system. 2-1.11 NONDESTRUCTIVE INSPECTION PROCESSES a. Nondestructive inspections shall be performed in accordance with the requirements and instructions of this specification. b. Operators of magnetic particle, penetrant, and radiographic inspection processes shall be examined and qualified to Level II/III in accordance with AIA/NAS NAS-410. 2-5 c. When visual inspection of components proves insufficient to firmly establish condition and disposition, the appropriate process shall be applied in accordance with NA 01-1A-16/TO 33B-1-1 to establish condition and disposition. 2-1.12 STRUCTURAL REPAIRS a. All structural repairs shall be accomplished in accordance with applicable structural repair manuals. The repairs shall be subject to the inspection and approval of the Cognizant Government Representative or Cognizant Engineering Authority. b. All previously installed repairs, not authorized by the above publications relative to the standards of repair workmanship enumerated therein, shall be reworked to authorized standards unless otherwise directed by the Cognizant Government Representative or the Cognizant Engineering Authority. Cases of this nature shall be brought to the attention of local engineering for determining disposition. c. Weld repairs of structural members and primary components require prior engineering approval from the Cognizant Engineering Authority. d. For repairs of a major nature not covered by applicable maintenance manuals, a rework activity shall submit to the Cognizant Engineering Authority for review and approval, a detailed description of damage, method and details of repair procedures, stress analysis, drawings, and specifications. e. Stress analysis criteria shall be obtained by the rework activity, as required, from the Cognizant Engineering Authority. f. The rework activity will certify that each structural repair of a major nature, as defined above, meets the structural strength requirements so specified. g. Record and submit a Structural Alteration Report to the Cognizant Government Representative. 2-1.13 NON-STANDARD INSTALLATIONS a. Rework shall not be performed on non-standard installations or on standard installations made non-standard, unless specifically requested by the aircraft custodian and approved by Cognizant Government Representative. b. When non-standard installations interfere with authorized rework, they will be removed to the extent necessary to facilitate the designated rework. Cases of this nature shall be referred to the Cognizant Government Representative for disposition. 2-1.14 STRUCTURAL HARDWARE a. SELF-LOCKING NUTS (1) The limitations and usage of self-locking nuts shall conform to the instructions of applicable aircraft maintenance manuals. (2) Previously installed self-locking nuts shall not be reused. b. TORQUE REQUIREMENTS (1) Comply with the standard torque values as specified in applicable aircraft maintenance manual, structural repair manual, manufacturer's drawings and other Cognizant Government Representative directives for all torque-required hardware affected by rework. (2) Apply torque stripe on specified torque-required hardware affected by rework. If torque stripe in areas not affected by rework are obliterated so that determination cannot be made as to whether slippage has occurred, re-torque and reapply torque stripe. 2-6 c. LOCK WIRING (1) Lock wiring of fasteners and connections shall be in accordance with AIA/NAS (NASM33540) and the aircraft maintenance manuals. (2) Lock wiring of electrical and electronic connections shall be in accordance with AIA/NAS (NASM33540) and the aircraft maintenance manuals. d. RIVETING (1) All riveting shall conform to the practices and procedures of the aircraft maintenance manuals and NA 01-1A-8. 2-1.15 ANTI-FRICTION BEARINGS a. All anti-friction bearings used on mechanisms, control systems, engine control linkages, rod ends, pulleys, etc., shall be inspected when required in accordance with applicable inspection criteria of NA 01-1A-503/TO 44B-1-122 unless otherwise specified in subsequent parts of this specification. b. Bearings shall be inspected based on the criteria contained in Chapter 13 of NA 01-1A-503 for visible damage, seized bearings, rough movement, looseness, or corrosion. c. Defective bearings shall be removed and replaced–new, or inspected, cleaned and processed in accordance with the applicable maintenance manual. d. Observe the maintenance precautions of applicable maintenance manuals to protect bearings from dirt, dust, moisture, cleaner, and other contaminants. (1) Vapor blasting, vacuum blasting, sandblasting or other uncontrolled application of abrasive material adjacent to or on exposed bearings is prohibited. (2) The use of steam or chlorinated hydrocarbons on bearings is prohibited. e. Clean and re-lubricate anti-friction bearings in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals immediately following the inadvertent application of corrosive contaminants. Purge sufficiently to assure removal of all contaminants. 2-1.16 REPLACEMENT PARTS AND SUBSTITUTIONS a. Replacement parts and material shall be of an OEM approved design in accordance with the maintenance instructions or illustrated parts catalogues for specific equipment as applicable unless otherwise directed by Cognizant Government Representative. b. Substitution of materials shall be subjected to positive engineering control to ensure that a substitute material possesses properties equal to or equivalent to those possessed by the original material. c. Substitution of parts and materials not authorized by manufacturer's publications or aircraft maintenance manuals are authorized only when approved by the Cognizant Government Representative. 2-1.17 FLIGHT CONTROL SURFACE BALANCING a. Control surfaces on the aircraft which require balancing are the elevator, elevator trim tab, rudder, rudder trim tab, and ailerons. b. Whenever one of the above control surfaces is painted, reworked and/or modified in any way, balancing must be accomplished as specified in the A1-T6AAA-3 Structural Repair Manual prior to reinstalling on the aircraft. c. Control surfaces shall be finish-painted, including all touch up, and have all applicable decals applied, prior to balancing. Balancing of control surfaces must be completed in a draft free area. 2-7 2-1.18 DISTURBED SYSTEMS Disturbed Systems: Aircraft systems, not otherwise assigned a requirement for an operational check/test, that are disturbed during ACI processing to the extent that the systems integrity (i.e., installation and operation) cannot be assured, shall receive an operational check/test to verify proper installation, function, and operation. 2-1.19 PROTECTIVE CLOSURES The use of bosses, caps, and tubing seals on open ports, fittings, and pipes is required. 2-1.20 TUBING a. System tubing shall be visually examined for security, deterioration, evidence of leakage, chafing, twisting, deformation, corrosion, and proper routing, as a minimum requirement. Fabricate, repair, test, clean, inspect, and store tubing in accordance with NA 01-1A-20 and applicable maintenance manuals. b. All replacement tubing shall be identified and marked in accordance with NA 01-1A-20 and applicable aircraft maintenance manuals. 2-1.21 FLEXIBLE HOSE ASSEMBLIES a. Inspect for defective synthetic rubber hose assemblies in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals and NA 01-1A-20. Replace all defective hose assemblies in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. b. Inspect, fabricate, and replace hose assemblies in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals and NA-1A-20. c. All replacement hoses shall be identified and installation date marked in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals and NA-1A-20. In addition, replacement shall be noted in the Miscellaneous Section of Aircraft Logbook. 2-1.22 IDENTIFICATION OF PIPING The identification of replacement pipe, hose, and tubing lines shall be in accordance with NA 01-1A-20 and the manufacturer's drawings. 2-1.23 THREAD COMPOUND a. Anti-seize and sealing thread compound shall be used on all tapered pipe threads exposed incident to rework. b. Thread lube shall be used on all male thread connections, as required by the maintenance manual. 2-1.24 PACKINGS, GASKETS, AND SEALS a. The use of packings, gaskets, and seals shall conform to the aircraft manufacturer's specifications. Leaky, damaged, or deteriorated gaskets, seals, grommets, plugs, or sealing compound shall be replaced. b. Non-metallic packings, gaskets, and seals removed or exposed by any disassembly required by this specification shall be replaced. 2-8 2-1.25 HYDRAULIC CONTAMINATION a. Hydraulic fluids in hydraulic systems shall be maintained per NA 01-1A-17 at the contamination levels directed by OPNAVINST 4790.2G, Volume II, Chapter 4, or to more stringent levels as required by the FST. 2-1.26 TEST AND SUPPORT EQUIPMENT a. Test and support equipment, including alignment fixtures, templates, etc., used in inspection requirements of this specification shall be that required by applicable documents, or approved by the cognizant engineering authority or cognizant government representative and have current calibration tags. b. CALIBRATION PROGRAM. The calibration program shall be maintained to meet the requirements of the applicable manuals or manufacturers specifications. c. HYDRAULIC TEST STANDS. Hydraulic test stands shall be managed and inspected for contamination per NA 0l-1A-17, Section VIII. d. LIFTING SLINGS AND RESTRAINING DEVICES. Lifting slings and restraining devices shall be maintained per NA 17-1-114. e. SUPPORT EQUIPMENT. For general purposes, a DRP performing DLM shall be considered an organizational activity when referring to applicable support equipment manuals and OPNAVINST 4790.2G. Support equipment used in support of a DLM program shall be properly maintained and inspected using the applicable O-level maintenance manuals. 2-1.27 ELECTRICAL WIRING a. Replacement electrical wiring shall conform to the requirements of applicable maintenance manuals and NA 01-1A-505/TO 1-1A-14 except in those instances in which the specified wire is not available. Substitute wire of equivalent properties shall be used only as approved by Cognizant Government Representative. b. Replacement electrical wiring shall be fabricated and installed in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (1) Electrical and Coaxial Connectors. Replacement electrical and coaxial connectors shall be those specified in the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions manual or alternate connectors authorized by the applicable aircraft assembly drawing. (2) Soldering. Soldering for electrical and electronic work shall be in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (3) Solderless Terminals and Splices. Solderless terminals and splices shall be of the environmental type. They shall be selected, fitted, crimped, and connected in accordance with manufacturer’s instructions, applicable maintenance manuals. (4) Bonding. Bonding for electrical purposes shall be in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. 2-1.28 TRANSPARENT PLASTICS The fabrication, maintenance, and repair of transparent plastic materials shall be per NA 01-lA-l, Section VI, and NA 0l-1A-12, Section IV, V, and VI, and the structural repair manual. 2-9 2-1.29 REINFORCED PLASTICS/COMPOSITES The fabrication and repair of reinforced plastics/composites shall be per NA 01-1A-22, Sections IV through VII, structural repair manual, and applicable documents. 2-1.30 RADOMES AND ANTENNA COVERS The assessment of damage, repair, and electrical testing of radomes and antenna covers shall be per NA 01-1A-22, Sections IV through VII, or the structural repair manual, and applicable documents. 2-1.31 TOLERANCES Tolerances shall be in accordance with the aircraft technical maintenance manuals, other configuration identifications or other authorized directives as approved by Cognizant Government Representative. 2-1.32 USAGE AND HANDLING OF GASES a. Observe the hazardous and precautionary notes of NA 01-1A-515 for usage and handling of gases. b. All pneumatic systems and all self-contained components normally serviced with air shall be serviced with dry nitrogen conforming to Federal Specification A-A-59503B, Type I, Class I, Grade B. 2-1.33 REPORT REQUIREMENTS a. The rework activity shall prepare and submit the following reports per Section VI: (1) Noted But Not Corrected (NBNC) Report. (2) Maintenance History Summary (MHS) Report. (3) Weight and Balance Report. (4) Structural Alteration Report. A separate structural alteration report shall be submitted for each significant structural alteration. A significant structural alteration is: (a) Replacement of any major structural component with an unused or new production part; (b) Interchange of any major structural component with a component from another aircraft with prior service use; and (c) Repair and reinstallation of a major structural component from the same aircraft. 2-2 INDUCTION INTO ACI REQUIREMENTS This section presents the responsibilities of the reporting custodian prior to induction of the aircraft, procedures for conducting the aircraft equipment inventory, procedures for performing the aircraft records analysis, and the procedures for preservation. 2-2.1 OPERATING ACTIVITY RESPONSIBILITIES PRIOR TO ACI a. Prepare and submit an ACI work request, at least one month prior to the scheduled induction date, to the 2-10 designated rework activity via the cognizant chain of command. The work request should contain the following minimum requirements: (1) List of all unincorporated applicable technical directives. (2) List of special work items requested to be accomplished. (3) Identify chronic system/component problems requiring depot level investigation. Furnish brief history of problem and what action has been taken at organizational level. b. Replace all O & I level life/time/event limited components that will not have sufficient operating time or calendar time remaining to satisfy the expected aircraft rework time, as well as the check flight and ferry flight time to and from the DRP. Request extensions on O & I level replaceable life/time/event limited components if appropriate. If the reporting custodian is unable to comply with this requirement, submit a special work request to the DRP. The DRP can request an extension on O & I level replaceable life/time/event limited components extension to account for requirements resulting from extended depot processing or from Operating Activity omissions after an aircraft arrives at a DRP site. c. Clear aircraft of all discrepancies, which are correctable by O & I levels of maintenance. If reporting custodian is unable to comply with this requirement, document all discrepancies which are correctable by O & I levels of maintenance which will not be able to be corrected by the time the airframe is inducted for DLM. A special work request should be submitted to have the DRP repair these discrepancies, otherwise O & I level repairable discrepancies will be noted on the NBNC list. d. Ensure aircraft is flyable at induction per the flight and maintenance manuals. e. Prior to delivery, remove and retain all unnecessary loose gear and equipment. Miscellaneous equipment necessary for aircraft security and safe ground handling will be delivered with the aircraft, including landing gear pins. If applicable, annotate the aircraft inventory log. f. Logs and Records. Deliver current and up-to-date logbooks and necessary records with the aircraft. Verify that all entries are current as of the date of delivery. Ensure that SRC Cards are inventoried and verified against installed equipment. g. Report any discrepancies encountered during delivery of aircraft to the rework activity. h. The operating activity will provide the rework activity with the dates and results of the latest Engine Performance Run performed on the engines. 2-2.2 AIRCRAFT EQUIPMENT INVENTORY a. Conduct an equipment inventory, jointly when possible, with a representative of the delivering activity as soon as possible after receiving the aircraft. When a joint inventory is not possible, the Cognizant Government Representative shall perform the joint inventory with the rework activity. (1) Accountability and shortages shall be in accordance with the aircraft inventory records. (2) All inventory equipment removed from an aircraft shall be reinstalled on the same aircraft from which removed or if required, shall be replaced with an equivalent serviceable item at completion of ACI. (3) Loose equipment, including personal survival equipment, shall not be repaired, but shall be properly tagged and stored to prevent damage and deterioration. 2-2.3 AIRCRAFT RECORD ANALYSIS a. Aircraft logbook and records shall be reviewed to determine the existence and extent of conditions that might affect the planned sequence of aircraft rework. Past historical performance shall be analyzed to determine possible chronic system and component trouble areas on which to apply added emphasis during aircraft examination. 2-11 b. High Time SRC's. Review aircraft logbook and records for any scheduled removal component that is high time or will become high time during ACI processing and check flight. Schedule appropriate action during subsequent rework. c. Determine and document additional items of rework such as the incorporation of outstanding technical directives/orders and other maintenance directives as specified by the Cognizant Government Representative. d. Document all noted discrepancies, areas requiring special consideration and required rework items. Schedule appropriate action during subsequent rework. e. Aircraft/engine/component logbook entries shall be compared with aircraft maintenance records and verified. Aircraft technical directive/order status shall be verified. 2-2.4 RECEIVING INSPECTION AND OPERATIONAL TEST a. Preliminary examination and operational tests shall be performed on each aircraft to validate reported discrepancies and to aid in the determination of unscheduled rework. The scope of the examination shall be of sufficient depth to avoid unscheduled rework from occurring at an inappropriate rework sequence. b. Note all discrepancies discovered during the performance of preliminary examinations and operational tests, those discrepancies reported by the delivering activity, and those discrepancies recorded in the aircraft logbook and associated records. c. Preliminary examinations and operational tests: (1) During the Receiving Inspection, service all systems, accomplish engine Power Assurance Run, inspect and perform operational checks as necessary to determine the condition and extent of adjustment or repairs required for all systems. (2) All discrepancies documented during aircraft checks shall be scheduled for corrective action at an appropriate rework sequence as required for compliance with ACI defect correction criteria. (3) Perform hydraulic fluid contamination check in accordance with the applicable maintenance manual. (4) Prior to preservation, perform an engine oil contamination check in accordance with the applicable maintenance manual. (5) Drained fluids, other than fuel, shall be disposed of as contaminated property. 2-2.5 PRESERVATION a. The T-6 engine and propeller are not removed as part of ACI, and shall be preserved and protected during DLM. b. Drain fuel tanks and lines in accordance with the applicable aircraft maintenance instructions. (1) Inspect aircraft fuel for contamination in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (2) Observe safety precautions when defueling aircraft. (3) Record the quantity of reusable fuel in the aircraft inventory record and credit to aircraft when reservicing is accomplished. (4) Non-Reusable fuel shall be properly disposed of as contaminated. c. Aircraft, engine, and components shall receive preservation in accordance applicable maintenance manuals, as modified by the latest revision of LES/JX T-6 0002 to permit the performance of DLM during a modified preservation status. This LES requires: (1) A compressor performance recovery/desalination wash and turbine rinse. 2-12 (2) An aircraft exterior wash. (3) Preservation of the fuel cells and fuel system with 1010 oil. (4) Draining of the engine oil. (5) The use of desiccant bags in the engine exhaust. (6) Covering of the engine inlet screen. (7) Protection of the canopy. (8) Specific de-preservation steps to prevent preservation oil from entering the fuel nozzles. d. Aircraft batteries and auxiliary power supply shall be removed, stored, and maintained in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals and NA 17-15BAD-1. e. Ejection seats shall be removed, stored, and maintained in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. 2-3 AIRCRAFT AND ENGINE CLEANING REQUIREMENT 2-3.1 CLEANING a. Metal Surfaces. (1) Clean aircraft external and accessible internal metal surfaces using methods and materials specified by applicable maintenance manuals. After cleaning, take special precautions to assure thorough draining of all liquids from between faying surfaces, crevices, and inspection doors. Re-clean all areas as necessary. b. Transparent and Reinforced Plastic Surfaces. (1) Clean transparent and reinforced plastic surfaces using methods and materials specified by applicable maintenance manuals. 2-3.2 PAINT SYSTEM a. External surfaces. (1) Stripping and repainting of the external metal surfaces is part of the ACI, and shall be performed in accordance with the latest revision of LES/JX T-6 0003. (2) Composite and fiberglass surfaces to be over-painted shall be scuff sanded, filled, primed, and have an anti-static coating applied in accordance with the latest revision of LES/JX T-6 0003 prior to application of the final paint system. b. Internal surfaces. (1) Examine accessible interior surfaces of the aircraft for defective paint finishes. Interior finishes shall be stripped only to the extent necessary to inspect for corrosion and defects in accordance with this specification or to restore protective coatings. (2) When over-painting is being considered, an adhesion tape test shall be performed in accordance with the A1-T6AAA-23 Corrosion Control Manual. (3) Surfaces to be over-painted shall be scuff sanded to reactivate the surface, surface treated, and primed prior to application of the final paint system in accordance with the A1-T6AAA-23 Corrosion Control Manual. (4) Take adequate precautions during stripping and subsequent cleaning operations to prevent intrusion of water, chemical stripping compounds, or cleaning compounds into engine inlet/exhaust openings, 2-13 static, pitot, and vent openings, bearings, bearing surfaces, electrical switches, relays, connectors, wires, and all other electrical and electronic components. Protect plastic glass and rubber parts during stripping and cleaning. Comply with all applicable safety precautions/procedures when using toxic stripping compounds. 2-3.3 CORROSION REMOVAL AND SURFACE TREATMENT a. Inspect for corrosion in accordance with NA 01-1A-509/TO 1-1-691, T-6 Corrosion Control Manual and the detailed requirements of this specification. NOTE Removal of fasteners at seams and lap joints is not required unless visual examination indicates corrosion of faying surfaces. b. Remove all corrosion in accordance with NA 01-1A-509/TO 1-1-691, T-6 Corrosion Control Manual. Replace corroded parts when the corrosion damage (after corrosion removal) exceeds the limits allowed by applicable maintenance manuals. c. Apply approved coatings, sealants, etc. to protect parts and components from corrosion during rework. d. Surface treatment: (1) Reapply surface treatment to all metal surfaces from which previously applied organic coatings have been removed. (2) Apply surface treatment to all newly fabricated metal parts in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (3) During assembly of components, parts and subassemblies, insulate dissimilar metals as specified by applicable maintenance manuals. 2-3.4 SURFACE RESTORATION a. Seam Sealing: CAUTION Do not use chemical corrosion removers. (1) Remove all loose or deteriorated sealant and contamination from the seams. Remove corrosion products by one of the mechanical methods described in applicable maintenance manuals. (2) Seal all seams using materials and procedures defined in applicable maintenance manuals. b. Aircraft Interior: NOTE Epoxy primer shall be MIL-PRF-23377 (Type 1, Class C1 or C2), or MIL-PRF- 85582 (Type 1, Class C1 or C2) (1) Finish interior metal surfaces in inhabited areas with epoxy primer and approved topcoat. (2) Finish interior metal surfaces in uninhabited areas using epoxy primer. (3) Finish battery boxes and battery bays using materials specified by applicable maintenance manuals. (4) Apply interior markings in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (5) Interior paint application by brush is authorized only to touch-up cockpit markings. 2-14 c. Aircraft Exterior: (1) Use epoxy primer and aliphatic polyurethane coating for exterior finish. Apply finish in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. (2) Protect plastics and rubber components during painting. (3) Apply standard exterior finish colors, servicing/maintenance markings and insignia in accordance with A1-T6AAA-23/TO 1T-6ABD-23, MIL-STD-2161, and manufacturer’s drawings. d. Bolt, Bearing, and Bushing Bores: (1) Remove any surface corrosion by the least aggressive means in accordance with NAVAIR 01-1A-509, Volume 2, Chapter 4. (2) Apply Chemical Conversion Coating MIL-DTL-81706 Class 1A, in accordance with NAVAIR 01-1A-509, Volume 2, Chapter 5. (3) For open bores, apply MIL-P-23377 Type II primer to the bore surfaces and allow to dry. For bushing or bearing installation, install wet with MIL-P-23377 Type II primer and allow to dry. (4) Apply a peripheral seal using AMS-S-8802 Sealing Compound around perimeter of bushings and bearings. 2-4 DISASSEMBLY 2-4.1 DISASSEMBLY, GENERAL a. The aircraft shall be disassembled to the extent required to accomplish planned examination, restoration, modification, and testing. b. Disassembly will normally be limited to the extent permitted by the removal of bolts and screws. This does not preclude the removal of rivets or high strength fasteners to permit inspection for suspected damage, to make repairs or, when necessary, to accomplish modification. 2-4.2 DISASSEMBLY, SPECIFIC All disassembly shall be accomplished in accordance with the applicable maintenance manual. The following parts and/or assemblies shall be removed for inspection access, processing and rework: (1) Engine Cowlings, including: (a) Upper Forward Cowling (211AT) (b) Lower Forward Cowling (211AB) (c) LH & RH Plenum Panels (821 & 822 respectively) (d) LH & RH Cowling Doors (823 & 824 respectively) (e) Oil Cooler Fairing (820) (f) LH & RH Lower Aft Cowl Skins (821AB & 822AB respectively) (g) Lower Aft Cowling (2) Battery (3) Auxiliary Power Supply (4) Canopy (5) Canopy Strut Assemblies (2 each) P/N 133-510059-1 (6) Cockpit False Floor Boards and Panels 2-15 (7) Forward and Rear Ejection Seats (8) Forward Ejection Seat Guide Rails NOTE While most components will be removed upon induction, the wing leading edge assemblies should only be removed when ready to perform the wing forward spar inspection. This will protect the spar and spar primer from damage during stripping, wing/fuselage separation, etc. (9) Wing leading Edge Assemblies (10) Aileron Assemblies (11) Elevator Assembly (12) Rudder Assembly (13) Horizontal Stabilizer Strut Assembly (discard bolts upon removal) (14) Horizontal Stabilizer (discard bolts upon removal) (15) Vertical Stabilizer (discard bolts upon removal) (16) Nose Landing Gear Drag Brace (17) Aft Power Quadrant (18) Cockpit Insulation/Soundproofing Pads (Number pads as they are removed from the cockpit and mark corresponding number on cockpit structure to identify location for reinstallation) (19) Seat Adjust Control, P/N 133-360055-1 from aft cockpit LH control panel (20) Anti-G Control Panel from aft cockpit LH control panel. (21) Aft Battery Circuit Breaker panel from aft cockpit LH control panel. (22) Dual Dimmer P/N 866-1-1 from RH control panel (located forward of Oxygen Flow Controller) (23) All access doors, inspection panels, plates, and fairings except as follows in Table 2-1: TABLE 2-1. Non-Removed Panels ACCESS PANEL NUMBER NOMENCLATURE ACCESS PANEL NUMBER NOMENCLATURE 251 Forward Cockpit LH Side Console Panels 267AR Left Side Egress Door 252 Forward Cockpit RH Side Console Panels 267AS Step Box Door 255 Forward Control Stick Forward Panel 268 Right Side Egress Door 257AB Forward Glareshield Upper Door (T-6A only) 351AD Horizontal Stabilizer Left Fairing 261 Aft Cockpit LH Side Console Panels 352AD Horizontal Stabilizer Right Fairing 262 Aft Cockpit RH Side Console Panels 361HB Elevator Left Fairing Tip 265 Aft Control Stick Forward Panel 362HB Elevator Right Fairing Tip 265AC Top Cover 530 Left Wing Tip Cap 267AA Aft Glareshield 621BT Flux Valve Access Door (T-6A only) Magnetometer Access Door (T-6B only) 267AB Aft Glareshield Upper Door (T-6A only) 630 Right Wing Tip Cap 267AC Top Cover 2-16 2-4.3 EXAMINATION DURING DISASSEMBLY a. Examine the aircraft during disassembly for the following: Loose or missing rivets and fasteners, cracks, corrosion, damaged controls, excessively worn hinges, attach fittings, bearings, bushings and bolts, distortion and elongation of bolt holes, and any signs that may lead to inspection and/or disassembly to a greater depth. b. If corrosion damage is evident or suspected at skin laps, remove rivets and peel back skin progressively in the immediate area for further inspection to determine the extent of corrosion progression. c. Particular emphasis shall be placed on examination of items that may require special examination and correction as a result of aircraft service record information, on items specifically requested by the reporting custodian, agreed to by the rework activity and authorized by the aircraft controlling custodian, and on items where past experience or analytical inspection has proven to be deficient or which may lead to discrepancies in associated parts or sub-assemblies. This shall include areas subject to known or suspected structural fatigue, deterioration, or corrosion. d. Disassembly examination shall be accomplished by personnel qualified in and experienced with detecting structural deficiencies in detail. 2-5 WORK AREA DESCRIPTIONS AND ZONAL INSPECTION PROCEDURES 2-5.1 GENERAL a. The inspection of the aircraft is divided into several work areas listed below and detailed in Paragraph 2-5.4, which are subject to zonal inspection. (1) Forward Fuselage (2) Cockpit/Canopy (3) Nose Landing Gear and Doors (4) Aft Fuselage (5) Horizontal Stabilizer (6) Elevator and Elevator Control System (7) Vertical Stabilizer (8) Rudder and Rudder Control System (9) Wing Assembly and Fuel Tanks (10) Main Landing Gear and Doors (11) Aileron and Aileron Control System (12) Flaps, Speed Brake & Control Systems b. Zonal inspections shall be performed on designated work areas as specified in Section 2-6 and 2-7 of this specification. c. Structure and installations within work areas that require more extensive inspections are separately identified by specific requirements. 2-5.3 INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS a. All inspections shall detect and note the following conditions dependent upon the structure and type installations located within the zonal boundaries. 2-17 (1) Structure: Corrosion, cracks, distortion, damage, loose and missing fasteners, defective sealant and seals. (2) Transparent Assemblies: Scratches, cracks, crazing, delamination, defective sealant and seals, frames for cracks, corrosion, damage and security. (3) Mechanical Linkages and Actuating Mechanisms: Cracks, corrosion, scoring, abnormal wear, evidence of improper alignment and adjustment, damage and security (including cotter pin condition, if applicable). (4) Control Cables and Flexible Shafts: Corrosion, fraying, chafing, kinks, untwisting, broken strands/wires, security, lubrication, and evidence of improper alignment, rigging or tension. (5) Pulleys, Fairleads, Pressure Seals, Rub-strips, Cable End Fittings, and Conduits: Excessive wear, damage, security, and improper alignment or adjustment. (6) Flexible Hoses: Fraying, chafing, twisting, deterioration, proper routing and security, and leakage. (7) Tubing and Ducting: Cracks, corrosion, security, leakage, chafing, dents, crimping, end fittings and clamps for security and proper installation, and identification. (8) Electrical/Electronic Equipment: Evidence of overheating, corrosion, proper bonding and security; defective vibration dampers/shock mounts corroded damaged pins (when disconnected), and damaged terminals and connectors. (9) Wiring and Wiring Components: Evidence of breaks overheating, chafing, fraying, corrosion, deterioration, fluid damage and proper routing, splices, terminals and connectors for damaged pins (when disconnected or unmated and stowed), deteriorated potting, security, and corrosion. (10) Bearings: All anti-friction bearings of mechanisms, control systems, engine control linkages, rod ends, pulleys, etc., shall be inspected in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals unless otherwise specified in subsequent parts of this specification. (11) Instruments: Evidence of overheating of electrical units; damaged faceplates, interference with moving parts, condition/security of units and attached wiring, hoses, and tubing. (12) Fiberglass Constructed Components: Inspect for cracks, erosion damage, delamination, and fraying. (13) General: Security, cracks, corrosion, damage, deterioration, distortion, deformation, interference, evidence of overheating and leakage, broken or missing parts, proper lubrication and bonding and presence and legibility of markings. b. All inspections shall be made from within touching distance. A mirror may be necessary to enhance visual access to all exposed surfaces in the inspection area. A flashlight or droplight may be required. c. A zonal inspection is a general visual examination of all structure and installations located within the defined work area as defined in Paragraph 2-5.4 to detect obvious damage, failure, or irregularity. d. A detailed visual inspection is an intensive visual examination of a specific area, system, or assembly to detect damage, failure, or irregularity. Inspection aids (such as a mirror, flashlight, or magnifying glass) shall be used as required to ensure all areas subject to the detailed visual inspection are thoroughly examined. e. Loose fasteners will require removal in order to measure fastener holes using appropriate measuring instruments (i.e., hole micrometer, ball gage, etc.). 2-5.4 WORK AREA DESCRIPTION a. Forward Fuselage. This work area consists of the entire fuselage forward of and including Frame 4 at F.S. 234.874. It is comprised of all external portions of the forward fuselage, including skins, spinner dome, propeller, cowlings (including Upper Forward Cowling, Lower Forward Cowling, LH & RH Plenum Panels, LH & RH Cowling Doors, Oil Cooler Fairing, LH & RH Lower Aft Cowl Skins, Lower Aft Cowling, and Upper Center Cowling), doors, hinges, latches, engine inlet duct, bleed air dump, external power receptacle 2-18 and oil cooler intake; internal structure including sub-floor structure, frames, longerons, stringers, engine mount truss, powerplant, access covers, hinges, latches, battery compartment and supporting components, antennas, wiring, cables, valves, hoses, drains, and fittings within the work area. It does not include items contained within the Cockpit/Canopy work area, or the Nose Landing Gear and NLG Doors work area. b. Cockpit/Canopy. This work area consists of the entire forward and aft cockpits, as well as the canopy. It includes the side panels, upper sidewall panels, console & instrument panels, control sticks, power control levers, and rudder pedals within both cockpits, as well as all handles and levers. This zone also contains the canopy frame, windshield, forward and aft transparencies, lock assembly, latch assembly, assist struts, canopy mounted environmental components, and canopy and airframe mounted egress components. c. Nose Landing Gear and Nose Landing Gear Doors. This work area includes the nose landing gear strut assembly, drag brace, trunnions, landing gear doors, hinges, wheel well structure, wheel assembly, tire, steering control assembly, actuator, mounting brackets, attaching hardware and all related hardware, switches and wiring. d. Aft Fuselage. This work area consists of the entire fuselage aft of Frame 4 at F.S. 234.874. It consists of the tail cone installation, strake assemblies, ventral fin, dorsal fin, doors, fuselage skins, all internal aircraft structure including horizontal and vertical stabilizer attach points, frames, longerons, stringers, brackets, hinges, and latches. Also included in this zone are all pulleys, flight control bell cranks, cables, push rods, wiring, antenna, lights and related hardware not included in other work areas. e. Horizontal Stabilizer. This work area includes left and right horizontal stabilizers. It includes skins, internal structure, elevator hinges, attach fittings, stabilizer strut, and attaching hardware. f. Elevator and Elevator Control System. This work area is the entire elevator assembly, elevator trim assembly, and the elevator control system. It consists of the skins, internal structure, hinges, balance weights, and attaching hardware. Also included in this work area are all elevator pulleys, springs, bell cranks, cables, push rods, trim actuator, and related hardware and wiring. g. Vertical Stabilizer. This work area is the vertical stabilizer. It includes skins, internal structure, rudder hinges, attach fittings, antennas, wiring, and attaching hardware. h. Rudder and Rudder Control System. This work area is the entire rudder assembly, rudder trim assembly, and the rudder control system. It consists of the skins, internal structure, hinges, balance weights, and attaching hardware. Also included in this work area are all rudder pulleys, bell cranks, cables, push rods, centering struts, trim actuator, and related hardware and wiring. i. Wing Assembly and Fuel Tanks. This work area consists of the entire wing, excluding the ailerons, flaps, and speed brake. The wing work area consists of the main spar, forward spar, aft spar, inboard diagonal spars, flap and aileron attach points, stringers, ribs, and skin panels. Also included are the fuel tanks, collector tank, all associated valves, hose, vents, plumbing and seals, wing tips, leading edges, stall strips, tip lights, and all associated hardware and wiring. j. Main Landing Gear and Main Landing Gear Doors. This work area consists of the main landing gear strut assemblies, side braces, main landing gear attach points, trunnions, inboard and outboard landing gear doors, hinges, wheel well structures, wheel assemblies, tires, brakes, up locks, actuators, mounting brackets, attaching hardware, and all related hardware, switches and wiring. k. Ailerons and Aileron Control System. This work area consists of the left and right aileron assemblies, the aileron trim tab assembly, and the aileron control system. It consists of the skins, internal structure, hinges, balance weights, and attaching hardware. Also included in this work area are all aileron bell cranks, push rods, centering spring, trim actuator, and related hardware and wiring. l. Flaps, Speed Brake & Control Systems. This work area consists of the left and right inboard flaps, the left and right outboard flaps, the speed brake, and the associated control systems. It includes the skins, internal structure, and hinges. Also included in this work area are the actuators, torque tubes, bearing blocks, interconnect pins, pulleys, cables, and related hardware and wiring. 2-19 2-6 INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS 2-6.1 GENERAL a. This part establishes the depot level maintenance requirements for structural items and general inspection requirements grouped by work areas. The purpose and scope of the work area inspections and a detailed description of each work area are specified in Section II, Paragraph 2-5.4. b. Frequency: All inspections are to be completed during each ACI except as specified in the threshold column in Table 2-2, and except as noted below for T/M/S specific inspections and intervals. These inspections are not required to be accomplished until the airframe has reached the threshold flight hours indicated. Total flight hours shall be verified in the aircraft logbook upon induction. After the threshold for each inspection has been exceeded, the inspection shall be accomplished during every subsequent ACI. TABLE 2-2. If the aircraft has reached the 7,000 flight hour threshold, perform the following inspections: (1) Elevator pressure box, P/N 133-524046-5 (a) Eddy current inspect the upper flange radius of the elevator pressure box for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-20-01. (2) Frame 5 below upper longeron, P/N 133-440058-99 (a) Eddy current inspect the left and right frame 5 flanges at the upper longeron for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-10-06. (3) (T-6A only)Wing lower skin at main spar, P/N’s 133-100126-11/-21 (a) Eddy current inspect the lower wing skin at the main wing spar for cracks from LH rib 11 (IWS 49) to RH rib 11 (IWS 49) IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-01. (4) (T-6A only)Wing Aft Spar Lower Cap, P/N 133-100189-1/-2 (forward) and 133-100189-3 (aft) (a) Eddy current inspect the forward and aft flanges of the lower spar caps of the aft spar between LH rib 8 (IWS 33) and RH rib 8 (IWS 33) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-03. (5) (T-6B only)Wing diagonal spar lower flanges, P/N 133-100170-7/-9 (a) Eddy current inspect the diagonal spar lower caps (left and right) between IWS 18 and IWS 33 (forward and aft flanges) for cracks at the lower wing skin fastener attachment holes IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6,WP 57- 10-02. (6) (T-6B only) Fuselage skin at RH avionics bay door cutout, upper aft corner, P/N 133-440027-3 (a) Eddy current inspect the fuselage skin adjacent to the right avionics bay access door cutout, aft upper corner at frame IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-30-01. Visually inspect the skin around entire cutout and eddy current inspect any suspicious areas. (7) (T-6B only) Horizontal stabilizer aft spar upper cap, P/N 133-620031-3 (a) Inspection procedures for the horizontal stabilizer aft spar upper cap have not been developed as of the release date of this specification. Contact CNATRA FST for further instructions if the inspection threshold has been reached. This specification will be revised to include these instructions when they are published in the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36). b. If the aircraft has reached the 10,000 flight hour threshold, perform the following inspections: (1) Upper Longeron Doubler at Frame 4, P/N 133-440068-3/-4 (a) Eddy current inspect the left and right upper longeron doubler at the rear pressure bulkhead (Frame 4) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 2-21 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-10-02. (2) (T-6A only)Wing Stringer drain holes, P/N’s 133-100127-1(stringer 1), 133-100127-3 (stringer 2), 133-100127-5/-6 (stringer 3). (a) Eddy current inspect (using either bolt hole or surface probe) the wing stringer drain holes (11 holes total) at wing stringers 1, 2, and 3 for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-04. (3) (T-6A only)Wing diagonal spar lower flanges, P/N 133-100170-7/-9 (a) Eddy current inspect the diagonal spar lower caps (left and right) between IWS 18 and IWS 33 (forward and aft flanges) for cracks at the lower wing skin fastener attachment holes IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6,WP 57- 10-02. (4) (T-6A only) Horizontal stabilizer aft spar upper cap, P/N 133-620031-3 (a) Inspection procedures for the horizontal stabilizer aft spar upper cap have not been developed as of the release date of this specification. Contact CNATRA FST for further instructions if the inspection threshold has been reached. This specification will be revised to include these instructions when they are published in the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36). (5) (T-6B only) Vertical stabilizer forward spar attachment fitting holes, P/N 133-640033-3 (a) Eddy current inspect vertical stabilizer front spar attachment fitting holes (6 holes) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6 Chapter 55-30-02. The front fitting located at frame 9 has six 0.25-inch diameter fastener holes. c. If the aircraft has reached the 12,000 flight hour threshold, perform the following inspections: (1) Frame 4 aft face clips, P/N 133-430059-55/-77/-78 (a) Eddy current inspect the clips located on the aft face of the rear pressure bulkhead (Frame 4) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-10-04. (2) Upper stringer splice at frame 5/6, P/N 133-440063-13/-14 (a) Eddy current inspect the left and right stringer splices between Frames 5 and 6 for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-20-02. (3) Canopy hinge lobes, P/N 133-510075-3/-5/-7 (a) Eddy current inspect canopy hinge lobes for cracking in the radius of the hinge lobes IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 95-10-01. Direct particular attention to the eighteen (18) inches at the forward and aft ends of the hinge. Note that the lower hinge half is a single part (-3), while the upper hinge consists of 2 parts (-5 upper aft, -7 upper forward). (4) (T-6A only) Fuselage skin at RH avionics bay door cutout, upper aft corner, P/N 133-440027-3 (a) Eddy current inspect the fuselage skin adjacent to the right avionics bay access door cutout, aft upper corner at frame IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-30-01. Visually inspect the skin around entire cutout and eddy current inspect any suspicious areas. (5) Aft fuselage skin at frame 9, P/N 133-440026-13 (a) Eddy current inspect the left and right sides of the upper aft fuselage skin at the fasteners along frame 9 adjacent to the vertical stabilizer for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-30-02. 2-22 (6) (T-6A only) Vertical Stabilizer Rear Spar, LH Cap, P/N 133-640029-19 (a) X-ray inspect the vertical stabilizer left hand rear spar cap between VSS 27.386 to 33.386 for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 2, Chapter 55-30-01. On aircraft with the L/ESS strain gages installed, the LH spar cap shall also be x-ray inspected at VSS 14.00. Inspect both flanges of the spar cap (at the spar cap-toskin attachment and the spar cap-to-spar web attachment). d. If the aircraft has reached the 15,000 flight hour threshold, perform the following inspections: (1) Frame 3A/3B fittings at pressure floor, P/N 133-430149-23/-24 (a) Eddy current inspect the fittings located at the pressure floor at frames 3A and 3B for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-10-01. Note that on each side of the aircraft there is a fitting at both frames for a total of 4 fittings to be inspected. (2) Frame 4B near lower longeron, P/N 133-440058-89 (a) Eddy current inspect the Frame 4B web at LH and RH lower longeron cutout for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 53-10-05. (3) (T-6A only) Vertical stabilizer aft spar attachment fitting, P/N 133-440054-5 (aft) (a) Eddy current inspect vertical stabilizer rear spar attachment fitting holes (6 holes) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6 Chapter 55-30-02. The rear fitting located at frame 10 has six 0.375-inch diameter fitting holes. (4) (T-6B only) Canopy Hook at FS 141 (a) Inspection procedures and parts to be inspected for the canopy hooks at FS 141 have not been developed as of the release date of this specification. Contact CNATRA FST for further instructions if the inspection threshold has been reached. This specification will be revised to include these instructions when they are published in the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36). 2-6.3 WING/FUSELAGE SEPARATION, INSPECTION AND REATTACHMENT NOTE While the order of operations for most of this specification is optional, the separation and reattachment of the wing from/to the fuselage disturbs numerous systems and components. These steps should be accomplished very early in the ACI process, and shall be performed before inspection of any of the disturbed systems and components. a. Separate the wing from the fuselage IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 57-00-00. (1) Discard the 4 bolts, P/N NAS6604-36 and the 4 nuts, P/N 130909N32 removed from the forward pressure floor support at attach points MS1, MS2, MS3, and MS4. (2) Discard the 2 bolts, P/N NAS6604-6 and the 2 nuts, P/N 130909N32 removed from the aft pressure floor support at attach points AS3 and AS4. (3) Discard the 2 bolts, P/N MS14181-08070P, the 2 washers, P/N 133-100030-5, and the 2 nuts, P/N MS14182P08 removed from the forward longeron/main spar attach points. (4) Discard the 2 bolts, P/N MS14181-06044P and the 2 nuts, P/N MS14182P06 removed from the aft longeron/aft spar attach points. 2-23 (5) Discard the 2 bolts, P/N NAS627-50 and the 2 nuts, P/N NAS1804-7 removed from the spigot fitting. b. Perform a zonal inspection of all areas of the fuselage and wing which are normally inaccessible when the wing is joined with the fuselage. c. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right wing shear plates, P/N 133-100113-1 at the main spar for corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. d. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right wing attach fittings, P/N 133-100056-3/-4 at the main spar for corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Use a video borescope or other suitable type equipment to visually inspect the bores of the fittings and wing mid spar for scratches/gouges or corrosion. Measure and record the minimum and maximum dimensions of the bores at various locations thru the depth of the hole. Note any wear, elongation, or other damage. e. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right fuselage shear plates, P/N 133-430091-3 for corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Plates are attached to the longerons, P/N 133-430113-5/-6. f. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right forward fuselage attach fittings, P/N 133-430088-3/-4 on the lower longeron between frames 2B and 3 for corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Use a video borescope or other suitable type equipment to visually inspect the bores of the fittings and fuselage longeron for scratches/gouges or corrosion. Measure and record the minimum and maximum dimensions of the bores at various locations thru the depth of the hole. Note any wear, elongation, or other damage. g. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the wing aft spar fittings, P/N 133-100181-5/-6 and the aft spar web P/N 133-100185-7 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Use a video borescope or other suitable type equipment to visually inspect the bores of the fittings for scratches/gouges or corrosion. Measure and record the minimum and maximum dimensions of the bores in the fittings at various locations thru the depth of the hole. Note any wear, elongation, or other damage. NOTE The aft fuselage attach fitting stack-up consists of the P/N 133-430089-1/-2 bracket, the P/N 133-430087-3/-4 lower longeron, and the P/N 133-430089-1/-2 fitting. The P/N 133-430089-1/-2 fitting is not shown in the Structural Repair Manual (A1- T6AAA-3; TO 1T-6ABD-3), but it is shown in appendix B, Sheet B-7. NOTE The P/N 133-430089-1/-2 bracket and the P/N 133-430087-3/-4 lower longeron have larger (but different from each other) diameters than the P/N 133-430089-1/-2 fitting. The critical diameter is that in the P/N 133-430089-1/-2 fitting. h. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right aft fuselage attach fitting stack-up for corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Use a video borescope or other suitable type equipment to visually inspect the bores of the brackets, fittings and fuselage longerons for scratches/gouges or corrosion. Measure and record the minimum and maximum dimensions of the bores in the P/N 133-430089-1/-2 fittings at various locations thru the depth of the holes. Note any wear, elongation, or other damage. i. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the fuselage spigot fitting, P/N 133-430076-1 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. j. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the fuselage spigot lower fitting, P/N 133-430070-1 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. k. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the wing spigot fitting, P/N 133-100105-1 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. l. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the upper and lower wing spigot fitting external straps, P/N 133-100135-7/-9 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. 2-24 m. Re-attach the wing to the fuselage IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 57-00-00. Use new hardware in place of that discarded above. (1) Bare aluminum surfaces require chemical conversion coating IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 20-03-00. CAUTION The wing installation requires bare metal contact to electrically ground the wing and fuselage. Do not apply epoxy primer or any other coating except MIL-C-16173E corrosion preventive compound. (2) Electrical continuity between the wing and the fuselage is accomplished through direct contact between the fittings and hardware. Rust inhibitor, MIL-C-16173, Class 1, Grade 2 is to be applied to the inside of all attachment holes and attaching hardware. Do not apply any other paint, primer, or sealants to these surfaces. (3) Ensure shims are installed as required IAW Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 57-00-00. (4) Ensure all bolts and nuts are torqued as required IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 57-00-00. NOTE Failure to properly and thoroughly seal surfaces IAW with the Maintenance Manual may lead to problems with cockpit pressurization. Repair may require extensive disassembly. (5) Ensure all surfaces are properly and thoroughly sealed as required IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 57-00-00. 2-6.4 FORWARD FUSELAGEWORK AREA NOTE Ensure all NDI procedures required by the flight hours the aircraft has accumulated are performed as instructed in Paragraph 2-6.2. a. Perform zonal inspection of the forward fuselage work area. (1) Pay particular attention to engine oil cooler hoses as they pass thru engine truss gusset, clamps, and clamp mounting bracket. b. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the fittings located at the pressure floor at frames 3A and 3B, P/N 133-430149-23/-24 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Note that on each side of the aircraft there is a fitting at both frames for a total of 4 fittings to be inspected. c. Perform a detailed visual inspection of all forward fuselage frames (listed in Table 2-3) for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Direct particular attention to upper and lower longeron frame cutouts, doublers, and vertical stiffeners. 2-25 TABLE 2-3. Perform a detailed visual inspection of upper forward cowling, P/N 133-910078-1 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. m. Perform a detailed visual inspection of lower forward cowling, P/N 133-910096-17 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. n. Perform a detailed visual inspection of left and right plenum panels, P/N 133-910067-1/-3 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. o. Perform a detailed visual inspection of left and right cowling doors, P/Ns LH 133-910071-37; RH 133-910070- 59 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. p. Perform a detailed visual inspection of lower aft cowling, P/N 133-910085-11 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. q. Perform a detailed visual inspection of upper center cowling, P/N 133-910072-59 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. r. Engine truss and truss attachment (1) Perform a detailed visual inspection of the following for security, cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage: (a) Forward pressure bulkhead bathtub fittings P/N 133-430064-3/-4 (upper), 133-430065-1/-2 (lower). (b) Yoke attachment fitting, P/N 133-430066-1. (c) Engine truss assembly, P/N 133-910026-1 including all tubes, fittings, brackets, fasteners and welds. (d) Engine mount isolators, P/N 95596-5/-6. (e) (T-6B only) Ballast weights, P/N 133-910136-0001 and ballast rack installation, P/N 133- 910133-0001. (2) Visually inspect condition of Ardrox AV-40 applied to the engine truss. (a) If not present, apply per the Corrosion Control Manual (A1-T6AAA-23; TO 1T-6ABD-23), Chapter 20-40-00. (b) Re-apply to the entire structure if the last application was more than 4 years prior. (c) Re-apply to any areas with disturbed or damaged coating. (3) Remove and replace engine truss attachments bolts. (a) Remove only 1 bolt at a time. Do not proceed with the next bolt until the first is installed and correctly torqued. Engine sling during bolt removal is not required if this procedure is followed. Do not move aircraft when any engine truss bolts are removed or not properly torqued. (b) Remove and discard the four (4) engine mount truss bolts, P/N MS20008-24 IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 71-20-01. (c) Remove and visually inspect washers, P/NMS20002C8, NAS1149F0832P and NAS1149F0863P. If any damage to the washers or coating is noted, replace with new hardware. (d) Remove and discard the upper and lower left and right barrel nut assemblies, consisting of P/N NAS578-8A retainers and NAS577B8A nuts. (e) With engine truss bolt and attaching barrel nut removed, use a borescope to visually inspect the bolt hole and barrel nut hole for corrosion or other discrepancies. A video borescope capable of capturing still photographs is preferred. 2-27 CAUTION The engine truss installation requires bare metal contact to electrically ground the truss and engine. Do not apply epoxy primer or any other coating except MIL-C-16173E corrosion preventive compound. (f) If the chemical conversion coating is disturbed, reapply MIL-DTL-81706 Class 1A IAW the Corrosion Control Manual (A1-T6AAA-23; TO 1T-6ABD-23). (g) Electrical continuity between the engine truss and the fuselage is accomplished through direct contact between the fittings and hardware. Apply corrosion preventive compound, MIL-C-16173E, Class 1, Grade 2 is to be applied to the inside of bolt and barrel nut holes in the truss fitting and firewall, as well as to the attaching hardware. Do not apply any other paint, primer, or sealants to these surfaces. (h) Install, torque, and seal new hardware IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 71-20-01. (i) Remove and discard the engine mount truss yoke attachment bolt, P/N MS20006-18, and nut, P/N MS21042L6. Remove and visually inspect washers P/N MS20002C6, NAS1149F0632P, and NAS1149F0663P. If any damage to the washers or coating is noted, replace with new hardware. (j) With engine truss yoke attachment bolt removed, use a borescope to visually inspect the bolt hole for corrosion or other discrepancies. A video borescope capable of capturing still photographs is preferred. (k) If the chemical conversion coating is disturbed, reapply MIL-DTL-81706 Class 1A IAW the Corrosion Control Manual (A1-T6AAA-23; TO 1T-6ABD-23). (l) Electrical continuity between the engine truss and the fuselage is accomplished through direct contact between the fittings and hardware. Apply corrosion preventive compound, MIL-C-16173E, Class 1, Grade 2 is to be applied to the inside of bolt holes in the truss fitting and yoke fitting, as well as to the attaching hardware. Do not apply any other paint, primer, or sealants to these surfaces. (m) Install, torque, and seal new hardware IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 71-20-01. 2-6.5 COCKPIT AND CANOPYWORK AREA NOTE Ensure all NDI procedures required by the flight hours the aircraft has accumulated are performed as instructed in Paragraph 2-6.2. a. Perform zonal inspection of the cockpit and canopy work area. b. Inspect canopy latch guide pin bushings at all locations for looseness and for lateral wear. Refer to Structural Repair Manual (A1-T6AAA-3; TO 1T-6ABD-3), Chapter 53-20-00. c. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the aft instrument panel, P/N 133-340108-49 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Direct particular attention to the panel attachment to the left and right upper longerons for cracks. d. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the forward ejection seat upper links, P/N 133-430092-7 and fittings, P/N 133-430090-7 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. e. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the forward ejection seat lower fittings, P/N 133-430132-9 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. f. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the aft ejection seat upper links, P/N 133-430072-5 and fittings, P/N 133-430072-3 for cracks, corrosion, or other damage. 2-28 g. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the aft ejection seat lower support, P/N 133-430059-113 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. h. Visually inspect condition of Cor-Ban 35 applied to the cockpit structure under the false floor. (1) If not present, apply per the Corrosion Control Manual (A1-T6AAA-23; TO 1T-6ABD-23), Chapter 20-40-00. (2) Re-apply to the entire structure if the last application was more than 4 years prior. (3) Re-apply to any areas with disturbed or damaged coating. 2-6.6 NOSE LANDING GEAR AND NOSE LANDING GEAR DOORSWORK AREA a. Perform zonal inspection of the nose landing gear (NLG) and NLG doors work area. b. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right NLG door installations, P/N 133-910097-1/-3 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Perform a tap test of the honeycomb core/skin panel to identify delaminations or disbonds. Any suspected delaminations or disbonds shall be confirmed by ultrasonic testing as necessary. 2-6.7 AFT FUSELAGEWORK AREA NOTE Ensure all NDI procedures required by the flight hours the aircraft has accumulated are performed as instructed in Paragraph 2-6.2. a. Inspect the installed bearings for visible damage, seizure, rough movement, looseness, or corrosion. 2-6.9 ELEVATOR AND ELEVATOR CONTROL SYSTEM NOTE The elevator and elevator control system work area contains all components throughout the aircraft used to control the elevator and elevator trim.
