Perform zonal inspection of the wing assembly and fuel tanks work area. b. (T-6A only) Eddy current inspect wing lower skin, P/N 133-100126-11 at the collector tank door cutout (access 151BB) and four fastener holes common to stringers 1 and 2 for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-05. Note that this inspection is only to be performed on the LH side of the aircraft. c. (T-6B only) Eddy current inspect the wing lower skin, P/N’s 133-100126-11 at the main spar, from LH rib 11 (IWS 49) to RH rib 11 (IWS 49) IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD- 36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-01. d. (T-6B only) Eddy current inspect the forward and aft flanges of the lower spar caps, P/N 133-100189-1/-2 (forward) and 133-100189-3 (aft), of the wing aft spar between LH rib 8 (IWS 33) and RH rib 8 (IWS 33) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10- 03. e. (T-6B only) Eddy current inspect (using either bolt hole or surface probe) the wing stringer drain holes (11 holes total) at wing stringers 1, 2, and 3 (P/Ns 133-100127-1/-3/-5/-6) for cracks IAW the Nondestructive Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-36; TO 1T-6ABD-36), Part 6, Chapter 57-10-04. NOTE All areas of the T-6 wing are susceptible to severe corrosion. A thorough visual examination of all areas is essential to ensuring the material condition of the aircraft. Inspection of the wing interior requires access through the wing access doors, and will require the use of flashlights, mirrors, and/or borescopes. 2-34 NOTE The primer used during original manufacture of the T-6 wing is brittle and susceptible to small chips due to minor impacts. Any break in the primer coating will reduce corrosion resistance. Inspection of the wing requires diligence and must specifically target any and all breaks in the primer coating. NOTE Due to high susceptibility to corrosion, all defects noted in the wing dry bays, in the fuel tanks, and on the wing forward spar shall be corrected during ACI. f. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the entirety of the wing dry bays for corrosion, security and integrity of the primer coating system and the Cor-Ban 35 CPC application. Re-apply to any areas with disturbed or damaged coatings. g. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the fuel tanks for corrosion, security and integrity of the primer coating system. NOTE Ensure the wing leading edges are removed prior to inspecting the wing forward spar. h. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the forward wing spar consisting of the upper cap, P/N 133-100041-1, lower cap, P/N 133-100041-5, and webs, P/N 133-100042-3/-5 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, other damage and integrity of the primer coating system. i. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the mid (main) wing spar consisting of the upper cap, P/N 133-100051-3, lower cap, P/N 133-100052-3, and webs, P/N 133-100057-1/-3/-5 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. j. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the left and right wing diagonal spars, P/N 133-100170-7/-9 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. k. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the wing aft spar for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. The aft spar upper cap is an assembly of P/Ns 133-100189-5/-6. The aft spar lower cap is an assembly of P/Ns 133-100189-1/-2/-3. The aft spar web is an assembly of P/Ns 133-100182-3/-4/-11/-12. l. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right aileron hinge fittings, P/N 133-100373-2/-4 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Additionally, perform a detailed visual inspection of the aileron hinge points on left rib 17, P/N 133-100316-23 and right rib 17, P/N 133-100317-24. 2-6.13 MAIN LANDING GEAR ANDMAIN LANDING GEAR DOORS a. Perform zonal inspection of the main landing gear (MLG) and MLG doors work area. b. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the left and right MLG forward trunnion fittings, P/N 133-100053-11/-12 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, evidence of bearing liner failure, or other damage. c. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the visible areas of the left and right MLG aft trunnion fittings, P/N 133-100220-13/-14 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, evidence of bearing liner failure, or other damage. d. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right MLG retract actuator attach fittings, P/N 133-100055-1/-2 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. f. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right outboard MLG door installations, 2-35 P/N 133-100701-23/-24 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. Perform a tap test of the honeycomb core/skin panel to identify delaminations or disbonds. Any suspected delaminations or disbonds shall be confirmed by ultrasonic testing as necessary. g. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the left and right inboard MLG door installations, P/N 133-100702-3/4 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. 2-6.14 AILERONS AND AILERON CONTROL SYSTEM NOTE The ailerons and aileron control system work area contains all components throughout the aircraft used to control the ailerons and aileron trim. This includes (but is not limited to) control sticks, interconnect rod, pulleys, springs, bellcranks, cables, push rods, trim actuator, and related hardware and wiring a. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the LH and RH outboard aileron hinge ribs, P/N 133-130004-13/-15 (LH) and P/N 133-130004-14/-16 (RH) for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. d. Perform a detailed visual inspection of the aileron trim tab assembly, P/N 133-130013-19/-20 for cracks, corrosion, distortion, working fasteners, or other damage. 2-6.15 FLAPS, SPEED BRAKE & CONTROL SYSTEMS NOTE The flaps, speed brake and control systems work area contains all components throughout the aircraft used to control the flaps and speed brake. This includes (but is not limited to) actuators, torque tubes, bearing blocks, interconnect pins, pulleys, cables, and related hardware and wiring a. Perform zonal inspection of flaps, speed brake and control systems work area. 2-7 SYSTEMS AND COMPONENTS a. This part establishes the depot level maintenance requirements for systems and components and general inspection requirements grouped by zones. The purpose and scope of the zone inspections and a detailed description of each zone are specified in Section 2, Paragraph 2-5. b. Frequency: Every inspection is to be completed at every ACI. 3-1 SECTION III ACI FUNCTIONAL CHECK FLIGHT AND ACCEPTANCE REQUIREMENTS 3-1 FINAL PROCESSING 3-1.1 WEIGHT AND BALANCE a. Weigh the aircraft in accordance with the Loading Data Manual (A1-T6AAA-5-2; TO 1T-6ABD-5-2/) and NAVAIR 01-1B-40, NAVAIR 01-1B-50. Complete Weighing Record DD Form 365B. b. Inventory the aircraft and complete Chart A, Basic Weight Check List, DD Form 365A, to reflect the actual equipment inventory. c. Update Chart C, Basic Weight and Balance record, DD Form 365C, to reflect the actual inventory of Chart A, plus the effect of any technical orders/directives or modifications incorporated during ACI. d. Update Chart E, as required, to reflect the effect of any technical orders/directives or modifications incorporated during ACI. e. Complete Weight and Balance Clearance Form F, DD Form 365F, to reflect actual load disposition for check or ferry flight. 3-1.2 LOGS AND RECORDS a. Conduct aircraft inventory and annotate aircraft records, DD Form 780, to reflect the actual inventory. b. Complete a Shortage Form DD 780-2 for all items marked as "missing" in the inventory record. c. Annotate the Aircraft Log Book in accordance with the specified instructions to reflect: (1) Accomplishment of ACI. (2) Accomplishment of applicable inspections. (3) Incorporation of compliance with Technical Directives. (4) Replacement of wing attachment bolts. (5) Replacement of engine truss bolts. (6) Replacement of vertical stabilizer attachment bolts. (7) Replacement of horizontal stabilizer attachment bolts. (8) Replacement of assemblies, accessories, and major components. (9) Other entries and page insertions specifically directed by the cognizant government representative or FST (10) Accrual of flight time during the period of aircraft custody by Rework Activity. 3-2 (11) Applicable aircraft records shall be annotated showing the month, year, and aircraft time that ACI was accomplished. The entries shall also reflect the Rework Activity name and the contract number. 3-1.3 INVENTORY EQUIPMENT Reinstall or replace with equivalent serviceable items, on the same BUNO aircraft, all inventory equipment removed during aircraft induction. See Subsection 2-2.2 of this specification. Ensure that all Equipment Historical Record (EHR), SRC, and ASR cards are inventoried and verified against installed equipment. 3-1.4 FLIGHT CONTROL SYSTEMS Perform both a Rigging and an Operational Check on Ailerons, Flaps, Elevator and Rudder in accordance with the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 27. 3-1.5 SERVICING After completion of all maintenance requirements specified herein, the aircraft, drive components and engine shall be depreserved per the applicable documents. Ensure systems are properly installed and serviced per the aircraft maintenance manuals and applicable documents. 3-1.6 HYDRAULIC SYSTEM a. SAMPLE HYDRAULIC FLUIDS. Sample each hydraulic system for particulate, water, and chlorinated solvent contamination prior to first flight per NA 0 l- lA-17, Section II and III, to determine if the hydraulic system is within the limits specified in applicable T-6 documents. Fluid sample shall be taken using the standard procedure detailed in applicable documents. b. DECONTAMINATION AND CORRECTIVE ACTION. Decontaminate hydraulic systems per NA 0l-1A-17, Section IV. Adhere to any follow up corrective actions, such as to components, specified in applicable documents. 3-1.7 EJECTION SEATS After installation of the Canopy or Ejection Seat and after maintenance of explosive components of the Canopy or Ejection Seat perform “Egress Final Inspection” IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 95-00-00. 3-3 3-1.8 OPERATIONAL CHECKS Accomplish operational and functional checks and calibrations as specified by LES/JX T-6 0004 (T-6 Aircraft Condition Inspection – Production Operational Check Procedures) and LES/JX T-6 0014 (T-6 Cockpit Altitude Warning Ground Check). Additionally, accomplish all operational and functional checks on any disturbed system as required by the maintenance manual. Correct critical and major defects discovered as a result of these tests. 3-1.9 COMPASS CALIBRATION Calibrate and compensate compasses using the applicable technical publications following completion of aircraft rework and systems testing and update compass corrections cards per NA 05-15-2. Update aircraft logbook, as required, per OPNAVINST 4790.2G, Volume II, Chapter 9. 3-1.10 SERVICING AND LUBRICATION After completion of rework as specified herein, the aircraft and engines shall be de-preserved, checked for structural and mechanical completeness and integrity, proper assembly and all systems serviced and lubricated in accordance with applicable maintenance manuals. 3-1.11 LANDING GEAR Perform an operational check of the Landing Gear System IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 32-00-02. 3-1.12 FUEL, POWER PLANT AND PROPELLER Perform a Fuel System Leak Check and Calibration. 3-1.13 POWER PLANT TURN-UP Perform Power Assurance Run following the procedures and making the checks specified in the applicable maintenance manuals. All discrepancies are to be corrected. 3-1.14 ONBOARD OXYGEN GENERATING SYSTEM (OBOGS) Perform OBOGS High and Lower Pressure leak checks, and OBOGS Purge and Operational Check IAW the Maintenance Manual (A1-T6AAA-2; TO 1T-6ABD-2), Chapter 35-10-00. 3-4 3-2 CHECK FLIGHT 3-2.1 PREFLIGHT/AIRCRAFT LAUNCH/ THRUFLIGHT a. Prior to the first checkflight of the day, perform Preflight and Aircraft Launch Inspections in accordance with T-6ABD Preflight, Thruflight, Postflight Inspection (A1-T6AAA-6WC-1; TO 1T-6ABD-6WC-1). b. Perform a thruflight inspection between subsequent flights on the same day in accordance with the T-6ABD Preflight, Thruflight, Postflight Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-6WC-1; TO 1T-6ABD-6WC-1). 3-2.2 FUNCTIONAL CHECKFLIGHT AND ACCEPTANCE a. A Functional Check Flight (FCF), Profile A, shall be performed. The FCF shall be accomplished in accordance with the Acceptance and Functional Check Flight Procedures Manual (T-6A: A1-T6AAA-FCL-200; TO 1T- 6A-6CL-1. T-6B: A1-T6BAA-FCL-200; TO 1T-6B-6CL-1). b. Aircraft mission equipment/systems are excluded from check flight requirements unless required due to unscheduled rework requirements. c. Contractors shall comply with the requirements of NAVAIRINST 3710.1/AFJI 10-220 throughout check flight and acceptance processing. 3-2.3 POST FLIGHT INSPECTION a. HYDRAULIC SYSTEM SAMPLING. Sample hydraulic system after final FCF per NA 01-1A-17, Section II and III, in order to determine if the system is within limits specified in applicable documents. Fluid sample shall be taken utilizing the standard procedure detailed in the maintenance manual. Accomplish decontamination and corrective actions per NA 01-1A-17, Section IV and the maintenance manual. b. LUBRICATING SYSTEM SAMPLING. Sample the engine lubricating oil per the applicable documents and the maintenance manual. c. SERVICING. Service all aircraft systems per the applicable aircraft maintenance manual. 3-3 ACCEPTANCE PROCESSING a. The Cognizant Government Representative shall verify that all special, loose and miscellaneous equipment and furnishings, and publications reflected as "installed" in the aircraft inventory record is appropriately stowed and that all required logbook entries have been accomplished. b. Prior to acceptance of the aircraft, all special, loose and miscellaneous equipment and furnishings and required publications, shall be installed and properly secured in the aircraft. c. Perform Preflight/Aircraft Launch Inspections in accordance with the T-6ABD Preflight, Thruflight, Postflight Inspection Manual (A1-T6AAA-6WC-1; TO 1T-6ABD-6WC-1) prior to the delivery/ferry flight. d. CORRECTION OF DISCREPANCIES. The DRP shall be responsible for the maintenance of the aircraft and the correction of all critical and major defects discovered until designated governmental activity acceptance. 4-1 SECTION IV COMPONENT REMOVAL/REPLACEMENT SCHEDULE 4-1 GENERAL: a. The removal and replacement of life/time/event limited components is not a requirement of ACI. b. Concurrent overhaul of components in accordance with Manufacturer's specifications and/or component overhaul technical manuals is not a requirement of ACI. c. Life/time/event limited components and hardware which are removed and replaced shall be properly recorded in the aircraft logbook. NOTE The listed hardware shall be removed and discarded regardless of the flight hours accrued since installation. d. ACI requirements are not written to duplicate phase inspection requirements. However, the scope and depth of the inspections completed at ACI meet or exceed the intent of numerous phase inspection requirements. This section will clearly identify phase inspection requirements that are satisfied during the completion of ACI. b. The accomplishment of phase inspections is not a requirement of ACI. However, phase inspections may be conducted concurrently with the ACI at the request of the reporting custodian and the approval of the controlling custodian. 5-2 SPECIFIC REQUIREMENTS a. Inspections during ACI shall not be considered accomplishment of aircraft special inspections. All special inspections shall be accomplished by the reporting custodian as required by the T-6A/B/D Scheduled Inspection and Maintenance Requirements Manual (A1-T6AAA-6; TO 1T-6ABD-6). b. All T-6A/B/D Aircraft Corrosion Control Manual (A1-T6AAA-23; TO 1T-6ABD-23) tasks are satisfied through the completion of ACI. 6-1 SECTION VI ACI REPORT REQUIREMENTS 6-1 GENERAL a. This section describes the reports, which shall be submitted to PMA 273, the JPATS Aircraft Program Office, and the reporting custodian no later than 30 days subsequent to government acceptance of each aircraft that has undergone ACI. For commercial DRPs, these submission requirements are also included in the Contract Data Requirements List (CDRL). An electronic report is acceptable as an alternate to a printed report. The electronic report shall use the same format provided in the following paragraphs. b. The following reports are required by this ACI specification: (1) NBNC Report (2) MHS Report (3) Weight and Balance Report (4) Structural Alteration Report (if applicable) c. Forward a copy of all reports to Engineering Department, T-6 APMSE, Program Manager Air (PMA-273), 48187 Standley RD, Bldg 4010, Pax River, MD 20670 via the Cognizant Government Representative. d. Forward a copy of all reports to the T-6 Assistant Program Manager at Joint Primary Aircraft Training System (JPATS) Aircraft Program Office, Tinker AFB, OK via the Cognizant Government Representative. 6-2 NBNC REPORT a. The NBNC report shall be prepared to list minor or major discrepancies that were discovered during ACI but were not required to be corrected per Section 2-1.3 of this specification. The completed NBNC report shall be attached to the aircraft logbook and a copy attached to the MHS report. The NBNC report shall be used by the reporting custodian to initiate action to correct the noted discrepancies. The NBNC report shall be typewritten on 8 ½ x 11-inch white paper or on a locally developed form. The report shall include the following: (1) BUNO/Tail Number, Aircraft Designation (2) Contract number/production sequence number. (3) Work specification number/change/date. (4) List of discrepancies. Each discrepancy shall be listed individually, and include: (a) Specific location (fuselage station, wing station, frame number). (b) Access panel thru which the discrepancy can be located (if applicable). (c) Description of discrepancy. (d) SRM or IPC chapter, figure, and item number. 6-2 6-3 MHS REPORT a. The MHS report shall be prepared to provide the data accumulated during the performance of ACI to the cognizant maintenance engineering activity and the procuring activity to permit proper management of aircraft condition and updating of ACI Specification requirements. The MHS report shall be typewritten on 8 ½ x 11-inch white paper or on a locally developed form. Reports shall be forwarded no later than ten (10) days subsequent to Government acceptance of aircraft. The report shall include the following: (1) Aircraft identification and flight hours including: (2) BUNO/Tail Number, Aircraft Designation (3) DRP sequence number (if applicable) (4) ACI induction and completion dates (5) Total aircraft flight hours and operational months. (6) Flight hours and operational months since last ACI. b. TDs complied with/incorporated and not incorporated by number and title. c. Accessories/components removed for repair/replacement. (1) P/N & nomenclature; (2) reason for removal; (3) corrective action taken d. Pre-induction special workload request accomplished. (1) brief description of work; and (2) man-hours expended. e. Man-hours expended on basic ACI requirements. (1) Inspection (2) Surface conditioning (strip/repaint). (a) aircraft exterior; (b) control surface wells; and (c) wheel wells (main/nose). (3) Airframe structural repair (other than corrosion) (4) Corrosion repair (5) All repairs other than structural and corrosion repairs. f. Listing of defects discovered and corrected. (1) Complete description of defect including size, severity, and criticality (critical, major, minor). (2) Accurate location of the defect; (3) description of corrective action taken. (4) man-hours to repair defect. (5) ACI task number when defect discovered. (6) For corrosion, report the type and severity as defined in Tables 6-1 and 6-2 on applicable Discrepancy Reports. 6-3 g. Description of special work requested by the Navy/Air Force, any difficulties encountered while performing the work, and the number of man-hours to complete. h. Date of government acceptance. i. Date DD 250 (Nov 92), Material Inspection Receiving Report, signed. j. A copy of completed ACI Inspection Discrepancy Reports, contained in appendices A thru N shall be attached. TABLE 6-1 CORROSION TYPE DESIGNATION CODE DEFINITION: A Direct surface attack B Galvanic or dissimilar metal corrosion C Pitting D Intergranular attack including exfoliation E Crevice attack or concentration cell corrosion F Fretting corrosion G Stress corrosion cracking H Corrosion fatigue I Filiform corrosion J Microbiological corrosion (As further defined and illustrated in NAVAIR 01-1A-509) TABLE 6-2 CORROSION SEVERITY DESIGNATION CODE DEFINITION: 1 Light corrosion removable by chemical cleaners and repairable by chemical treatment. 2 Light to moderate corrosion removable by manual application of mild abrasive compounds or soft grit blasting and repairable by chemical 3 Moderate to severe corrosion removable by mechanical methods and repairable by chemical treatment. 4 Severe corrosion removable by mechanical methods and repairable by Structural Repair Manual. 5 Severe corrosion not removable by any method and requires replacement of the affected part. 6-4 6-4 WEIGHT AND BALANCE REPORT A copy of the Weight and Balance reports shall be provided to the reporting custodian as required by Paragraph 2-2.3 and 3-1.2 of this specification. The reports shall be prepared per NA 0l-1B-40 and NA 0l-lB-50. The record shall include aircraft identification data, date weighed, basic weight, moment and center of gravity. 6-5 STRUCTURAL ALTERATION REPORT a. A Structural Alteration Report shall be prepared and submitted to PMA 273, the JPATS Aircraft Program Office, AND NAVAIRWARCENACDIV Warminster, Pax Code 4.3.3.3, per NAVAIRINST 4720.2A for each significant structural alteration. A significant structural alteration means: (fixed wing aircraft only) (1) Replacement of any major structural component with an unused or new production part; (2) Interchange of any major structural component with a component from another aircraft with prior service use; and (3) Repair and reinstallation of a major structural component from the same aircraft. Page 1 Jun 06/16 MODEL 3000 ILLUSTRATED PARTS CATALOG INTRODUCTION INTRODUCTION 00 1. GENERAL This Illustrated Parts Catalog provides the information required to identify and order parts for the Model 3000 aircraft. This manual is supplemented by the following publications: Wiring Diagram Manual, TO 1T-6A-2-110 Wiring Diagram Manual, TO 1T-6B-2-110 Wiring Diagram Manual, TO 1T-6D-2-110 Structural Repair Manual, TO 1T-6ABD-3 Main Landing Gear Wheel Assy, Build-up/Tear Down and Inspection Manual, TO 4W1-3-34-2 Nose Landing Gear Wheel Assy, Build-up/Tear Down and Inspection Manual, TO 4W3-3-112 Corrosion Control Manual, TO 1T-6ABD-23 Canopy Maintenance and Build-up Manual, TO 16W2-13-2 Egress Maintenance and Build-up Manual, TO 13A5-69-2 2. ASSIGNMENT OF SUBJECT MATERIAL This Illustrated Parts Catalog is prepared in accordance with the Air Transport Association No. 100 (ATA 100) format. The contents of this publication are organized in four levels as follows: A. Group Groups are primary divisions of the manual that enable broad separation of content. Typical of this division is the separation between Air Frame Systems and Power Plant. Groups are identified by blue divider tabs. B. System Groups are broken down into major systems such as air conditioning, electrical power, landing gear, etc. Each system is assigned a number, which is the first element of a standardized numbering system. The element 28 of the number 28-00-00 refers to the fuel system. Everything concerning the fuel system will be covered in this chapter. Systems are identified by yellow divider tabs. C. Subsystem Each of the systems on the aircraft are broken down into subsystems, and are identified by the second element of a standardized numbering system. The element 40 of 28-40-00 identifies the indicating portion of the fuel system. MODEL 3000 ILLUSTRATED PARTS CATALOG Page 2 Jun 06/16 INTRODUCTION D. Subject A subject within a subsystem is identified by the third element of the numbering system. This number is assigned by the manufacturer and may, or may not, be used and will vary in usage. The element 05 of the number 28-40-05 applies to the fuel gages portion of the fuel indicating system. 3. APPLICATIONS Other T-6A and T-6B publications conforming to this format use the same basic numbering system even though some chapters may be omitted because they are not applicable to the aircraft or publication. Thus, whether the publication is for maintenance, parts, or wiring, the person requiring information concerning the fuel storage or fuel indicating portion of the fuel system would refer to Chapter 28, Fuel. For example: 28-00 General 28-10 Storage (tanks, cells, caps, instruments, etc.) 28-20 Distribution (fuel lines, pumps, valves, controls, etc.) 28-30 Dump (if in-flight dumping system were installed, it could appear here) 28-40 Indicating (fuel quantity probes, gages, etc.) 4. ORGANIZATION A. List of Effective Changes The list of effective changes follows the Title page in the front of this manual and lists changes currently effective for this manual. B. Record of Changes The record of changes follows the list of effective changes. When a change is inserted into the manual, the change number, the date inserted, and the initials of the person(s) inserting the changes should be recorded on this page. C. Introduction (1) ATA chapter index guide The ATA chapter index guide is a listing of the groups, systems, subsystems, and subjects that are applicable to this publication. (2) Alphabetical index The alphabetical index is a listing of the main components or systems, subsystems, and subjects in which those elements are located. It also contains a cross-reference listing between the Maintenance Manual and the Illustrated Parts Catalog. (3) Supplier listing The supplier listing consists of the names, addresses, and vendor codes for all vendors that supply items not carried under the prime manufacturer's part number. INTRODUCTION Page 3 Jun 06/16 MODEL 3000 ILLUSTRATED PARTS CATALOG D. Alpha-numeric Index The alpha-numeric index is a complete listing of each part number in alpha-numeric sequence, of each part number listed, except for those part numbers that apply as attaching parts. Parts are listed once for each time the part appears within the catalog in order to reflect the different systems, subsystems, etc. E. Table of Contents A table of contents following each chapter divider tab lists the issue or change date of each page that is effective for that chapter and the title of the subjects covered in that chapter. F. Changed Text As text is changed by additional or changed information, solid change bars are added along the outside edge of the changed page. The change date appears at the bottom of the page to allow the reader to differentiate between the previous issue and the later changed page. G. Illustrated Parts List (1) Illustration Each illustration, located on the page preceding a parts list page, contains a pictorial representation of the system, subsystem, subject, and item numbers being described on the adjacent page. NOTE Illustrations in this manual are to be used only as aids in identifying parts and should not be used for maintenance procedures. Illustrations are only representations of parts and may not be an exact likeness of the parts represented. (2) Parts list The parts list consists of installations broken down into assemblies, subassemblies, detail parts, and attaching parts. Refer to Figure 1. A separation symbol (-----*-----) follows the list of attaching parts to distinguish them from the detail parts. If two or more assemblies, consisting of a majority of identical parts or opposite (left or right) parts, are listed, the detail parts are common to all of the assemblies. Only the left or right parts will be indexed and illustrated with the differences noted in the description. When "/SEE CHAPTER. . . /” appears in the description, the assembly and its detail parts are broken down somewhere else in the book. The Units Per Assy column lists the quantity of parts required for each assembly that immediately precedes either the attaching or detail parts. NP indicates non-procurable and AR indicates as required. When a number is shown in the Usable On Code column, refer to the effectivity codes at the end of the parts list for each subject to determine the aircraft serial effectivity. Each subject has its own distinct code and may not be the same for other subjects. Refer to Figure 2 for information on how to locate a part when only the description is known. Refer to Figure 3 for information on how to locate a part when the part number is known. MODEL 3000 ILLUSTRATED PARTS CATALOG Page 4 Jun 06/16 INTRODUCTION 5. LOCATING INFORMATION A. Parts List The indenture system is used to indicate parts included in any given assembly. Parts shown in column 2 are component parts of the immediately preceding assembly in column 1. Parts shown in column 3 are component parts of the immediately preceding assembly in column 2, etc., through column 7. In the example in Figure 1, the 133-524058-1 rudder pedal assembly would include items 5 through 25 when ordered. Note that the attaching parts (items 1 through 4) are not part of the pedal assembly and need to be ordered separately. There may be instances when a part number consists of more than 16 characters; in that case, an asterisk (*) will appear at the end of the part number and the remainder of the number can be found at the beginning of the description field. B. When a Part Description is Known From the list of pages/table of contents in front of each system, look for the subsystem and subject in which the part is listed. The alphabetical index and cross-reference guide, in the front of the manual, may also be consulted. This guide locates each major part within the Illustrated Parts Catalog and references them to a location within the Maintenance Manual. Immediately preceding the parts list is an illustration. Refer to Figure 2. The item number next to the part illustrated will appear in the parts list under the column entitled Sub-sys, Subject, & Item No. The required part number will be found immediately to the right of the item number. C. When the Part Number is Known Consult the alpha-numeric index, in the front of the manual, when the part number is known. The system, subsystem, subject, and item number can be found immediately to the right of the part number. Refer to Figure 3. 6. ATA 100 PAGE BLOCK GUIDE Pages are numbered consecutively for each subsystem and subject beginning with page 1. 28-10-05 PAGE 1 TITLE PAGE 28-10-05 PAGE 2 ILLUSTRATION 28-10-05 PAGE 3 TEXT 28-10-15 PAGE 1 TITLE PAGE 28-10-15 PAGE 2 ILLUSTRATION 28-10-15 PAGE 3 TEXT 28-10-15 PAGE 4 ILLUSTRATION 28-10-15 PAGE 5 TEXT 7. WHEN OBTAINING PARTS Always use the complete manufacturer’s part number listed in the part number column. Be sure the aircraft serial number accompanies all spare parts orders. Model designation and serial number are provided on the serial placard located on the fuselage exterior and indicated by the check marks in Figure 4. INTRODUCTION Page 5 Jun 01/21 MODEL 3000 ILLUSTRATED PARTS CATALOG 8. SUBSTITUTIONS When government standards or specifications (AN, AND, MS and NAS) have been cancelled, superseded, or made inactive, they may be substituted as defined within that particular standard or specification. It is permissible to substitute part number 132732-1-(X) for WSI-4-(X) and part number 132732-3-(X) for WSI-332-(X), where (X) represents a length. 9. PAINTED SPARES To prevent an AOG condition, it is permissible to supply the painted spare with the identifier for one specific customer to another customer provided the same basic number is used. (e.g. There are different basic part numbers used for the Hydraulic Service Door. Therefore, 133-440029-11PT may be supplied in place of 133-440029-11PN, but 133-440029-11PT may not be supplied for 133-440029-139PN.) The basic part number 133-440029-11 may be supplied in place of 133-440029-11PN and 133-440029-11PT part numbers. For painted spares, the part numbers with -PN will also be good for the PM customer. Painted spares with the same basic part number ending in PT or PN are suitable for use on Navy T-6s or T-6B aircraft. For the purpose of Navy NALCOMIS OOMA baseline part number assignment, Usable On Codes (UOC) for all basic part numbers having painted variants may be ignored and assigned across both T-6A and T-6B baselines provided the basic number is the same. Example 1 - 133-610003-23, 133-610003-23PN and 133-610003-23PT may be assigned to both baselines regardless of identified UOC. Example 2 - 133-610003-25 having no painted variant is restricted for assignment by identified UOC. 10. SPARES AND ALTERNATES SPARE: For example, if 133-xxxxxx-5 says “for spares, order 133-xxxxxx-7”, this indicates the -7 is the preferred part for spares. • The 133-xxxxxx-5 can only replace a -5, allowing any remaining stock to be used. • The 133-xxxxxx-5 shall not be used to replace a -7. • The 133-xxxxxx-7 must be replaced with a -7. ALTERNATE: For example, if 133-xxxxxx-5 says “alternate for 133-xxxxxx-7”, this indicates the -5 and -7 are interchangeable and either can be used as a replacement. 11. DASH NUMBER EQUIVALENTS 133-xxxxxx part numbers, with dash numbers identified as -X, -0X, -00X, or -000X are considered equivalent and identifiers of the same part.
